<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6516 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSHA-BENEFIT-AZR &LR;      09-27 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSHA-BENEFIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA LAST IN AID PAID TO SURVIVORS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
For Sue Scully, the question doesn't go away.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It haunts her as she drives the 75 miles from Golden Valley,
west of Kingman, to her job as a grocery store checker in Boulder
City, Nev. It stays with her as she sits in her dilapidated mobile
home, and watches the bills stack up. It gnaws at her when she
thinks about her two sons.
</P>
<P>
   How can her husband's life be worth $183.75 a week?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Scully gets from workers' compensation _ a poor
replacement for her husband, Regis, who was killed in an industrial
accident in Kingman in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very hard,'' said Scully, 45, through a voice choked
by tears. ``We have no money left over.''
</P>
<P>
   Scully's situation is not unique. Arizona ranks dead last among
the 50 states in workers' compensation benefits paid to widows and
widow ers of workers killed on the job. At $183.75, Scully gets the
maximum. In the highest-paying state, Iowa, surviving spouses
receive $817 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (benefit levels) are an embarrassment,'' said Sandra Day,
a Mesa lawyer who represents injured workers. ``They're an
indication that workers don't have much status or financial value
to the public policymakers in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, more than 114,000 workers received medical benefits and
about 15,000 received reim bursement for lost work days, ac cording
to the Arizona Industrial Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, more than 1,000 workers end up on permanent disa
bility. &QL; 
INJURY BENEFITS ALSO POOR
</P>
<P>
   While the survivors' benefits rank last, the benefits are almost
as bad for workers injured on the job. Arizona ranks 45th
nationally in the maximum wage available under workers' comp _ $322
per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people, on these cases, if your claim gets denied, you
are going to be broke immediately,'' said Chris Johnson, who also
repre sents injured workers. ``If you get accepted, you'll probably
be broke in a few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gila County deputy sher iff Joseph Llewellyn can attest
to that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990-91, he was hurt on the job, not once but twice. Neck and
back injuries left him 50 percent disabled and in constant pain. He
received $500 a month from work ers' compensation, and some of that
went to the lawyer he hired to get his benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He was financially devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our credit, lost a vehicle, almost lost our home,''
said Llewellyn, 51, a Vietnam veteran and 13-year deputy who had
made $25,000 a year. ``Our family had to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Llewellyn, who went to college during his rehabilitation, now
works for the state Rehabilitation Services Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Llewellyn said he found there was virtually no support for
workers injured on the job. He says the law needs revision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to be a support system, then it should support
you, like a crutch does a broken leg,'' he said. ``If it's not a
support system, let's get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   While people such as Scully and Llewellyn are forced to
struggle, the state workers' compensation system is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Premiums have been cut by double digits in each of the past four
years. In 1997, the State Compensation Fund _ the state's largest
workers' comp provider _ returned more than $75 million in
dividends to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Arizona ranks last in benefits, the premiums paid in the
state _ which are set by a national rating bureau _ are below
average, according to a national study by the Oregon Department of
Consumer and Business Services.
</P>
<P>
   Those low rates are a selling point in attracting new business
to the state, and that has blunted attempts by organized labor to
get the Legislature to raise benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is then you have the Legislature and the
governor's office and everybody saying, `Boy we want to really
protect this. This is really a plus for the state,' '' said Larry
Etchechury, director of the Arizona Industrial Commission, which
administers workers' com pensation. &QL; 
LOW RATES A SELLING POINT
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a selling point,'' said Jerry LeCompte,
director of the State Compensation Fund. ``Espe cially when
compared to the system that California had. The benefits had gone
crazy and there was so much fraud in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, LeCompte recognizes that benefits levels may
have to be raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, personally, I don't believe the benefit levels in Arizona
should be last in the nation,'' LeCompte said. ``Should they be
first in the nation? I don't believe that, either.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the five-member In dustrial Commission wrote to the
Legislature, asking for benefits to be increased for the first time
in six years. Nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the commissioners noted the state Constitution
calls for a ``just and humane'' benefit to workers injured on the
job. They said raising benefit levels could be offset by premium
decreases.
</P>
<P>
   But the task of increasing bene fits falls to the Legislature,
which has been frozen on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 50th out of 50 states,'' said Chuck Huggins,
secretary-treasurer of the Arizona AFL-CIO. ``That's below the
federal poverty line. How do we justify that?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, labor unions backed a bill that would have increased
benefits by indexing the payout to a percentage of the state's
average weekly wage, which is $506. It didn't make it out of
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, business leaders want a number of technical revisions
to the law, dealing with issues such as judicial review,
reemployment and the loss of earning capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But neither labor nor business can gain an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a standoff,'' said Farrell Quinlan, a spokesman for
the Arizona Chamber of Commerce. ``Both sides have enough power to
blunt the other, but not enough to advance our agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jones, who heads a state Chamber committee that deals with
workers' comp, says it will be a tough sell as long as the economy
is doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us realistically see any changes in the workers' comp
law in the next year or two,'' Jones said. ``The economy is too
good. To be perfectly realistic, workers' compen sation insurance
premiums have been going down in the last six to eight years, and
as long as they're going down, no one wants to rock the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Except people like Javier Figue roa.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Yuma County man lost his arm and was paralyzed
in a cotton gin accident in Roll last year.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa was on a catwalk when his jacket sleeve was caught in a
pulley of a machine that was supposed to have been turned off. He
was tossed 35 feet into the air, hit the ceiling and then hit a
beam on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his left arm, and broke his back, his ribs and his
ankle. He now must use a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed everybody around me, completely,'' he said. ``I'm
talking familywise. Everybody's personality has changed because of
this. They've got to do special things for me. I don't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers' compensation insurance paid for his wheelchair, his
medical care and a new wheelchair-accessi ble mobile home. &QL; 
CAN'T COVER THE BILLS
</P>
<P>
   But Figueroa, who has two young sons, can't cover his bills with
the $1,050 he receives each month in workers' compensation. Making
things worse, his wife had to stop working so she could care for
him. Before the accident, they were making close to $2,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``A family of four can't live on a thousand dollars a month,''
he said. ``Not when you're used to having two paychecks coming in
every week.'' &QL; 
As for Sue Scully, she continues to struggle to get by.
</P>
<P>
   Each of her children _ ages 8 and 19 _ receives $315 a month
from workers' compensation. She and her youngest child receive a
combined $1,300 a month from Social Security, which pays survi vors
benefits based on what the deceased made during his or her life.
</P>
<P>
   Scully's life has changed drasti cally. Before the accident, she
and her husband worked opposite shifts, so they didn't need day
care. It now costs her several hundred dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
   And she has no health insurance. Every time a kid has the
sniffles, it comes straight out of her pocket. And she has to pay
for her own expensive blood pressure medica tion.
</P>
<P>
   Regis was insured for $20,000. Still, mortgage payments, water
assessments and repairs have eaten up all the money. Her husband,
an expert mechanic, is no longer around to keep the car running or
fix things around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Unless survivors can fall back on family members or carry hefty
life insurance policies, they don't have enough to live on. Others
are forced to go to court.
</P>
<P>
   Under Arizona law, an employee (or his family) cannot
successfully sue his direct employer for a workplace injury or
death, unless the employee turns down workers' compensation
coverage when he's hired.
</P>
<P>
   But the law doesn't protect other companies that are involved in
an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Carrie Jayo-Thomas. Her husband, Sabino Jayo
Jr., was killed in May 1994 when a wall collapsed on a job site at
the Yuma Proving Ground. While she couldn't sue his direct
employer, she filed a lawsuit against the general contractor,
another subcontractor and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the case was settled for an undisclosed sum,
requiring Jayo-Thomas to pay back all the workers' compensation
benefits she had received.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awful what they put you through.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or
 &UR; at bill.muller &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
