<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC OVERMATCHED BY FLORIDA STATE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Hurricane Georges barely made an appearance
Saturday, depositing just a few intermittent bursts of showers
above Doak Campbell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Which means it left a far stronger impression on the locals than
USC's offense, which was as close as anything came to being
declared a natural disaster in this city.
</P>
<P>
   At least USC took its offense home with it. The 18th-ranked
Trojans certainly didn't leave it on the field in an embarrassing
30-10 loss to 10th-ranked Florida State before 79,815.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a test of USC's mettle, but it turned
out to be an expose of its greatest shortcoming, an offense that
barely mustered a whimper against the Seminoles' swarming defense.
</P>
<P>
   USC's quarterbacks amassed 23 yards passing, a total so low that
school officials were going to have to research the last time the
Trojans passed for so few yards.
</P>
<P>
   Several Trojans teams have passed for 0 yards, the last time
against College of the Pacific in 1945. But the Trojans did not
even attempt a pass in that game.
</P>
<P>
   The offense was so anemic that Florida State wide receiver Peter
Warrick threw for more yards (14) than USC quarterback Mike Van
Raaphorst (5 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned into girls and didn't play,'' said USC offensive
lineman Travis Claridge, analyzing how his unit got totally
outclassed by its opponent.
</P>
<P>
   On most plays, the quarterback simply snapped the ball, waited
about two seconds and got hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very good feeling,'' freshman quarterback Carson
Palmer said. ``There's nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After entering this game confident from their 3-0 start, the
Trojans were taught just how far their offense remains from testing
one of the nation's elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a huge game for USC football,'' Trojans wide receiver
Billy Miller said. ``And a big blow. We didn't do anything with the
ball. We looked like we belonged in Division I-AA.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest was also viewed as USC coach Paul Hackett's first
chance to direct the Trojans against a top-notch program.
Obviously, he's got a lot of work ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, they overwhelmed us,'' Hackett said. ``We tried
different schemes. We tried moving the quarterbacks. We changed
blocking styles and they still got pressure on the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Van Raaphorst was bothered by flu-like symptoms,
neither he nor Palmer were able to stress the Seminoles (3-1).
Together, they completed just 3 of 19 passes.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the defense's strong performance, USC trailed only
13-3 at halftime. The Trojans were still in the game after freshman
tailback Frank Strong's 73-yard run set up a touchdown that cut the
lead to 20-10 with 25 seconds left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Strong's game-breaking run turned out to be nothing more
than an aberration. He also had two fourth-quarter fumbles that
ended drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need a contribution from an offensive standpoint to
keep in the mix,'' Hackett said. ``We couldn't get the ball in the
air. The penalties continue to plague us. We've got some issues on
the offensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps USC's last gasp occurred early in the fourth quarter,
with the Trojans losing 23-10. With a third-and-1 at their own 39,
nearly 10 seconds burned off the 25-second clock as Palmer talked
to assistant coach Ken O'Brien on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Palmer joined the huddle and the offense lined up,
there was no chance to snap the ball before the clock expired.
Palmer completed a bomb to R. Jay Soward over the middle, but the
play had been whistled dead before the snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we made the decision to fake on the line, and go for a
touchdown,'' Hackett said. ``We couldn't get the mechanics to
Carson on how to do it in time. I've got to take a close look if
it's not too much for him. We've got to examine if maybe it's too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's offense also struggled, but made several clutch
plays. Quarterback Chris Weinke completed just 13 of 31 passes, but
passed for 228 yards and two touchdowns. The Trojans also got
burned repeatedly by Warrick, who caught six passes for 112 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense was just good enough to win,'' Florida State coach
Bobby Bowden said. ``We've got all the pieces on offense. (But) the
inconsistency of our offense can undo the potential that is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, Hackett tried to hold things together as the
Trojans became the 36th straight opponent to leave Doak Campbell
Stadium without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not all that shocked. This is the level we need to play
at. We were not up to that today,'' he said. ``There was no
shellshock at all. This football team, we're not going to blink.
This team has too much character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
