<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      09-27 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros won't have anything of importance to play for until the
playoffs begin in a few days. Nevertheless, their intensity remains
as strong.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Umpire Eric Gregg ruffled some feathers on the home team with a
controversial, rally-killing call in the Astros' 3-2 loss to the
Chicago Cubs on Saturday at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg called pinch hitter Dave Clark out for running out of the
baseline on a play that would have brought the tying run home in
the ninth inning. Gregg's call ended the game and left the Astros
in a foul mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a brutal call,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``How
could two (umpires) miss that? And then they take off running up
the tunnel, and there's nothing you can do about it. That was just
a bad call.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros didn't like it, one can only imagine what the San
Francisco Giants thought of Gregg's game-ending decision. The
Giants, who beat Colorado, would have gained sole possession of the
wild-card lead had the Astros defeated the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Giants and Cubs hold a one-game lead over the Mets, who
will be eliminated today if they lose to the Braves or if either
the Giants or Cubs win.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets are eliminated, the Astros will host San Diego in
the Division Series beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Astros haven't lost sight of their ultimate goal,
Saturday's postgame rhetoric was heavy on Gregg and light on the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the hell Eric saw,'' Clark said. ``It was a
bad call. I didn't get to say anything. He made the call and got
the heck off the field. He didn't even ask for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Eric sees the replays. I have to believe the Giants
hated that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg's explanation of the call was short and to the point: ``I
called him out for running out of the baseline when he (Cubs closer
Rod Beck) tried to tag him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the commotion was a strong outing by Astros starter
Shane Reynolds, who deserved more than a no-decision. Reynolds, who
was attempting to become a 20-game winner for the first time,
scattered seven hits over seven innings and allowed just one run
while striking out 11.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds left with the score 1-1, but reliever Jay Powell
couldn't keep the Cubs off the scoreboard and the Astros' offense
disappeared in the middle seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   All of Reynolds' strikeouts came in the first six innings, and
the Cubs advanced just two runners into scoring position before
Gary Gaetti led off the seventh with a double and scored on a
sacrifice fly by pinch hitter Orlando Merced.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetti provided the finishing touch in the eighth with a two-run
double off Powell (7-7).
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Magnante retired Mickey Morandini on one pitch to
start the eighth inning, Dierker summoned Powell from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa, who was 2-for-4 with a pair of singles, and Mark
Grace greeted Powell with back-to-back hits. Glenallen Hill took a
called third strike for the second out of the inning. Gaetti then
ripped a slider into the gap in left-center to give the Cubs a
two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made two good pitches to Sosa and Grace, but they found the
holes,'' said Powell, who has allowed only one other hit _ also a
double _ to Gaetti in nine career confrontations. ``The pitch to
Gaetti was just a bad pitch. It was a hanging slider _ a terrible
slider. It just seems like he sits on certain pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was all Beck could do to sit on the 3-1 lead in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros appeared ready to work some more of their late-inning
magic when Jeff Bagwell led off with a solo homer off the back wall
of Lefty's Pub. Bagwell, who was 3-for-4, drove in the Astros'
other run with a single to center in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou followed Bagwell's homer with a double and moved to
third on a ground ball by Carl Everett. At that point, all it would
have taken was a sacrifice fly to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a good shot,'' Bagwell said. ``Everyone is so
used to us coming back, but it's not going to happen all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck struck out Tony Eusebio on four pitches, setting the stage
for the game-ending drama.
</P>
<P>
   Clark tapped a slow chopper down the first-base line and veered
away from Beck, who fielded the ball and attempted to tag Clark.
Unsure if he had made the tag, Beck wheeled and threw toward first,
hitting Clark in the back. The ball bounced away as Alou crossed
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Players rose from the Astros' bench to greet what they thought
was the run, and even Beck was unclear regarding what had
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the tying run had scored,'' said Beck, who earned
his 50th save and claimed he tagged Clark. ``I was turning around
to argue with Eric, but when I saw him make the out call, I said
`Yeah!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
