<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-RICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' 6 TDS DRIVE LONGHORNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ For those seeking the first watershed moment in Texas
football coach Mack Brown's tenure, consider what his team did last
night in Royal-Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns took the suspense out of a matchup with Rice,
scoring early and often en route to a 59-21 romp.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to throttle lesser lights with regularity figured
heavily in the reassignment of predecessor John Mackovic after the
1997 season. But there was no struggle for these Longhorns, who
followed the record-setting lead of tailback Ricky Williams to
improve to 2-2 after consecutive losses against top 10 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Williams rushed for a career-high 318 yards and six touchdowns,
bettering his five-touchdown performance in last year's 38-31
nail-biter at Rice Stadium. He averaged 10.6 yards per carry on 30
attempts and, with 32 yards in receptions, set a school record with
350 all-purpose yards. Williams' all-purpose total provided more
than half of Texas' school-record 692 yards total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky looked as good tonight as anybody I've ever seen,''
Brown said. ``He's just a fabulous football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Major Applewhite, the team's redshirt freshman quarterback, also
thrived on a Rice diet, completing 71.4 percent of his passes (15
for 21) for a career-high 258 yards and two touchdowns. He directed
a first-team offense that exploded for 616 yards on 58 snaps (10.6
average) before retiring for the evening with 5 minutes, 50 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UT's performance, which included a season-high four sacks by a
swarming defense, stood in stark contrast to its effort in last
week's 48-7 loss to No. 5 Kansas State. It also stood in marked
contrast to Mackovic's five career matchups against Rice, which
included two victories by a touchdown or less and a 19-17 loss in
1994 that broke the Longhorns' string of 28 consecutive victories
in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``College football is a game of momentum, and we needed a game
like this to establish ourselves and boost our confidence,'' said
offensive guard Ben Adams. ``It's hard to predict the future, but
this win could be very big for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly qualifies as big for Williams' Heisman Trophy
campaign, as well as his pursuit of several NCAA career records. On
the strength of a six-touchdown night, Williams jumped from 17th to
seventh on the NCAA career scoring list and, with 62 touchdowns,
stands within three of the NCAA career mark (65) held by Indiana's
Anthony Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely in the zone out there ... more than I've ever
been,'' said Williams, who missed a potential seventh touchdown
with a lost fumble at the Rice goal line in the second quarter.
``For the first time in a while, I felt like a real running back. I
was relaxed and I made some moves on their safeties. I expected to
get at least 250 yards against Rice. But when I got to 300, that
was special. It proved I had the conditioning to take it that
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' scoring runs varied in length from 16 to 41 yards.
Most were accomplished dragging Rice defenders into the end zone as
Owls coach Ken Hatfield stood in wonder while his team dropped to
1-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is a great back, but they've got the best offensive line
we've seen all year,'' Hatfield said. ``They've bigger than us,
they're faster than us, they're stronger than us, they're a better
football team than us and they beat the dog out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, Hatfield never uttered similar remarks after a
matchup against a Texas team coached by John Mackovic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
