r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYING-AZR &LR;      09-27 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS OUR ETHICS WANE, LIES GROW
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started in the Garden of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   Adam was contemplating his na vel when Eve walked up wearing a
new fig leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, do you think this makes me look fat?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, Eve. It looks great.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first lie.
</P>
<P>
   No, just a little fib. Would you believe, Eve was standing by
this tree, see, checking out some fruit, when a serpent slithered
up and hissed, ``Trust me, you'll like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that's the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, President William Jefferson Clinton is hardly unique
when it comes to temptation and dishonesty. Humankind's story is a
rollicking saga of deceit.
</P>
<P>
   Herodotus, the father of history, was also dubbed ``the father
of lies'' because his accounts were so bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Scriptures bulge with tales of perfidy, from Genesis to Peter's
denial that he knew Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Niccolo Machiavelli said success ful princes are ``those who
give their word lightly, who have known how to trick men with their
cun ning.''
</P>
<P>
   The namesake of our nation, Amerigo Vespucci, lied about being
the first to discover South America.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon wrote fantastically fraudulent dispatches of military
exploits.
</P>
<P>
   The story about George Washington's cherry tree is a myth
concocted by a minister with a penchant for fibbing.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler advocated ``the big lie,'' and perfected it with
propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon appeared on TV to say, ``There can be no whitewash
at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver North conducted covert operations in defense of truth,
justice and the American way _ then lied to Congress about it.
</P>
<P>
   And now a president faces possi ble impeachment while much of
the public seems indifferent to his deceit. Polls, if you can trust
them, say six of 10 people believe Clinton lied under oath about
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, yet an equal number don't want him
out of office. &QL; 
WATERGATE EFFECT
</P>
<P>
   Philip Kerr, author of The Pen guin Book of Lies, wrote in 1989
that the public conscience changed after Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas before we expected politicians to lie, and to resign
if they were caught, today we expect them to lie as much, and then
we excuse them for it. . . . We seem to want to excuse them just as
we would want to be excused ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethics, honesty and truth are no longer perceived to be of
such fundamental importance in public life because they are not
perceived to be of much importance in private life, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some of us are more virtuous than others.
</P>
<P>
   But four of 10 Americans are said to fudge on taxes. We lie
about traffic tickets, sell cars and houses without mentioning
defects, falsify resumes, exaggerate in arguments and ask our kids
to fib on the phone. &QL; 
MOST HAVE REASONS
</P>
<P>
   In Lying: Moral Choice in Public and Private Life, Sissela Bok
ob served: ``The fact is that reasons to lie occur to most people
quite often. . . . Not many stop to examine the choices confronting
them.''
</P>
<P>
   So, as a nation judges its presi dent, it may also want to take
time out for soul-searching on deceit.
</P>
<P>
   Lies are seldom detected, fre quently effective, sometimes harm
less, occasionally even good.
</P>
<P>
   We fabricate to avoid conse quences, enhance ourselves, damage
others, gain esteem, make money. Lawyers and undercover cops are
paid to deceive. We maintain social grace with white lies,
protecting others from hurt as in the fable of Eve's silly leaf. We
dupe our kids about Santa Claus. We may lie to prevent a greater
evil _ telling the Gestapo, for instance, that we don't know where
Anne Frank's family is hiding.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue raised by Clinton's affair is not about Anne Frank
or Santa. It is about misleading others for selfish reasons. And it
is an old story, right down to the excuses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1668, Englishman Samuel Pepys duped his wife _ at least for a
while _ about an affair with a young maid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth (is) that I did adven ture upon God's pardoning me
this lie,'' Pepys wrote in his diary, ``knowing how heavy a thing
it would be for me to be the ruin of the poor girl; and next,
knowing that if my wife should know it all, it would be impossible
for her ever to be at peace with me again.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of rationalization would later prompt Friedrich
Nietzsche, the German philosopher, to observe, ``The most common
lie is the lie one tells to one self; lying to oth ers is
relatively the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Another phi losopher, Im manuel Kant, argued in the 18th century
that deceit is always wrong because it strips humans of dignity. In
Kant's mind, man was distinct from beasts because of an ability to
make ethical choices based on truth. To use deception, Kant
reasoned, is to corrupt that power and to rob others of their
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deceit and violence _ these are the two forms of deliberate
assault on human beings,'' wrote Bok. ``Both can coerce people into
acting against their will.''
</P>
<P>
   Each lie distorts our faith. And, as Shakespeare pointed out,
one lie usually results in a tangled web.
</P>
<P>
   Gini Graham Scott, author of Making Ethical Choices, Resolving
Ethical Dilemmas, says dishonesty is dragging American culture down
in a miasma of cynicism. &QL; 
REDEFINING LYING
</P>
<P>
   ``You have enough people doing it and pretty soon nobody can
trust anybody,'' she notes. ``We're sort of redefining lying as
being OK. I think what's happening in our soci ety today _ why
we're in this sort of social melt-down _ is that we're losing our
moral grounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Societies have collapsed in the past because they haven't paid
attention to moral principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, a sociologist and anthropol ogist, says Clinton's
predicament is a symptom rather than the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's not the sex thing, as distasteful as that may be.
It's the lying. It's sort of a statement of where we've dissolved
as a society. The law of the jungle starts prevail ing. And I think
that's where we are today.''
</P>
<P>
   What rises to the top?
</P>
<P>
   The National Enquirer. Jerry Springer. Professional wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Popular icons revel in glory like pigs in muck. Political
spin-doctor ing is regarded as art. Hit movies such as Liar, Liar
and Wag the Dog romanticize deceit. Television is a cesspool of
intrigue about conniving cops, lawyers and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   We laugh at the staged deceit of Joe Isuzu, Maxwell Smart or
John Lovitz _ all parodies of the bull artists we know, or are.
</P>
<P>
   We elect a president nicknamed ``Slick Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists have found that honesty varies from generation
to generation, gender to gender, class to class. But virtually
every creed and culture in history has featured overt or tacit
rules against lying.
</P>
<P>
   In the Judeo-Christian heritage, deceit is banned in a
commandment handed to Moses: ``Thou shalt not bear false witness .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, parents in 10 Western nations were asked to rank
qualities they wished to pass on to their kids. In nine of those
nations, the No. 1 response was: honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Yet lies keep growing like Pinoc chio's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Josephson, president of the Josephson Institute for
Ethics, found in a study that seven of 10 high school kids cheated
on tests in the past year _ a rate that is rising. &QL; 
GETTING AWAY WITH IT
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hole in the moral ozone and it's getting bigger,''
Josephson says. ``There's a sense that cheaters get away with it.
Liars lie and we shrug it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Dale Fushek, pastor of St. Timothy's Catholic Church in
Mesa, suspects that integrity has declined because we are
disconnected _ products of broken families, modern technology and
mobility. Without bonds, there is no faith in one another. Without
faith, truth dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have become more self-centered,'' he adds.
``That becomes your highest priority, and if you have to lie to
meet your own needs, people are more willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Most ethicists say the paradox is that lies damage the deceiver
as much as the deceived. There may be an instant benefit, notes
Fushek, but dishonest people ultimately lack an inner peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible says, `Truth will set you free.' Whenever you lie,
you bind yourself somehow. It always catches up with you. But in
our microwave society, the short term is all that people look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Chase, director of the Center for Applied Christian Ethics
at Wheaton College in Illinois, said he's troubled by the nation's
seem ing acceptance of deceit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cynicism is evident. It's underlying the statements of
people saying, `Let's just put this behind us and get on with the
business of the country.' Why would we put this behind us? This
seems to be a situation that's right for moral reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Dobrin, a secularist pro fessor of humanities at Hofstra
University in New York, says virtue is its own reward, adding,
``The point of truth-telling is that we really can count on one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin says Clinton's drama may infect children, much as it has
adults, with cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't trust the president, whom can you trust?'' he
asks. ``That's pretty serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin says the Clinton crisis is a morality lesson for kids of
all ages:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes good people do bad things. Sometimes bad people do
good things inadvertently.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Dennis Wagner can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8874 or at dennis.wagner &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
