<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--SOSA-HNS &LR;      09-27 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--SOSA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
OK, Sammy, you were right all along.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire is The Man.
</P>
<P>
   While you were doing boring stuff like hitting clutch singles,
hustling to balls in the outfield, pumping up your teammates in the
dugout and speeding home with the go-ahead run against maybe the
best team in baseball, The Man hit another pair of home runs in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think this is, Sammy, baseball? Some 51,950
Astrodome fans were disappointed in you. They wanted you to bring
your big stick Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted streamers and booming shots. They wanted high-flying
action _ Rip Taylor tossing confetti to the crowd, bright lights,
announcers reaching for higher octaves, fireworks. They wanted
curtain calls and tips of the cap.
</P>
<P>
   They even booed Astros starter Shane Reynolds, poor guy, as he
masterfully worked his way through seven innings looking for his
20th win. Reynolds had the nerve to get you out, and few seemed to
appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted you to be the man, Sammy, but all you could give
them was the game's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   You came ready to play some good old-fashioned baseball, but
they wanted you to do what The Man did as he was the guest of honor
at another wild carnival in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Man swung for the fences, hammered blasts to the bleachers
and smiled that familiar broad smile as he rounded the bases
slamming forearms with everyone in sight. The Man hit Nos. 67 and
68. Wow.
</P>
<P>
   You know what this means, Sammy. Yet again, The Man has put some
distance between you and him in this remarkable home-run race. And
there's only one day left in this season _ for The Man, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It means McGwire probably has secured the illustrious home-run
title with this latest effort. Sure, you've heard that line before,
but this time we really mean it. McGwire is The Man. Just like you
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably hit some more (today),'' you told us after
sparking the Cubs' 3-2 win over the Astros on Saturday. ``I hope he
gets to 70.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he probably will. You all but conceded the home-run race
to McGwire after Saturday's game, although we did notice that
twinkle in your eyes when you said it.
</P>
<P>
   And it was hard not to notice something else, too. The Man has
only today remaining in this remarkable season, then the circus
will leave town and McGwire will be off to do those things
larger-than-life figures do _ books, talk shows, driving contests
against Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But you still have your team fighting for playoff life, thanks
to, well, you. A win over the Astros today would guarantee at least
one more game, maybe three, four, five or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw today why Sammy is our guy,'' Cubs veteran Mark Grace
said Saturday. ``He's our MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   You're everybody's MVP, Sammy. You hustled and scratched out
hits, rounded the bases, like you have all year. You even talked
about just wanting ``to make contact'' during the critical late
innings Saturday when the Astros and Reynolds all but had your
season at its breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   You again showed why the case for the Astros' Craig Biggio or
Moises Alou winning the MVP honor has been a long shot all along.
You showed why McGwire will get votes, and deservedly so, but won't
get the award.
</P>
<P>
   You're bringing the Cubs to the Astrodome today tied with the
San Francisco Giants in the race for the wild-card berth and only a
game ahead of the New York Mets. You have helped your team stay
alive all year, and now it's all there in front of you _ the
playoffs, not the carnival.
</P>
<P>
   You sliced a single in the eighth Saturday, moved up on a hit by
Grace and scored the go-ahead run on a clutch double by Gary
Gaetti. When you crossed the plate, you skipped around in the dirt
and shook your fists as if you had just homered. But you didn't.
You just played baseball. And that's why you are what you are.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there will be one more carnival in St. Louis every time
McGwire steps to the plate. But in the Dome, there will be a good
old-fashioned playoff race on the line every time you do, a chance
to move on to an elimination game or maybe a date with the Atlanta
Braves in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say it is the biggest game of my career (today),''
you said. ``It's been a great year, but we need to get to the
playoffs. I just want to do anything I can.''
</P>
<P>
   A single, a double. A sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really says something when there's someone like McGwire who
has 68 home runs, or more, and someone else who could get the
MVP,'' Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. ``That really says
something about Sammy.''
</P>
<P>
   It says what you said with your actions again Saturday, Sammy.
The Man is McGwire. The MVP is you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
