r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TCU-AIR-FORCE-TEX     09-27 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-AIR-FORCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNED FROGS DENY LATE BID, UPSET AIR FORCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ For the second time in as many games, TCU sophomore
cornerback Greg Walls found himself in the spotlight with the
outcome of the game in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   But showing tremendous growth from two weeks ago, Walls
responded with two spectacular pass breakups in the waning moments
last night to preserve TCU's 35-34 upset victory against No. 23 Air
Force before 26,418 spectators at Amon Carter Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As Air Force threatened, Walls came through twice to break up
pass plays from Falcons quarterback Blane Morgan to receiver Dylan
Newman, with the final effort giving the ball to TCU on downs with
1 minute, 25 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Oklahoma Sooners threw a game-winning
touchdown pass over Walls in the corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference this week was confidence,'' said Walls, a
first-year starter. ``I knew they had watched the game film and
they were going to come right at me. But this time around I came up
and made the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   As did his Horned Frogs teammates, who earned the school's first
victory against a Top-25 opponent since upending No. 23 Kansas in
1994 at Amon Carter Stadium. The victory last night also puts TCU
atop the Mountain Division of the Western Athletic Conference
Mountain Division with a 1-0 league mark and 2-1 mark overall.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the players were confident they had erased many of
the demons from last season's 1-10 mark under former coach Pat
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is huge,'' nose guard J.W. Wilson said. ``Never in my
wildest imagination did I think we would come out of this thing
with a win. This team has really come a long ways.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was never more evident than when the Frogs fought back
from an 11-point third-quarter deficit to take a 35-31 lead early
in the fourth quarter against the previously undefeated Falcons
(3-1, 2-1 WAC).
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a spirited performance in his first action at
tailback this season, LaDainian Tomlinson scooted 2 yards up the
middle to cap an impressive 15-play, 70-yard drive that began in
the third quarter and ended with 13:21 remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   One series earlier, fullback Lance Williams charged up the
middle for a 13-yard scoring run that seemed to give the Frogs some
momentum. And they gained even more confidence when quarterback
Patrick Batteaux rolled right to complete the two-point conversion
pass to tight end B.J. Roberts, pulling TCU within 31-28 with 3:08
to play in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' offense, showing much improvement over their effort
two weeks ago against the Sooners, stayed on the field for 77
offensive snaps and won the time-of-possession battle 36:42 to
23:18. TCU gained 256 yards on the ground, with Tomlinson coming
off the bench with the key contribution of 99 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing for us tonight was execution,'' said
Batteaux, who completed 10 of 19 passes for 95 yards. ``When we
were down we still kept our focus and that was difference.''
</P>
<P>
   That focus also was evident in the second quarter, when TCU
scored 20 points to take a 20-17 halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
