<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6527 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     09-27 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATING RANKED FOE THE TONIC TCU NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The bleeding, a full year's worth, stopped
at 9:24 last night.
</P>
<P>
   Having forgotten the routine, obviously, the TCU Horned Frogs
danced across the football field to the student section. They
hugged. They high-fived. They warbled the alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the friskier Frogs attempted an impromptu version of the
Lambeau Leap, but they were able to vault only partly up the high
concrete wall.
</P>
<P>
   Flying Frogs? That must come later.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the tourniquet is in place. The resurrection at Amon
Carter Stadium continues. Rising to the occasion, TCU dominated the
time of possession and upset No. 23-ranked Air Force last night,
35-34.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's wounds, when the program went winless for three
months, are finally behind the Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great confidence builder,'' new coach Dennis
Franchione said. ``It was a great emotional win. I think it stopped
the bleeding from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to keep building on it.''
</P>
<P>
   This, however, was no small nail to drive. The Falcons of coach
Fisher DeBerry came into the contest as the nation's eighth-highest
scoring team and with the NCAA's No. 2 running game.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half, when so many Saturdays last season
seemed to wither on the vine, the TCU defense rose to stymie three
critical Air Force drives. The Falcons' final four possessions
produced only one field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give a lot of credit to TCU,'' DeBerry said. ``They came out
with a lot of different schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   Schemes? Formations? Certainly the extra week of preparation
that the TCU coaches enjoyed was exploited to the max. But this was
a night made more for heartbeats than chalkboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a case of us wanting to win more than they did,'' TCU
linebacker Joseph Phipps said.
</P>
<P>
   Like we said, the resurrection continues.
</P>
<P>
   As Franchione, the master rebuilder, prepared for his first TCU
season, he had wished aloud for a night just like last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a nice win early _ to build our confidence,''
Franchione said back in August.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the new coach had one in the season opener, winning on
the road at Iowa State. Were it not for a bounce here, a knee
there, he almost had another one two weeks ago against Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   But this one, the Frogs' first victory against a ranked opponent
in four seasons, puts a loud, purple stamp of validity on what
Franchione and his staff are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess when you're a Top 25 team,'' Air Force's DeBerry said,
``your opponent comes out ready to play and plays hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't take it so personally. Franchione has had the Frogs
trying to fly for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One of Franchione's other preseason wishes had been that the
Frogs would not turn tail at the first sign of adversity, the way
they did so often under Pat Sullivan a year ago. But TCU faced
several of those game-turning moments last night, only to emerge
unrattled.
</P>
<P>
   One came when the defense let Air Force quarterback Blane Morgan
march the Falcons 79 yards in seven instant plays to knot the
score, 17-all, right before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' Patrick Batteaux responded with a swift drive of his
own, leading to a Chris Kaylakie field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential killing blow came when return man Royce
Huffman lost a third-quarter punt. Officials ruled a fumble.
Franchione argued animatedly that Huffman had been interfered with.
Air Force promptly scored in three plays to take a 31-20 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But, behind Batteaux and LaDainian Tomlinson, the Frogs came
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to put the dagger in, and we didn't come up
with the big plays,'' the Falcons' DeBerry said.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs, on the other hand, reaped a telling abundance of big
plays. They converted nine of 18 third-down situations. And with
Morgan trying to move Air Force into field-goal range in the final
minute, Greg Walls and the TCU secondary rose to swat the ball
away.
</P>
<P>
   When Batteaux ran out the final seconds, the symbolic bleeding
was over. TCU, the eternal train-wreck victim, had a healing
victory at last.
</P>
<P>
   One day, maybe sooner than anyone ever expected, Frogs will fly.
In the meantime, watch them try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
