<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NORTH-T     09-27 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NORTH-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES' OFFENSE STRUGGLES IN WIN OVER NORTH TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M put a little air into its
offense during a ho-hum 28-9 victory against North Texas before
56,072 at Kyle Field last night.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains, however, as to whether the Aggies' offense
will float in the Big 12, into which A&AMP;M (3-1) ventures for the
first time next week at Kansas. Considering that at kickoff 99
teams in Division I-A had better pass defenses than that offered by
the winless (0-4) Eagles, a season-high of 247 passing yards can be
considered little more than a trial balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was less than impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in our play tonight,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum
said. ``I thought we were very sloppy. We've got a whole lot of
work to get done to get ready to play in the Big 12 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, but I'm glad we were able to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggies split end Chris Cole and junior backup quarterback Randy
McCown were among those who escaped Slocum's blanket of
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Cole surpassed his three-game season yardage total (162) with
six receptions for a career-high 174 yards and three touchdowns,
his first three scoring catches of the season. A&AMP;M obliterated a
previous season-high, 139-yard passing total against Louisiana Tech
_ in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Cole hauled in a 60-yard TD pass from Branndon Stewart on the
Aggies' first play from scrimmage. He also scored on receptions of
35 and 52 yards from McCown as A&AMP;M probed deeply into an
ineffective and injury-weakened UNT secondary.
</P>
<P>
   McCown completed 11 of 13 passes for a career-high 167 yards and
the two touchdowns. He also regenerated doubt as to whether he or
Stewart should be running the offense. After completing his first
pass to Cole, Stewart went 3-for-9 for only 20 more yards and threw
his first interception of the season into double coverage at the
UNT 13.
</P>
<P>
   McCown relieved Stewart for the last series of the first half
and guided the Aggies 85 yards in nine plays for a 14-3 halftime
lead. Cole's scoring catch in the end zone culminated that drive
after McCown scrambled out of trouble on third-and-16 at the UNT
35.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches just told me to be ready to play this week,''
McCown said. ``Our offensive line gave us time to throw tonight and
our receivers made some big plays. Chris Cole was outstanding. It's
the first time we've seen a receiver play like that since Albert
Connell.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's defense was not exactly Wrecking Crew awesome. But it did
set the table for Sirr Parker's 3-yard scoring run with 6:30 left,
when linebacker Warrick Holdman popped Eagles quarterback Jason
Attaway and end Rocky Bernard recovered the resulting fumble at the
UNT 16. Extra points A&AMP;M sophomore kicker Russell Bynum missed
field-goal attempts from 35 and 27 yards after hitting the first
five of his career. Bynum kicked three points-after-touchdown, but
was relieved of that duty on the last TD by sophomore Terence
Kitchens. ... UNT split end Jay Young caught 11 passes for 105
yards. ... Cole's 174 receiving yards rank No.4 on A&AMP;M's
single-game total. ... LB Dat Nguyen's seven tackles put him into
the 400-tackle club along with Johnny Holland (455), Mike Little
(448) and Ed Simonini (425). ... Stewart's interception came after
72 attempts without one. ... Dante Hall and Parker combined to gain
133 yards on 27 carries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
