A6537 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     09-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRISSOM LEADS BREWERS PAST DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marquis Grissom is going home after today. And
he's not happy about it,
</P>
<P>
   After batting .390 in the past three World Series, Grissom finds
himself on the last day of the regular season at Dodger Stadium,
about as far as one can get from the center of the baseball
universe.
</P>
<P>
   But he showed up Saturday night and hit two home runs in the
Milwaukee Brewers' 6-1 victory in front of 30,645 at Dodger
Stadium. That is as many as he has hit in 336 career at-bats
against the Dodgers. And it was the first time in 1,280 career
games that Grissom hit more than one homer in a game.
</P>
<P>
   So much for numbers. He'd trade them all to be back in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom helped the Atlanta Braves beat Cleveland in 1995 by
hitting .360 (9 for 25). The next year, when the Braves lost to the
New York Yankees, Grissom batted .444 (12 for 27).
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Grissom was traded from Atlanta to the Indians as
part of a deal for Kenny Lofton. He batted .360 (9 for 25) in a
tense seven-game loss to the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Lofton returned to the Indians and Grissom went to
the Brewers, who are 27 games out of first place in the National
League Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was going to the postseason, but I'm looking forward
to going home and getting healthy,'' said Grissom, who is playing
with a sore right shoulder. ``Cleveland will do well, but they have
to go through the Yankees. Anything can happen in the best-of-seven
series. We proved that last season.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-climax of this series is striking. Only 35,000 are
expected for today's Fan Appreciation Day, usually a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the usual giveaways of Toyota Corollas, fans have a
chance to see Chan Ho Park go after a career-high 15th victory.
Most of all they can bid farewell to a disappointing Dodgers
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers enter the game with an 82-80 record, which
guarantees a winning season for the fifth consecutive year. But in
the end, this team hardly has the look of a winner. If Raul
Mondesi, who has missed the past three games with a injured left
index finger, doesn't play today, the Dodgers will not field one
member of their Opening Day lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game suffered from a distinct lack of energy. It was
scoreless until Grissom homered with one out in the fourth against
Dodgers starter Carlos Perez (11-14), who was going for his fifth
consecutive complete game.
</P>
<P>
   Perez and Milwaukee's Scott Karl were a study in contrasts.
Perez came in allowing just three earned run in his previous 36
innings. Karl hadn't won since Aug. 9, with five losses and three
no decisions. But after six innings, it was Karl (10-11) who had
the 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Karl, who gave up seven homers in four losses to St. Louis this
season, did not allow a Dodgers baserunner to reach third in six
innings. He allowed just three hits and struck out seven.
</P>
<P>
   Perez probably would have finished this one, too, but he
sprained the index finger on his pitching hand trying to field
Fernando Vina's bunt RBI single in the seventh that gave the
Brewers a 2-0 lead. Perez was taken to Centinela Hospital Medical
Center for precautionary X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Before departing, he pitched to one more batter, Mark Loretta,
but nearly threw two pitches over the head of rookie catcher Angel
Pena. Sean Maloney took over and finish the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Karl was replaced by right-hander David Weathers, who gave up a
home run to Matt Luke, his first batter. Weathers also allowed a
two-out pinch double to Charles Johnson after getting ahead 0-2 in
the count. But Roger Cedeno grounded out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers added a run in the eighth on Grissom's second homer
that just cleared the fence in left-center. It was his 10th of the
year. They scored three in the ninth, two on an RBI singles by
Loretta off the Dodgers' fourth pitcher, Eric Weaver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
