<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHOT DOWN IN SEASON FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Walter Zenga had to be satisfied with the
Revolution's fourth shutout in five games Saturday night. But the
Revolution also failed to score and lost the post-match shootout to
the MetroStars to finish the season with the worst record in Major
League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well and had good chances to score,'' Zenga said.
``In the second half, we got a little tired, but that is
understandable with the third game in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   In the games since Zenga replaced Thomas Rongen late last month,
the Revolution were 3-2 and outscored the opposition, 11-6. But
they nonetheless finished with 29 points, their lowest total and
the second-worst record in the three-year history of the league.
</P>
<P>
   But even though there were no playoff stakes for either team, a
crowd of 24,763 attended the match, raising the season average to
19,158, third-highest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   This was a curious matchup of coaches. Zenga had not coached
before last month and the MetroStars' Bora Milutinovic was in his
first MLS game and did not even know the names of all of his
players.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga displayed a winning touch with the Revolution, though it
came too late to salvage the team's playoff hopes. And he nearly
concluded the season with a victory, as Carlos Rocha hit the post
with a first-half header and Paul Keegan's goal off a corner kick
was disallowed on a questionable offside call.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution appeared fatigued in the second half, and
Zenga used only one substitute _ Jamar Beasley for Rocha.
Midfielder Jair, who converted the clinching goal in a 2-0 win over
Columbus Sept. 12, remained on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that played well for the last month,'' Zenga
said, indicating that the players deserved to conclude the game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution discovered some cohesion under Zenga,
who is attempting to build a foundation for next season. They had
few major defensive breakdowns in the final five games, and
minimized them Saturday night, though the Metro-Stars nearly won
the match in the final minute, but Tab Ramos hit the side of the
net with a volley.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's high-energy approach produced many
opportunities in the first half. But the MetroStars nearly
capitalized on a bobble by goalkeeper Ian Feuer in the 30th minute.
Mike Sorber sent a low 30-yard shot from the right side that
bounced off Feuer's chest to Giovanni Savarese. With a clear shot
on goal, Savarese sent a low drive toward the far post. But Brian
Dunseth, whose giveaway had allowed Chicago tie the score in a 3-2
loss Wednesday, cleared off the line.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution starters were optimistic about next season, based on
what they've seen in recent games. ``We played well in the first
half; we should have scored a couple of goals,'' midfielder Edwin
Gorter said. ``It's normal that we would be tired playing our third
game in seven days. It's the same everywhere in the world. But this
gives us something to build on for next year, that's for sure.
Hopefully, we can start where we left off this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Joe-Max Moore, ``We are on the way to putting a good team
on the field. Walter is going to try and figure out a way to put a
better team on the field, and he has the resources to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution named Moore most valuable player and Mike Burns
defensive player of the year. Gorter was named Revolution man of
the year in a vote conducted by the Midnight Riders fan group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
