</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE HITS TWO FOR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Citizens of coastal Florida removed plywood from
window frames and most Nebraskans watched the Cornhuskers slug it
out with Washington. In the nation's capital, Beltway insiders
prepared for the weekly Sunday morning talk show spin.
</P>
<P>
   But no one else in the Americas strayed too far from the Great
Home Run Chase Saturday, and on a 90-degree day in the shadow of
the Great Arch, Mark McGwire hit home runs Nos. 67 and 68 to regain
the lead he's held most of the summer. In Houston, Sammy Sosa
remained ``stuck'' on Route 66.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never let go of this season,'' McGwire said after the
game. ``I'll always hold onto it. It might not ever happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's 67th was a heat-seeking missile to left in the fourth
inning off Dustin Hermanson. Then came No. 68, a 435-foot rocket to
center in the seventh off Kirk Bullinger. When he hit the second
one, McGwire held his bat aloft in his right hand and pointed to
the heavens as he trotted down the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   The hardball gods must be crazy. These home run numbers
represent wild new territory. It is as if scientists had discovered
two additional planets in our solar system. All this time, we
thought 61 was the home run limit. Maybe 62. Suddenly, the number
70 doesn't sound impossible. And yet the Great Home Run Chase is
still not over.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his two-homer lead, McGwire said, ``Obviously, it
feels nice. But I got one more game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since this is the wacky, unbelievable summer of '98,
Sosa might have two more games. The Cubs are in a three-way
scramble for the final National League wild-card slot and Sammy
might get to slam in a 163d game if there's a tie among the Cubs,
Giants, and Mets. And forget the asterisk. A playoff game would
count for the Cubs slugger. So even though he holds a two-homer
lead, McGwire remains very much threatened by the Sosa challenge.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire claimed he hadn't thought about the prospect of Sosa
playing an extra game. ``That's the first I've heard of it,'' said
Big Mac. ``Would it count?'' Assured that it would, he responded,
``Well, there's absolutely nothing I can do about it. I'll be home
on the beach. So sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire fell behind by one Friday night when Sosa cranked No.
66, but that lead lasted only 45 minutes, until the St. Louis
slugger came to bat in the fifth inning against Shayne Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the second time that McGwire trailed in the Home
Run Derby. On Aug. 19, Sosa hit No. 48 at Wrigley Field while
McGwire was stalled at 47. Precisely 58 minutes later, McGwire went
deep in the eighth inning of his game, then hit No. 49 in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   They were tied at 55 after 138 games, and again at 62, 63, 65,
and 66. But today they are tied no more because of McGwire's
Saturday Afternoon Double Feature.
</P>
<P>
   Game 161 was just another day in paradise for the
baseball-crazed citizens of this town. At 9:30 a.m., the 910-room
Adams Mark Hotel in downtown St. Louis had already sold all copies
of Saturday's St. Louis Post-Dispatch. At this moment, everything
is a souvenir. An hour before the gates opened, a sea of
red-shirted fans splashed up against the perimeter of Busch
Stadium. When the doors were unlocked, Big Mac Maniacs stormed into
the team store to snap up the last of the authentic $200 McGwire
jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   While Sosa was going homerless in Houston, McGwire took back the
lead with a first-pitch shot over the left-field wall in the
fourth. No. 67 was estimated to have traveled 403 feet. There was
no guess on travel time. Speeding bullets don't register on the
radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up a fastball,'' he said. ``It was a nice, easy
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The second bomb of the day exploded in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard sinker in. I just tried to drive it back at
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The magical ride ends Sunday for McGwire. He said he'll be on an
airplane bound for California by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to sit back and reflect on anything till
it's over. It doesn't matter who comes out on top. It's just
fantastic what we've done in the last two months. He and I are the
only ones who know what we've gone through. It hasn't been easy.
Believe me, it has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody understands how difficult it is. Once we
got to 62, everybody wanted more. Instead of cherishing what we
did, it was, `Oh, no, they went three or four games without a home
run. What's wrong with them?'''
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire and Sosa were rescuing baseball and racing past
Babe Ruth and Roger Maris, it's been fashionable to say that the
chase would probably go down to the last day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has. And that day is Sunday. McGwire is in St. Louis
against Montreal and Sosa is at the Astrodome, desperately trying
to put the Cubs into a division playoff game. Two worthy warriors
will go at it one more time to see who replaces Maris in the record
book.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet against McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' he said. ``But I've got enough left for one more
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 0218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
