<HEADLINE>
INJURIES, ILLNESS PLAGUE TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst required
intravenous fluids before USC's 30-10 loss to Florida State on
Saturday, after suffering severe flu-like symptoms prior to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get sick until I was here,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``I
couldn't really function.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst's illness was considered far more serious than the
case of food poisoning he experienced the night before USC's season
opener against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike came down with something,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``He was not 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst tried to downplay the effect the illness had on
his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's never an excuse for me. I should have played better,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Chad Morton re-injured his strained back while scoring
on a 7-yard run in the third quarter. A Florida State defender hit
Morton in the back with his helmet near the play's completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just really sore. It's just hard to move right now,''
Morton said. ``I felt like I did when I first got (hurt).''
</P>
<P>
   Few touches: Until tailback Frank Strong's 73-yard run in the
third quarter, only three USC running backs or wide receivers _
Morton, R. Jay Soward and Petros Papadakis _ had gotten the ball.
Strong's run was the first game in which the freshman showed why he
had been so impressive during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping that somebody was going to do something. They
brought it a little bit harder than we thought they would,'' Strong
said. ``I just had the faith that I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictable outcome: With the loss, USC dropped to 3-8-1 against
top 25 opponents since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Notable ref: The game's head referee was Jim Knight, who has
suffered seven heart attacks and had to be revived during last
year's Virginia-North Carolina game.
</P>
<P>
   Total player: USC linebacker Chris Claiborne continues to be one
of the nation's top players. He had 14 tackles, and single-handedly
stopped Travis Minor on a fourth-and-1 at the USC 4-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Career kick: USC kicker Adam Abrams made a career-best 49-yard
field goal in the first quarter. It was USC's longest field goal
since Quin Rodriguez made a 54-yarder in 1990. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
