<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6542 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-BOS &LR;      09-27 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA'S REAL RACE IS FOR WILD CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It has suddenly become all so clear for Sammy Sosa and
the Cubs. The slugger's home run race with Mark McGwire has been
placed on the back burner with the realization that with one more
victory Chicago can control its destiny as it fights for a
wild-card berth in the National League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa went 2 for 4 _ two singles _ in Saturday's 3-2 victory over
the Astros, and thus fell behind McGwire, who cracked home runs
Nos. 67 and No. 68 in St. Louis. But more important to Sosa, the
three-team race for the final postseason spot has come down to the
season's final day with the Cubs tied with the Dusty-come-lately
San Francisco Giants, who outlasted Colorado Saturday while the
Mets lost to Atlanta, dropping the New Yorkers one game back.
</P>
<P>
   So the Cubs are in OK position as they enter the final day of
the wild-card race, but Sosa needs yet another miracle day if he is
to win the home run crown. He may get an extra crack at it. Should
the Cubs and Giants both win Sunday, there would be a one-game
playoff Monday at Wrigley Field. A victory by either team this
afternoon eliminates the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right where we wanted to be,'' says Chicago's Gary
Gaetti. ``It would be nice to have it wrapped up. But it didn't
happen that way. This is what you play for. We're down to the final
day in a 162-game season. That's pretty interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's quest has so dominated the headlines that you almost
forget that the Cubs had put themselves in a must-win situation by
losing five of six prior to Saturday. The crowd of 51,950 at the
Astrodome gave Sosa his due Saturday and seemed to fully expect him
to hit No. 67. Instead, he singled twice and scored the go-ahead
run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home run chase is not on my mind,'' Sosa insisted
afterward. ``I'm more concerned about the wild card. I'm just happy
when I do my job every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow is going to be great. Anything can happen. Whatever
feelings there are have to be good feelings. It's not for sure that
every time I hit the ball, it's going to go out of the ballpark. As
for Mark, he's still ahead of me and tomorrow he'll probably hit
some more. I hope he finishes with 70.''
</P>
<P>
   Home run derby aside, the Cubs had their own business to take
care of Saturday. Chicago went ahead to stay with two runs in the
eighth. Sosa hit a one-out single and advanced on a single to right
by Mark Grace. The 40-year-old Gaetti, who had scored the tying run
in the seventh, then plated both runners with a double to center.
</P>
<P>
   As Gaetti sees it, Sosa has carried a big load for a long time,
and now it's time for other Cubs to step into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Sammy gave it his best shot at trying to hit a home
run,'' he said. ``He fell behind in the count each time, but he is
such a good hitter he was able to do what he had to do to get on
base. This is a good day. We kept pace and keep ourselves tied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
