<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SMASHED BY ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Whither the Davis Cup as far as the United States is
concerned? It's all in the hands of Julia Levering now that the
guys she inherited when she took over as president of the US Tennis
Association have crashed to the most abysmal American defeat in
nearly a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing touches were applied Saturday by the fine Italian
hands of Diego Nargiso and Andrea Gaudenzi in a frantic 3 1/2-hour
skirmish that was marked by US reprieves and even hope for a pardon
in the fifth set. But there was to be no stay of execution for the
last-chance pairing of novitiate Justin Gimelstob and erratic Todd
Martin, who were beaten, 6-4, 7-6 (7-3), 5-7, 2-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to settle the five-match semifinal series, 3-0,
and send the unlikely Italians into their seventh Cup final Dec.
4-6 at Milan against defending champion Sweden, a 3-0 victor over
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The ecstatic Gaudenzi, who ignited the US disaster by beating
Jan-Michael Gambill Friday, whooped, ``Maybe they'll believe in us
at home now. When we beat India and Zimbabwe at home, everybody
said, `So what? We beat nobody.' But now, to beat the US in the US,
we deserve some credit. Also, it's nice this is the first final
Italy will have at home.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to go back to 1975 to find such a home shocker for
the US: Back then, Mexico, spurred by Raul Ramirez, defeated a host
side led by Stan Smith and Roscoe Tanner, 3-2, at Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   So where does Levering come into this picture? The Stowe, Vt.,
woman took over in February as the first female president in the
USTA's 119 years, and now she must try to sell Pete Sampras, Andre
Agassi, and Michael Chang on the virtues of giving the US a lift
next year.
</P>
<P>
   With them in the lineup this weekend, it's improbable that the
Italians would have soared. But Sampras has avoided the Cup as
though it contained hemlock. And Agassi, who drove the year's two
wins over Russia and Belgium, is incensed that the USTA picked
Milwaukee rather than his hometown, Las Vegas, for the semi. He
remained at home, presiding over a fund-raiser benefitting his
charitable foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Selection of the 1999 captain will also be Levering's choice.
Though she has told a friend that she'll retain Tom Gullikson,
winner of one Cup (1995) in five years, there will be much lobbying
on behalf of John McEnroe, a hero on five Cup-winning teams, and
Brad Gilbert, Agassi's coach. Low key, and admired by his players,
Gullikson has been an ideal leader in this international
competition in which the captain is a US ambassador of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Bostonians connected with the US team's appearance at Longwood
Cricket Club next July 16-18 will be praying for Levering's success
in convincing the elite Americans to enlist. It's particularly
important for the US to put its best sneakered feet forward,
because that will be the 100th-year celebration of the Davis Cup,
which was launched at Longwood in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   OK, even though you've never heard of Nargiso or Gaudenzi,
they're big in Naples and Faenza, respectively. Particularly since
Gaudenzi came into the weekend with a gimpy right shoulder, loaded
with cortisone, and Nargiso is under a physician's care, recovering
from hypoglycemia.
</P>
<P>
   They ought to name a Neapolitan alley for Nargiso _ Viale
Nargiso? _ because he deceptively hit so many alleys with passing
shots that startled the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good idea,'' laughed Adriano Panatta, who fired Italy to its
lone Cup in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Nargiso, a slim 28-year-old lefthander who lives for Davis Cup
doubles _ this is his 11th campaign _ almost passed out of the
equation a month ago in collapsing at Bing-hampton, N.Y., playing a
minor tourney. ``I lost my balance, I was dizzy,'' he said. ``They
put me in the hospital for hypoglycemia. Had to correct an
electrolytes imbalance. I'm OK now.''
</P>
<P>
   Very much so. Despite a No. 107 ranking, Nargiso was a
well-balanced performer in the left court, returning cleverly,
moving briskly for poaches and interceptions at the net. ``Gaudenzi
and I are friends; we've played a lot of Cup matches together (now
5-1),'' he said. ``That helps us when things are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Cemented by togetherness experience, they cruised deep into the
third set, nothing looking tough for them for 2 1/2 hours. Martin
and 21-year-old Gimelstob, debuting as an entry, seemed out of it
as soon as Martin butchered the third game with a double fault and
a pair of ugly errors. ``It was no way to start,'' he said. ``I'm
afraid it set the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Gimelstob, who appears to have a Cup future with his fine
doubles instincts, stonewalled in serving out of two match points
to 5-5 in the third, their only distinction was as the loftiest
team ever to represent the US. Gimelstob is 6 feet 5 inches, Martin
6-6.
</P>
<P>
   But that resistance seemed to lift them higher, and the loud and
fervent gathering of 4,200 urged them along a seven-game run to 4-0
in the fourth. The Americans were clicking at last and responding
to the ``U-S-A!'' chants plus the horn-blowing of a woman _
Virginian Renee Rucker _ garbed as Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Gimelstob double-faulted twice to lose serve to 1-3
in the fifth _ ``it was egregious; I panicked'' _ they stormed back
to topple Nargiso. As Martin held to 3-3, the joint rocked and
rattled.
</P>
<P>
   The homeboys' final opportunity came in the next game as they
pushed Gaudenzi to deuce from 40-15, but the Italians countered to
seize 10 of the match's last 11 points. At deuce, Nargiso took
over: first, a poach; then an incredible backhand save of an angled
volley, flicking the ball down the line past an incredulous Martin,
of course into the alley.
</P>
<P>
   His wicked forehand took Gimelstob to the last break point.
There a Gaudenzi return skipped off the tape and beyond the
American for 5-3. Quickly Nargiso served it out and went on a roll
across the court, hugging Gaudenzi.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Gullikson lamented, ``I never dreamed we'd lose three
straight matches. But we were a team with great chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Test tubes aside, however, what he needs is great players. They
exist. Money, though generously dispensed in six figures already,
won't buy Sampras, Agassi, or Chang. It's up to Levering and her
powers of persuasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
