<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PADRES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLSON SAVES BEST FOR LAST, STOPS PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's been a season of second chances for Diamondbacks
pitcher Gregg Olson.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old right-hander came to spring training with
Arizona as a non-roster invitee, hoping to resurrect a career that
had all but disappeared from the baseball map since 1993, his fifth
season of 20 or more saves with the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been happy with 10 saves,'' Olson said of his
expectations for this season.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he made it three times that many by earning his
30th in the Diamondbacks' 3-2 victory over the San Diego Padres in
front of a sellout crowd of 48,196 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   After a 29-save effort in 1993, Olson had a total of 13 in the
four seasons that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Olson wasn't asking for anything major in 1998. He wasn't even
sure he would make the Diamondbacks, much less be the closer.
</P>
<P>
   He had an opportunity to notch No. 30 on Friday night, but
allowed the Padres to score a run in the ninth. He ended as the
victor, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two bad pitches, then I was fortunate to be able to come back
today,'' said Olson, who on Sept. 7 picked up the 200th save of his
career, joining eight others in that elite club.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter did not hesitate to run Olson back out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That situation, there's no other place in baseball like it,''
Showalter said. ``We have a lot of confidence in Oly.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson wasn't throwing well at the beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, you go out and do what you can do. Then things
started to come around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better throwing the ball now than I did then (with
Baltimore). I'm more under control. Before, I just threw as hard as
I could and gave the hitters a barrage of curveballs. Everybody
pretty much knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I go out and locate the fastball, try to get ahead early.
I'm more of a pitcher. I do more thinking, have more of a strategy.
And I don't show my best stuff until I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Saturday's ninth inning was going to follow a
similar path as Friday's.
</P>
<P>
   Olson gave up a one-out single to Wally Joyner. Then Mark
Sweeney, who delivered a pinch-hit single to tie the score in the
ninth on Friday, hit a line drive to right. The Diamondbacks' Karim
Garcia was there to snag it, however. He quickly fired the ball to
Travis Lee at first to double up pinch-runner James Mouton to end
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking double play, but not a line-drive bullet at the
right fielder,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bullet to right field by third baseman Matt Williams as
leadoff man in the sixth that provided what proved to be the margin
of victory. The Diamondbacks (65-96) assured themselves a better
record than the other expansion club, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
(63-98).
</P>
<P>
   Williams hit a 3-2 pitch from left-hander Sterling Hitchcock
over the fence in right field to give Arizona a 3-2 lead. Right
fielder Tony Gwynn, who gave the Padres their first run with a
first-inning homer off Amaury Telemaco, jumped and extended his
glove above the fence, but couldn't reach the drive.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 20th homer of the season for Williams, and 299th of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed Telemaco (7-10) had his best effort since Sept.
4, when he gave up a run on six hits in seven innings to beat
Houston. The only damaging hits were Gwynn's homer (his 16th of the
season) and an RBI single by Greg Vaughn (No. 117) in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I pitched well,'' said Telemaco. ``I came here to a new
team and I'm thankful they gave me a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco also made the most of his at-bat in the fifth inning,
when he hit an RBI double to left-center that made it 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco gave credit to infielder and fellow Dominican Tony
Batista for showing him the more wide-open stance that Batista has
used this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was swinging a little wild during batting practice,''
Batista said. ``I said that he couldn't do that in a game, that if
he wanted to be serious, he had to get down lower in his stance,
open up a little and be more ready. I guess it worked pretty
good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
