r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-CASSTEVEN     09-27 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
68 SPEAKS FOR ITSELF  
 HOME RUN RACE DEFIES DESCRIPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS - Going . . . going . . . gone!
</P>
<P>
   Okay, it's trite. Unoriginal. You could say that about any home
run.
</P>
<P>
   How about this then . . .
</P>
<P>
   `` When the white sphere met the bat with a Ruthian crack, all
eyes turned'' ``toward the heavens as if in prayer, a nation
spellbound, mesmerized by the'' ``meteoric flight of a baseball,
rising into the early-fall sky, four-ply gray'' ``wool yarn encased
in cowhide leather, soaring now, rising, becoming smaller'' ``as it
breaks its bond with Earth and continues on its rendezvous with''
``history''. ``''. ``''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Our editors would shoot me.
</P>
<P>
   So what ``do'' you say about Mark McGwire's 67th and 68th home
runs? How do you describe what he did Saturday on the next-to-last
day of this head-shaking, myth-making season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Toledo!'' announcer Jack Buck cried after No. 67, giving
Ohio a plug. ``I think that's going to do it!''
</P>
<P>
   When Big Mac smoked No. 68 and trotted down the first base line,
holding his bat aloft like a scepter, Buck spoke for all of us. ``I
never thought I would see anything like this in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Sammy Sosa, stuck at 66, catch him now?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. But if we have learned anything this magical
summer, it is not to underestimate Sosa or count his team out.
</P>
<P>
   For pure entertainment, perhaps the only thing that might match
McGwire vs. Sosa would be a Cubs-Red Sox World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us in the media are guilty to varying degrees of
overdramatizing The Great Home Run Race. Forgive us our press
passes.
</P>
<P>
   How can you not become emotionally involved? The joy McGwire and
Sammy Sosa have provided runs through baseball like an electrical
current. To be here, to see Big Mac turn on the ball and crush it
435 feet into the center-field seats for his second home run of the
afternoon was a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how they love him here. You should have heard the cheers.
Anyone who doesn't feel ``something'' needs to check for a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has become part of our national consciousness. The
government should put his face on a $68 bill.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have we watched the replays of the Cardinals
slugger uncoiling on a fastball, hello/goodbye, and then dropping
his bat, like a used napkin? Our eyes follow him, step for step _
striding to first, then second, not the mincing steps of Babe Ruth
on the old herky-jerky newsreels.
</P>
<P>
   What would Ruth think of Big Mac?
</P>
<P>
   I like to think he would shake his hand. While reinventing the
long ball this summer, McGwire took time to pay tribute to Ruth and
Roger Maris, the man whose record he broke.
</P>
<P>
   He also tipped his cap to Sosa. All Sosa did this summer was
perform with quiet dignity and define relentlessness in his own
image. Down the stretch, he matched McGwire homer for homer,
heightening the drama and providing delicious suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball hasn't had a story this big since Hank Aaron hit No.
715 and broke Ruth's all-time home run mark. That night in 1974
sportswriters stared at their typewriters, searching for the right
words to do justice to the event.
</P>
<P>
   In the radio booth, Atlanta broadcaster Milo Hamilton felt the
pressure, too. What should he say? How should he describe history?
</P>
<P>
   When Ted Williams hit a home run in his last at-bat in the
majors, Curt Gowdy uttered a brace of repeated sentences. `'It's
got a chance! It's got a chance! And it's gone!''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Rizzuto, the Yankee broadcaster, had time to prepare for
Maris' 61st home run, but when the moment arrived he fell back on
his favorite line. ``Holy cow!'' Rizzuto cried. ``That's gonna be
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Author George Plimpton wrote a magazine piece about the night
Aaron hit No. 715. In it he described Hamilton's growing anxiety in
advance of the climactic homer. In the evenings, Milo would sit
alone and let his imagination take over, picturing Aaron's home run
ball as it sailed into the seats. The announcer's lips murmured.
Sentences formed. Milo hoped to prepare some utterance that would
be so perfect, so memorable, that his words might earn a place in
``Bartlett's Famous Quotations''.``''
</P>
<P>
   When history happened, spontaneity took over. In his excitement,
the announcer forgot his planned comparison between Ruth and Aaron.
``It's gone!'' Hamilton heard himself say. ``It's 715! There's a
new home-run champion of all time! And it's Henry Aaron!''
</P>
<P>
   So what do you say?
</P>
<P>
   How do you describe Mark McGwire's heroics? He has done
something no other human being has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``One small step for man . . .'' has a nice ring. ``Holy
Toledo!'' isn't bad, either. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or
david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
