r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-AZR &LR;      09-27 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIORITY ON PLAYOFFS  
 CUBS CHANCES ARE REAL, SOSA'S HRS SEC ONDARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's time to make official what all Chicago Cubs fans
feel deep in their hearts: The Cubs appear incapable of making
things easy.
</P>
<P>
   After another turbulent turn on an emotional roller coaster that
has taken tens of millions of fans for wild rides, the Cubs appear
on the verge of making just their third playoff appearance since
World War II, a span of 53 years.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, baseball's most lovable losers could not close
Saturday's deal without some form of anguish, even if just for a
few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what happened before the Cubs managed an
edge-of-your-seat, nail-biting 3-2 victory over Houston, which
turned into as wild a finish as the Cubs have seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   For once, though, the Cubs were on the receiving end of a break
when home plate umpire Eric Gregg ruled that Houston's Dave Clark
ran out of the baseline while trying to avoid pitcher Rod Beck's
tag in the bottom of the ninth inning for the final out of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Beck's throw to first base, which hit Clark in the back and
bounced away, did not matter. Brant Brown, who dropped what would
have been the final out of a victory Wednesday afternoon in
Milwaukee, only to see it turn into a three-run error that lost the
game, breathed a tremendous sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou's game-tying run did not count. Clark was out, and
the game was over. The Cubs sprinted off the field still tied for
the lead in the National League wild-card race, dead even with
surging San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like taking a free fall,'' Brown said after watching
the final out Saturday. ``You just didn't know what was next for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs next move is the regular season's last game this
afternoon here in the Astrodome. The possibility of the Cubs making
the playoffs is now real.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets, who had the lead for the NL's final playoff
spot in the middle of last week, are one game back of the Cubs and
the Giants with one day remaining in the regular-season schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Victories by San Francisco and Chicago would force a one-game
playoff Monday afternoon at Wrigley Field in Chicago. Just imagine
what that scene would be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Cubs town,'' first baseman Mark Grace said of Chicago.
``It's starving for a winner. I'm starving for a winner. All the
times you play with a sprained knee or take those long bus rides in
the minor leagues, this is what it's for.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Sammy Sosa's home run tango with Mark McGwire seems
secondary. The spotlight is entirely on the Cubs and their chances
of reaching the playoffs. Nothing else really matters now.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire zoomed past Sosa on Saturday, blasting his 67th and 68th
home runs and pulling two ahead of Sosa, who basically conceded the
race to McGwire after Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was thinking only of the possibility of playing in his
first playoff game. Little else mattered. Even his 132nd run scored
became a topic of conversation in the sardine-like post-game
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've scored so many runs this year, but none have mattered
more to me than (Saturday's),'' Sosa said. ``It was my favorite of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa scored ahead of Grace in the top of the eighth after Gary
Gaetti, picked up off waivers five weeks ago, ripped a two-out
double into the left-center field gap, breaking a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are on the verge of continuing their season. McGwire
and the St. Louis Cardinals know their season is over this
afternoon. Take a guess who is the most jealous between McGwire and
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who has not played in the postseason since 1992, would
gladly trade more than a couple of his home runs to swap spots with
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago will place its dreams in the left arm of veteran Terry
Mulholland, who has tangled with Cubs management for most of the
season but insists that will not be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned long ago you have to let external stuff go,''
Mulholland said. ``You have to crawl into a shell when you step out
there. Nothing else matters now, and there's nowhere else I'd
rather be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
