<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6551 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-TKACHUK-ANALYSIS-     09-27 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TKACHUK-ANALYSIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES,  TKACHUK FELT HEAT  
 PRESSURE OF HOLDOUT KEY TO RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The pressure finally got to them. In the end, they all
did the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody ever expected the Coyotes and superstar Keith Tkachuk
to kiss and make up this quickly. Tkachuk, the team's bruising
power forward, had a better chance of winning the NHL's Lady Byng
Award as the league's most gentlemanly player.
</P>
<P>
   How did both sides resolve their bitter differences seemingly
overnight, when Tkachuk agreed late Friday to a restructured deal
and a one-year contract extension worth a total of $16.7 million
through the 2000-2001 season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Bob Murray (Tkachuk's agent) the other day, `If this
thing keeps going the way it's been going, it'll be easy to find
the losers,' '' General Manager Bobby Smith said. ``But you're
definitely going to have a problem finding a winner in this
situation.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankfully, we found a win-win situation that works for both
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk and the Coyotes will attempt to put on a positive spin
of happy-happy, joy-joy and bury their acrimonious past. After
working out with the team on Monday, Tkachuk will appear with Smith
at a feel-good news conference and they both will go back to work,
probably swearing off commenting on the subject any further this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The truth to exactly how and why this dispute finally ended may
never be known.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a theory, of course.
</P>
<P>
   There were indications several weeks ago that Smith, the
Coyotes' third-year executive, was never willing to let Tkachuk sit
out the entire upcoming season, or even any part of it. He would
play hardball with Tkachuk, wait as long as he could while taking a
strong stance publicly, but eventually was prepared to give in to
Tkachuk's demands, within reason.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk didn't get the $40-plus million over five years he had
been seeking, but officially, his pay this season was bumped to
$4.1 million from $2.8 million, he will get $4.3 million the
following year (up from $3 million), and the extra year will net
him $8.3 million, a little less than the $10 million initially
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Smith) could be setting a bad precedent by doing what he
did,'' an NHL source said. ``Now players are going to think it's OK
to sit out _ even if they have a contract _ because teams are going
to start caving in.''
</P>
<P>
   They may not have exactly caved in, but the Coyotes felt like
they had no choice. They couldn't trade him because the teams that
could afford him didn't have enough to offer in return. And they
aren't strong enough to let him sit and collect dust while
struggling to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Tkachuk had more than enough reasons to settle for
less cash and take the best offer he could get.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, his teammates were starting to talk. When
training camp opened and Tkachuk was immediately suspended, most of
them all tried to say the ``right thing.'' You've heard it before:
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you always want to see a guy get as much money as
he can get. But it's not right for me to say anything. It's a
situation that's between Keith and the team. Hopefully, something
will get worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The more the questions kept coming, however, the more a few key
Coyotes players like Rick Tocchet and Jeremy Roenick felt
comfortable dropping the gloves, as they say. Both of them _ and
others _ said repeatedly that while Tkachuk had the right to do
what he thought best, they were quick to add if they were in his
shoes, they'd honor their contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree,'' Coyotes goalie Nikolai Khabibulin said. ``If you
sign a contract, you play by that contract. But that's just me.''
</P>
<P>
   A contract has never had the same hold on Tkachuk. He also
staged a holdout last season _ after just two years of his
five-year contract _ by reporting to camp but refusing to play in
any preseason games. He had contract squabbles in Winnipeg, too,
one that ultimately led to the Chicago Blackhawks signing him to
$17 million offer sheet, which the Jets matched. But by paying
Tkachuk $6 million in the first year of that deal, the team then
had to unload another star player, and a year later Teemu Selanne
was dealt to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this kid isn't careful, he'll play himself right out of the
National Hockey League,'' one NHL executive said recently. ``He's
not doing anything to help his reputation. Trust me, this stuff
follows you.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver Canucks Coach Mike Keenan said as much when asked
about Tkachuk's holdout last week after a preseason game in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's doing the smart thing,'' Keenan said.
``He's the captain of that team and he needs to set an example, in
my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The captaincy issue, many believe, also may have played a major
role in Tkachuk getting signed. Perhaps in no other sport does the
team captain carry so much weight. Tkachuk, who had his captaincy
stripped three years ago, needs the ``C'' to feel complete.
</P>
<P>
   Had he continued his holdout, it eventually would have been
taken away again. Only this time, he probably never would have
gotten it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't be the same player if it happened to him again,''
one Phoenix player said privately. ``I don't think he could handle
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure finally got to them. In the end, they all did the
right thing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 0315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
