<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RAMS-HOLCOMBE-AZR     09-27 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-HOLCOMBE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLCOMBE TO GET DEBUT VS. CARDS  
 MESA HIGH GRADUATE TAKES PLACE OF INJURED RAMS RUNNING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Rookie running back Robert Holcombe was in need of a
pep talk because the start of his NFL career had gone much
differently than he had planned.
</P>
<P>
   He was healthy and eager to play, but St. Louis Rams coaches
chose not to activate him in each of the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   Down and confused, Holcombe, a second-round draft pick from
Illinois, decided to talk to one of his former coaches at Mesa High
School, Kenny Wantland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him a week ago and he said, `Just keep your head
up,' '' Holcombe said. ``He also said, `I just have a feeling
you'll be out there starting against Arizona.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Holcombe thinks Wantland is ``psychic or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe not only will make his NFL debut Sunday against the
Cardinals at the TWA Dome, he will be the featured back.
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe will be in the lineup because starting running back
Greg Hill suffered a broken leg while getting 158 yards in last
week's victory at Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Greg went down, that's something you never want to see,''
Holcombe said. ``I think Greg is a great person, and we developed a
friendship since I've been here. But I do want to play. I want my
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe tried to be patient earlier, but he acknowledged that
it had been frustrating not dressing for games.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he had missed a game was his freshman year at
Illinois, when he suffered a broken hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' said Holcombe, who moved from Houston to
Arizona his junior year of high school to live with his aunt and
uncle. ``I didn't understand it. I don't think anyone else in my
position would understand it. It was a new experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Rams Coach Dick Vermeil didn't dress Hill or Holcombe in the
season-opening loss to New Orleans, a move for which he was heavily
criticized. Hill played the next week, but it made little sense why
Holcombe, who was No. 2 on the depth chart, wasn't used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that (Holcombe) was ready to be a pure
running back, not ready to be in the total complex of the game, in
third-down situations,'' Vermeil said. ``I've felt all along that
if our starter did get banged up that I would activate him and get
him going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm second-guessed tremendously by everybody. But when I tell
you I have confidence in him, I have confidence in him. If starting
him Sunday doesn't prove what I've been telling you all along, then
I'm an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe didn't find out he was starting until Wednesday morning
when running backs coach Wilbert Montgomery interrupted a film
session to make an announcement. He told Holcombe, ``By the way,
Robert, you're going to get a lot of reps in practice this week. As
a matter of fact, you're going to be starting. So I need your
undivided attention on everything we're doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe said he doesn't expect to be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's the NFL, but it's still football,'' he said.
``Once the whistle blows, it's you against them. You are out there
trying to execute assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals hope Holcombe doesn't play in his first victory in
nearly two years. He finished his career with the Illini losing 17
consecutive games, including all 11 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cardinals scouts loved Holcombe, who had 4,015 career
yards and 28 touchdowns at Illinois, and they nearly drafted him in
the second round. But they took defensive back Corey Chavous and
offensive tackle Anthony Clement ahead of him because they already
had traded for running back Adrian Murrell and signed free agent
Mario Bates.
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe will be reunited with Cardinals defensive end Simeon
Rice, his former Illini teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the greatest work ethic I've seen,'' Holcombe said of
Rice. ``He's one of the hardest-working athletes I've been around.
He was someone I tried to pattern after. I knew if I could work as
hard as he did, I'd go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe doesn't think it's fate that his first game is coming
against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one of those things,'' he said. ``Stuff like that
happens every now and then in life. But the best thing is my family
in Arizona will get to see me play (on TV). That's very good
news.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
