<HEADLINE>
WILL MOISES ALOU BE LEAVING AS TROS?  
 FATHER'S FUTURE MAY DETERMINE DESTINA TION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a subject that makes many Houston Astros fans very nervous.
Because
 &UR; Moises Alou was acquired in the middle of a multiyear deal, he
would be within his rights to request a trade after this season. If
the Astros do not comply, Alou could become a free agent on March
15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to talk after the season and see what happens,''
Alou said. ``I like it here, and I like it a lot. But we still have
(more to do) . . . a lot of things can happen between now and then.
Winning is going to make a lot of difference in what I do. If we
win it all, I'll beg to come back to Houston. If we don't, we'll
talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see where this team is going. To me, it looks
pretty good. We have a new stadium coming, and I'm sure they would
like to go to the new stadium with a good team. Winning and having
a good team is something I'd like to see if they want me to stay.
But I don't know if they're going to want me to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou is owed $15 million over the next three years, a bargain
considering the production he has brought to Houston. In any other
season, he would have a legitimate shot at MVP. The Astros
definitely want Alou roaming left field when they move into the
Ballpark at Union Station in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moises has been absolutely tremendous,'' Astros General
Manager  &UR; Gerry
 &UR; Hunsicker said. ``We hope he will continue to be a part of this
ballclub. But now is not the time to comment on that situation
because it's not an issue right now; certainly not on the eve of
the postseason. We're prepared to sit down after the postseason,
and if that situation presents itself, we'll address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for Houston to tear up the remaining years on Alou's
contract and give him a big raise, probably one that will pay him
around $8 million per season. Of course, if Alou's father  &UR; Felipe
Alou becomes the Dodgers' manager, all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my father, and you always want to be with family,'' Alou
said. ``That doesn't mean I want to go play for him next year. I've
always said I want to play for him again. Who doesn't want to be
with his family?'' &QL; 
Realizing a mistake &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The morning after San Diego's players openly criticized their
own organization for putting on an extravaganza, which definitely
went overboard, for  &UR; Sammy Sosa, Padres owner  &UR; John Moores
apologized to his players for the team's role in saluting Sosa, but
not to the club's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We screwed up,'' Moores said. ``It was inappropriate. It was
crazy. I didn't like the music or the fireworks. It's just as well
I didn't see (the flashing scoreboard). Anyone who criticizes the
fans for applauding Sosa misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the fans and am thrilled they came and enjoyed.
But the organization made a terrible mistake with our reaction.
Talk about a mixed message. We want to win. For the organization to
cheer a homer that beats us in this situation sends a terrible
signal.''
</P>
<P>
   The players were especially perturbed at the fireworks set off
by the club, as well as the salsa music played over the
loudspeakers and the Padres' cheerleaders dancing and blowing
kisses to Sosa, who had just hit an eighth-inning grand slam to
break a 2-2 tie. &QL; 
The nuclear fallout &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reality has to set in out in Orange County, where Anaheim's
latest September gag exposed the problems afflicting the Angels. At
the top of Anaheim's winter wish list is acquiring a big bopper who
can hit 40 or so home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The one name that jumps out is a certain catcher who made quite
a name for himself in Southern California.  &UR; Mike Piazza, a
potential free agent after this season, would certainly be a boon
for the Angels, who have long lived in the shadow of their Los
Angeles-area neighbor, the Dodgers.  &UR; Mo Vaughn also could be
available.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels would also love to add a front-line pitcher.  &UR; Kevin
Brown and
 &UR; Randy Johnson, who played college ball at nearby Southern
California, jump to mind. The big question is whether the folks who
also own the Disney empire will loosen the necessary funds.
</P>
<P>
   But acquiring a couple of big-name players is only half of the
Angels' winter plan. The club will apparently do some housecleaning
along the way.
 &UR; Randy Velarde, a fabulous clubhouse presence, does not appear to be
the same player he once was, his defensive skills having
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gregg Jefferies' option will not be picked up, and it appears
unlikely  &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Juden and  &UR; Trevor Wilson will be kept around. The biggest shock may
be the Angels making center fielder  &UR; Jim Edmonds available in a
trade. &QL; 
A different kind of streak &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The third-longest streaks for a player and a pitcher not
appearing in a post-season game will end this week when Cleveland's
 &UR; Travis Fryman and  &UR; Doug
 &UR; Jones each make their first playoff appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had made 718 career appearances through Friday without
being a part of the playoffs; Fryman, who spent his first six years
with Detroit, had played in 1,238 (through Friday) postseason-less
games.
</P>
<P>
   Among pitchers,  &UR; John Franco of the New York Mets, who has gone
829 appearances, and Toronto's  &UR; Dan Plesac (757) have endured
longer postseason droughts than Jones. Franco's could end if the
Mets emerge as the National League wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's  &UR; Dave Martinez is the current leader among position
players, having gone 1,525 games without appearing in the playoffs.
Sosa is next at 1,238. His streak also could end, depending on the
wild-card outcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A definite All-Star when it comes to being the bridegroom:
 &UR; Terry
 &UR; Collins has managed five seasons in the major leagues, three with
Houston and two with Anaheim. Collins' clubs have finished in
second place five times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; You want to talk home run king: Negro League great  &UR; Josh
 &UR; Gibson hit 75 home runs in 1931 and 69 in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; From the Now It Can Be Told Dept.: The Diamondbacks could have
selected  &UR; Rick Helling, who became a 20-game winner for Texas last
week, in the expansion draft. Instead, they took middle infielder
 &UR; Edwin Diaz from the Rangers with their sixth pick in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback (postseason edition): Francisco Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How the NL West was lost: After posting a 4-15 record in their
first 19 home games, the Colorado Rockies entered the weekend 37-23
at Coors Field since that dismal start.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How the AL West was lost: Texas played at Anaheim three times
this week and beat the September Swoon Artists, or Angels if you
prefer, by scores of 9-1, 9-1 and 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Attention baseball junkies: The full-page Baseball Insider will
disappear after this week until next spring. Not to fret; a smaller
edition will appear throughout the postseason and intermittenly
during the off-season. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sammy Sosa's 12 home runs against Milwaukee pitching fell just
two shy of the major league record shared by Cubs'  &UR; Hank Sauer
against Pittsburgh in 1954 and the Braves'  &UR; Joe Adcock against
Brooklyn in 1956. Sosa hit his 12 homers in 12 games. In Sauer and
Adcock's days, teams played 22 games against each other.
</P>
<P>
   With his seven strikeouts Saturday, Philadelphia's  &UR; Curt
 &UR; Schilling joined an elite fraternity that includes just four
pitchers who have struck out at least 300 batters in consecutive
seasons. The others:  &UR; Rube
 &UR; Waddell (1903-'04),  &UR; Sandy Koufax (1965-'66),  &UR; Nolan Ryan
(1972-'73-'74, '76-'77) and  &UR; J.R. Richard (1978-'79).
</P>
<P>
   The last time San Francisco had two players reach 100 RBIs in
consecutive seasons,  &UR; John Kennedy was in office.  &UR; Barry Bonds and
 &UR; Jeff Kent joined  &UR; Willie Mays and  &UR; Orlando Cepeda, who achieved
the feat in 1961-'62.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles'  &UR; Carlos Perez has pitched four consecutive complete
games, two of which were shutouts. The last Dodgers pitcher to
accomplish that was  &UR; Orel Hershiser, who pitched five straight
shutouts during his Cy Young Award season of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The high-octane Colorado Rockies offense went from having four
players with at least 30 home runs the past two seasons to just one
this year in  &UR; Vinny Castilla, who has a career-high 45.
</P>
<P>
   Just like all the players who will participate in the Arizona
Fall League, St. Louis outfielder  &UR; J.D. Drew, ``persona non grata''
anywhere near the Philadelphia city limits, will begin playing in
the Valley later this week. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All-Star third baseman  &UR; Robin Ventura appears to be tiring of
all the peripheral mess surrounding the Chicago White Sox, and the
free agent may decide to leave the south side this winter.
</P>
<P>
   It now seems that Cincinnati General Manager  &UR; Jim Bowden has
fallen behind the other two primary candidates to take over as
Baltimore's GM _ Cleveland assistant  &UR; Dan O'Dowd and Florida
assistant  &UR; Frank Wren.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis may be priming itself for one heck of a flurry of
activity this winter. The Cardinals, whose bank accounts swelled
because of
 &UR; Mark McGwire this summer, may be on the verge of going after
free-agent pitcher  &UR; Kevin Brown and trying to trade for shortstop
 &UR; Barry Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is letting it be known that  &UR; Paul Konerko can be had
in a trade. Konerko, who the Reds believe can only play first base,
will not get that opportunity with Cincinnati because of the
presence of  &UR; Sean
 &UR; Casey.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, the Rockies fire Manager  &UR; Don Baylor, look for
them to try to lure  &UR; Jim Leyland to Denver. Also, do not discount
 &UR; Art Howe as a replacement for Baylor. Howe and Rockies owner
 &UR; Jerry McMorris have an excellent relationship. Howe's Oakland
contract is up after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia outfielder  &UR; Ruben Amaro Jr. announced last week he
will retire as a player and join the Phillies' front office as a
special assistant to GM  &UR; Ed Wade. The Stanford-educated Amaro, who
is fluent in Spanish and was the club's bat boy when it won its
only World Series in 1980, plans to hire his father and former
Phillies player, coach and scout,  &UR; Ruben
 &UR; Sr., in some capacity. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
