<HEADLINE>
SUNS' OFFICES QUIET; AINGE FRUSTRATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 and BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Normally, with a little more than a week before the
scheduled opening of training camp, Suns officials would be busier
than White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be an especially frenetic period for the
Suns, who have only three players under contract for next season.
</P>
<P>
   For two years the club's front office positioned its roster and
its available salary cap room for this summer, when about 190
players became free agents. The Suns were supposed to be retooling
in an effort to once again contend for an NBA title. With players
such as Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Vlade Divac available,
this off-season held a lot of promise for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, General Manager Bryan Colangelo is in Europe. Coach
Danny Ainge was on a Mormon-history tour last week in the Midwest.
The club's offices are quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little frustrating,'' Ainge said. ``I'd like to sit
down with the members of my staff to start planning what kind of
offense and defense we're going to run. But we don't know what our
roster is going to be like yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The three Suns under contract for next season are guard Jason
Kidd, forward Danny Manning _ who may be back from knee surgery
before the beginning of the year _ and Mark Bryant, who has one
year left on his deal, which became guaranteed when the Suns didn't
waive him before the NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The club has a dozen free agents of its own, some of whom it
will attempt to re-sign, including Rex Chapman and Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   And the Suns have to come to terms with their two rookies: Pat
Garrity, who was the 19th pick in the first round by Milwaukee,
then traded to Dallas, then to Phoenix; and Toby Bailey, the 45th
overall pick by the Los Angeles Lakers who also was traded to
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a lot of work to be done and not a lot of time to do
it if the lockout continues into October and threatens or cuts into
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs could have as little as 10 days to two weeks to sign
players when the lockout is lifted, especially if it goes into the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a problem for the Suns, who apparently have
interest in Pippen. The perennial All-Star small forward had back
surgery this summer, and there won't be much time to do homework on
him or evaluate his condition. During the lockout, clubs cannot
have contact with players or their agents. So all the Suns can do
is wait. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 0329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
