r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-FREE-AGEN     09-27 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-FREE-AGENTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKOUT'S END COULD MAKE MESS  
 TOP FREE AGENTS COULD BENEFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Settling the NBA labor dispute might be easier than
cleaning up the mess it leaves behind.
</P>
<P>
   About 190 NBA players are free agents. Another 60 or so were
drafted. Others, like developing players from the Continental
Basketball Association and Europe, also are looking for NBA jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the league's 29 teams have only a handful of their
own players under contract.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the league has said little about what contingency plan will
take effect if the league lockout of its players ultimately cuts
into the regular season, or even pushes up against the Nov. 3
start.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and general managers don't know what roster or
salary-cap rules will come out of the collective-bargaining
process, so they can't do much planning.
</P>
<P>
   How long will they have to put a team together? Will there be
abbreviated training camps? Any exhibition games? What is the point
of no return, after which regular-season games will be lost?
</P>
<P>
   Players don't know how long they'll have to make a decision
about where they will play, or which teams will have the most money
to offer. Agents don't know which teams will end up being the best
situation for their clients.
</P>
<P>
   And fans can just forget about their fantasy league draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us knows what the new system is going to be, so it's
all speculation,'' agent Marc Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   But league sources say there probably will be a short window
during which players may sign contracts. It could be as little as
10 days to two weeks, if that will mean saving regular-season
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, it's going to be a feeding frenzy,'' Suns
forward Danny Manning said. ``A lot of players are going to have to
make a decision before they explore all their options.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kleine, a former Suns center who is a free agent this summer
after spending last season with the NBA champion Chicago Bulls,
figures the top-echelon free agents _ players such as Scottie
Pippen of the Bulls, Vlade Divac of the Charlotte Hornets and Tom
Gugliotta of the Minnesota Timberwolves _ will get good offers and
sign quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The rest may not find the market so friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably going to be a lot of `Take it or leave it,'
'' Kleine said.
</P>
<P>
   Manning also worries that a lot of players will show up in less
than desirable condition because free agents won't want to risk
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to have something happen like it did to
Christian Laettner,'' Manning said. ``That's a terrible
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner played for Atlanta last season and was considered a top
free-agent prospect. But he suffered a serious Achilles' tendon
injury in a summer pickup game and now has little free-agent value.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to give some guys a little excuse not to do as much
work,'' Manning said. ``Not all players, but there will be some.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Dan Majerle agreed, and while he's known for his work
ethic, he admitted it's difficult to get motivated. Players are
locked out of league facilities, so they work out at home or in
health clubs. It's tougher to find competitive pickup games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Majerle said. ``Normally, we'd have everybody in
town at the (America West) arena playing every day. Now, you don't
know who is going to show up, or what time you're going to start.
It's like a zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleine figures that whatever the system is when the lockout
ends, some teams will have a good plan in place and others will
not. And the players generally have an idea about which
organizations will do it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better organizations will have a timetable and a plan,''
he said. ``They'll go to the first player they want, make an offer
and give them a timetable for a decision, maybe 48 hours. If they
don't have it, they'll go to the next guy on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   So who does that favor?
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that it will favor the top-level free agents,''
Fleisher said. ``Normally, teams would start with an offer, then
come back with another offer or maybe two later on. I think the top
free agents are going to get bids quickly and for a lot more money
because teams are going to be afraid they won't get the guy they're
after. They're going to come with their best offer right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second tier also should do well, because teams are
probably going to make offers to more than one player because they
don't know if they're going to get their top guy.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be somewhat like college recruiting in which top programs
identify three or four players at a position and make an offer. The
first player to make a commitment gets the scholarship. The idea is
to prevent getting shut out completely.
</P>
<P>
   And who gets hurt?
</P>
<P>
   Manning said it will be the players who didn't have a chance
during summer leagues that were canceled, or during a preseason, to
prove themselves and win a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solid veteran players will be signed,'' he said. ``The
stars will be signed. You've got Michael Jordan and that type of
player who has taken the league to a new level of popularity. But
you also have the Steve Kerrs, the Jud Buechlers and the Randy
Browns. Those are the guys who make the league go 'round.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 0330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
