<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6558 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-OREGONSTATE-A     09-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-OREGONSTATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LEADS CHARGE AGAINST UPSTART BEAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Was that a mild breeze snaking through Sun Devil
Stadium on Saturday night, or a collective sigh of relief by
Arizona State fans?
</P>
<P>
   Someone finally woke the sleeping giant. It probably won't be
the Sun Devils' sharpest effort of the season, but it was enough to
put away Oregon State, 24-3, in front of an announced crowd of
59,630.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the defense with the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud of this football team,'' ASU Coach Bruce
Snyder said. ``The defense took a lot of hits, criticism,
internally and externally.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense limited the Beavers to nine rushing yards and held
the Pac-10's top running back, Ken Simonton, to 33. ASU gave up the
fewest points since yielding three to UCLA in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the big picture looks more promising. Although the
opportunity for a national title disappeared weeks ago, the Sun
Devils at least appear competitive in the conference again.
</P>
<P>
   They'll know more in the next two weeks when they visit Southern
California and host Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much our schemes as it was our players'
efforts,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder took a different approach with his defense before and
during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Practices this week were shortened so the players would have
fresher legs. Indeed, the unit played much more aggressively.
Beavers quarterback Terrance Bryant was pressured much of the game
and sacked twice.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Sun Devils played with two linebackers _ Adam
Archuleta and Joe Cesta _ and five defensive backs much of the
game. It gave the group more speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they played aggressively up front,'' Beavers Coach
Mike Riley said. ``Give them credit for carrying out their game
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, ASU appeared more in sync, although at times it
still lacked the sharpness it displayed during the second half of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The receivers who were the subject of much preseason hype lived
up to their billing.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Tariq McDonald seemed to make every play that came his
way. He caught four passes for 63 yards and a touchdown. Senior
Kenny Mitchell proved that last week's 88-yard, one-touchdown
effort against North Texas was no fluke with three catches for 39
yards.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, J.R. Redmond kept Oregon State's defense off balance.
He finished with 23 carries for 83 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But get this. He wasn't even the leading rusher. Gerald Green,
who spelled Redmond because Davaren Hightower was sidelined because
of a knee sprain, gained 86 yards on 17 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Ryan Kealy completed 12 of 27 passes for 173 yards
and two touchdowns. Bryant was 29 of 50 for 198 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond put ASU ahead, 7-0, with 6:23 remaining in the first
quarter on a pitch he took 2 yards into the end zone. Four plays
earlier, he took a pass from Kealy and went 20 yards after putting
a move on the Beavers' Keith Heyward-Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State ate up almost five minutes on its next possession
but could only get a 29-yard field goal by Jose Cortez out of it.
J'Juan Cherry broke up a pass on third and 7 to force the kick.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald increased ASU's lead to 14-3 in the second quarter by
connecting with Kealy on a 17-yard pass play. Creig Spann put the
Sun Devils in scoring position with a 15-yard reception the play
before. Green carried five times for 27 yards during the drive.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Stephen Baker missed a 52-yard field goal, and Oregon
State's Cortez botched a 46-yard attempt late in the second
quarter. The Sun Devils went into the half with an 11-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers committed the most costly penalty of the game in the
third quarter with a roughing-the-kicker call on fourth and 34.
That set up an ASU drive that was capped by Baker's 45-yard field
goal with 3:56 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   It was an important possession because it ate up 6:48 minutes.
Snyder wanted to keep the ball out of the Beavers' hands as much as
possible. That drive did.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers had more mistakes in them. Roddy Tompkins fumbled a
punt 12:32 remaining in the fourth quarter, and ASU's Courtney
Palmore immediately jumped on it. On the next play, Kealy hit
Lenzie Jackson for a 19-yard scoring pass to give the Sun Devils a
24-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. The Sun Devils were not without flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ASU is still penalty prone. It committed 12 for 128 yards. The
Beavers had eight for 70.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond is revealing a propensity for fumbling, something that
hasn't bothered him until this season. He fumbled twice Saturday to
give him five for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ASU improves to 2-2 overall and 1-1 in the conference. Oregon
State, 2-2 and 0-2, will travel to Utah State on Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
