<HEADER>
A6559 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-YOUNG-QUARTERBACK     09-27 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-YOUNG-QUARTERBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL OF HARD KNOCKS  
 DEFENSES ATTACK YOUTHFUL QBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Playing quarterback in the NFL never was meant to be
a duck-and-cover exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was it meant to be an entry-level job for a 23-year-old
kid making enough to buy his own HMO, but there are 13 starting
quarterbacks this weekend who are in their first, second or third
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals start one, Jake Plummer, and they face one, Tony
Banks of the Rams, this morning at 10 (Arizona time) at the TWA
Dome in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Defenses are teeing off on them with blitzes, particularly zone
blitzes, where the risk of being burned by a big play is minimized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame them,'' said Cardinals left tackle Lomas
Brown, a seven-time Pro Bowler. ``Defenses in this league are going
to take advantage of every weakness. If you've got a young
quarterback in there, they're going to try to rattle him, bring as
many looks as they can. It's a league of attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' offense, with Plummer at quarterback, was booed
coming off the field at Sun Devil Stadium last week. That was
before Plummer and the offense scored on their final three drives _
17 unanswered points _ and ran nearly five minutes off the clock to
preserve a victory over Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to judge a quarterback early in his career because
the guys around him also have to be up to speed,'' said Cardinals
backup quarterback Dave Brown, who was a starter for the New York
Giants for 4{ seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake is under a lot of pressure. He's got to be team captain,
he's kind of a national hero here in Arizona, and he's also got to
play quarterback. He's done a good job handling that. Now it's a
matter of the collective team playing better to help him out,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The season reaches the quarter mark today. Plummer acknowledges
that the sum of the offense is not the equal of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time it's just me not responding and being the
athlete that I am and making the plays,'' Plummer said. ``I'm not
pressing. I'm trying to take what people are giving me and allowing
the athletes around me to make plays. But we have definitely not
utilized the talent that is there.'' &QL; 
Rookies struggle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's critics should note that neither Peyton Manning, the
first pick in the draft who is starting for Indianapolis, nor Ryan
Leaf, the second overall pick who starts for San Diego, has sent
defensive coordinators back to the film room to devise new schemes.
Last week, Leaf went 1 for 15 at Kansas City. The Colts, with top
pick Manning at the throttle, are winless.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Lions rookie quarterback Charlie Batch has looked dazed
and confused since being promoted. Bobby Hoying, Philadelphia's
third-year quarterback in his first as a starter, was sacked nine
times by Seattle and knocked out of the game last week by blitzing
Cardinals linebacker Ron McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a learning curve for everybody,'' said Marc Trestman,
the Cardinals new offensive coordinator. ``We've simplified things
to a degree in our nickel and third-down packages to help Jake. For
a young quarterback, that's the most difficult place to be, in a
nickel situation. And we've had a lot of third-and-longs.''
</P>
<P>
   It'snot just a young man's problem. There are older
quarterbacks, playing behind more experienced lines, who have been
devoured by sack-craving defensive wolves. Proven veterans such as
Seattle's Warren Moon, 41, Denver's John Elway, 38, Miami's Dan
Marino, 37, San Francisco's Steve Young, 36, and Minnesota's
Randall Cunningham, 34, have seen it all. Even they are not immune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defenses are bringing more than offenses can handle,''
Trestman said. ``Because of the zone blitz, where they're playing
zone behind it, they're not giving up the big play. They're
bringing the extra guy and they're getting free shots. The blitzing
situation is very unique in the NFL right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Leafs and the Mannings are taking shots, and I'm sure the
league is going to look at it. Teams have made huge investments in
some of these young quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Cardinals are on the right track. He was
encouraged by Adrian Murrell's 101 rushing yards in the fourth
quarter of the win over Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest key to beating the zone blitz is running the
ball,'' Brown said. ``Defensive linemen are kind of light in their
stance because they're dropping out into coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we used to play against (former Cardinals and
Philadelphia Eagles Coach) Buddy Ryan, we knew we were going to get
hit a lot, but we also knew if we hung in long enough, we were
going to get a big play off his man-to-man blitzes. With the zone
blitz, you've got to be more patient. You've got to nickel-and-dime
it. If you can fire out and run the ball like Denver does, you're
going to control the blitzes a lot better.'' &QL; 
Making adjustments &QL; 
Defensive coordinators aren't the only copycats. Offensives are
beginning to emulate the manner in which the Broncos deal with the
zone blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what Denver is doing, not only running the ball but by
spreading teams out with five wide receivers and putting Elway back
in the shotgun, is taking teams out of what they want to do
blitzing-wise,'' Brown said. ``Teams that stay bunched up are
really susceptible to the zone blitz because defenses are going to
drop guys to those certain areas, and they can make it to those
areas by the time the zone blitz hits the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   But the one thing the copycats won't have is Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we watched film of Denver and Green Bay, teams with guys
who've been around eight, 10, 12 years, it's awesome because it's
almost automatic to them,'' said third-year Cardinals center Aaron
Graham, who is in his first season as full-time starter. ``The
quicker we can get to that point, the better we're going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around the league at the young quarterbacks, and it's
not like Jake is the only guy who ever messed up. Bobby Hoying,
Ryan Leaf, Peyton Manning _ they're all going through the exact
same stuff. With young quarterbacks, it's a race right now to see
who will be the first to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same with offensive linemen, and we have a young
line. We're having to make the same reads Jake makes. When we've
had a few sack problems, we're not physically getting beat. It's
mental. The defenses are bringing so many people and we have a
split second to adjust and react. The way for a young offense to
get better is through experience, and I'd be surprised if we're all
not doing things a whole lot better by the middle of the season.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
