<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE-TUNED SUN DEVILS MIGHT BE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - This was a solid coaching job. A week when Bruce
Snyder earned his money. A game that tempts you to give the man a
raise.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a meaningless coincidence, a quirky phenomenon. But in
the same week that a $45,000 bump in salary clears its last
bureaucratic hurdle, Snyder turned in his best coaching performance
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The kind you expect for nearly $600,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the surface of a 24-3 victory over Oregon State were two
key maneuvers. For starters, Snyder wisely turned down the volume
in practice, refreshing his sunburned squad. On Saturday, they were
aggressive, fleet and mean, clearly a fresher bunch. And he made a
key tactical adjustment that paved the way for surprising defensive
domination.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck with an underachieving linebacker corps that had a hard
time making basic tackles, Snyder switched to three cornerbacks and
two safeties. He took one linebacker off the field. On occasion, he
even threw a dime package at the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a faster football team. A speed-oriented defense
that completely shut down Oregon State's rushing attack. A defense
that completely compensated for a lackluster offense, and where
have we seen that before?
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Snyder has a certain Zen-like quality. A certain
eloquence and charm that must work wonders in the living room of
prize recruits. And there's no arguing the turnabout he's
orchestrated in Tempe or the foundation he's laid in leading ASU to
the upper echelon of college football.
</P>
<P>
   But his past six games have been a mix of good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   His players claimed they weren't prepared in last year's
season-ending loss to Arizona. Then came a masterful dismantling of
Iowa in the Sun Bowl, a performance that Athletic Director Kevin
White called one of the best coaching performances he's ever
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Forward to 1998, a season that opened with a poorly coached
debacle against Washington, another game where players blamed a
lack of preparation. Then came the spanking at BYU, followed by an
uninspired victory over North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for fans and media to get sucked in by the sirens
of optimism. It's another thing for a coaching staff to misread its
own talent level and lack of leadership. You expect a little more
from an architect of Snyder's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But to his credit, Snyder accepted part of the blame. It seems
he has finally found the pulse of this team, and on Saturday, both
he and the Devils produced their finest efforts of the season. And,
if the offense ever becomes a consistent force, they might be
giants, after all.
</P>
<P>
   What's disconcerting about this group is the complete lack of
rhythm on offense. One series, they gobble up yardage. The next,
they can't move the chains. One series, Ryan Kealy looks like Jake
Plummer. The next, he looks like Jake the plumber. One series, J.R.
Redmond can't be stopped. The next, he can't stop dropping the
football.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Redmond has fumbled in four consecutive games. Kealy's
radar goes in and out with alarming frequency. The yellow flags
continue to fly. And for all their fearsome weapons, this is not a
riveting, highly-entertaining attack. Boring, you might say.
</P>
<P>
   Which would explain why their second consecutive home game
produced another disappointing crowd, but that will change.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lock that no apathy will surround their next home game.
Notre Dame will pay a visit, and no matter how you feel about the
Irish, it was a stroke of good fortune that they rallied to beat
Purdue on Saturday. Bottom line is, the Sun Devils need as many
quality-of-schedule points as they can get.
</P>
<P>
   They also need a big victory. And before Notre Dame, there's a
crucial game at USC. If the Sun Devils can beat the Trojans in the
Coliseum, they will climb back into the polls, back into national
consciousness, back into the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, a half-effort won't get it done. And by now, a
quality team with a top-20 coach should be able to get it right. On
both sides of the ball. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
