<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE STILL SINGING OFF-KEY, JACK SON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Receiver  &UR; Lenzie Jackson saw progress from
Arizona State's offense Saturday night, but that doesn't mean he
was satisfied with the Sun Devils' performance in a 24-3 victory
over Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ASU lacked an offensive rhythm for much of the game, and the
passing game doesn't appear nearly as good as it was in the season
opener against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Ryan Kealy, who was not available for comment after
the game, completed only 12 of 27 passes for 173 yards. He passed
for two touchdowns and was intercepted once. In the third quarter,
he was 0 for 4 with an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually hit those passes in practice,'' Jackson said. ``I
don't think anybody on offense is completely happy with where we
are.'' &QL; 
Cherry bomb &QL; 
Cornerback  &UR; J'Juan Cherry left a trail of yellow flags behind him
in the first half Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry was penalized four times, twice for pass interference,
once for holding and once for grabbing an Oregon State player's
face mask.
</P>
<P>
   The four penalties cost ASU 47 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry, a junior, was a backup last season. He earned a
reputation then for his aggressive play, but he also crossed the
line occasionally and was called for several penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry's performance Saturday wasn't all bad, however. He was
instrumental in stopping the Beavers from scoring a touchdown late
in the first quarter. On third and 7 at the ASU 12, Cherry batted
down a pass to  &UR; Tim Alexander that, if completed, would have given
the Beavers a first and goal.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry wasn't alone in his penchant for being penalized. The Sun
Devils were penalized 12 times for 128 yards. One of those included
a late hit by safety
 &UR; Mitchell Freedman, who belted Oregon State quarterback  &UR; Terrance
Bryant after he had run out of bounds. Those types of mistakes are
becoming commonplace for Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping the ball &QL; 
ASU running back  &UR; J.R. Redmond fumbled twice Saturday, continuing a
troubling trend for the junior. In four games, Redmond has fumbled
five times.
</P>
<P>
   One of his fumbles Saturday proved costly. In the second
quarter, ASU had a third and 2 at the Oregon State 11 when Redmond
fumbled as he was tackled just short of the first down. The Beavers
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Quick kicks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting sophomore defensive end  &UR; Quincy  &UR; Yancy suffered a mild
concussion in the first half and did not return. His prognosis is
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Levi Jones, a redshirt freshman, replaced Yancy.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver  &UR; Tariq McDonald, a sophomore, caught four passes, a
career high _  &UR; Gerald Green, who backed up Redmond, rushed 17 times
for 86 yards, career highs in both categories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 0338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
