<HEADER>
A6562 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-DEFENSE-AZR &LR;      09-27 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE WAKES UP, PAVES WAY FOR DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Yes, it was Oregon State, but not your older
brother's Oregon State, not the Pac-10 doormat. The Beavers have
become competitive, and their 2-1 record equaled the program's
average number of victories in the 1990s. Now they are merely a
throw rug.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Arizona State's defense was in no position to judge
anyone but itself, and it had been a harsh judgment. Going into
Saturday's game at Sun Devil Stadium, ASU was ninth in scoring
defense and eighth in total defense in the conference. Each of its
three previous opponents, Washington, Brigham Young and even North
Texas, produced many points and/or yards at the Sun Devils'
expense.
</P>
<P>
   So it was of some note if not a sign of progress that on a night
the Sun Devils' best plays on offense came on punts (roughing the
kicker on fourth and 34, and a muff), the defense made the
difference in the 24-3 ASU victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to,'' said linebacker Adam Archuleta, who was in on 11
tackles, recovered a fumble and had a sack. ``We hadn't stopped
anyone yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils put in a slight wrinkle, using two linebackers
and five defensive backs. They swarmed, stuffed and punished a
Beavers offense that is not Nebraska, but not Kansas State's weekly
selection from the pastry cart, either.
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers thrived. Archuleta and Joe Cesta had solid
games, their best of the season, with strong support from the front
four and secondary. Cornerback J'Juan Cherry had seven unassisted
tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Archuleta, a 6-foot, 202-pound junior from Chandler High School,
had the type of performance he was waiting for after laboring in
the shadow of Pat Tillman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest thing has been confidence,'' he said. ``Following
Pat, everyone was saying, `This guy's too small,' or `He has big
shoes to fill.' I was looking for a confidence booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I had the ability. I knew I could play. But it's
hard when you haven't played in this league. I know I'll get
better. But I can't play like a normal, rock 'em, sock 'em
linebacker. Everyone looks at me and and thinks, `Who's this skinny
kid playing linebacker?' Everyone wants Andy Katzenmoyer, not a
little guy like me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers' Ken Simonton probably wants no part of Archuleta,
or the rest of the Sun Devils. A fireplug of a redshirt freshman at
5 feet 8, 181 pounds, he came in as the only Pac-10 running back
averaging more than 100 yards a game on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the missing linebacker and four 300-pounders on
his offensive line, Simonton in the first half ran eight times for
five yards, a crisp 0.6 yards per carry. The Beavers didn't get a
first down rushing until the final minute of the third quarter, a
quarter in which Simonton's average rocketed to 1.5. He finished
with 33 yards.
</P>
<P>
   After it became clear Simonton was going nowhere, Oregon State
Coach Mike Riley placed the game in the hands of his left-handed
quarterback, Terrance Bryant. A junior college transfer, Bryant has
a strong arm, which he often shows off by overthrowing receivers.
He completed an ineffectual 29 of 50 passes for 198 yards, dogged
by the Sun Devils' most forceful line surge of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was telling us we have so much talent on defense,''
said end Erik Flowers, a transfer from Trinity Valley Community
College in Texas, who got his first sack. ``Now it's time to use
it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
