<HEADER>
A6563 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NAU-WESTERNSTATE-     09-27 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NAU-WESTERNSTATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORAN, COOPER HELP NAU COAST TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - Who were these guys and why were they here?
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona came up with the perfect homecoming opponent
Saturday, and the Lumberjacks toyed with Western State en route to
a 28-9 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The win before an announced crowd of 11,616 over the Division II
school from Gunnison, Colo., with 2,500 students didn't prove a
whole lot, but it gave NAU the opportunity to do a little
experimenting and tinkering, mixing and matching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of the other school doesn't matter,'' said NAU safety
Raymond Perryman, who got in some huge hits. ``We regard all teams
highly. We won't step down our tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jerome Souers was able to pick up a few insights along the
way that might prove beneficial when NAU (3-1) returns to Big Sky
play next week. He learned, for example, that versatile David
Moran, a safety who wanted to be a receiver, makes a pretty good
quarterback, and that running back Tavon Cooper is back to full
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Moran played quarterback the entire second half, subbing for
Clay Brown, who suffered a bruised knee. Clay Brown became the
starter two weeks ago when Travis Brown was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Moran has been taking snaps for only 2{ weeks, and his numbers
weren't spectacular. But he threw a touchdown pass and ran for
another, and he made some significant plays at opportune times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what's going to happen next week,'' said Moran, a
transfer from Oregon State who played high school football for
Prescott Valley Bradshaw Mountain. ``I knew I'd be playing a half
tonight. But I love defense, and I like to hit and run up and down
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest contribution came on a fourth and 3 from the Western
State 35. He ran a keeper, got two blocks, and ran for 24 yards,
setting up his own touchdown a bit later, also on fourth down. That
upped the Lumberjacks' lead to 21-3, and they coasted from there.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper got his first full-time action after a shoulder injury,
and the former Peoria High School star ran for 107 yards on 22
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's joy at being able to run without worrying about the
shoulder injury that he suffered in the season opener was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is great to be healthy,'' he said. ``Being as competitive
as I am, just sitting on the bench is really hard. I had to go. The
feeling is just awesome. Our line did a great job, and I think this
kind of a game will help us after losing last week.''
</P>
<P>
   NAU scored its first two touchdowns on short runs by Kevin
Shelton and led, 14-0, at the break. They built up a 28-3 margin
before Western closed out the game with a pair of field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountaineers (1-2) managed 225 total yards to NAU's 341. The
NAU defense recorded five sacks, giving it 21 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Souers said the Lumberjacks achieved their goal of better
offensive execution. The opponent, whom he credited with playing
hard throughout the game, came at the right spot in the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was good for us for a lot of reasons,'' Souers said.
``We were missing people, so we had to play a lot of new guys, so
this can really help us play better later. Our guys did a lot of
good things that we are excited about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to elevate our play . . . and the better we get, the
more fun we will be to watch.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
