<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Oct. 4.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Spirit Catches You and You Fall Down: A Hmong Child, Her
American Doctors, and the Collision of Two Cultures &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Fadiman. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13.
</P>
<P>
   An immigrant child's harrowing medical crisis ignites a series
of mutual misunderstandings between decent, well-meaning physicians
in Merced, Calif., and a loving family barely removed from their
tribal roots in Laos. ``This fine book recounts a poignant
tragedy,'' Melvin Konner said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost Man's River &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Matthiessen. Vintage International, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The author's second novel in a proposed trilogy about the
Everglades is narrated by Lucius Watson, a self-doubting loner who
embarks late in life on a quest to uncover the complicated truth
about his murdered father -- and himself. His research turns up all
sorts of dim facts and slippery memories that gradually reveal a
vast web of kinship involving families whose fortunes and
misfortunes are mirrored in the history of the state. In 1997 our
reviewer, Janet Burroway, called this ``a project of enormous
ambition'' and praised the author's ``perfect ear for the cadences
of Southern speech.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bright College Years: Inside the American Campus Today &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Matthews. University of Chicago, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the author witnessed the full-scale canon wars being
fought at the convention of the Modern Language Association; five
years later, she returned to find the wars over and the academics
for the most part happily defanged. ``Matthews is a good
storyteller and reading this book is marvelously soothing,''
Larissa MacFarquhar wrote in these pages last year. A far gloomier
critique of contemporary university life is found in  &UR; Tenured
Radicals: How Politics Has Corrupted Our Higher Education &LR; , by
Roger Kimball (Elephant/Ivan R. Dee, $12.95), a 1990 call to arms
that has been revised and includes a new introduction. In building
his case that the student protesters of the 1960s have become
today's professors of women's studies, homosexual studies and other
newfangled studies, Kimball ``has dished it out beautifully,''
Roger Rosenblatt said here eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pandaemonium &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Leslie Epstein. St. Martin's Griffin, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   This Hollywood novel set during World War II is populated by
dreamy European exiles caught between the Old World and the New,
between heaven and hell. Its narrator is a fictionalized Peter
Lorre, once a Viennese esthete but now a B-movie actor living on
drugs and possibilities. In 1997 in these pages, David Freeman
admired the ``exuberant mixture of high art and low comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Troublesome Offspring of Cardinal Guzman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Louis de Bernires. Vintage International, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In an imaginary South American city, a demon-plagued cardinal
tries to save souls by persuading people to get religion and then
killing them before they have a chance to change their minds. In
1994 in the Book Review, James Polk called this a ``wondrous
novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Gay Metropolis: 1940-1996 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Kaiser. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In chronicling the progress of homosexuals in overcoming
prejudice and gaining acceptance, a journalist focuses on New York
City, the main postwar destination for gay people seeking a life
without shame. Last year our reviewer, Phillip Lopate, called this
``a generously stocked'' social history with ``fascinating, curious
side trips.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Chin Kiss King &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ana Veciana-Suarez. Plume, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   This first novel revolves around a young Cuban-American woman
who turns to her mother and grandmother for support after giving
birth to a handicapped infant. ``Veciana-Suarez's quirky approach
is a great success,'' Jim Gladstone said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Taking Charge: The Johnson White House Tapes, 1963-1964 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited and with commentary by Michael R. Beschloss.
Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16.
</P>
<P>
   The Lyndon B. Johnson who emerges from this selection of
conversations taped during his first nine months in the Oval Office
is a master of flattery, manipulation and insincerity -- a volcanic
presence capable of both large vision and great pettiness. The book
is ``superbly edited and annotated,'' Alan Brinkley wrote in the
Book Review last year.  &UR; Mutual Contempt: Lyndon Johnson, Robert
Kennedy, and the Feud That Defined a Decade &LR; , by Jeff Shesol
(Norton, $17.95), focuses on the longstanding bad blood between two
feisty figures who sought to control the Democratic Party during a
crucial period. In 1997 our reviewer, David M. Oshinsky, called
this ``a penetrating and richly detailed account.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Girls in the Grass: Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Melanie Rae Thon. Owl/Holt, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 tales in this collection revolve around themes of
despair, guilt, pain and desire, typically expressed in the
yearnings of adolescents. ``The reader is swept along not only by
Thon's remarkable characterizations but also by the taut, magic
current of her prose,'' Constance Decker Thompson wrote here in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Secret Book of Grazia dei Rossi &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jacqueline Park. Scribner, $13.
</P>
<P>
   This first novel unfolds in the diary of a daughter of a wealthy
Jewish family in Renaissance Italy who discusses everything from
medicine to mysticism in an age of political corruption and
religious intolerance. ``Park has fashioned a dense, sweeping
narrative,'' Lauren Belfer said here last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
