</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-WHEAT-WOES (Kahlotus, Wash.) _ In a normal year, 90
percent of the wheat crop here in the Pacific Northwest is exported
to Asian markets; but this is not a normal year. Hammered by a
sharp fall-off in demand because of Asia's economic crisis, the
region's farmers are faced with one of their biggest stockpiles
ever _ 340 million bushels, enough to fill a line of rail cars from
Seattle to Chicago. The price of wheat has dropped to a 21-year
low. A look at how the Asian economic crisis is affecting the
Northwest's economy. By Sam Howe Verhovek
</P>
<P>
   RENO-HOSPITAL (Washington) _ Attorney General Reno is
hospitalized after fainting in church.
</P>
