<HEADER>
A6706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-EUROPE-475&AMP;AD     09-27 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-EUROPE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS HAIL KOHL'S HISTORICAL ROLE, EXPRESS CONFIDENCE IN
SCHROEDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GERMANY-VOTE, GERMANY-REACT, GERMANY-KOHL.) 
(lh) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ European leaders marked the end of an era Sunday,
congratulating both Gerhard Schroeder and Helmut Kohl, the man he
defeated after 16 years as chancellor in Germany's elections.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France, a conservative like Kohl,
and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, whose fellow Socialists saw in
the victory of Schroeder's Social Democrats a continuation of a
European trend that brought them and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair's Labor Party to power last year, paid tribute to both in
almost equal measure.
</P>
<P>
   Both hailed Kohl's historic role in consolidating European unity
after German reunification in 1990, and expressed confidence that
Schroeder would carry on in the same tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, in Blackpool, England, for a Labor Party convention,
telephoned Schroeder to congratulate him and told reporters later,
``It's a tremendous thing that we will now see center-left
government in Britain, France and Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay tribute to Helmut Kohl for all of the things he has done
for Europe,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Shimon Peres of Israel, whose Labor
government was turned out by voters there in 1996, said of Kohl,
``He did an outstanding job uniting Europe and making Germany a
part of Europe instead of the previous attempt to make Europe a
part of Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy has its own rules, and it was apparently time to
change guards,'' Peres said. ``I want to express my deepest thanks
to Chancellor Kohl and congratulate Gerhard Schroeder as a friend,
a leader and a man upon whose shoulders rest great
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the conservative government of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Israel was confident of continued close
relations with Schroeder as chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   A turn by German voters to the left after a generation marked a
historic turning point that was not so much about ideology as about
German self-confidence and assertiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change has already taken place,'' French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine said the other day. ``It's a different Germany from
the one we knew from 1949 to 1989.''
</P>
<P>
   What he meant was that, more than half a century after the end
of World War II, Germans no longer feel the need to buy
respectability as partners in the building of Europe. They feel
they have earned it, by their performance as the economic
powerhouse of the continent, as good neighbors to all nine of the
countries on their borders, as allies with the United States and
Britain within NATO, and as supportive partners of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Never before in its history had Germany enjoyed good relations
with all these countries at once, Kohl kept telling voters during
his campaign, and Schroeder did not contest the achievement.
Germany, both men clearly agreed, could now pursue its legitimate
national interests within Europe freed of the complexes that
inhibited it in the past.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, Kohl's government surprised its European partners at a
summit meeting in Amsterdam, Netherlands, last year by announcing
that Germany was no longer willing to be taken for granted as the
rich uncle of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Even with only 15 members, Europe is strained to its financial
limits. But if Poland and Hungary were admitted tomorrow, the
common agricultural policy by which industrial Germany agreed to
support French farmers in exchange for access to the Common Market
in 1957 would bankrupt Europe as it currently operates.
</P>
<P>
   And Germany has made clear it will not go on paying unless the
rules are rewritten more equitably. ``The Germans are still good
Europeans, but they don't give anything away any more,'' Vedrine
said. ``We defend French interests with great energy, as the
British defend theirs, and the Germans are becoming more like us.''
</P>
<P>
   With only Italy among major European states now governed by
conservative parties, there were also those who saw the chance for
a new, coordinated European approach to the intractable problems of
unemployment and instability in global financial markets in
Schroeder's victory.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Schroeder's victory could ge seen as a victory for
European social democracy, Jack Lang, a French Socialist who
campaigned for him in Germany, agreed, adding, ``There's a great
chance to give new dynamism to a Europe that has been a bit in the
doldrums recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Austria's Social Democratic chancellor, Victor Klima, described
the German election result as a ``historic success'' for Social
Democrats but also ``a success for a Europe of employment, a
success for a Europe with more social justice and a success for a
Europe of social democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, expressed ``respect and thanks to a truly great
European, Helmut Kohl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
