<HEADER>
A6720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIES-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-27 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWO CITIES': STYLISTIC VIRTUOSITY; DISTORTED HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his previous novels and essays, John Edgar Wideman has
engaged in an extended exploration of that most American of
subjects: racial and personal identity hammered out inside the
menacing margins of urban life. What has also distinguished Wideman
as a voice in American letters is the vigor of his style. This is a
writer of an especially dense and musical quality whose prose is a
harmonic blending of high and low, of the music of the streets and
the music of the spheres.
</P>
<P>
   Wideman's new novel is ``Two Cities,'' a book that strikes many
of the same themes as his earlier work and is written with his
usual stylistic virtuosity. It tells the intertwining stories of
three vividly portrayed characters who grope toward a kind of
familial refuge from the surrounding darkness and degradation of
American life.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Two Cities'' is also an angry and intemperate book, so
focused on that darkness and degradation as to be demagogic in its
effect: exaggeratedly negative in its vision of American life and
therefore politically reductive as well. There is no doubting
Wideman's writerly craft or his remarkable ear for black American
cadences and jive. From those points of view, ``Two Cities'' is a
great pleasure. What is troubling is its use of a kind of distorted
history to substantiate a veritably cultish, mythic vision.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is told in the separate, intercutting voices of three
main characters who alternate with a more conventional narrator in
the telling of what is really a love story. The central figure is
Kassima, an attractive young woman who lives in protective retreat
following the deaths, in a single year, of her husband (of AIDS in
prison) and her two sons (in gang violence on Pittsburgh's
streets). One night, feeling restless and needy, she goes to a bar
where she is picked up by Robert Jones, a ``nice man'' of middle
age who has left behind an earlier family but grown wise with
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Kassima, as it turns out, lives in the neighborhood where Robert
grew up, possibly in the same house on Cassina Way in Pittsburgh.
For Robert, in other words, finding Kassima is a homecoming of
sorts, a chance to do things right. But one day, Robert almost gets
into a fight with the .357 Magnum-wielding satrap of a local
basketball court. Kassima is so terrorized by the prospect of
another loss that she abandons her nascent attachment and returns
to protective mourning. ``Won't never be my head on a tray you can
just take with you when you decide to go down,'' she tells Robert
on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Kassima has a boarder in her house named Mallory, an eccentric,
aging, unwell World War II veteran who travels around Pittsburgh
with a camera in a shopping bag recording the passing scene. He
emerges as a kind of chorus to the love affair of Kassima and
Robert, a common-man commentator on surrounding events, a
rememberer of the things past that brought matters to their current
bleak state. Mallory and Kassima become friends. When one day he
crawls into her bed and dies, leaving her his boxes of photographs
and negatives with instructions that she burn the lot of them, she
turns to Robert for help.
</P>
<P>
   That is the essential story, but Wideman weaves a tapestry of
American life tightly around it, telling stories reminiscent of the
Homewood trilogy, a set of earlier novels set in the neighborhood
in West Pittsburgh where Wideman grew up. Mallory also provides a
kind of atmosphere, an attitude about the surrounding society
through his experiences. There are encounters with gang members,
who are presented without apology as swaggering terrorists. Mallory
remembers being a soldier in World War II and being almost gunned
down in a racist attack by fellow soldiers after he and a buddy
went on a sensuous picnic with two Italian women.
</P>
<P>
   More important are Mallory's nostalgic memories of John Africa,
the leader of Move, the radical group whose members were killed by
the Philadelphia police in a well-publicized episode of official
brutality in 1985. John Africa, whose real name was Vincent
Leaphart, is seen by Mallory _ and, it would seem, by Wideman as
well _ as a kind of departed saint whose death at the hands of the
authorities was a kind of martyrdom. Wideman's evocation of John
Africa is razor sharp, but it is also where this novel takes on the
feel of propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   A first clash between the police and Move was in 1978, resulting
in the death of a policeman and murder convictions for the group's
members who were in the raided house. ``The way the Nazis killed a
hundred hostages for every German soldier the partisans ambushed,''
is Mallory's ill-conceived comparative thought on that incident.
Several years later, police actually firebombed the Move home on
Osage Avenue, killing all 11 people inside, including some
children. ``A span of years, a span of prisoners reaching backward
and forward,'' Mallory thinks, ``one arc of suffering and loss and
the world too small to hold the lamentations.''
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting that the John Africa presented here as a
near- saintly figure seemed in real life to have been something of
a madman, more a cult leader than a civil rights sage. He eschewed
medicine, bathing and electricity. Neighbors complained to the
police about garbage and rodents and the group's practice of
broadcasting anarchist harangues over loudspeakers at night. None
of this background is noted in ``Two Cities.'' The Move members
were also heavily armed.
</P>
<P>
   Wideman's book is, of course, a novel not a history, but it is a
novel that uses history to present his main characters' striving to
carve out a circle of sanity in a landscape of almost total moral
and spiritual debasement. In the final passages in the novel, the
characters are almost destroyed by full-scale gang warfare erupting
in the funeral home where Mallory's body rests.
</P>
<P>
   These final passages, like much else in ``Two Cities,'' are
lyrically rendered by Wideman but they are so lurid as to be
cartoonish in effect. They also represent the deeply demoralized of
American life that is at this novel's heart.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TWO CITIES'
</P>
<P>
   By John Edgar Wideman
</P>
<P>
   242 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
