<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAGAN-BIOGRAPHY-ART-     09-27 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-BIOGRAPHY-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13 YEARS AND COUNTING FOR A REAGAN BIOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Edmund Morris is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question stings for the estimated 726th billionth time.
</P>
<P>
   When will historian Edmund Morris publish his epic, authorized
biography of Ronald Reagan, a high-profile project 13 years in
preparation, composed in longhand with a green marbled Eversharp
fountain pen on lined paper and written with such an unconventional
strategy that the book's publishers are loath to reveal details.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, the former president's official biographer, calculates
that he has been needled with the question 726,354,925,267 times, a
figure he cites in a personal essay that was published in the fall
issue of Forbes FYI magazine with a subheading, ``His Biography Is
Finished (So Stop Asking!).''
</P>
<P>
   Ask again. The current answer from the book's patient publisher,
Random House, is that the long-awaited biography _ or, more
precisely, ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' _ is not finished,
and that the company has delayed October plans to ship copies of
the work it recently promoted as the ``most anticipated book of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really far along,'' said Ann Godoff, the president and
editor in chief of Random House. ``There were just some additions
to the material. It's delayed, but I'm not sure by how much. It
depends on copy editing. The guy has been working on it for 13
years, and it's really a question of getting it exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Morris said, ``The book's been delayed because of the
fanatical perfectionism of the neurotic author.'' He said he was
trimming and polishing the book, which was originally scheduled for
publication seven years ago. ``If I had my druthers, I would spend
the rest of my life perfecting it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that he remained eager for publication.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Morris and his publisher have been reluctant to
characterize in great detail the book, a project that traces some
of its early beginnings to an intimate Georgetown dinner that
brought together a group of historians, including Morris, and the
president and Nancy Reagan to ponder the delicate work and role of
biographers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Godoff declined to discuss the specific nature of the
manuscript, and so did Robert Loomis, Morris' editor, who through a
spokeswoman said that he was prevented from discussing the contents
because of the company's exclusive contract with Newsweek to run an
excerpt of the book.
</P>
<P>
   But Loomis made obvious hints that the book was not a standard
biography in an appearance in September 1997 on C-Span's ``About
Books'' program when he remarked that he had just finished reading
the last chapter. ``He's got a new idea about how to write this
book, which I don't want to talk about right now, which is
controversial, but it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing to characterize the years of effort, Loomis, a veteran
Random House editor, said, ``It's been not troubled exactly, but
he's worked very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A person in publishing circles, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that at one point during the long writing process
Morris, 58, inserted himself as an imaginary young contemporary of
Reagan, observing and witnessing Reagan's early childhood in
Illinois. Someone else, who read the manuscript, said Morris had
adjusted his own age within the text in order to surface as an
observer during Reagan's acting days in Hollywood in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview if he had used such a literary technique,
Morris paused and then declined to address the question. ``I don't
think I want to comment about the book,'' he said. ``I feel it's
premature, and it's still being rewritten. The book will explain
itself when it's published, and the book is _ I repeat _ changing
even as we speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the brief catalogue copy promoting the book simply says,
``Morris has transcended the conventional bounds of biography _
presenting the story through a unique first-person narrative, which
gives this chronicle an almost photographic immediacy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Morris describes the book that has so long
occupied his life as ``simply a memoir of Ronald Reagan.'' He said
that he himself emerges not as a character in the book, but as a
``biographer who had unique access to the subject.'' He added, ``I
don't think there's ever been a presidential biographer who has
been able to see his subject's life happening as a close
eyewitness.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he does appear as an imaginary character in the
president's childhood, Morris replied: ``I'm me, but I'm a
biographer. I'm the biographer perceiving Reagan and the things
that I personally discover. For example, I come across a batch of
his teen-age and student papers, and I'm able to deduce Reagan's
imaginary life and the only way I can convey this is by talking
about the literary detection.''
</P>
<P>
   This technique is a departure from the more traditional
biography of Theodore Roosevelt that won Morris a Pulitzer Prize
and attracted the attention of legacy-minded Reagan administration
officials and supporters who admired the biographer's work and
sought to match him with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for the book for a long time because I think
Edmund is a superb writer,'' said Michael Deaver, a former top aide
to Reagan. ``If you look at his Theodore Roosevelt biography, it's
beautifully written.''
</P>
<P>
   As former members of the Reagan administration recall it, Reagan
and his wife settled on Morris as the official biographer some time
after Mark Hatfield, then a senator from Oregon, was host at a
dinner in the early 1980s at his Georgetown home with guests that
included President and Mrs. Reagan, Morris and three other
presidential historians, including George Nash and Arthur Link.
Over a meal of lemon piccata chicken, the group sat around a dining
room table on a snowy Valentine's Day while each biographer
described his efforts to explore the life of a president.
</P>
<P>
   The historians were not there auditioning as candidates to write
a biography, Hatfield said, but to formally discuss the often
difficult process of documenting the presidency. The authors urged
the Reagans to save every scrap of paper and to remember the
thoughts that led to their actions, Hatfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all very much of the opinion that some kind of time
with a president would have meant so much more to them and would
have been much more helpful to the observation role that they would
play,'' Hatfield said.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, Reagan responded to those suggestions, eventually
allowing Morris such unprecedented access that a former Reagan
speech writer, Anthony Dolan, remembered ``looking over at the
senior staff in the morning and Edmund would be sitting there.''
Dolan added: ``And he saw Ronald Reagan for long chats whenever he
wanted, and it was really up to Reagan whether he was forthcoming
in those talks. Edmund got to attend almost every meeting that he
chose.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's latest delay does not particularly faze many former
Reagan administration officials or supporters who enthusiastically
participated in the effort. Deaver, for instance, said it was
probably a difficult task to write a biography of Reagan, the man,
since ``he's such a private person.''
</P>
<P>
   At Reagan's office in Century City, Calif., his chief of staff,
Joanne Drake, said diplomatically: ``We expected it years ago. I
guess we'll see it when we see it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lyn Nofziger, the former Reagan aide, said that his interest
in the book had waned some with time. ``I've had a number of people
ask me whatever happened to Edmund Morris and his book,'' he said,
adding, ``I don't think it's eagerly anticipated anymore because
most people have forgotten about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield, who organized the dinner for the Reagans and the
biographers, said he had stopped asking Morris for status reports
about the book. ``I could tell it was not a question that he
enjoyed commenting on,'' said Hatfield, who added, ``I'm 76, and I
want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The more immediate result of the latest delay is that Random
House will miss a peak holiday buying season to sell the book along
with incurring the costs of tying up $3 million in advance money
for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Woll, the president of Cross River Publishing Consultants
and the author of ``Publishing for Profit,'' said that with a
standard contract the interest incurred on a $3 million advance
over 13 years would amount to more than $2.1 million. With the long
passage of time, the publisher has to sell even more books to make
back its money, he said. And in this case, he estimated that Random
House would have to sell more than 800,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have gotten it before Christmas,'' said
Ms. Godoff, Random House's president. ``That would obviously have
made a difference to us.'' But she added: ``With a serious book,
there's always another season, particularly with a book like this
because it's been so long in the doing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Morris pointed out, it has taken time to get to know his
subject and to develop understanding. He needed time for writing.
(His wife, Sylvia Jukes Morris, worked 15 years on her biography of
Clare Boothe Luce.) Then there was the rewriting, polishing,
editing. Morris quoted Anatole France to describe the process, ``A
work of art is never finished, only abandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, he was overly optimistic when he wrote his essay
for Forbes FYI announcing the completion of his project. ``I wrote
the article in the summer, and writers always think they're going
to be finished before they are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In that article, he also quotes Ronald Reagan, who gave him a
White House photograph of the two of them shaking hands at some
black-tie affair. Inscribed in the president's hand is a variation
on the same old question that stings: ``What are you doing here?
Why aren't you writing?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
