<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges will press inland Monday, after battering
parts of the central Gulf Coast with wind gusts over 100 mile an
hour and a storm surge resulting in tides more than 10 feet above
normal. Winds and seas will gradually subside later Monday as the
hurricane's circulation weakens over land. Torrential rainfall will
then become the primary threat.
</P>
<P>
   Weak steering currents in the middle levels of the atmosphere
will propel Hurricane Georges at less than 10 miles an hour Monday,
and the storm could even stall for a time. Drenching rains will
fall near and to the east of the hurricane's center. Flooding is
expected as some areas receive more than 10 to 20 inches of rain.
Bands of tropical downpours and bursts of wind will spiral
counter-clockwise hundreds of miles from the center of the
hurricane. Some of these squalls are capable of producing isolated
tornadoes over parts of Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama, eastern
Georgia and the Florida panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will move south from the Middle Atlantic states.
Scattered thunder will precede the front from southern Virginia to
the Carolinas. Meanwhile, breezes from the northwest will deliver
cooler and drier air to the Northeast and Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of moist air will activate thundershowers over the
central and southern Rockies. Scattered strong storms will also
form in the central Plains. Over California, a meandering pool of
very chilly air near 18,000 feet will sponsor pockets of showers
from the central coast to the northern Sierra. Tranquil weather
will embrace much of the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Storm Surge
</P>
<P>
   While the winds around a strong hurricane can cause considerable
damage, the storm's most dangerous part is water. As the hurricane
nears land, water is pushed toward the coast on the storm's
right-forward flank by fierce onshore winds. As the bottom becomes
more shallow, water being shoved ashore piles up, causing an
abnormal rise in sea level. Called the storm surge, this sudden
rise can reach heights up to 30 feet. Battering waves ride atop the
surge. This formidable wall of water can level houses and small
buildings. Storm surges swell when they occur at the time of normal
high tides.
</P>
</TEXT>
