<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-AD-COLUMN-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SPRINT'S SUDDEN SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sprint Corp. has unexpectedly dismissed J. Walter
Thompson San Francisco after 17 years and moved most duties for
consumer advertising, with billings estimated at $150 million, to
McCann-Erickson New York.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt change, made on Friday without a review, underscores
the ferment in the telecommunications industry as competition
intensifies among Sprint, AT&AMP;T Corp. and the newly formed MCI
Worldcom Inc., the company that resulted from Worldcom's recently
completed acquisition of MCI Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint shuffle involves work for the long distance and local
telephone divisions, including the well-known campaigns to promote
the Sprint Sense dime-a-minute calling plan. The switch exemplifies
just how suddenly and swiftly many long-term relationships between
big marketers and agencies are ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the midst of planning quite significant changes in
how we handled Sprint,'' said Chris Jones, chief executive of J.
Walter Thompson Co., a unit of WPP Group PLC in New York, ``and we
had a presentation locked and loaded in the computer'' to be shown
to Sprint executives on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives never saw it, he added, because when they
arrived at Thompson ``they said, `Before you make this
presentation, we've got to tell you something.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the only example on Friday of the fragility of
longtime client-agency relations. At the same time that Thompson
lost the bulk of its Sprint account to McCann-Erickson New York,
McCann-Erickson New York was dismissed by Nabisco Inc. after 12
years of handling advertising for domestic cracker brands like
Triscuit and Wheat Thins. Those duties, with billings estimated at
more than $20 million, were moved _ oddly enough _ to the Chicago
office of Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   For Sprint, the change in consumer agencies comes as the company
undertakes an ambitious effort to redefine itself as a full-service
provider of communications services rather than simply a purveyor
of long distance calling plans, the aspect of its business that
Thompson San Francisco had long promoted in ads featuring Candice
Bergen. Interestingly, Sprint and Ms. Bergen had agreed to end her
endorsement deal on Sept. 18, after eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson ``helped us build the consumer long distance brand,''
said Tom Kessler, assistant vice president for marketing at the
Sprint consumer services group in Kansas City, Mo., but now ``we're
looking to evolve our advertising in a broader direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've concluded that McCann-Erickson, with their relevant
industry experience and recent proven results for companies such as
Mastercard, Motorola and Gateway 2000, can help us strengthen our
brand position,'' he added, ``as we pursue new markets, achieve new
sales and attract new customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``industry experience'' describes the campaigns
McCann-Erickson created for AT&AMP;T in categories like
business-to-business and wireless advertising. AT&AMP;T dismissed
McCann-Erickson in November to consolidate assignments at its two
other New York roster agencies, Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding and Young &AMP;
Rubicam Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson is ``thrilled'' to be ``back in the
telecommunications business,'' said Don Dillon, president and
regional director for McCann-Erickson North America, who also
oversees McCann-Erickson New York. The agency _part of the
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising unit of McCann-Erickson World
Group, which is owned by Interpublic Group of Cos. _ has been on a
new-business hot streak, landing more than $2.5 billion in added
billings since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of telecommunications has never been more complex or
more complicated,'' Dillon said, ``and the assumption is that it
will only continue. Every company is being challenged to compete as
never before.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Thompson San Francisco had been the lead Sprint agency,
Sprint executives approached McCann-Erickson early this year for a
project, he added, after ``Sprint asked Draft, our sister agency,
to be introduced to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon's reference was to Draft Worldwide in Chicago, which
handles direct marketing aimed at retaining present long-distance
customers for Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Another McCann unit, McCann Relationship Marketing, will now
handle direct marketing campaigns aimed at attracting new Sprint
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The project for Sprint ``resulted in some commercial
presentations that never aired,'' Dillon said, as well as a project
for a football spot ``that will run a few weeks from now.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the shift came with no review, he added, ``there was a
long working-together process during which Sprint got a very good
idea of what kind of agency we were.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint surprise is the second instance in a month of
Thompson's unceremoniously losing a large account to a rival. Dell
Computer Corp. dismissed Thompson Chicago after only nine months
and moved its worldwide brand account, with billings estimated at
more than $100 million, to the BBDO New York unit of Omnicom Group
.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge difference'' between the two losses, Jones of
Thompson said, because with Sprint the agency had realized ``that
we were going to have to make changes to keep the account.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely disappointed'' with Sprint's decision, he added,
since it was ``a very, very bad blow for our agency in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   About 50 of the office's 200 employees work on Sprint, and
``there will have to be layoffs,'' Jones said. The office, which
also works for marketers like Chevron Corp. and Nestle SA, ``will
not be closing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's New York office will continue to handle broadcast
media buying for Sprint on a corporate basis. Other Sprint agencies
are unaffected by the switch; they include Grey Advertising in New
York, for business-to-business ads, and the Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney
unit of Publicis SA in San Francisco, for the Sprint PCS wireless
brand. The Competitive Media Reporting unit of VNU NV tallied total
Sprint ad spending last year at $274.3 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thompson's bad news from Sprint was somewhat offset by the good
news from Nabisco. The budget for cracker campaigns is expected to
be increased next year to stimulate demand for brands like Ritz,
the nation's best-selling cracker; Premium saltines, and Vegetable
Thins.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nabisco leads the cracker field in market share, unit
sales have been declining for the last 18 months. Thompson ``has a
longstanding history of creating impactful advertising for
packaged-goods firms'' like Nestle, said Ann Smith, a spokeswoman
for Nabisco, a unit of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. in Parsippany,
N.J. ``We believe our cracker portfolio will benefit from their
strength in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   And two key Nabisco executives _ James Kilts, president and
chief executive, and Richard Lenny, president at Nabisco Biscuit
Co. _ worked with Thompson Chicago while they were top managers at
the Kraft Foods unit of Philip Morris Co.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, McCann-Erickson New York also lost A.1 steak sauce,
sold by Nabisco Specialty Products Co., after handling that brand
for a year. Billings were estimated at $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   A.1 is being moved to Foote, Cone, a unit of True North
Communications in New York that also handles Nabisco cookie brands;
another Nabisco condiment, Grey Poupon mustards, and overseas
assignments. The shift eliminates McCann-Erickson from the Nabisco
domestic agency roster, though the agency continues handling some
brands overseas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
