<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY: STANDARDS AND THE PUBLIC INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most ominous trends in Washington is a growing belief
that private industry, particularly any technology-based industry,
is better suited to serving the public interest than are elected
lawmakers and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a recent speech on digital television, William
Kennard, the chairman of the Federal Communications Commission,
said that the government should encourage industries to set their
own standards and should be involved only ``when arguments are
distorted by the prism of self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But by most accounts, distorted self-interest is a pretty
accurate description of the slow-motion train wreck that has been
the digital television standards-setting process of the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   And for some who took part in the process, the recent spate of
complaints from TV industry executives rings disingenuous at best.
</P>
<P>
   Years before the adoption of the new digital TV standard,
members of the Advanced Television Standards Committee
(www.atsc.org) _ whose proposals were adopted almost verbatim by
the FCC _ engaged in a long and vicious battle with digital
technology experts over technical features.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the committee, which was heavily populated by
broadcast-industry representatives, argued against making
television more friendly to the display of computer-generated
images and text. In the early days, when the debate was only about
high-definition television, they even debated whether the standard
should be analog or digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even brought in a demonstration of the first Internet
browser back in 1993 or 1994,'' said Richard Solomon, an image
specialist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, who helped
develop the first HDTV camera with Polaroid. ``The computer people
got it right away, but the TV people just didn't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Liebhold, former director of Apple Computer's broad-band
multimedia research group, said his inclusion of educators, print
publishers and medical people in early discussions with the
standards committee ``was characterized as computer industry
interference'' and was ``pretty much ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   When the dust finally settled, the TV people appeared to have
won virtually every point. In fact, the announcement of the new
standard on Dec. 26, 1996, noted with pleasure that ``the specific
video formats to be used for digital broadcast television will be
the subject of voluntary industry standards.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``voluntary industry standards'' set by the television
industry are precisely what that industry is now complaining about.
</P>
<P>
   The digital TV standard as proposed by the committee and adopted
by the FCC supports at least 14 different scanning formats, the
technical specifications that describe how a television picture is
created, broadcast and displayed. These formats encompass standard
and high-definition television, as well as what the FCC calls
computer-friendly formats.
</P>
<P>
   But the new digital TV standard does not require programmers to
broadcast any single specific format, as is the case with today's
broadcasts. Neither are equipment manufacturers required to build
receivers that receive any specific format.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, both the television industry and the critics who
accuse the FCC of adopting an overly broad standard acknowledge
that the resulting market chaos will put consumers in an untenable
position. They might have to buy separate receivers to view a wide
variety of programming. In addition, upgrading to more capable
systems is likely to be exponentially more expensive than simply
buying a new television set or set-top box.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the key role that television plays in world culture,
critics say, the willful creation of such chaos does not serve the
public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Or does it?
</P>
<P>
   William Schreiber, a television and film pioneer who was
director of the Advanced Television Research Program at MIT until
his retirement in 1990, has been active in the digital TV standards
process since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   In a detailed document (available at
www.nytimes.com/tech/schreiber.html), he describes the problems at
length, including, he says, the domination of the standards process
by television broadcasters and TV-set makers. He also asserts that
the FCC has acted against the public interest by not opening the
process to independent evaluation and selecting a single,
technically superior standard.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard, the commission's chairman, responds that the broad
range of formats embraces both the computer industry and
broadcasters, ``at least preserving the possibility that the
marketplace might not be dictated'' by any single industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC was caught in the position where Congress had decided
to give away spectrum to existing broadcasters in exchange for them
making the transition to HDTV,'' Kennard said. The spectrum would
remain free, Congress said, only if it were used exclusively for
high-definition television.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's position, Kennard said, was, ``Who are we to dictate
what this technology should be used for?''
</P>
<P>
   Though Liebhold, Solomon, Schreiber and other critics are
disappointed that the digital TV standard has not achieved their
technical ideals, the television industry ``stopped the train from
barreling down the tracks, and they won, though they may not want
to admit it,'' said an industry insider who spoke in exchange for
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started this process,'' this insider said, ``the
broadcasters thought they had it completely locked down. Now either
they will step up to the task or morph into a completely new
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains: In a world where the forward march of
technology often serves only to create chaos, is the public
interest better served if standards are set by the government or by
the marketplace?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the really important question that has not yet been
answered,'' the insider said. ''If we give broadcasters the
spectrum for free, what does the public get back in return?
Separate from developing new services and products, `public
interest' obviously needs to be redefined. If it's just about
pretty pictures, why bother?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
