<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV-KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND YOUNG MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children's ears and eyes have not been shielded from coverage of
the scandal enveloping President Clinton. And many parents cringe
at the questions the coverage may have raised in their youngsters'
minds.
</P>
<P>
   To help promote parent-child discussion, Nickelodeon will
televise a ``Nick News Special'' Monday at 9 p.m. Linda Ellerbee,
the host, leads 10 children, ages 10-14, in expressing their
concerns about the president and in questioning Katie Couric of NBC
News and Reid Weingarten, a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beforehand, people said to me, `What will you do if the kids
ask explicit sex questions?''' Ms. Ellerbee said. ``But not one of
them did. That's not what they wanted to talk about. They talked
about honesty and the importance of being loyal to your family.
They asked what is censure, what is perjury and what will happen to
the country if Clinton stops being president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they said Congress shouldn't have put the whole Starr
report on the Internet because kids use that as their backyard,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a companion poll last week, Nickelodeon found that 100
percent of children ages 8-14 had heard about the scandal; 90
percent said they had learned about it from television. When asked
what they thought was the biggest news event right now, 60 percent
of the children named the Clinton-Lewinsky matter. Only 17 percent
named the home-run derby between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission in these specials is to help kids make sense of
the news they're hearing,'' said Ms. Ellerbee, whose company, Lucky
Duck Productions, produces the Nickelodeon news specials. ``Not to
tell them what to think, but to let kids know it's OK to have
questions about these things and OK to discuss them, and to let
parents see that kids do have questions and are thinking seriously
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Most children in the Nick News taping thought Clinton should be
punished but not removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid said, `Couldn't we give him a timeout?''' Ms. Ellerbee
said. ``I told him it sounded like a reasonable idea, but the law
didn't provide for that punishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
