A6757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALL-MOVIES-COX     09-27 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-MOVIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hollywood recycles plots, stars for fall movies
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fall movie season is here.
</P>
<P>
   The fall movie season is here.
</P>
<P>
   Might as well get used to seeing double. It's this autumn's
trend out of Hollywood, where it's no longer just cattiness that's
next to godliness. Now, copycatiness is too.
</P>
<P>
   Mad asteroid movies (``Deep Impact,'' ``Armageddon'') released
mere months apart? Pffft. World War II (``Saving Private Ryan,''
the upcoming ``The Thin Red Line'') times two? C'mon, you ain't
seen nothing yet.
</P>
<P>
   And yet again.
</P>
<P>
   Herein a (twin) peek at how the movies will repeat themselves
this fall. Read it or weep when you find yourself sitting through a
third straight movie about someone who dies in a car crash. (Movie
release dates, in parentheses, are subject to change.)
</P>
<P>
   _ What themes may come: Three things in life are certain
according to the movies: Death, taxes and life after death. First,
Robin Williams searches the afterlife for his wife in ``What Dreams
May Come'' (Friday). Then Michael Keaton returns to his grieving
family as a snowman in ``Jack Frost'' (Nov. 6). And, finally, Brad
Pitt assumes a dead man's identity in ``Meet Joe Black'' (Nov. 13).
</P>
<P>
   _ Hey, Norton! Edward Norton, a '96 Oscar nominee, has two films
out this fall: ``Rounders'' with Matt Damon (in metro theaters) and
``American History X,'' (Oct. 16) in which he co-stars with another
Edward (Furlong), whose ``Pecker'' was released Friday. Are we all
clear now?
</P>
<P>
   _ Give me a large popcorn and a can of Raid: Supposedly, it's an
ant movie, ``Antz'' (Friday), vs. a whole insect world movie, ``A
Bug's Life'' (Nov. 20). But don't kid yourself. It's really a
battle between DreamWorks and Disney to see which studios' computer
animators can squash the other's like a . . . um, a bug.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Jones gang: Want to know what it was like to be a World
War II soldier? Catch ``The Thin Red Line'' (January in Atlanta),
based on James Jones' novel. Want to know what it was like to be a
World War II soldier's kid? Catch ``A Soldier's Daughter Never
Cries,'' based on a novel by Jones' daughter Kaylie, which opened
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Great, but when will we open presents? Not one, but two hugely
anticipated movies. Not one, but two hugely anticipated movies
starring John Travolta. Not two, but one day on which they both
open. Coming up _ on Christmas of all days _ are ``The Thin Red
Line'' and ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Return to . . . Vince Vaughn and Joaquin Phoenix: Co-stars of
August's ``Return to Paradise,'' they co-star again in ``Clay
Pigeons'' (Friday).
</P>
<P>
   _ Return to . . . Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche: Co-stars of
August's ``Return to Paradise,'' they co-star again in ``Psycho''
(Dec. 4).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dying Jung: Two films about dying mothers (Meryl Streep in
``One True Thing,'' in metro theaters, and Susan Sarandon in ``The
Stepmom,'' which opens Christmas Day), the younger women in their
lives (Renee Zellweger and Julia Roberts, respectively) and how
they're forced to come to psychological terms with each other.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get on the bus: ``Just Write'' is the story of a tour bus
driver's affair with an actress and ``The Cruise'' is the story of
a New York City tour bus.
</P>
<P>
   _ And on a related front, Sir John Gielgud now sings lead for
Def Leppard: Two heavy-metal rock stars are making feature film
debuts. ``A Letter From Death Row'' was written by and stars
Poison's Bret Michaels. ``Dee Snider's Strangeland'' (not to be
confused with 1996's ``William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet'')
stars Twisted Sister's frontman as an Internet stalker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
