<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISCARRIAGE-COX     09-27 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISCARRIAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A common event, miscarriage is an emotional blow
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The news came in the waning minutes of Atlanta radio
station Star 94's morning show: On-air personality Vikki Locke
announced to more than 400,000 listeners she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The radio station's Web site crashed that mid-September day
while processing almost 200 e-mails of congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   But three days later, Locke was pacing the bedroom floor of her
home, fighting cramps and a severe backache. She prayed and she
debated going to the emergency room and calling her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   And later, in the silence of the night, she miscarried.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the public airways, Locke's husband, Mike Hughes,
cradled her as she cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a part of my soul has been ripped from me,'' Locke
said in her first interview after the miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   She initially worried that she worked too hard _ not only coming
in at 5:30 for the morning show and meeting with clients, but also
attending several evening charity events. In fact, one of the
reasons she decided to tell listeners about the pregnancy in the
first place is because she had been ordered by her doctor to cut
back on her work hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to lie about why I couldn't do these events,''
she said. ``So I thought if I just told the truth, people would
understand. And they did.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the miscarriage, her husband and her doctor reminded
her that guilt was not necessary. ``I kept wondering if it was
because I wasn't getting enough sleep, if that had something to do
with it,'' she said. ``And my husband kept telling me I had nothing
to feel guilty about. That I had taken good care of myself as soon
as I had found out'' I was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Since her miscarriage, she has heard from dozens of metro
Atlanta couples who could identify with her very public pain, in
part because the event is so common.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians and researchers think about one in four pregnancies
ends in miscarriage. Many women do not even realize they are
pregnant, instead believing they are simply having a particularly
heavy period.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who are aware of their condition _ and desperately
want the child a pregnancy promises _ the event can be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   And ironically, better medical care and technology has made the
pain worse.
</P>
<P>
   Old World customs often dictated that cribs and clothes not be
made or bought before the baby was born _ a nod to nature's
harshness toward pregnancies. But better medical care has given
many a stronger sense that humans can control the outcome of
reproduction and birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many young, married couples who have planned out
everything _ when they're going to get pregnant, when they're going
to have their baby,'' said Dr. Sujatha Reddy, an assistant
professor with Atlanta's Emory Clinic. ``And when something like
this happens, it's very hard on them. This wasn't supposed to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents also get attached to a pregnancy much earlier. In
previous centuries, women usually didn't know they were pregnant
until they experienced morning sickness. And the traditional rabbit
test required a missed period, a scheduled doctor's visit and two
days of lab testing before a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a woman can determine whether she's pregnant barely a day
after she's missed her period. And with ultrasounds being performed
earlier, couples often have _ and share _ pictures or videos of
their offspring months before it's born. (For example, Locke,
almost 12 weeks pregnant, had already had two ultrasounds by the
time she miscarried.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that for the couple who truly wants a
baby, a pregnancy equates a child,'' said Dr. Carlene Elsner, a
reproductive endocrinologist and infertility specialist for
Reproductive Biology Associates Inc. ``When they lose a pregnancy,
it's awful. We witness them go through the same grief process as
parents who have lost a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Most miscarriages are caused by chromosomal defects, but other
factors include uterine deformities, infections and illnesses.
Miscarriages, however, are not typically caused by any particular
behavior by the women.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say exercise, sex, eating certain foods or even having
low-level illnesses, such as a cold, is not going to disrupt a
healthy pregnancy _ and women should not blame themselves for a
miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got patients asking me, `Was it the pesticides and the
bug man?' `Was it because I didn't take all my vitamins' or
`Because my husband and I had sex,''' said Reddy. ``People really
tend to look for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one factor that does contribute to miscarriage is a
woman's age.
</P>
<P>
   In women who are 38 or older, the pregnancy rate drops and the
miscarriage rate increases, a result of ``old'' eggs and
poor-quality embryos, Elsner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in this age group can get pregnant and have a healthy
baby,'' Elsner said. ``But they have to be prepared for more of a
roller coaster ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in medical technology have, however, made it easier
for doctors to correct problems that lead to miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
   For example, women can have uterine operations to correct such
problems as fibroids. They can take hormone supplements until
pregnancies can be sustained on their own. Women can have blood
tests to check immunity problems or viral infections. And couples
can have chromosomal tests to check for DNA defects.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's no indication that just because a woman has one
miscarriage, she'll have any more. And even if she's had two
consecutive miscarriages, she still has only a one in three chance
of experiencing another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a lot of exciting good news,'' Elsner said.
``Couples are getting better educated about their health and so,
even if they lose a pregnancy, they're taking more time to learn
what they can do the stack the deck in their favor the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   People are also getting more astute on how to handle miscarriage
_ from bosses to grandparents. It's expected that a couple will
take at least three to six months to recover. And in some cases, if
the miscarriage occurred late in the pregnancy, or it's one of
several, the parents may never totally recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep waiting to feel like myself again,'' said Locke. ``I
think, physically, I'm all right. But emotionally, I'm just not to
the point where I can socialize and feel good yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Share Atlanta Inc., a pregnancy and infant loss support group,
runs classes on such topics as grief and the loss of family dreams,
how fathers can help mothers and fears about the safety of future
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors still recommend that prospective parents hold off in
telling co-workers and bosses about pregnancies until they are
clear of the first trimester. But if a couple break the rules and
then face a loss, they are finding many people have also
experienced a similar loss and can garner support.
</P>
<P>
   Although Locke could not talk to her mother about the
miscarriage _ in part because she was worried her mother would
immediately fly into town to be with her _ she faced her listeners
three days after she lost the pregnancy. Her co-host, Steve McCoy,
who has lost a child of his own, scoured her desk for baby clothes
and congratulations cards before she arrived.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sept. 16, Locke talked about unplugging the phone and
watching 16 videos over the weekend. By the end of the day, she had
received more than 60 e-mails from people giving support and
revealing their own heartaches.
</P>
<P>
   Locke said one listener's letter particularly touched her: ``It
said, `Consider yourself lucky. You now have your own tiny angel
watching over you forever.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
