<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-HOSPITAL-NYT &LR;      09-27 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-HOSPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO HOSPITALIZED AFTER FAINTING IN CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno fainted Sunday morning
during a church service in suburban Maryland and was hospitalized
at Georgetown University Medical Center, where she will be held
overnight for observation, Justice Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Donovan, a hospital spokesman, said that Reno was awake,
alert and talking. A Justice Department statement quoted Dr. Paul
Katz, the hospital's chief operating officer, as saying Reno's
vital signs were ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, 60, fainted while standing during services at the Full
Gospel AME Church in Clinton, the Justice Department said. A
physician on the Georgetown Hospital staff, Dr. Rodney Ellis, who
is a member of the congregation, treated Reno and accompanied her
in an ambulance to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department statement said that Reno told aides she
was ``feeling fine.'' She spoke with President Clinton, who called
from Air Force One while en route from Los Angeles to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Although apparently unrelated to her fainting episode, Reno also
suffers from a mild form of Parkinson's disease, a neurological
disorder diagnosed in late 1995 that causes a shaking of her left
hand. Reno and her doctors have said that the disease has not
impaired her work or her physical activity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sunday was not the first time Reno has experienced dizziness in
public. In 1997, she fainted while attending a conference in Mexico
and was later found to have gallstones.
</P>
<P>
   Then as now, Reno was at the center of several high pressure
decisions on whether to seek an independent prosecutor to
investigate possible illegalities in how Democrats financed
President Clinton's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has until November to decide on three 90-day preliminary
inquiries that could lead to an independent prosecutor to
investigate political fund-raising issues.
</P>
<P>
   One inquiry centers on whether Vice President Al Gore was
truthful in his statements about telephone fund-raising
solicitations from the White House. Another centers on whether
Harold Ickes, the former White House deputy chief of staff, lied
about efforts to help the teamsters resolve a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The third centers on whether Clinton violated the federal
election law during an effort to raise money sent to state parties
to finance political advertising campaigns that benefited his
campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6767 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-BUG-KAN &LR;      09-27 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BUG-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD GRAPPLES WITH WAYS TO EXTERMINTE YEAR 2000 BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES AND FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (breaks down)
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Ratcliffe of Pleasant Valley, a disabled former office
worker, can't afford to move. But she's worried. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm figuring at least six months of everything being messed
up,'' said Ratcliffe, who's stocking up on canned food and kerosene
lamps. She's worried that those who have prepared will become
targets for those who haven't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm contemplating whether I should get some 2-by-4s to put
bars over the doors and windows,'' Ratcliffe said. ``I'm trying to
decide whether I should buy a weapon.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One expert sees self-interest driving much of the panic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consultants benefit from the year 2000 fear that helps pay their
skyrocketing fees, said Nicholas Zvegintzov, president of Software
Management Network of New York and a programmer for 35 years.
Politicians also benefit from a puffed-up problem they can fix
without much effort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there's no political clout in common sense,''
Zvegintzov said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Bennett, a Utah Republican who coordinates the Senate's
year 2000 efforts, isn't doing anything to add to the national
calm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a July 15 speech to the National Press Club in Washington,
Bennett told journalists to expect electrical brownouts and
regional blackouts. He predicts some banks will go bankrupt and
some water systems will break down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such alarm might actually be good, said Heidi Hooper, year 2000
director for the Information Technology Association of America. She
said the general public could use a serious wake-up call. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These huge Fortune 100 companies are spending, collectively,
billions and billions of dollars. I don't think that's hype,'' she
said. ``They are not going to spend that money for no reason. They
know, bottom line, that if they are going to make money they have
to stay in business.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for some businesses to stay afloat, other businesses will
have to drown, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need, unfortunately, is examples of failures,'' Hooper
said. ``That's going to start soon enough in 1999. And the private
sector is not going to share that information, so it's going to
have to be up to the federal government to step in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the federal government is in no shape to provide
leadership. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overall, one congressman gave the federal government a ``D'' on
its most recent year 2000 preparedness report card, up from the
``F'' it received in June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a grade you take home to your parents,'' said Rep.
Steve Horn, a California Republican and chairman of the House
subcommittee on government management of information and
technology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Horn predicts the government will not be able to fix a
substantial number of ``mission critical'' systems by 2000. And the
price tag to fix the 24 governmental departments surveyed is $6.3
billion, up $1 billion from the estimate given by the Office of
Management and Budget. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The executive branch has a deadline that cannot be extended,''
Horn said. ``There is no margin for error.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Kansas City is requiring all city departments to
submit contingency plans by October for dealing with the year 2000
problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What to look for: Will traffic lights work? Will prisoners be
released early if a computer mistakenly thinks an inmate has been
jailed for more than 100 years? Will fire trucks start, and what is
the backup plan if they don't? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to overreact, and we're not,'' said John
Franklin, assistant city manager. ``But there is a real issue here
for public managers that's kind of scary.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Water District No. 1 of Johnson County will spend
$1.56 million to fix 4,109 computer programs and 701,021 lines of
code by the end of next summer. The district says the job is 75
percent complete, and General Manager Byron Johnson said he was
confident the district would be prepared. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But experts aren't prepared to declare victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole theme from day one is we need answers,'' said
Yardeni, the Yale economist and managing director of Deutsche Bank
Securities. ``I'm not trying to foment panic. I'm not trying to
create revolution. But you have to be a naive optimist to think
things are going to be pretty relaxed Jan. 1, 2000.'' &QL; 
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
