<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6768 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-BUG-KAN &LR;      09-27 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BUG-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVOUS WORLD GRAPPLES WITH WAYS TO EXTERMINATE YEAR 2000 BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Marilyn Allison has spent the last three years
making sure computers at Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City
don't fail after the ball drops on New Year's Eve 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allison is confident Blue Cross has the problem well in hand.
And she thinks most of Kansas City does, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But she still is planning to sock away enough food, water, cash
and firewood to last a couple of weeks in case everything does go
haywire on Jan. 1, 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's the rub of the year 2000 bug, a glitch that could cause
some computers, machinery, medical equipment, utilities and VCRs to
quit working, or spit out bad information, when the 1900s become
the 2000s. Nobody really knows what's going to happen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem stems from computer systems and billions of embedded
computer chips that might read the ``00'' in a computer program as
1900 rather than 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, one of the nation's leading economists,
forecasts a 70 percent chance of global recession because of the
bug. Another leading forecaster, David Wyss, chief economist for
Standard &AMP; Poor's, doesn't expect significant disruption. He even
contends the resulting fallout might be fun _ if we keep a sense of
humor about it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But everyone acknowledges something is coming down the tracks,
said Leon Kappelman, a university professor and author who is
spending much of his time these days talking about the year 2000
problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The uncertainty is whether it's a locomotive or a bicycle,''
Kappelman said. ``And it's difficult to get definitive evidence.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until now there hasn't been much information to rely on. Some
credit cards with ``00'' expiration dates have been rejected. A
104-year-old Minnesota woman was invited to report to kindergarten,
and a computer docked an Olathe couple $17,800 for insurance
premiums. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But those are just scattered hints of the trouble to come. The
real warning lies in our growing reliance on vast networks of
technology _ a single misfire in the wrong place can sabotage lives
in far-flung places. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, when just one satellite malfunctioned in May,
millions of pagers and automated teller machines went out for two
days. An ice storm in eastern Canada knocked out part of the
country's power grid and shut off power to millions of people for
more than a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think if all of that _ and more _ happened on one day: Jan. 1,
2000, a Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American businesses rely on computers to do almost everything.
They run huge manufacturing machines, answer telephones, pay
employees and control alarm systems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal government computers track airliners, generate Social
Security checks, and control satellites in space and missiles on
the ground. Cities use computers to run traffic lights and dispatch
police officers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Utilities use them to operate water and sewage systems. Grocery
stores use them to keep track of stock and place orders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even more important than the software that runs those computers
are the tiny, embedded computer chips buried in the guts of
technological gadgets, heavy machinery, airliners and even
granddad's pacemaker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are 40 billion of the chips, most of them hard or
impossible to test, said Dave Hall, an expert with the CABA Corp.
in Oak Brook, Ill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Estimates vary on how many of those chips will fail. Hall says 1
percent. Others say failures could go as high as 10 percent _ and
even higher in some medical equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even a 1 percent failure rate means 400 million chips would
fail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kappelman, the University of North Texas professor, thinks the
interrelationships between all those elements will cause serious
disruptions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it's unlikely that America's electric utilities
will be caught unprepared on the last New Year's Eve of the 1900s.
In fact, an industry report released last week said utility
problems seemed to be fewer _ and easier to fix _ than expected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if only a few plants shut down on Jan. 1, 2000, the strain
on the rest of the power grid could trip a cascading failure that
causes widespread brownouts or blackouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This will change the way we see the world,'' Kappelman said.
``We'll see our dependence on technology in a whole new way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if embedded chips are hard to check, the software problem
shouldn't seem too difficult to fix _ on the surface, at least. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For decades, computers have been programmed to recognize dates
using six digits: today's date is 09//27//98. When the calendar
rolls over at midnight on New Year's Eve 1999, computers that
haven't been taught differently will see the year as 1900 or some
other date entirely. If they work at all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So solve the problem. Add a couple of numbers to the programming
code. No big deal, right? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's become a very big deal. For Sprint Corp., that small fix
means programmers must pore over 80 million lines of code. The fix
will take two years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big business thinks the problem is so significant that fixing it
has become a big business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. is spending $200 million on year 2000 repairs;
Hallmark Cards, $25 million; Blue Cross in Kansas City, $25
million; UMB Bank, $22 million; Yellow Corp., $17 million. Johnson
County taxpayers will pay $17.2 million to fix that county's year
2000 problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All told, the fix in the Kansas City area will easily top the
$400 million mark. Worldwide, the total is estimated at $300
billion to $600 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Entire companies have sprouted just to deal with the year 2000
bug. More than 140 public companies, ranging from Acceler8
Technology to Zmax Corp., are touting their solutions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where there's a problem, there's a lawyer. Law firms have
established special teams just to handle potential litigation from
the year 2000 problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Companies that cater to survivalists are hawking canned or dried
food and survival gear to those with year 2000 angst. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That type of hype is spreading across the Internet on hundreds
of year 2000 Web sites. A few of the most radical year 2000
worriers already have moved to rural areas to get away from what
they think will be urban chaos when the lights go out and the food
supply chain breaks down. &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
