<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-DEBATE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAY NIXON AND KIT BOND DEBATE ABOUT TOBACCO, HEALTH CARE AND
CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (OSAGE BEACH, Mo.) _ Democrat Jay Nixon charged Saturday that
Republican U.S. Sen. Kit Bond is soft on crime while Bond stopped
just short of branding Nixon a liar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to Jay Nixon, you just can't trust what he
says,'' Bond said. ``I don't have time to correct all the
misstatements.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of charges and countercharges took place during
an hour-long debate sponsored by the Missouri Bar. Nixon,
Missouri's attorney general, is trying to unseat Bond in the
November election. Both men answered questions from three reporters
in their second of five scheduled debates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon criticized Bond's vote against an anti-crime bill in
Congress and said the senator opposed both the death penalty for
terrorists and gun-free zones in public schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested Bond erred as governor in 1974 when a state
prison inmate convicted of murder was paroled after serving ten
years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ex-prisoner was then hired as a guard at the same prison,
Nixon said, and accused of another killing shortly afterward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kit Bond's record is a lifetime of being soft on crime,''
Nixon said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the debate Bond told reporters any decisions on releasing
inmates were based on recommendations by the state probation and
parole board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the gentleman or the instance he (Nixon) is
referring to,'' Bond said. ``That was only a quarter of a century
ago. I'm sorry my memory is not that good.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond also said that when he was governor he worked for
restoration of the death penalty and as senator he has supported
limits on death penalty appeals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have a good record,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond repeatedly blasted Nixon's decision to hire 36 attorneys to
try to settle Missouri's tobacco lawsuit. They stand to make up to
$429 million for less than a year's work, Bond contended. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Firms where those attorneys work contributed more than $180,000
to Nixon campaigns, Bond said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a scandal,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon countered that tobacco interests have spent more than $1
million in this year's Senate race, partly to benefit Bond, who
voted against an anti-tobacco bill earlier this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon lumped Bond with the ``boys who have been smoking in the
men's room with big tobacco lobbyists.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon and Bond also bickered over proposed legislation to
provide medical patients with new rights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill Bond backs is seriously flawed because consumers could
not sue their health maintenance organizations, Nixon said,
contending that Bond earlier filed a multimillion lawsuit of his
own in a financial dispute. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There shouldn't be one set of rules for you and another set of
rules for everybody else,'' the attorney general said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond said the GOP health-care bill addresses concerns from
Missouri consumers while the version Nixon backs is supported by
Massachusetts Sen. Ted Kennedy and would benefit trial attorneys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond also said Nixon's campaign has been riddled with
misstatements. He said Nixon waged one of the dirtiest campaigns in
state history when he was elected attorney general in 1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one more example of Mr. Nixon living down to his
reputation,'' the Republican said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon promised he would fight for Missouri interests on health
care, Social Security, taxes, crime and education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the fights Kit Bond hasn't made and won't make,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond countered that his longtime experience in public life makes
him more effective today than ever. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise I will fight for you every day of the year,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
