<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINT-MARKETPLACE-AR     09-27 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SPRINT'S CHAIRMAN KEEPS HIS POWDER DRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ Sprint Corp. has not followed the script.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, driven by the bull market and federal
deregulation, the telecommunications industry wound itself into a
frenzy of consolidation. In the excitement, the roster of companies
that agreed to disappear through acquisition grew to include Nynex,
Pacific Telesis, GTE and Ameritech. Just two weeks ago, MCI
Communications Corp. was absorbed by Worldcom Inc. And
Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's No. 2 cable television
company, has a pending agreement to become part of AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, no company has generated a higher ratio of
merger-and-acquisition hyperbole to merger-and-acquisition reality
than Sprint. With the exception of BellSouth, Sprint, based here,
is the largest communications company in the nation that has not
been part of a big merger.
</P>
<P>
   So is this what happens when your chairman is a former
investment banker?
</P>
<P>
   William Esrey, Sprint's chairman, joined the company almost 20
years ago from the old Dillon, Read &AMP; Co. When he says that Sprint
has the strategic pieces in place to thrive on its own, he is
credible. Besides being the No. 3 U.S. long-distance carrier,
Sprint has a cash cow in its local phone business. The company also
has strong data communications offerings, an emerging wireless
business and an international strategy that has at least the
potential to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But three things are clear. First, that Esrey is and has been
prepared to sell his company, for the right price. Second, that one
window for doing so has already closed. And third, that Esrey is
convinced that many more chances will come along _ even if not
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   So while he says that selling Sprint is not his plan, he can
certainly come up with many scenarios for doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone asked, `Have you missed the opportunity to hedge
your bets in some way and hook up?' first of all I doubt that very
much,'' he said in an interview in his office here.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the foreign options, for example. Deutsche Telekom and
France Telecom, each of which owns 10 percent of Sprint, are not
allowed, by contract, to increase their stakes. But when Esrey
thinks about foreign communications carriers that would want to
expand into the United States, he says, ``There's a lot of other
large companies, though Japan's on its back right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Esrey said, the best strategy would be ``keeping
your powder dry'' and awaiting better merger chances ahead. ``In
the U.S., the Bells can't be into long-distance right now,'' he
said. ``So that opportunity, if you want to call it that, is still
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Esrey's keeping his powder dry, part of that decision has
already been made for him. It turns out that some of Sprint's top
executives were convinced their company would have made an
excellent partner for GTE. A combined GTE-Sprint, the thinking
went, would have had to sell some wireless assets, but other than
that, the companies would have melded beautifully. The deal would
have produced a huge, high-margin local phone business, a fiber
optic network for GTE's growing long-distance business and, because
neither company has the Bell legacy, a minimum of regulatory
hassle.
</P>
<P>
   But a GTE-Sprint pairing was not to be. This summer GTE agreed
to be acquired by Bell Atlantic for $52.9 billion. That deal was
criticized on Wall Street because it did not provide a premium for
GTE's shareholders even while it did provide that Charles Lee,
GTE's chairman, would keep his job in the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   GTE did not seriously pursue Sprint, and on Wall Street there
are at least two main lines of thought as to why. One is that GTE
was gun-shy after losing its takeover battle with Worldcom last
fall for MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory on why GTE did not pursue Sprint is that GTE
simply did not want to admit the magnitude of the strategic blunder
it committed when it sold its interest in Sprint in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: US Sprint, the long-distance carrier, was formed in
1986 as a 50-50 joint venture between GTE and United
Telecommunications, an old local phone company whose chief
executive had been William Esrey. But GTE eventually decided that
the long-distance business was not sufficiently attractive and by
1992 had sold its entire interest in Sprint to United for $1.1
billion. At that point, United renamed itself Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, of course, is that over the last few years GTE has
started all over again in the long-distance market. GTE declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint executives have not been as keen about a potential
acquisition by a regional Bell company, at least right now. The
Bells are still not allowed to sell long-distance service to
customers within their traditional regions, but Sprint already
sells long-distance service all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting questions percolating among
telecommunications bankers and analysts has been whether the
regulatory situation makes any potential Sprint-Bell company deal
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Theories abound on how an acquisition of Sprint by a Bell could
be structured. The long-distance unit could be put into some sort
of trust, perhaps, until the Bell won entry into the long-distance
market. Or the deal could simply be made conditional on the Bell's
getting long-distance approval.
</P>
<P>
   But Esrey is not a big fan of those scenarios. He does not want
to lock his shareholders into a deal that may never happen. If he
were to sell Sprint to a Bell, he would prefer to wait until the
Bell already had long-distance approval and he could move with
speed and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter who, if anyone, comes after Sprint, they are
probably going to have to pay top dollar. As a former banker (and
one who just built a new ranch in Colorado), Esrey is likely to
assign a higher priority to a merger premium than to any continued
role for himself in a combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's stock traded around $70 for most of the year, and Esrey
has not done much to dispel the consistent talk on Wall Street and
in the industry that his company could be acquired for around $100
a share.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Part of the talk of $100 a share has been built around the
widely known fact that Esrey stood to get options for a million
shares of Sprint at the attractive strike price of $47.94 if the
stock reached $95.875. (Sprint's shares ended the week at $77.25 on
the New York Stock Exchange.)
</P>
<P>
   What is not as well known is that Sprint's board recently
changed the terms of those options, so that Esrey could
automatically exercise them in the event of a takeover, regardless
of the stock price at the time. The change would ease a Sprint
takeover by allowing the acquiring company to use an accounting
method known as a pooling of interests, which brings substantial
tax benefits to the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the accounting method, any acquirer of Sprint is
probably going to have to face some earnings dilution; Sprint's
stock is now trading around 43 times estimated earnings, much
higher than the earnings multiple of the shares of most potential
acquirers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's high multiple is about to change, at least on the
surface. The main reason that Sprint's stock is trading at such a
premium is that about a third of the company's earnings are being
erased by losses in its wireless venture, an operation that still
requires big up-front investments. But in about six weeks, Sprint
plans to issue a separate tracking stock for its wireless unit,
allowing the market to value that business separately from Sprint's
others.
</P>
<P>
   The tracking stock, however, would not lower another hurdle to
acquiring Sprint. Almost any domestic company that would be
interested in Sprint would probably not be interested in the whole
company.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unlikely that any of the Bells, for example, would
want the wireless unit, because it would simply duplicate much of
their own existing wireless operations. On the other hand, a big
communications conglomerate that might actually want to expand into
wireless _ say, Worldcom in a few years _ would have little need
for Sprint's long-distance and local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a separate tracking stock, a company acquiring all of
Sprint could still have to sell the part it did not want _ with
sizable tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But the same diversification that could make Sprint a cumbersome
company to buy is also an attribute that enables Sprint to go it
alone for now, and allows Esrey to keep his powder dry for a while
longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
