<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-27 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZED LABOR BLUNDERS AGAIN, OPPOSES GOP TAX-CUT BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ If you've ever wondered why organized labor keeps
losing market share, so to speak, the AFL-CIO crusade against the
Republican tax-cut initiative helps put the problem in
perspective. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has joined forces with the Clinton administration
and congressional Democrats to oppose the pitifully modest
election-year tax-relief bid by launching an ad campaign themed to
Social Security scare tactics. This is the same bogus tactic used
by President Clinton and his economic brain trust. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture? The presidency is under siege,
which puts Democrats in Congress at a disadvantage. Meanwhile,
declining membership puts unionism's long-term viability in
question. The curious response by these beleaguered allies is to
oppose a GOP attempt to ease the national tax burden by a piddling
$80 billion over five years. This is less than 1 percent of all the
revenue Uncle Sam is expected to collect over this period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may be understandable for some pols to oppose tax cuts, but
why would an organization representing working folks favor the
government's interests over those of its members? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for this opposition is the assertion that the
money for the tax cut would come from budget surpluses owed to
Social Security. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recently dismissed the whole idea by saying, ``We can
pass the tax cut and then just dismantle the Social Security
system.'' The AFL-CIO ads warn that ``the Republican Congress wants
to spend this Social Security surpluseven as there's talk of
cutting Social Security for future retirees.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments are what make the opposition's position bogus.
It's true that this year's budget surplus probably will come
entirely from excess Social Security tax revenues. It's also true,
however, that the federal government cannot save any part of the
Social Security surplus. Most Americans don't understand how the
system works, though, which is why demagoguery of the Social
Security issue is worth a try for desperate politicos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the leftover Social Security receipts aren't returned to
taxpayers, Washington will spend the money just like it spends all
other tax receipts. (Either that or use it to retire maturing
federal debt.) The Social Security trust fund will get its usual
IOU in the form of a nonmarketable security to be redeemed as
needed later by future taxpayers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's important to remember is that not a dime of it can be put
aside for the benefit of current or future Social Security
beneficiaries. All that can be put aside is the IOUs that the
Treasury gives the trust fund. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for putting the needs of government above the needs of
taxpayers, here is something else that is true: Over the first 11
months of the 1998 fiscal year, federal revenue was nearly 10
percent higher than last year. How many American worker-taxpayers
can boast annual income gains of this magnitude? How many have
gotten raises of even half this much? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats and their handmaidens in organized labor were
politically astute, they'd be bashing the Republicans for their
Scrooge-like approach to tax relief. In fact, the GOP proposal
should be considered an embarrassment to a party that probably
enjoys its congressional majority because of past bold tax-relief
and reform efforts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those making a big deal of opposing it actually make this
pathetic GOP exercise look much more attractive than it really is. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
