<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-VOTE-ART-650(     09-27 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-VOTE-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ERA ENDS IN GERMANY AS SCHROEDER DEFEATS KOHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: GERMANY-VOTERS, GERMANY-EUROPE, GERMANY-KOHL)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN, Germany _ On Sunday, Gerhard Schroeder, a Social Democrat,
defeated Helmut Kohl to become German chancellor, ending an era in
Germany and opening a new one in Europe where center-left
governments now dominate the continent's politics.
</P>
<P>
   After a hard-fought campaign, the victory was decisive, a clear
expression of the weariness of Germans with Kohl's 16-year rule.
Schroeder swept aside the Christian Democrat chancellor who oversaw
the peaceful reunification of Germany in 1990 and personified the
Cold War's end in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With the defeat of Kohl, the last of the European politicians
who were in office when the Berlin Wall came down in 1989 has
departed, reflecting the new priorities that confront Europe as it
grapples with the competitive pressures of a global economy,
overburdened welfare systems and high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Like other center-left leaders in Europe, including Tony Blair
in Britain and Lionel Jospin in France, Schroeder will now have to
confront a central issue: how to adjust Germany's expensive welfare
system to global competition without dismantling it, and at the
same time create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in the post-war republic that Germans
voted a sitting chancellor out of office, and they did so with
gusto, dismissing Kohl's warnings of instability to usher in the
first Social Democratic chancellor of Europe's most powerful state
since Helmut Schmidt in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   When Schmidt left office, the main issue in Germany was the
deployment of medium-range U.S. missiles on German soil aimed at
the former Soviet Union _ a measure of the colossal distance
traveled in Germany and in Europe under Kohl, the longest-serving
German chancellor since Otto von Bismark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters have chosen a change of generation,'' Schroeder,
54, declared to a cheering crowd outside the Social Democratic
Party headquarters in Bonn. Schroeder had embodied youth during the
campaign, and a Germany less burdened by its past. It was on this
wave that he rode to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think politics is more psychological than rational, and this
result for us Germans is an injection of energy,'' said Henning
Frase, 20, a student. ``It is ridiculous, in a democracy, to have a
leader for as long as we had Kohl.''
</P>
<P>
   Born into poverty, Schroeder came into politics on the leftist
wave of the 1960s. But his outlook evolved toward pragmatism, and
he fought this campaign on an often vague platform of modernization
and renewal under the slogan of ``The New Middle'' and the clear
inspiration of Bill Clinton and Britain's Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   While Kohl pressed his vision of the rise from the ruins of
Nazism and his view of Germany's place in Europe on his countrymen,
Schroeder talked about jobs. The strategy worked because a new
generation of Germans is tired of history lessons and more
concerned that their society is fraying than they are about
geo-strategic threats.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder and his followers said many things at once _
reassuring businessmen with talk of lower taxes and the need to
reform the welfare system, while reassuring workers with promises
of better benefits and pensions _ and the first months in office
may confront him with wrenching choices between divergent campaign
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining an estimated 41.2 percent of the vote, up from 36.4
percent at the last election in 1994, the Social Democrats
inflicted their most decisive victory ever over the Christian
Democrats, whose vote plunged more than 6 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only once before, under Willy Brandt in 1972, had the Social
Democrats gained more votes than their principal rival.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what kind of government Schroeder
would form. Computer predictions suggested he would have a narrow
majority in the 656-member Bundestag, or parliament, in a coalition
with the environmentalist Greens, the party with which he has said
he wants to govern.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such a ``Red-Green'' coalition has never been tried since the
Federal Republic was established in 1949. In what has been a
conservative country, where repeated upheaval has spawned an
aversion to risk, the coalition would mark a radical departure.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens have, in the past, called for a review of Germany's
NATO membership, causing concern in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, however, vowed continuity in foreign policy. He also
promised to foster reconciliation in a country still divided
between the West and its formerly communist East, and said his most
important goal would be the fight ``against the plague of
unemployment.'' More than 4 million people in Germany, or 10.6
percent of the population, are out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Two central transformations of German society set in motion
under Kohl will now have to be completed by Schroeder: the return
next year of the captial to Berlin, 44 years after Hitler's defeat,
and the abandonment in 2002 of the German mark, symbol of post-war
stability, for a European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not opt for an alliance with the Greens, the
alternative for Schroeder would be a so-called ``Grand Coalition''
with the Christian Democrats, an unwieldy alliance not tried for
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl already has dismissed this possibility, saying the
electorate ``has clearly opted for Red-Green.'' And Kohl's finance
minister, Theo Waigel, said such a coalition would be ``absolutely
the wrong way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared clear that, having suffered an overwhelming defeat,
the Christian Democrats were determined to allow Schroeder to
confront Germany's problems without them, hoping to benefit from
the difficulties he is almost certain to encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl made clear in a statement that he would abandon the
leadership of the Christian Democrats. He said he would ask the
next party congress to propose a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe that Kohl made a fundamental mistake in
seeking a fifth term himself, rather than passing the mantle to his
deputy, Wolfgang Schauble. Several opinion polls have shown
Schauble to be the most popular politician in Germany, while Kohl's
lack of popularity was driven home by the fact that on Sunday he
lost his home seat of Ludwigshafen to a Social Democrat on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary turnabout for the leader universally
hailed just eight years ago when Germany was reunited. But
unification has proved more costly and difficult than foreseen, and
the tensions it engendered certainly contributed to Kohl's
downfall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
