<HEADER>
A6784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD-500     09-27 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD STILL EMBRACING CLINTON, SCANDAL AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-HILLARY-POLITICS, CLINTON-JONES,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-STRATEGY.) 
(nk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ Madonna dropped in on Saturday night at a
Democratic fund-raiser in Beverly Hills honoring President Clinton.
Barbra Streisand defended Clinton the other day and said that many
of the greatest presidents seem to have had affairs, too. And David
Geffen and other moguls said that Clinton's personal life was his
own business.
</P>
<P>
   They still adore Bill Clinton in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   No president, including John F. Kennedy, has worked the powerful
and rich Democratic establishment in Hollywood like Clinton. While
several Democrats here are privately upset, most of them, at least
publicly, are still firmly behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He outdoes JFK,'' remarked Lew Wasserman, the 85-year-old
former chairman of MCA Inc., and the dominant Democratic mogul and
fund-raiser here since the days of Harry S. Truman. ``He works the
crowd here, and he sees them as friends. They genuinely like him.
There's no decline in support. So he made a mistake. He said he was
sorry. What else can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Like other Democrats, Clinton has come to Hollywood in recent
years with hat-in-hand to raise campaign money from the swarm of
wealthy liberal Democrats in the entertainment business. Saturday
night was no exception: He attended a dinner at the mansion of Haim
Saban, co-owner of Fox Kids Worldwide Inc., that raised $1.5
million for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other Democrats, who sometimes privately resent the
posturing of what one top producer here termed ``rich, liberal
do-gooders,'' Clinton seems, by all accounts, to enjoy coming here,
and not only for the money.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hollywood community, at least the Democratic part of it,
seems to see the president as one of their own. Part of it is
generational _ many of the most powerful people are members of the
baby boom, just like Clinton. And, on a personal level, Clinton is
thoroughly identifiable to many people here _ not only his charisma
and star qualities, but his complicated marriage to a powerful
woman, his compromises and, of course, his scandalous behavior with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a set of contradictions, and many of those
contradictions work quite well within the moral structure of
Hollywood,'' said Marshall Herskovitz, a Democrat who was producer
of the television series ``thirtysomething,'' and is now a film
director. ``The scandal is really a referendum on sexual morality
in the country. Those people whose sexual morality accepts the
possibility of complexity and ambivalence in a marital relationship
have not judged Clinton as badly as those who see marriage as a
monolithic simple entity. And in Hollywood, marriage is often not
seen as a monolithic simple entity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Daniel, a producer and activist Democrat, put it more
bluntly. ``Hollywood has seen worse,'' he said. ``When it comes to
private matters, Hollywood has made its peace with far more
scandalous behavior. And there's an understanding here that you can
have a messed-up private life and still do good work.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, Clinton's personal tastes and style seem to mirror
(like few presidents) the tastes and style of many of those
executives and even stars, like Ms. Streisand, Tom Hanks, Steven
Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg, Rob Reiner and others, who support
him. Clinton, for example, gave Ms. Lewinsky an Annie Lennox CD,
listens to Sarah McLachlan, the Canadian singer and Lilith Fair
founder, and was the first president to invite a rock musician, Lou
Reed, to perform at a state dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tinge of show business about Clinton, and people
here recognize that,'' said Larry Gelbart, a Democrat, who created
the television show, ``M.A.S.H.,'' and co-wrote the film,
``Tootsie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His glamour is almost in his ordinariness _ he hasn't got
Kennedy's dash or classic good looks. But there's something about
him that people recognize here. He likes a walk on the wild side.
And he doesn't feel he sullies himself by going around with actors
or glamorous people.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Marty Kaplan, who is former chief speechwriter for
Vice President Walter Mondale, has written screenplays (''The
Distinguished Gentleman'') and is now associate dean at the
University of Southern California Annenberg School for
Communications, said Clinton, flaws and all, was the perfect
Hollywood president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to cast the presidency, they want to cast it
with someone who's idealistic, young and energetic _ and Clinton is
happy to fill that need,'' said Kaplan. ``Sure, people are
privately feeling devastated or betrayed or hurt. Somehow, it's one
part Capra film, one part Michael Douglas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's most fervent high-profile supporters are
unwavering, although one of them, Steve Tisch, a producer and
member of the wealthy Tisch family, said that, for the moment, he
wanted to curtail campaign contributions. ``I've got to respect
someone and the process a lot more before I start writing checks,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others said privately that Clinton's support in Hollywood was
actually paper-thin, and that if his favorable poll ratings fall
sharply, the Hollywood community will follow suit. ``If Clinton
becomes an embarrassment, this town will drop him like a hot potato
because Hollywood does not like to be embarrassed; it likes to be
cool, it likes to be with a winner,'' said David Horowitz, a
Republican who is president of the Center for the Study of Popular
Culture, a conservative-oriented group based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But others made it plain that they were far more offended by
Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr than Clinton _ and
that their support for the president was resolute. ``People
understand what this whole thing is about _ most people feel
there's a big difference between running the country and one's
private life,'' said Geffen, a co-founder of Dreamworks and a
prominent Clinton supporter who, like others here, have stayed
overnight at the White House. ``Even though his private behavior is
regrettable, his handling of the country is exemplary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Streisand said, ``The Republicans want to impeach! Impeach
for what? What they can't stand is that this president disagrees
with their agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to say that former presidents, ranging from Thomas
Jefferson to Kennedy, also had extramarital affairs but that the
press no longer ``respected the boundaries between public and
private behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's friendships with such figures as Geffen, Spielberg and
Katzenberg, who own Dreamworks, has led to reports and speculation
that the president would one day move to Los Angeles and work at
the company. There have also been reports that Dreamworks and Tom
Hanks were planning to buy a home for the Clintons. Andy Spahn,
head of corporate affairs for Dreamworks, said, ``There's no truth
to any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The $5,000-per-person dinner at the home of Saban Saturday night
included such entertainment figures as Madonna, who stayed briefly;
Berry Gordy, the founder of Motown; and Mimi Rogers, the actress.
Sen. Barbara Boxer, who is in a tough re-election fight, as well as
Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic gubernatorial candidate, were
among the politicians who also attended the event. Clinton did not
directly discuss the scandal but cited the ``rancor of Washington''
which, he said, ``undermines what we so desperately need in this
country now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton is hardly universally welcomed in Hollywood.
Actor Charlton Heston, a Republican, spoke acidly about Hollywood's
identification with Clinton. ``Hollywood is a fairly active town
sexually,'' he said. ``The community has been overwhelmingly
left-liberal for a long time. They'd be disinclined to turn away
from Clinton or take this sex issue very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   And Frank Price, a former studio chief who describes himself as
a liberal Republican, said he was dismayed _ but not too surprised
_ at the double standards of Hollywood. Take the V-chip, he said,
which is supported by the administration and designed to restrict
children's access to certain television programming. ``Had a
Republican administration tried to put through something like this,
the cries of outrage in Hollywood would have been deafening,'' he
said. ``With Clinton it was muted.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Lionel Chetwynd, a writer and director who is a
Republican, echoed the views of even the most fervent Clinton
supporters. ``He's an extension of their own personalities,'' said
Chetwynd. ``They're very comfortable with him. His flaws are very
understandable to them and very digestable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
