<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE MAY VOTE ON MODERNIZING FINANCIAL SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, efforts to lift Depression-era
regulations on the nation's financial services industry have come
to no avail. But that may end this week, as a measure to modernize
the industry, one long written off as dead, is showing remarkable
signs of life in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The financial services businesses lobbied heavily late last week
and over the weekend, as the Senate prepared to vote this week on
the measure, which would make it easier for banks, brokers and
insurance companies to merge into huge financial conglomerates. By
last count, it appeared that the Senate leadership was close to
corralling the 60 votes needed to cut off any filibuster and allow
for a floor vote on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, compromises carefully worked out between
insurance agents, consumer groups, Wall Street executives and
bankers appeared to be holding, though some outstanding issues
remained to be resolved. ``The odds are favoring getting the bill
to the floor and it passing,'' said Kenneth Guenther, lobbyist for
the Independent Bankers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would put into law what the marketplace, in large part,
is already doing: It would provide for the creation of huge
financial conglomerates able to underwrite securities, sell
insurance and take bank deposits, all under one roof. It would do
so by overturning the Glass-Steagall Act, written during the
Depression, and the Bank Holding Company Act, written in the 1950s,
that erected walls between commercial and investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed this measure by a single vote in May, and its
backers are racing to gain Senate approval before Congress adjourns
in October. ``Time is our main enemy right now,'' a Wall Street
lobbyist said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders are trying to work out as many problems as
possible so the bill can be considered on the floor with few
disruptions. At the same time, the lobbying machine is cranking up:
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. is planning radio ads in Washington on the
morning Don Imus program; insurance agents across the country plan
to work on grass-roots telephone banks, and a letter has been sent
by 50 top financial executives to all senators warning of dire
financial consequences if the bill is not passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply must modernize our own financial system,'' the
letter says, ``if America is going to credibly advocate financial
sector reform in Japan, Southeast Asia and other parts of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Those signing it included Jon Corzine of Goldman, Sachs; Harvey
Golub of American Express; Richard Grasso of the New York Stock
Exchange and David Komansky of Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The main obstacle appears to be Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who
opposes expansion of government requirements that financial
services companies provide low-cost banking services to low- and
moderate-income consumers. He has threatened to ``body block'' the
bill with a filibuster, several lobbyists say, if it is not
modified.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues still in play include a provision that would
prevent savings and loans from being sold to commercial businesses;
Washington Mutual, the largest savings and loan, is leading a
battle against this. Efforts are also under way to smooth out a
dispute between banks and insurance agents over the regulation of
bank sales of insurance products.
</P>
<P>
   A big obstacle to the bill's becoming law is a threatened veto
by President Clinton over a provision that favors the Federal
Reserve in the financial regulatory structure at the expense of the
office of the comptroller of the currency, a branch of the Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
   But many say that Clinton will be hard pressed to make good on
that threat because of current global economic turmoil. And amid
impeachment talk, the president needs the support of congressional
Democrats who are behind the measure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the bill clears the Senate, it would land on the president's
desk just about the time a meeting of international central bankers
called by the Fed and the Treasury Department to address the global
financial crisis convenes in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One of its main topics is a push by U.S. officials for other
countries to modernize their financial services industries _ making
it difficult for Clinton to veto a bill to do just that in the
United States. ``How can the president veto the bill while asking
others to modernize their financial systems,'' a banking lobbyist
said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``It would undermine our
ability to restore world financial confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
