<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-REPORT-MEDIA-(2     09-27 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-REPORT-MEDIA-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POST-LEWINSKY WINNER IS THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LISA NAPOLI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Longtime users of the Internet often laugh when mainstream media
talk about ``defining moments for the Net.'' To them, it was
defined long ago.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few weeks the Internet has done more than
promote discussion and information about a big news event, as it
did during last summer's Mars Pathfinder exploration or in the
aftermath of the death of Diana, princess of Wales. It has played a
pivotal role in news events _ the release of the Starr report and
President Clinton's videotaped testimony before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Each medium has created its own dynamics, its own archetypes and
behavior. Movies led to the cult of the movie star and the movie
buff, radio to the news broadcast, television to the couch potato
and the talking heads. What hints of the future lay in the coverage
of the Lewinsky matter on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   _ Television Transcends the Den. Video of the president's grand
jury testimony appeared on World Wide Web sites, creating a hefty
new audience: the workplace. Adam Clayton Powell 3rd of the Freedom
Forum in Arlington, Va., said, ``Think of all of the workplace
desks that have PCs but no TVs, and you begin to appreciate a very
large potential audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites of several cable channels claim wider online
viewership than their televised components. The Clinton testimony
underscored that the biggest concern for employers may soon not be
the time-wasting employee who makes personal phone calls. And
computer connections are usually faster at the office than they are
at home _ making it easier, for example, to watch the Clinton
testimony on line from the office desk than from the den.
</P>
<P>
   As the power of the traditional networks continues to erode and
competition for viewers increases among cable channels, media
brands are seeking alternate ways to keep their names in the public
eye. The Web is just one of them; CNN Interactive, for instance,
just renewed its deal to provide news headlines to Pager Net, a
beeper provider that has 1.4 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Citizen as Editor. So you didn't kill four hours watching the
Clinton testimony _ either on the television or on your personal
computer. Perhaps you actually had something more important to do.
Perhaps you couldn't stand the commentary. So, in the dark of
night, you signed on to the Web and went to your favorite source.
It might have been a site from a traditional news organization. Or
maybe it was America Online. And you downloaded the bits and pieces
you wanted to see. On the Alta Vista search engine, you could even
type in a key word or phrase and search the entire four-hour video
for it. ``Now,'' promises the site, ``you don't have to watch the
entire four hours of testimony or depend on others to spoon-feed
you sound bites.''
</P>
<P>
   With tools proliferating on the Net that allow users to pick and
choose sports scores, stock quotes and stories that are of
interest, the individual has greater control over news consumption
_ and particularly over the time when the consumption actually
takes place.
</P>
<P>
   All this draws attention to the pressure of the 24-hour news
cycle. Tutored by CNN in the early 1980s, viewers learned to expect
news more on their own timetables. The Internet intensifies the
process. Television networks are no longer competing against only
one another, but with expanding offerings on their own and others'
Web sites, including those of newspapers. Newspapers must now
grapple with how to unload information in the course of the day,
rather than hoarding it until the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Digital Water Cooler. Once the cultural Zeitgeist was
reflected in the nightly Johnny Carson monologue or a ``Saturday
Night Live'' weekend sketch. Now, office chit-chat has been
enhanced by digital jabs and jokes that arrive in the e-mail
in-box. Faster than you can say ``Office of the Independent
Counsel,'' jokes about the presidential liaison, in particular,
have been darting across the Net. Some of the recent notables
include a song that mixes Clinton's confessional speech on Aug. 17
with an updated version of an Elton John song; a photograph from
what was described as an ``actual parade in Germany'' in which a
float depicts a giant Clinton figure grabbing the breasts of a
buxom Statue of Liberty; and a video file of Clinton's nose
growing, Pinocchio-style, as his campaign promises are recounted to
the tune of ``My Favorite Things.''
</P>
<P>
   Once cartoons were clipped from the daily newspaper and pinned
on the cubicle wall. Today jokes spread farther and wider by simply
pressing the forward button. ``Look at how much people are
depending on the Net for news,'' said Bob Hirschfeld, a satirist
who posts jabs daily on his Web site. ``The same thing is happening
with topical humor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web also proves itself as a great place to spread
disinformation. Last week a flurry of e-mails quoted Kenneth Starr
as saying on a ``60 Minutes'' broadcast in 1987, ``Public media
should not contain explicit or implied descriptions of sex acts.''
The message was a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defining Sex. Internet publishers scratched their heads about
how to deal with the salaciousness of the president's testimony. It
raised the larger questions of how _ or whether _ to regulate the
content of the Net and what role news organizations must play
online.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting episode: MSNBC took flak for bleeping out one
section of the testimony involving the now-infamous cigar _ not on
its cable station, but on its Web site. Yet, after the live
broadcast, a Web surfer could log onto the site and pull up the
entire speech, unedited. Why was it all right to provide the
salacious material in one setting but not the other?
</P>
<P>
   Governing what gets said online has been a political hot potato
since the birth of the Net, but the Starr report and the Clinton
testimony may strengthen efforts in Congress to pass bills that
would fine even a news organization for posting content deemed
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what did most people read of the Starr report? The
dirty stuff. One ratings service found that more people read the
sections about sex than those about perjury.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _ Vox Populi. More each day, it often seems, the media culture
mirrors the surreal universe presented in the movie ``Network.''
There is no vein-popping Howard Beale commanding disgusted
television viewers to throw their television sets out the window,
but that is because with the growing popularity of online chat
rooms, who needs Howard Beale? For that matter, who needs to wait
on the phone to ask a question on ``Larry King Live'' or rant on a
local radio talk show?
</P>
<P>
   As the president's speech rolled, chat rooms on America Online
were filled to capacity and bulletin boards allowing expressions of
opinion there and on news Web sites overflowed. Not every event
elicits such passion, of course, but this one firmly establishes
the Net as the soapbox _ and barroom _ of our times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Triumph of the Nerds. Keep these players in mind:
Broadcast.com &UR;  &LR; and Real Networks, new media creatures that work on
the assumption that a network is not needed to broadcast video.
They present and aggregate video and audio events happening on the
Web, and they also provide technical help to the networks' Web
sites in times of great demand.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of live video on the Net is still primitive at worst
and unreliable at best, yet its sheer availability to anyone with
the proper gear is important. Wall Street clearly thinks so:
Broadcast.com's stock rose 22 percent on the day of the president's
taped broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rise of the On-Line Journalists. Since January, when the
one-man-band pundit and gossip Matt Drudge disclosed that Newsweek
was sitting on the Monica Lewinsky story, journalists have watched
in amazement as he has gained power. Now the host of his own
television show on Fox News, Drudge brags on his Web site that his
name came up six times in the Clinton testimony. He quotes the
president: ``Well, I had a little anxiety the next day, of course,
because of the Drudge Report.''
</P>
<P>
   The online magazine Salon, meanwhile, took heat for publishing a
report of an extramarital affair more than 30 years ago involving
Rep. Henry J. Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, who
is in charge of preliminary action toward impeachment proceedings
against the president. Salon's staff members had to evacuate their
offices because of a bomb threat, and they suffered a new type of
political vengeance. Protesters waged a ``fax attack,'' barraging
the magazine's machines in an effort to break them. And thousands
of e-mails from angry protesters clogged Salon's servers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXODUS-COX     09-27 1667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXODUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exodus International aims to change gay behavior
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On two Thursdays each month, Les Michael
hurries from his job as a landscaper to a bright pink church on
Conniston Road in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a regular in the support group meetings there for
five years. In rapid bursts loaded with religion and recovery, he
tells the half-dozen men around him of the torment he has endured
through 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   Michael speaks of his daily struggle against temptation and
relapse. He implores all to surrender to a higher power. The men
pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is hope,'' he says. ``There is a way out, and I have
found it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael and his group aren't trying to rid themselves of alcohol
or drug abuse. They seek to eliminate a behavior they believe is
just as destructive: homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The word behavior is essential to this meeting of the Worth
Creations ministry. Its followers think homosexuality is a behavior
rather than an orientation decided at birth. Their message is stop
having gay sex, and you stop being gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest misconception about us is that we are in denial,''
said Richard Culbertson, the group's director. ``If this is denial,
then that's fine with me because it works, and I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Culbertson, 59, said he rejected the gay lifestyle he was living
20 years ago and has been celibate since. In 1985, he formed Worthy
Creations and affiliated it with Exodus International, which for 25
years has served as the umbrella organization for scores of
ministries whose stated purpose is to turn gays straight.
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists argue that there is neither need nor justification
for turning people away from what they are and that the Exodus
movement is intolerant and homophobic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these folks operate on is that there's something wrong
with being the person you are,'' said Rebecca Isaacs of the
National Gay and Lesbian Task Force in Washington, D.C. ``For them,
it's not about freedom of choice but repression and brainwashing.
We would never condemn an individual who wants to be who they are.
Why do they?''
</P>
<P>
   Culbertson insists that he does not recruit clients from the gay
community. He says Worthy Creations exists only as an option for
those who want to change and offers them a bridge to return to the
traditional church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gay community has a lot of legitimate gripes against the
church,'' he said. ``For years, churches have said they've hated
the sin but loved the sinner. Yet they've also said we don't want
them in our churches. Because of Exodus, these people have been
able to find a way back to Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the sexual conversion movement was invigorated by a
national advertising campaign sponsored by the Center for
Reclaiming America, a conservative Christian ministry founded in
Fort Lauderdale by D. James Kennedy. Culbertson has his office in
the Federal Highway building operated by Kennedy's Coral Ridge
Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most exciting time for us I can remember,''
Culbertson said. ``Up until now, we've been the best-kept secret in
South Florida. But with Reclaiming America's help, we're getting
our message out and letting people know that there is hope for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of a ``truth in love'' campaign, the Center for
Reclaiming America spent more than $200,000 for full-page ads in
USA Today, the New York Times and the Washington Post. It is the
beginning of a media blitz that is aimed at the fall elections and
has the financial and spiritual blessings of groups such as the
Christian Coalition, Concerned Women for America, the Family
Research Council and the American Family Association.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign grew from criticism leveled at pro football
player Reggie White and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott over
recent statements on homosexuality. Lott likened it to an
addiction; the Green Bay Packers' White referred to it as ``one of
the biggest sins in the Bible'' in a speech to the Wisconsin
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Reclaiming America said it has launched its
counteroffensive in the interest of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anyone tell you it isn't a homophobic campaign,''
Isaacs said. ``The right saw this as a really good issue to take
into the November elections. They always have to have one major
enemy, one scapegoat. Communism is dead. How about gay people?''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa McWhorter, executive director of Compass Inc., Palm Beach
County's gay services organization, takes issue with the Exodus
call for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that there's nothing to convert people
to or from,'' McWhorter said. ``But if it's a religious belief,
everyone in this country has a right to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists and medical professionals also have voiced opposition
to the Exodus approach. The nation's largest society of
psychologists last year passed a resolution aimed at discrediting
therapeutic practices that attempt to change sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The American Psychological Association, by a vote of 106-4,
renounced conversion therapy and endorsed the American Psychiatric
Association position that homosexuality is not a mental illness
that needs fixing. Both groups say conversion attempts are
ineffective and can be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science may be inconclusive,'' Culbertson said. ``But if
you're able to change your lifestyle, then that change is
conclusive for you. For me, this is conclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Culbertson says he has no statistical evidence on how successful
Worthy Creations has been through its 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the scientific resources to keep tabs on
people,'' he said. ``But I know of dozens of people who have
changed their lifestyle. Some have gotten married, had children and
raised families.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of the people who come to Worthy Creations
meetings are male. Groups meet in Miami Beach, Fort Lauderdale and
in West Palm Beach at the Lighthouse Christian Center. Those who
attend quote scripture and offer personal testimonies much like a
12-step program. Exodus claims to have counseled 200,000 nationally
since 1976; Culbertson says about 500 people participate in his
ministry each year and that he has reached ``several thousand'' in
its 14-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that women have a much harder time getting out because
of the emotional bonds they form,'' Culbertson said. ``The reason
most people fail is because of a lack of resolve. It is like an
alcoholic in some respects. You get to a point where you want to
change, but you go out and fall again.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond treating homosexuality as a psychological disorder,
conversion ministries also regard it as a moral transgression, a
sin: ``We base our presentation on the Bible, which states clearly
that homosexual behavior is not in God's plan for men and women,''
Exodus states in published literature. ``We're not condemning
anyone. At the same time, it isn't unloving to talk about sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Professing a different theological view is the Universal
Fellowship of Metropolitan Community Churches, a California-based
Christian ministry that embraces gay, bisexual and trans-gender
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scripture Exodus always quotes is from the Old
Testament,'' said Frank Zerilli of Metropolitan's world center in
West Hollywood, Calif. ``Well, you can find people in the Old
Testament condemned for eating shrimp or condemned for eating
oysters or condemned for wearing different color clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is that Jesus said absolutely nothing on the
subject of sexual orientation. If it is so important to salvation,
why didn't he say something about it? He didn't because it doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   About 300 congregations in 19 countries have Metropolitan
Community affiliation, including churches in West Palm Beach,
Delray Beach and Boca Raton. The church was founded in 1968 and has
grown steadily, drawing followers who felt ostracized by more
conservative ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the church owes the gay community an apology,''
Culbertson said. ``The church has not reached out to them the way
it should have. They are the un-harvested harvest.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl, who asks that his surname be withheld, is a 40-year-old
construction contractor from Lake Worth. He is married with three
children and says he has engaged in homosexual sex before and
during his marriage. For the last six weeks, he has been attending
Worthy Creations meetings in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the church understood or was willing to help me
until I found this group,'' Earl said. ``When I went to my pastor
and told him about my homosexual tendencies, he told me to go out
and have sex with a female prostitute. This way is much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael says he went through a decade of emotional turmoil after
he and his wife divorced in the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always had homosexual tendencies and urges, but I fell
into the gay lifestyle totally after my divorce,'' he said. ``I did
all the bath houses. I abused alcohol. I nearly overdosed on drugs.
I lost my job. I just wasn't happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sober for 14 years, Michael, a hyperactive man who puts Jesus in
most paragraphs, says he has found a serenity he never had until he
joined Worthy Creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only true fulfillment is in a relationship with Jesus
Christ,'' he said. ``My friends in the gay community think I'm a
turncoat. But this is what I want and what I need. I have never met
a homosexual who was really happy _ really happy in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael says he still has occasional twinges of attraction
toward men but that those have diminished through the years. He
said he has made two attempts to have relationships with women, but
those quickly failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exodus is not for everybody,'' he said. ``You have to want to
change. Once you do, you learn that you can have something that's
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael said he is celibate and hopes to remain so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
