<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-HOUSE-RACE-ART-8     09-27 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-HOUSE-RACE-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOP, RARE HOPE IN BOULDER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
Colorado's 2nd Congressional District is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Could Boulder, the liberal lighthouse of the
Rockies, send a Republican to Congress?
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a quarter century, Colorado's 2nd District has been a
safe seat for Democrats _ and an altar for Republican sacrificial
lambs. The last Republican to run from this district, Pat Miller,
vowed to be the ``voice'' of paramilitary groups in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But now the GOP have fielded Robert Greenlee, a moderate who
favors abortion rights and enjoys a wide following as Boulder's
first Republican mayor since 1971. A self-made millionaire,
Greenlee, 57, has deep pockets to finance his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, Mark Udall, who is in his first term as a
state representative, is mounting what appears to be an equally
strong candidacy. An heir to the Udall Western political legacy
forged by his father, Morris, a former congressman, and uncle,
Stewart, who was Interior Secretary as well as a congressman, the
48-year-old Udall enjoys fervent support from local and national
environmental groups. An avid mountain climber in a district where
outdoor recreation is king, Udall directed the Colorado Outward
Bound School for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   No opinion polls have been taken, but among Colorado's six House
races, this one is seen as the only truly competitive race this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have two of the most progressive people in state politics
running against each other,'' said Timothy Wirth, a liberal
Democrat who represented this district from 1974 to 1986. ``It's
now going to be an extremely interesting race.''
</P>
<P>
   Both national parties focused on the district immediately after
David Skaggs, the Democratic incumbent, announced last year that he
would not run for re-election after completing his sixth term. A
liberal stalwart of the House, Skaggs has received a near perfect
voting rating from liberal groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans took aim at the seat, noting it was one of only
16 nationwide where Democratic incumbents were not seeking
re-election. The Democrat Party is determined to hold onto the
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a race we are pretty excited about,'' said Thomas
Eisenhauer, a political strategist from the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, who traveled from Washington to
attend a debate between the two candidates on Wednesday. ``Mark is
a really strong candidate who proved in the primary he can raise
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Udall was a long shot this year when he won a crowded primary,
defeating better known candidates in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Udall's image is not of a strict Democratic partisan, but much
more of a thinking environmentalist,'' said Floyd Ciruli, president
of a polling and political consulting company in Denver. ``Udall
not only has the cachet of the name, but also the ability to raise
money around the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   That ability is a special asset in this race, said Ciruli, who
predicted that it would be the most expensive House campaign in
Colorado history, costing about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The district centered on Boulder is no longer a safe seat for
Democrats because of several factors. The seven states in the Rocky
Mountain State time zone arguably have become the nation's most
consistently Republican region, with only three Democrats serving
in the House _ Reps. Skaggs, Diana DeGette of Colorado's First
District, which includes Denver, and Ed Pastor of Arizona's Second
District. Republicans also control the legislatures in six of the
seven states, the exception being New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade in Colorado, Republicans have become the
party with the largest number of registered voters, 35 percent to
30 percent. In that time, the Congressional delegation has shifted
from an even balance to 6-2 favoring the Republicans. In the 2nd
District, once firmly Democratic, voter registration gives the
party only a small edge over the Republicans, 32 percent to 30
percent. The rest are independents.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic control of the seat here dates to 1974, when the
party's candidates were swept into office around the nation, riding
a wave of anger over Watergate and President Richard M. Nixon, who
had just resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a parallel, but I don't think that Clinton's
problems resonate in the same way that Nixon's problems resonated
with voting public,'' said Paul Talmey, president of a Boulder
polling company. ``Today, the world is at peace, the economy is
doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hourlong debate between Udall and Greenlee on Wednesday,
and the question-and-answer session that followed, the subject of
President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky never came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very good sign,'' Udall said. ``Last night, I was
out knocking on doors, and it came up a few times. Mostly to say,
`We are sick of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate, Greenlee said: ``I don't intend on using it
in my campaign. But it's like a 350-pound gorilla. It's out
there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Addressing a business audience, Greenlee painted himself as an
entrepreneur who had ``started 12 businesses'' and fought
``government regulations.'' He called for overhauling the Internal
Revenue Service, paying down the national debt, instituting a
system in which government vouchers could be used to pay for
private schooling, and giving more opportunities to people in
contrast to the government.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed his success in building two of the Denver area's
largest radio stations and a major restaurant chain. Apparently out
of deference to the religious right, his campaign literature does
not mention that he also is a major investor in Colorado's largest
casino.
</P>
<P>
   In a deliberate appeal to the lesser-known side of the 2nd
District, Greenlee has placed his campaign headquarters not in
Boulder, but in Broomfield, a fast growing suburb where
high-technology companies are setting up shop.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Coloradans are to vote an initiative that would
make Broomfield the state's first new county in 85 years.
</P>
<P>
   Voting registration records in the 2nd District show that more
newcomers are registering Republican than Democrat. Udall, aware
that the district is still dominated by the University of
Colorado's largest campus, called for strengthening public
education.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, Udall came off as a more polished campaigner than
his adversary, who has served on the Boulder City Council for the
last 15 years. While answering questions from the audience, Udall
managed to tip his hat to two locally prominent Democrats attending
the debate, a county attorney and a state senator, and to mention
that his 74-year-old mother, Pat, is a Colorado native and a
resident of Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Still, without opinion polls, it is unclear who has the
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a lifelong Democrat, but for the first time in my life, I
don't know who I will vote for,'' said Russell Shaw, a systems
theory consultant, who attended the debate. ``They are offering
different philosophies. Udall is trying to fix things. Greenlee is
trying to empower citizens, instead of the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
