<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMINICAN-SOSA-0928-C     09-27 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-SOSA-0928-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STRUGGLING TO COPE IN AFTERMATH, DOMINICANS LOOK TO 'SAMMY' FOR
INSPIRATION
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO de MACORIS, Dominican Republic _ As Sammy Sosa came to
bat for the final time Sunday, the crowd of about 150 men in what
may have been the only place here, in his hometown with a working
television set chanted: ``Sammy! Sammy! Sammy!''
</P>
<P>
   The pool players stopped their games and crowded around the
large screen over the bar in the pool hall with the unusual name,
``Florimar Car Wash.''
</P>
<P>
   With a flash of his bat, Sosa hit a towering drive deep into
centerfield. The crowd shrieked with excitement, the noise so loud
it made peoples' ears ring. But as the ball sank for a long fly
out, the cheers turned to moans and cries of ``Oh, no!''
</P>
<P>
   For many in the bar, the chance to watch Sosa's bid to catch
homerun king Mark McGwire in the last regular season game for Major
League Baseball -- though unsuccessful -- was a brief respite from
the struggle to put their lives back together since Hurricane
Georges crashed through here Tuesday killing at least 200 people,
and leaving more than 250,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   San Pedro is on the eastern end of the island of Hispaniola --
which the Dominican Republic shares with Haiti -- and bore much of
the brunt of the hurricane. Thousands of trees were toppled.
Buildings were crushed. Shattered signs lay twisted across
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Munoz, 22, had been repairing the roof on his home
with two friends when they stopped to watch the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the hurricane passed, we have been fixing and helping
people ... but this is important,'' Munoz said inside the
sweltering bar. ``A lot of people whose houses were knocked down,
they are here waiting for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside a sports betting parlor, Juan Richards, 28, listened to
the game intently through a small radio earpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Sammy Sosa is doing something grand. He is a hero for
us. He represents hope and success.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards, whose house was largely destroyed by Georges, said
listening to the game gave him a chance to briefly put aside his
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among all the bad, there is some good, and the good is Sammy
Sosa and this game today,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was frustration too. The electricity was out for the
fifth day and cable television was unavailable even in those
buildings were power was provided by a generator. In the betting
parlor, the men listlessly watched a television set showing a World
War II submarine movie. Florimar's bar had television through the
generosity of a consortium of television stations which provided
two satellite trucks to the town for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Sunday, on the streets of this gritty town of 120,000
life went on. Motorcycles, cars, trucks and an occasional
horse-drawn cart vied for the road. Men shovelled mounds of debris
into overloaded trucks. People gathered at outdoor cafes or sat
beside the open doors of houses and stores. In a plaza where Sosa
once shined shoes and washed cars, shoes were being shined and cars
were being washed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good for the future that God has given (Sosa).'' said
Eduard Torreano, 32, who once shined shoes and washed cars with
Sosa and now does it with others. ``He always comes back. We are
his people, he hasn't forgotten us.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tetelo Vargas stadium ``Home of the Dominican Big Leaguers,''
where Sosa once played baseball, young boys played stickball amid
toppled light towers and a collapsed centerfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is for Sammy,'' shouted an 11-year-old boy as he hit
what he claimed was his third home run of the day against his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they couldn't watch or listen to the game, Sosa was very
much on people's mind.
</P>
<P>
   At an outdoor pizzeria, patrons yelled ``Sammy Sosa,'' when a
couple of American reporters walked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to win,'' said Richard Clement, 32. ``Everybody in
San Pedro likes him. We feel good for Sammy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Rice Evanson, 48, sporting a Boston Red Sox baseball cap,
said ``Sammy has a big heart because he is believes in God and
feels for his country. He might live in North America, but he was
born in the Dominican Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Scattered around town were evidence of the people's devotion to
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   On the dirty rear window of a car heading for the city, someone
had written ``Sammy 65.''
</P>
<P>
   A motorcycle bore a sticker: ``Sammy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the window of the betting parlor, Sosa's name was written
with soap.
</P>
<P>
   At the 30-30 Plaza, a small horseshoe-shaped shopping center
which Sosa owns -- named Plaza 30-30, after his first 30-homer,
30-steal season -- a local radio station displayed a banner that
read ``step by step with Sammy.'' In the plaza's center, a small
statue of Sosa -- bat over his shoulder -- stood in a birdbath over
a non-working fountain.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that McGwire finished the season with an astounding 70
home runs -- four ahead of Sosa did not damped his countrymen's
support. Sosa has a final, though improbable chance of catching
McGwire Monday when the Chicago Cubs play the San Francisco Giants
in a sudden-death play-off game for the National League wildcard
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a lot of pride for Sosa, and I think tomorrow
when he wakes up that he will be able to do it,'' said David Milan
Rodriguez, 36, who was wearing a Sosa jersey. ``I have very strong
faith in Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sosa's 21-year-old younger brother, Carlos, the only member
of the family staying at the home Sosa built for his mother, said
he wouldn't be disappointed if McGwire finished first.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always said that McGwire is the man,'' Carlos said. ``He
is a hero here and it's not that important that he break the
record. That's more important to the American press.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Sosa said his brother -- who has already said he
would sell his 62nd home run ball to help the Dominican Republic --
cares about and will help his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy can only do so much because the infrastructure and
agriculture have been destroyed,'' the younger Sosa said, adding
that his brother's achievement as the second man to break the
homerun marks of 60 and 61 set by Babe Ruth and Roger Maris,
respectively, has been a tonic to this poor country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a symbol of hope and success.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
