<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside College Football: UCLA, Miami to make up game
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some fallout from the weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _ We have it on very good authority that UCLA and Miami will
make up their game, which was postponed last Saturday by Hurricane
Georges. Last Thursday Miami officials said the game was
``canceled'' and might not be played. They didn't count on the
immediate outcry from the football powers that be, who knew not
playing the game could potentially play havoc with the Bowl
Championship Series, especially if UCLA finishes 10-0. Take this to
the bank: The game will be played on Dec. 5, and CBS will get the
right of first refusal to broadcast the game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of CBS, it's hard to understand why the network
passed on this week's game between Georgia and LSU, two undefeated
teams, to show Tennessee and twice-beaten Auburn at 3:30 p.m.. But
here's the explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Word on the grapevine is that CBS really wanted to do
Florida-Alabama, but when the Crimson Tide crashed at Arkansas,
that plan was scrapped. Since the broadcast will be national
instead of regional, the network gurus went with Tennessee, which
already has big wins over Syracuse and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an extremely tough call, but we went with the
highest-ranked team (Tennessee) in a game we feel will be very
competitive,'' said Mike Aresco, the vice president for college
programming at CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is the beneficiary of this largess, and will show
Georgia-LSU at 7 p.m. Florida at Alabama, goes to Jefferson-Pilot
at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson and South Carolina are both 1-3 after ugly home losses
to Wake Forest (29-19) and Mississippi State (38-0) respectively.
But here's the real reason why the two coaches, Tommy West and Brad
Scott, are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   At Clemson's game, a crowd was generously ``announced'' at
60,000 fans, leaving at least 21,000 empty seats at Memorial
Stadium. And it doesn't figure to get much better as the Tigers are
getting into the meat of their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   At Columbia, only 70,052 fans showed up, the smallest crowd
since Williams-Brice Stadium expanded to 80,000 in 1996. And most
of those were gone by halftime, when the Gamecocks trailed 28-0.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches can survive a lot of things, but not empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning QB: Some things you might have missed
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Couch is talented, but very much in need of a reality
check. Kentucky has won exactly two SEC games _ Alabama and
Vanderbilt last season _ with Couch at quarterback. Still, Couch is
feeling very confident after Saturday's 51-35 loss to Florida. In
fact, he predicted the Wildcats would win the rest of their games
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we made a whole lot of improvement,'' said Couch, who
threw for 406 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, as a football team, we think we are
going to run the table. We think we are going to win the rest of
our games and have a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   That's bound to make a few bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Colorado was very lucky to escape with an 18-16 win over
Baylor late Saturday night. The Buffaloes blew a 15-3 lead and lost
quarterback Mike Moschetti to a sprained ankle. Down 16-15,
Colorado rallied behind Adam Bledsoe, Drew's younger brother, and
got a 31-yard field goal with two minutes left to win.
</P>
<P>
   _ Our leading candidate for understatement of the year comes
from Prairie View coach Greg Johnson. Prairie View ended its NCAA
record 80-game losing streak by beating Langston 14-12 Saturday
night. Prairie View's last previous victory was Oct. 28, 1989. Said
Johnson, a former Langston coach: ``It was well overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The best game you didn't see Saturday involved Mississippi,
which rallied from a 22-point deficit with 9:45 left and beat SMU
in overtime 48-41. ``Nine minutes shouldn't be enough time to score
that many points,'' Rebels coach Tommy Tuberville said. ``But
that's the way it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince and Barbara Dooley were among the 22,281 fans at the
Cotton Bowl to view the game. The Dooley's youngest son, Derek, is
an assistant coach at SMU for Mike Cavan, a former Georgia
assistant and player.
</P>
<P>
   _ The second best game you didn't see was the longest in NCAA
history as Bethune-Cookman needed eight overtimes to beat Virginia
State 63-57. It was especially heart breaking for Virginia State,
which rallied from 26 points down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
