<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves go out on high note; Mets go home
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The overture's last note sounded just as Mike Piazza's
pop-up settled into Tony Graffanino's glove for the 27th out, the
moment on Sunday that signaled the end of the beginning for the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   They whipped New York one more time, 7-2, winning for the
seventh straight time, for the 14th time in 16 games, taking the NL
East by 18 games. While their League Division Series opponent is
still TBA, the Braves hung up No. 106 on the season's last day,
signaling the preliminary round is over. Before the sun went down,
the bunting was hung at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preseason is over now,'' third baseman Chipper Jones said.
``We can settle in.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but this regular season cannot pass without mention of
the 11 primary franchise records and three Atlanta records set by
these Braves. Only eight National League teams this century have
reached 106 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he wished he could upgrade for the playoff's second
season, general manager John Schuerholz said, ``Nothing. I like who
we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about this club,'' said shortstop Walt Weiss,
``especially after the way we played just three weeks ago. I wasn't
too sure what to expect. But we really played well the last 10 days
or so. I definitely feel good about where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta terminated the Mets with a barrage of doubles. They hit
seven on Sunday, 13 during the three-game series. Doubles accounted
for six runs in the final game. That those 13 doubles came from 12
different Braves says something about the way the team enters the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux earned his 18th victory, and while he allowed five
hits and a run before the bullpen took over, he avoided his first
winless month since 1990. He finished the season with an NL-low
2.22 ERA. The pitching staff wound up allowing 15 earned runs in
the last 12 games (1.26).
</P>
<P>
   ``For guys in here, it's pretty special to win more games than
any team in franchise history,'' Jones said. ``But I think everyone
is focused on something further down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   No Braves team since 1900 scored more in a season that this one.
No Braves team ever had better fielding (97 error-less games). No
major league team in 73 years had a more balanced pitching staff.
And they finished the schedule on a dead sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``That what this team is all about -- the World Series,''
centerfielder Andruw Jones said. ``I think we have the team to do
it. And if we keep playing like we're playing right now, I think we
will get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
