</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1998 Braves not your usual team
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since beginning their run in 1991, the Braves have
annually tossed old paper out of their record book as the club's
performances improved with each season. But season, they have
pulled out hunks of history.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Braves broke 11 franchise record as well as an Atlanta
record and this time, it wasn't about pitching. It was about
everything else. These Braves hit with more power and fielded
better than any this century.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you can say the Atlanta Braves this year rely
solely on their pitching or rely solely on their hitting or
fielding or bullpen,'' said John Smoltz, who will start Game 1 of
Wednesday's League Division Series. ''We have a combination that
equated to 106 wins. When we've had guys who contributed things
this year on and off the field, you can't rely on one particular
area to win 106 games.
</P>
<P>
   Among the franchise records to fall:
</P>
<P>
   Runs (since 1900): 826. (Old record: 803 in 1964).
</P>
<P>
   Doubles: 297. (Old record: 284, 1987).
</P>
<P>
   Home runs: 215. (Old record: 207, 1966).
</P>
<P>
   Total bases: 2,483 (Old record: 2,425, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Extra-base hits: 538. (Old record: 489, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   RBI (since 1900): 794. (Old record: 758, 1973).
</P>
<P>
   Slugging percentage: 453. (Old record: 442, 1957).
</P>
<P>
   Most hit by pitch: 61. (Old record: 51, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Fewest errors: 91. (Old record: 108, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   Highest fielding average: .985 (Old record: .983, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   Most error-less games: 97. (Old record: 90, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta records:
</P>
<P>
   Most runs: 826. (Old record: 799, 1973).
</P>
<P>
   Tied highest batting average: .272. (Set 1983).
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a good season,'' said Chipper Jones. ''Everybody had a
good season.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster making
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will not make up the roster for the League Division
Series until late Monday or Tuesday but will wait until the
deadline of 9 a.m. Wednesday to file it with the National League
office.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no need to (file before then),'' manager Bobby Cox
said. ''It'd be crazy to do it because you can't change it once
it's in. We could go out Tuesday and somebody gets hurt and if
you're already submitted, you're put of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   No rest
</P>
<P>
   Cox didn't order the Braves to work out today. The weatherman
did.
</P>
<P>
   ''Normally, I'd give them a day off Monday,'' Cox said, ''but
Tuesday with the
</P>
<P>
   rain coming in, there's a great chance we may not get on the
field. We can get on (today) but maybe not Tuesday and maybe not
even the start of the playoffs (Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the club will work out at noon. Plans for Tuesday have
not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's take
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux reached 18 victories for the seventh time in his
career and his 2.22 ERA wound up the fifth lowest he has posted in
his 12-year career. This is the same pitcher who just came out of a
five-game winless streak.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll take some time off,'' said Maddux, who is not scheduled
to pitch until Game 3 of the LDS on Saturday. ''But mentally and
physically, I think I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   While that news rang gladly through the clubhouse, it was not
the best sign that Maddux saw over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good to see (second baseman Keith) Lockhart and
(shortstop Walt) Weiss out there at the same time,'' Maddux said.
''That's a big lift for us. Those two guys are a huge reason why we
won a lot of games in April and May, a huge reason. We got them
back together.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lockhart and Weiss started this season, the Braves went
42-16.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
