</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BISHER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets needed pinch-hitter in 2nd
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that it was all said and done, there was little
left to say or do, if you're thinking Braves. I did hear somebody
drop this little pearl about Bobby Valentine, the Mets manager who
holds himself in high esteem: ``If Bobby Valentine had known it was
going to be this way, he'd never have invented baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody asked me, but I could have helped the little
genius Sunday afternoon. Last game of the season, one game back of
the Cubs and Giants, one last gasp left. Mets load the bases in the
second inning and the pitcher, Armando Reynoso, coming to bat with
two out. The Mexican from San Luis Potosi has never beaten the
Braves, the team that brought him to the major leagues, and they
already have touched him for a run in the first inning. Pinch-hit
for him. The Mets still had a chance, slim as it was. You need
desperately to win. You need runs. You've got a dugout full of
fresh arms and they've got all winter to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso grounds out, three runs die on base. The Braves take him
apart the next inning. They bat around and score six runs, and the
big hit is delivered by Greg Maddux. He scorches one to the center
field wall, drives in a run and wins the ``Silver Slugger,'' a
trophy limited to the private pitching club. When Maddux
punch-bunted a single the next time up, he nailed it down. His
booming average was .240.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we have seen why the Mets fell from grace, suppose we
take a look at a crowded Sunday afternoon. Television is trying to
cover Mark McGwire in St. Louis, Sammy Sosa in Houston, an almost
no-hitter by a rookie named Halladay pitching for Toronto,
automobile racing, two golf tournaments, and happily, Bill Clinton
had the day off. It was like a thunderstorm breaking out over your
head.
</P>
<P>
   The screen flashed to St.Louis and McGwire hit another home run,
his 69th. He had tied Joe Hauser, who hit 69 in Minneapolis, and
Bob Crues, who hit 69 in one of those West Texas minor leagues.
Sosa drove in a run for the Cubs with a single, as big as any home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Miko Haakinen won a Formula One race on some side of another
continent. A NASCAR race was roaring on. NFL football scores
flashed across the screen. The despondent Washington Redskins were
getting trumped again. Terry Mulholland, the pitcher, drove in a
pair of runs for the Cubs. (See, Bobby Valentine?)
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit another home run, his 70th. He had passed Hauser and
Crues, but he wouldn't catch Joe Bauman. Joe is the old first
baseman/filling station guy who hit 72 in the Longhorn League. In
138 games. Let McGwire try that. Too bad, so sad for Sammy, as the
home runs fall, but he had bigger fish to try.
</P>
<P>
   Down in his private box, Ted Turner had come to celebrate the
ending of another bumptious season. The Braves were rollicking
along and Bobby Cox was clearing the bench. In the old minor
leagues, some managers would give players a chance to play any
position they wanted to on the last day of the season. Nothing at
stake. Have fun.
</P>
<P>
   In Charlotte, a Washington farm club then, the catcher had said,
``I can pitch better than some of these guys I'm catching.'' So he
got his chance to pitch on closing day. The game went 22 innings
and Red Barbary, the catcher, not only pitched the distance, he
drove in the winning run. Sadly, he also had thrown his arm away,
and a promising career with it. Clark Griffith, who owned the
Senators, fired the manager. Red Barbary went back to the mill team
in South Carolina, but he lived happily ever after. And still does.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor for the Atlanta Journal,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
