<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-600&AMP;ADD     09-27 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN POLITICIANS SEE NO DEAL BETWEEN CONGRESS AND PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Ark., Mass.)  (See also: CLINTON-HILLARY-POLITICS, CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD,
CLINTON-JONES, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-STRATEGY.) 
(lh) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Democrats and the White House, buoyed by polls,
sharpened their attacks against Republicans Sunday, three veteran
politicians said that there would be no deal between President
Clinton and Congress until after the Nov. 3 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nonstarter,'' Bob Dole, a former presidential candidate
and Senate majority leader, said on the NBC program ``Meet the
Press.'' ``Look down the road three or four months, who knows, but
now it's a nonstarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's remarks met with agreement from Howard Baker, also a
former Senate Republican leader, and Leon Panetta, Clinton's former
White House chief of staff, who said the election's outcome posed a
more immediate dilemma for Clinton than the specter of impeachment.
All three men have been mentioned as possible mediators between
Congress and the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election is going to tell us a lot more what happens here
with regards to the impeachment process than the impeachment
process itself,'' Panetta said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans win seats, especially in the Senate, ``I
think that's trouble for the president,'' Panetta said. If
Democrats win seats, he said, ``I think there is a much better
chance that this issue will be settled sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Heartened by recent national surveys that show a backlash
against Republicans for their handling of the scandal and for
releasing mounds of documents with lurid detail, Democrats
continued to float alternatives to impeachment Sunday, displaying
relief at the latest turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   His own confidence brimming anew, Clinton has now taken to
lashing out at Republicans for putting ``partisanship over
progress, politics over people,'' as he said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans bristle at the charge, saying they are busy passing
legislation, including tax cuts and spending bills, while Clinton
is off raising money, trying to change the subject and stirring up
partisan animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just more of their pattern of conduct that goes all
the way back to Arkansas, a pattern of conduct that's been
established now by Ken Starr of lying, of covering-up, of
stonewalling, and destroying your enemies,'' Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas, the Republican whip, said on the ABC program ``This Week
With San Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee has scheduled a vote in early October on
whether to go forward with an impeachment inquiry. This vote, if
successful, would be followed by a full House vote. If the
resolution passes the House, the committee would begin the
fact-finding and hearing phase of its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to avoid impeachment hearings at this
point,'' Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., who is on the panel, said on
``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking their cue from Clinton, his advisers and supporters
stepped up their campaigns Sunday and challenged Republicans to
make a decision as soon as possible on whether there is enough
evidence to impeach the president. If not, they said, the matter
should be dropped without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who has been extremely critical
of the president's behavior, on Sunday gave Clinton her strongest
backing since his controversial Aug. 17 speech and painted the
impeachment proceedings as unjustifiably partisan. Judging from the
evidence so far, Ms. Feinstein said, the president should not be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to me so far that's come out to say that this
reaches the level of impeachment, where affairs of state, matters
of state, public policy are impacted in any way, shape or form by
this,'' Ms. Feinstein said on ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Carville, Clinton's adviser and most tenacious supporter,
took aim on the same program at the Whitewater independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, and also unloaded a volley of accusations against
Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporal Cue Ball Carville will be rolling into battle against
Newt Gingrich,'' Carville said. ``Because Newt Gingrich, this
entire thing has been under the orchestration, supervision and
direction of Newt Gingrich and Ken Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fought back by shifting the focus to the impeachment
proceedings. ``I don't read the polls,'' DeLay said, ``I read the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic offensive, with Clinton and his wife leading
the charge, did not sit well with all Democrats, some of whom
worried about antagonizing the very members of Congress who will
decide the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts said he wished the Clintons had
not chosen to attack Republicans. ``I don't think that was
advisable,'' Kerry said on the CBS program ``Face the Nation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
