</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-U.S.-COHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN EXPRESSES GUARDED OPTIMISM OVER BOSNIAN ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Secretary of Defense William
Cohen said on Sunday that the national elections here created
``some room for optimism'' for the future of Bosnia's shattered
society. However, he warned that Bosnian leaders had to make more
progress or risk losing international support.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, the highest ranking American official to visit Bosnia
since elections here two weeks ago, said the United States was
pleased by the lack of unrest during voting and by the victories of
some moderate candidates, even though the Bosnian Serb leader
endorsed by America, Biljana Plavsic, lost her bid for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Nikola Poplasen, the leader of the Serb Radical Party who was a
paramilitary official during Bosnia's three-and-a-half-year war,
defeated Ms. Plavsic to become president of the Bosnian Serb
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Poplasen's election is widely seen as a setback for Western
efforts to reunite Bosnia. But the Clinton administration has found
promise in gains made by moderates in the Bosnian Serb parliament
and the half of Bosnia controlled by Croats and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Since his victory, Poplasen, whose party calls for a
reunification of Bosnian Serbs with Yugoslavia, has pledged to
abide by the 1995 Dayton peace accords that ended the fighting in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say that the United States is prepared to work with all
of the newly elected officials, as long as they support the Dayton
accords and do so not only with their words, but by their deeds,''
Cohen said during a news conference at the American Embassy on his
first visit to Bosnia's capital as secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours before he arrived, under the cover of darkness,
American troops arrested a Bosnian Serb facing charges at the
International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia at the
Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Todorovic, a former chief of police in Bosanski Samac,
has been wanted by the tribunal for allegedly ordering and carrying
out murders, rapes, torture and other ``inhumane acts'' in his
village during June and July of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nato officials declined to discuss the details of the
operation, Todorovic is now the 37th accused war criminal _ out of
roughly 80 named in public or sealed indictments _ who has either
surrendered or been captured and turned over to the tribunal,
officials said. A year or so ago, there were only a handful in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the top international officials charged with bringing
peace to Bosnia, Cohen told them they had to improve coordination
of the myriad international and nonprofit efforts to rebuild the
country. Cohen saved his toughest public statements for the Bosnian
leaders, calling on all sides to end corruption, to build a
credible, unified police force and to protect refugees trying to
return to homes in areas dominated by other ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Without progress, he warned, support would erode for the NATO
operation to help maintain peace in Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
