u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      09-27 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC FAITHFUL RALLY ROUND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif.)  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-HILLARY-POLITICS,
CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD, CLINTON-JONES, CLINTON-STRATEGY.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Outside, the signs were savage for President
Clinton in the six cities he visited over the weekend to raise
money for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oust the louse,'' said one sign in San Jose, Calif. In San
Diego, protesters held up a banner reading, ``If the dress won't
bleach, you must impeach.'' In Los Angeles, a man showed up along
the president's motorcade route dressed as a 6-foot-tall cigar. In
San Antonio, someone wired to a fence a scarecrow resembling Monica
Lewinsky wearing a blue dress.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the millionaires' homes where Clinton spent the
weekend raising nearly $4 million for Democratic candidates, the
reception was much warmer. In Silicon Valley, in Hollywood, in
south Texas, Clinton was embraced and praised by loyal Democratic
donors, who offered the president moral support as they opened
their wallets for the party.
</P>
<P>
   At a fund-raising lunch in San Antonio Sunday afternoon, Ann
Richards, the former Texas governor, offered her own inimitable
endorsement of the beleaguered president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton isn't the first man I've had to forgive, and he
probably won't be the last,'' Ms. Richards said, as Clinton
guffawed.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Mauro, the Democratic candidate for Texas governor for
whom Clinton came here to campaign, offered the president an
unqualified public vote of confidence Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Bill Clinton, well, he's my friend,'' said Mauro,
the Texas land commissioner, who trails far behind Gov. George Bush
in statewide polls. ``I stand beside this president, I stand behind
his policies and I stand behind him 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Mauro called the president's affair with Ms.
Lewinsky ``indefensible.'' He said that ``nobody likes to be lied
to,'' but he added that he did not think the president's actions
were unforgivable or worthy of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro then sounded a theme that has animated Clinton and the
White House the past week _ that Republicans in Congress and
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, have overplayed
their hand and turned public opinion against them and in the
president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Starr had just laid out the facts, he might have had a
chance to really hurt him,'' Mauro said. ``Instead, the people just
got mad at him and the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Clinton has emphasized his policy differences with
the Republican majority and essentially presented the American
people with a choice: Stand behind him and what is left of his
political agenda, or support the Republicans as they move toward a
full-scale impeachment inquiry based on Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And, oddly for a man who has lived for nearly six years in the
White House, Clinton is campaigning against ``Washington,'' which
he has begun to use as a code word for congressional Republicans
and the media, whom he accuses of being preoccupied with his
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington,'' Clinton said Sunday afternoon, ``people
think, `Things are going well, so why don't we fight with each
other and see who we can hurt?'''
</P>
<P>
   He made a similar point on Saturday at a fund-raising lunch at
the suburban San Diego home of William Lerach, a wealthy trial
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe elections should be about the people that live
outside Washington, not about who's crawling on whom in Washington,
D.C,'' the president said. ``So I ask you, go out there and make
sure that's what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Barry Toiv, assured reporters that
Clinton's reference to ``crawling'' was a figure of speech for
partisan infighting, and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that many people at the fund-raising events this
weekend had offered him private encouragement and words of solace.
At the lunch Sunday, as on other occasions this weekend, Clinton
acknowledged the support and gave a small signal of the pain he is
feeling. ``You know, it's easy to forget in Washington, but
presidents and their families are still people, and it meant more
to me than you'll ever know, and I thank you for that,'' he said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Clinton's hosts have refrained from discussing the
scandal and the possibility of impeachment. But Lerach felt no such
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, it's time for Democrats _ fund-raisers, voters,
officeholders _ to roll up their sleeves tonight and go to work and
stand up against an ugly witch hunt to drive from office one of the
best and most popular presidents in history,'' Lerach said,
bringing the crowd at his house to its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, my friend, don't have a broken spirit,'' Lerach
added. ``Don't resign. Don't quit. You stay there and you fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
