A6831 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-27 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BENEFITS FROM BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So the Bruins got their bye, after all. Strip away
the lost Heisman exposure for Cade McNown and the unrealized
revenue _ approximately $700,000 for an athletic department that
just signed a $19 million deal with Adidas _ and the canceled game
at Miami is just that, a bye.
</P>
<P>
   It's the best thing that could have happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the players and coaches feel differently. They fear the
cancellation will shackle their national championship and Rose Bowl
dreams. And it may, if:
</P>
<P>
   _ They finish 10-0 and Miami has a seven- or eight-win season.
In that case, UCLA's strength-of-schedule rating _ a crucial
component in the formula that determines No.1 vs. No.2 _ would
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   _ They finish in a three-way tie for the Pac-10 title with
Arizona and Oregon, each of which has a 3-0 nonconference record.
(UCLA's is 2-0.)
</P>
<P>
   Both scenarios re feasible, but not probable.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of a bye, however, are myriad.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins would have played without 2{ defensive line starters.
One end, Kenyon Coleman, is out at least another week with a
sprained knee. The other, Pete Holland, wouldn't have played
because of a nagging sprained ankle, and nose guard Micah Webb was
ill on departure day.
</P>
<P>
   The bye provides Webb and Holland a chance to heal before Pac-10
play begins Saturday against Washington State. It's one less game
without Coleman, UCLA's most talented defensive lineman. And it
gives two true freshmen, nose guard Ken Kocher and end Anthony
Fletcher, more time to learn.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary, with three position changes and two first-time
starters, also benefits from the additional practice.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the young, talented Hurricanes, in sweltering heat, in
the Eastern time zone _ the wake-up calls were set for 4 a.m. body
time _ would have been a difficult task for UCLA, which has just
seven senior starters.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the bye should refresh the collective spirit after a
depressing game at Houston. Since their 12-game winning streak
began 54 weeks ago, the Bruins have shown a remarkable ability to
exist in the present. They neither dwell on previous
accomplishments nor drift toward future challenges.
</P>
<P>
   But the 42-24 victory grated on them like no other. Perhaps it
was the arduous playing conditions. Perhaps it was the injuries to
Coleman and Freddie Mitchell. Whatever, the Bruins did not dispose
that game with their usual efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation allowed them to cleanse their psyches _ and do
it under the most opportune conditions. Because it wasn't a
scheduled bye, they were locked and loaded for four days, until
word of the cancellation arrived Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to lose your competitive edge,'' McNown said.
``The fact we didn't know it was a bye was great. We kept our
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a day to slack, Friday was it. Instead, the
Bruins lifted weights at 6 a.m., watched film of Washington State
and cruised through a crisp, physical practice _ the perfect way to
turn their gaze to Pac-10 play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really concerned,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``But they
did a great job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
