A6834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-FAKE-DOCTORS-AR     09-27 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-FAKE-DOCTORS-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW DELHI SLUMS, AMATEUR `DOCTORS' THRIVE ON TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Mohammad Gulam Mustafa is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ As dusk falls on Jhuggi Jhonpri Colony No. 8,
a teeming slum that sprawls along the Yamuna River, a barefooted
parade of fish peddlers, maidservants and rickshaw pullers line up
at the storefront offices of their neighborhood ``doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is a clinic here where a qualified doctor sees
patients two mornings a week, the slum dwellers, too poor to give
up even a morning's wages, usually rely on ill-educated amateurs
who are open for business till 10 every night.
</P>
<P>
   In dingy little shops that swarm with flies, weary people,
illuminated by dangling bare light bulbs, unquestioningly accept
all manner of pills and shots from young men who have never gone to
college.
</P>
<P>
   As the rural poor have streamed into India's great metropolises
in recent years, these men, ``indigenous practitioners'' in the
polite terminology of health experts, have come along with them. As
there is currently no law that explicitly prohibits their work,
they operate with impunity in more than a thousand slum areas,
known as jhuggis, that are home to about a third of this capital
city's 10 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   The health minister for the state of Delhi, Harsh Vardhan, is
trying to shut them down but so far he has been stymied. Last year,
with strong backing from the Delhi Medical Association, he proposed
the Quackery Prohibition Act, which would make practicing medicine
without proper credentials a crime punishable by up to three years
in prison. The bill is now languishing in a committee of the local
legislative assembly where it was referred for further study.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are not qualified to practice medicine are playing
with the lives of the poor and illiterate by prescribing and
injecting medicines,'' he said. ``This is happening all over the
vast country of India on a vast scale.''
</P>
<P>
   But some leading health policy researchers question the wisdom
of Vardhan's idea. In a city where ill-educated medical
practitioners are at least as plentiful as real doctors, and where
the public health care system for slum dwellers is seriously
inadequate, they say it may make more sense to train these young
men to correctly dispense a limited array of medicines than to
simply forbid them to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know these people are here to stay,'' said Saroj Pachauri,
regional director for South Asia at the Population Council, a
nonprofit research organization. ``They can't be wished away.''
</P>
<P>
   At J.J. Colony No. 8, a jhuggi where people bathe, wash their
dishes and prepare meals next to open drains filled with excrement
and garbage, ill-educated ``doctors'' have many devoted customers.
They offer something that neither the clinic doctor nor the
government hospital can provide: a caretaker the slum dwellers know
personally who is available seven days a week right in their
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Munisa Begum, 40, lives with her extended family across the lane
from the clean, well-lit clinic where Dr. Abha Gupta holds office
hours from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. on Tuesdays and Fridays. The four
adults in her household earn less than $100 a month. For 4 rupees,
about 10 cents (an affordable sum for those who live in the
jhuggi), Mrs. Begum could consult Gupta, who works for the
nonprofit group ASHA, or Action for Securing Health for All.
</P>
<P>
   She could also go to the government hospital, but the bus fare
round trip would cost 20 cents and the visit would take more than
half a workday. Then she would have to wait in several lines, only
to see a doctor she had never met.
</P>
<P>
   The man Mrs. Begum trusts to look after her family is around the
corner: Mohammad Gulam Mustafa, 27, who completed only 11 years of
school. The son of a rice farmer, he migrated to Delhi from the
state of Assam thinking he would ``do whatever I got first.'' He
landed a job at the age of 16 in a doctor's office, then opened his
practice when he was 19.
</P>
<P>
   He is a friendly man with a kindly face who speaks the language
of the villagers. He can make ordinary aches and pains go away.
When someone has a headache, he gives them tablets of
acetaminophen. If they have a cough, he pours them a small bottle
of syrup.
</P>
<P>
   He also lets customers pay on credit and advises them in their
dealings with an intimidating municipal bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have important visitors, we invite the doctor to meet
them,'' Mrs. Begum said respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   One recent evening, Mustafa shone a flashlight into the
throbbing ear of a fish peddler's wife, then sent her on her way
with eight pills wrapped in newsprint. The woman accepted his help
gratefully. She handed over a 10-rupee note, worth about 25 cents,
toward the 60-cent cost of the visit and the medicine. He told her
she could pay the rest later.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell and the streets rang with the clanging bells of
bicycle-rickshaw peddlers returning home from work, Naima, a
vegetable-seller's wife who said she has no last name and does not
know her age, brought in her year-old daughter, Nargis, who had
diarrhea and a skin disease on her back.
</P>
<P>
   For the diarrhea, Mustafa said he had already given the baby
Lomotil _ a medication that pediatricians say can cause dehydration
in young children _ and that night he gave the mother another
medication to try. He also injected the baby with one shot of
gentamicin, an inexpensive antibiotic that doctors say should be
given twice daily for at least five days.
</P>
<P>
   Mustafa and others like him said they make about $70 to $100 a
month. His earnings are strongest in the monsoon season, when
diseases fester in the heat and damp. ``Summer is a very good
season for us,'' he said. He readily admits he has no formal
medical education. Much of what he knows about the drugs he hands
out he has learned from the drug company salesmen who daily ply the
narrow lanes of the slum, sample cases in hand, peddling
antibiotics and painkillers and cough syrups in the little shops
like Mustafa's, which are almost as prolific as vegetable stands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The directions on virtually every medication are in English, a
language spoken by fewer than 5 percent of Indians. Mustafa speaks
no English, though he claims he can read the English-only warnings
on the rows of dusty pill bottles that sit on shelves lined with
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salesmen give us free samples and tell us how to use
them,'' he said. ``We only buy them if they work and they're not
too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, he said, he prescribes a two-day course of the
antibiotic tetracycline for fever or a seasonal cough _ a practice
that disturbs public health doctors. While individuals treated so
briefly with antibiotics often get better, the bacteria they were
infected with can become drug-resistant for a whole community,
which complicates efforts to treat disease, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Mustafa said he was unaware that antibiotics given for too short
a time can lead to drug-resistant strains of bacteria. A patient
who does not get well in a couple of days will simply go to another
informally educated doctor, he said, and nobody would take a
medicine regularly for five days, even if he gave it to them, a
sentiment echoed by other practitioners. More pills cost more
money, they explained. And the jhuggi residents are also just not
in the habit of taking pills regularly on their own.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Mustafa said, he dreamed of being a real doctor,
but could not afford school. He would like to learn to do his job
better, but asks where he can go to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Verghese, program coordinator for ASHA, which operates the
clinic in Jhuggi Jhonpri No. 8, said her group has tried to train
some unqualified practitioners. ``These people give services right
in the slum,'' she said. ``They're there, day in, day out. Even if
you pass a law, people will go to them on the sly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
