<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-SCRUTINY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHTER RESTRICTIONS ARE SEEN AFTER HEDGE FUND BAILOUT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week's $3.5 billion bailout of the hedge fund
Long-Term Capital Management LP could bring closer scrutiny and
tighter restrictions on such funds.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said that he had
asked the staffs of federal agencies that are members of the
president's Working Group on Financial Markets _ which he is the
chairman of _ to study the ``potential implications'' of the
operations of hedge funds and their relationships with their
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   The group is expected to focus immediately on determining
whether more hedge fund regulation is required, then examine the
lending requirements of commercial and investment banks that lend
money to the funds, some regulators and industry executives said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge fund is a generic term for a category of investments that
have been in existence for more than 30 years. They are private
investment vehicles that have gone largely unregulated on the
assumption that they are meant only for wealthy individuals
presumed to be knowledgeable investors, who are aware of the high
risks that such funds often take on in search of high profits _ and
who are not in need of regulatory protection.
</P>
<P>
   The funds are usually structured as a limited partnership, in
which a general partner manages the fund and determines its
investment strategy. It is open only to accredited or
``sophisticated'' investors who must generally have a net worth of
$1 million or more and an annual income of $200,000 or more in each
of the most recent two years (or $300,000 jointly with a spouse).
</P>
<P>
   The funds maintain a great deal of secrecy and may use a wide
range of investment strategies. Unlike mutual funds, hedge funds'
choice of investment tools, the amount of leverage used, their
degree of diversification and detailed reports of holdings are not
strictly regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Many hedge funds operate under an exemption in the Investment
Company Act of 1940. The exemption was originally intended to allow
family businesses that invest in securities to avoid federal
regulation. But over the years, the exemption has been interpreted
to include pools of money, including investment clubs, that have
fewer than 100 investors and that do not offer shares to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds can also operate under a 1996 amendment to the
federal securities laws that exempts from regulation funds limited
to fewer than 500 ``sophisticated'' institutions or individuals _
meaning institutions with total investments exceeding $25 million
and individuals with investment portfolios of at least $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   An SEC rule allows some employees of hedge funds to also invest
in the pools, even if they do not meet the minimum investment
criteria, said Barry Barbash, director of the SEC's division of
investment management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It limits investment by employees to nonclerical,
nonsecretarial employees who are involved in the management of the
pool,'' Barbash said. ``We drew the line at people who would know
something about investing in the deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
