u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      09-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT PUSHES PALESTINIANS AND ISRAELIS ON STALLED ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright pushed on
Sunday for agreement on pivotal details of a long-stalled peace
agreement between Israel and the Palestinians, with American
officials saying the White House hoped to announce concrete
progress in the peace talks when President Clinton meets with Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said that an overall settlement
was not imminent despite Albright's meetings in New York this
weekend with Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader.
Both men were here to speak before the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the White House was still eager to
announce at least some progress in the Israeli-Palestinian talks at
Monday's meeting in Washington, if only to show that American
foreign policy has not been hobbled by the scandal surrounding
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great interest in showing that we're not being
sidetracked by the circus in Washington,'' said an American
official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``We want to lock in
key elements of this agreement while all of the parties are still
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday, Netanyahu suggested that he and
Arafat were still far from agreement on several issues, most
importantly the security arrangements for areas of the West Bank
that Israel would cede to the Palestinians under a new peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't have yet is the whole Palestinian side of this
equation,'' he said. ``How do they assure us the areas that we hand
over to them and have handed over to them do not become bases of
terrorism?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believed that Clinton's ability to focus on foreign
policy _ and specifically on the Middle East peace effort _ had
suffered because of the scandal in Washington, Netanyahu replied,
``Not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 18 months without visible progress in the peace
process, Israel and the Palestinians are reported to be close to a
deal under which Israel would turn over 13 percent of the West Bank
to the Palestinians, with 3 percent designated at nature reserves
to prevent Palestinian settlements. But several details remain
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Time for further negotiations on American soil has nearly run
out. Netanyahu is expected back in Israel Tuesday evening for the
Yom Kippur holiday. Albright met separately with both the Israeli
and Palestinian leaders here late Saturday night and was scheduled
to meet them again late on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   There is something of a deadline for the talks: May 4 of next
year, when the Oslo peace agreements that provided a framework for
the peace talks expire. Arafat has said that if there is no
settlement by then, he will declare the creation of a Palestinian
state, a move that would outrage Israel.
</P>
<P>
   According to a draft of a speech scheduled for delivery on
Sunday in New York, Arafat was prepared to repeat the pledge.
Without an agreement by next May, ``We will have no choice but to
unilaterally declare the establishment of the Palestinian state,''
it said. ``We do realize the implications and consequences of this
on Palestinian-Israeli relations as a whole and also on
Arab-Israeli and international relations.''
</P>
<P>
   But in what may have been a concession to Israeli sensitivities
and a response to pressure from the United States, those lines were
dropped from the speeches delivered, and Arafat referred only
cryptically to the significance of a deadline next May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community, all peace-loving people, must
exert every possible effort to insure the implementation of the
agreements by May 4, 1999,'' Arafat said in his speech to the
Center for Middle East Peace and Economic Cooperation, a private
group. ``It just cannot come and go like any other day.''
</P>
<P>
   American and Israeli officials are waiting anxiously to hear
what Arafat will say when he addresses the General Assembly on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Arafat have not attempted to dampen speculation that he
will use the speech to criticize Netanyahu's government harshly and
to solicit support for his plans to declare statehood. Netanyahu
has warned that a unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state
could scuttle the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech on Sunday, Arafat accused Netanyahu's government
of ``procrastination and evasion'' in the peace talks. ``This
Israeli government,'' he said, ``began to export blame to the
Palestinians and to export fear to Israelis in an obvious political
attempt aimed at undermining its obligations and agreements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
