<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCKING THE DOUBTERS WITH TEASING VAMPS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a story that Sam Cooke, at the height of his
gospel-singing career, could make a crowd detonate simply by
choosing the perfect moment to smile. In some rarefied chamber
beyond professionalism, a musician can transmit power with the
merest gesture. A performer is lucky to find this magic zone every
once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the artist formerly known as Prince at a packed Madison
Square Garden on Friday night, it was easy to feel that he had a
complete mental map of his music, and accessing the zone was as
simple as finding a dot on that map.
</P>
<P>
   Then he made the chosen moment surreally significant with a
single action: thrusting a leg, grinding a bump, singing a trill,
running, jumping, mimicking the curve of a funk line with a limb or
his shoulders, rolling a guitar line over and under, playing a
chord on the piano or performing a pelvic thrust atop it.
</P>
<P>
   He did it again and again during Friday night's 100-minute
greatest-hits set, with a light show to follow what seemed like his
every whim. ``Before we go on,'' he announced at one point, ``this
light _ it don't match my suit!'' He snapped his fingers, and the
spotlight blinked from yellow to deep red.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he came through town, touring with Chaka Khan and
Larry Graham, the artist played a show at which he appeared only in
the company of his supporting acts. The Madison Square Garden
concert was a different animal: a tightly scripted, proper
three-act show called the 1998 New Power Soul Festival, with the
same supporting acts, Larry Graham and Chaka Khan, each given an
opening set.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was decked with the artist's groovy bywords _ flags
atop the stage announced ``Faith,'' ``God,'' ``Patience,'' ``Joy.''
Representing his earthier side, an enormous prop in the shape of a
pair of women's legs flanked the stage, beginning at the ceiling
and ending in ankle-strap heels down by the floor. The glyph
signifying his name flashed in gold lights between the giant legs;
at one point he posed in victory underneath the sign, a potent
propaganda image for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Proud of his newfound business autonomy _ he has released his
last three albums on his own label, NPG Records, and bypassed most
chain retailers _ he mocked the doubters who claimed he couldn't
sell out the Garden, and introduced ``I Could Never Take the Place
of Your Man'' by boasting, ``This is from my most unsuccessful
album.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally proud of his domestic partnership, he had his wife,
Mayte, emerge for a stylized belly-dance during ``The One,'' from
the newest album, ``Newpower Soul''; it was lighted so delicately
and framed so lovingly within the show that it could have been a
soft-focus sequence of a film. At its climax, he coyly turned to
the audience to utter, ``Excuse me'' before giving her a deep kiss.
</P>
<P>
   The revuelike procession included a few dismal excesses: The
smooth-jazz saxophonist Candy Dulfer, now part of the touring band,
performed a solid-schmaltz version of ``Summertime,'' and rapper
Doug E. Fresh came out for some crowd-nuzzling, as well as to rap
anticlimactically over ``Erotic City'' and ``Pop Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But certain kinds of excess are just the artist's speed. Amid
medleys, vamps and teasing single verses, one of the few numbers he
played extensively was ``Purple Rain,'' and in it he performed a
super-expressive power-ballad guitar solo; it could have been the
finest of its kind. How can it be described, except that it worked
gradually from a few sculptured notes to many, that each note
counted and that the journey was fully realized?
</P>
<P>
   This solo had sex appeal and a hair style and expensive shoes
and feelings; it was oversized and pained and martyrizing, and it
was what arena concerts in pop are for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
