<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBEL-MEDIA-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON REPORTERS AND SOURCES IN LAWSUIT AGAINST `60
MINUTES' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., N.M., Texas.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is shortly before the end of a tough ``60 Minutes'' report on
the U.S. Customs Service in San Diego, and a memo flashes on the
screen, with telling phrases highlighted. The document seems to
support the report's basic thrust: the southwestern border is a
sieve through which huge drug cargoes pass with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   There is just one problem. The internal memo, the Customs
Service says, is a hoax. Rudy Camacho, the director of the Customs
Management Center in San Diego, contends he approved no such thing.
He has sued CBS, the ``60 Minutes'' correspondents Mike Wallace and
Lesley Stahl, and the report's producer, Lee Zeidman, for libel.
</P>
<P>
   Libel suits are an occupational hazard for investigative
reporters. What makes this one interesting is the fifth and final
defendant, Michael L. Horner; he is not one of the network's
journalists, but one of its sources. Horner, a former customs
inspector who has long maintained his work was thwarted by corrupt
superiors, provided ``60 Minutes'' with two copies of the disputed
memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   If, as customs and Camacho contend, the memo is a forgery and no
trace of it can be found on customs computers, a highly respected
television news magazine has been snookered. But, Wallace points
out, the evidence of a hoax comes from customs itself. ``The fact
is they've undertaken the investigations and say, `We've proved it
to ourselves,' '' he said. ``Well, the fox is proving it to the
chickens.'' Horner, on the advice of his lawyer, has declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Camacho lawsuit opens a window into the complex relationship
between reporters and their sources. In such relationships, there
is a tug of war between trust and skepticism. Motives are always
open to question _ particularly when, as here, there is a knot of
feuds in a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   For journalists trying to unravel such knots, a good source is
priceless. And Horner seemed to be that rarest of journalistic
treasures, a man with reliable inside knowledge of official
wrongdoing, a passion for justice and the guts to put his name
behind his accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Horner is hardly the only source who has made allegations about
records disappearing from customs computers or adjustments in
customs procedures that could make life easier for drug smugglers.
But he has been particularly active. Since he left the Customs
Service in 1992, Horner has been cited as a source in
border-corruption reports by at least five news outlets, including
The Los Angeles Times and the TV news magazine program ``Dateline
NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   This has left a bad taste with customs officials. But even
without Horner, there had been reason to explore the rumors
swirling around the border. At least 46 federal, state and local
law-enforcement officials were indicted on or convicted of
drug-related corruption charges from 1994 to 1997 in Arizona,
California, New Mexico and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also strong evidence that the ``60 Minutes'' memo,
shown on April 20, 1997, was forged. The effect of the memo was to
encourage customs agents to process trucks owned by a company that
``60 Minutes'' said had links to Mexican drug cartels ``as quickly
as possible.'' Customs officials can demonstrate the disputed June
1996 memo is filled with titles and bureaucratic coding that had
been changed and updated the year before. They said that all hard
disks on agency computers were checked for traces of the memo, in
vain.
</P>
<P>
   Horner also provided a former aide to Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., with at least two affidavits from customs inspectors
saying they had seen the memo. When asked, these inspectors said
their names had been forged. The aide, Susan Kennedy, could not be
reached for comment, but had passed the sworn disavowals to a
Customs Service spokesman, Pat Jones, who confirmed this account.
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters still swear by Horner. Jamie Dettmer, a reporter
for Insight magazine, a sister publication of The Washington Times,
worked with Horner and said ``any information he supplied to us
almost always turned out to be correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Other journalistic and professional allies of Horner have become
wary. ``I believe Mike was an honest broker early on,'' said Tom
Isbell, a customs inspector, who, with Horner, told federal
investigators years ago about what he regarded as suspicious
practices within the service. ``But he became enamored of all this
publicity,'' Isbell added.
</P>
<P>
   When a series of federal investigations _ including a grand jury
inquiry into some of Horner's accusations _ ended inconclusively in
the last two years, Isbell said, ``Mike was terribly, terribly
disappointed.'' He added, ``When the grand jury investigation was
not conclusive, Mike just seemed to fade into the woodwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Scholl, a producer for ``Dateline NBC'' said, ``Mike
was a very well-intentioned man who generally provided accurate
information _ up until a certain point.'' Scholl worked with Horner
on a 1995 report, but canceled a follow-up, he said, after
documents provided by Horner proved to be fake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point where the accurate information flow from Mike
stopped was after the grand jury's investigation ended,'' Scholl
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
