BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECURITY FLAW IS DISCOVERED
</P>
<P>
   A potentially serious security flaw has been discovered in the
programming language used by Netscape Communications' Navigator and
Communicator software that could allow an outsider to steal
information on a personal computer user's hard disk. The weakness
was disclosed in Usenet online discussion groups on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN MAY DELAY STOCK OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs is likely to announce this week that it is
delaying its initial public offering, which had been scheduled for
November.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES TIMES IS REORGANIZING
</P>
<P>
   One year after Mark Willes, the chief executive of Times Mirror,
also became publisher of The Los Angeles Times, the newspaper is
reorganizing in a move that could provide it with a higher national
profile.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE TO CONSIDER BANK MEASURE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to consider a measure to modernize the
financial services industry this week. The proposal would make it
easier for banks, brokers and insurance companies to merge into
financial conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   GANNETT COMBINING 11 NEWSPAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Gannett Suburban Newspapers planned to merge its 11 papers in
Rockland, Westchester and Putnam counties in New York into one
newspaper named The Journal News.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITES GUIDING INDUSTRIES
</P>
<P>
   Jim Long, chief surveyor for the Black Thunder coal mine in
Wright, Wyo., uses a global positioning system that was originally
intended for military navigation and for such commercial purposes
as mapping delivery routes, tracking products all the way from the
floor of a factory to shelves in retail stores, and monitoring the
whereabouts of mobile workers.
</P>
<P>
   REAL NETWORKS IN TECHNOLOGY DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks plans to announce Monday that America Online has
chosen its technology for its newest online software.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEBATE OVER HDTV CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   The debate over whether government or the private sector should
create the standards for digital television continues.
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVISION TO OFFER STAR TREK GAMES
</P>
<P>
   The game maker Activision plans to announce this week that it
has licensed from Paramount Pictures the exclusive rights to make
Star Trek video games. The company said the Star Trek games could
bring $600 million in revenues over 10 years.
</P>
