<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCARNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nascar Notes
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE RACE BY LAPS:
</P>
<P>
   The First 100:
</P>
<P>
   After pole-winner Ernie Irvan led the first 14 laps, Ricky Rudd
and John Andretti swapped the lead over the next 90, setting a
blistering pace that only Andretti could maintain. It didn't help
the race momentum when Brett Bodine spun in turn two on lap five,
bringing out the first of many caution flags for five laps.
Attrition was almost immediate following Bodine's spin. Rusty
Wallace made an early pit stop and lost 18 laps. Dick Trickle went
in for a vibration problem and emerged 36 laps later. The pace of
the race was such that only 21 cars were on the lead lap after the
first 100. Among those who were lapped was Dale Earnhardt, who
finished 22nd, five laps down. Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin could
not make a move toward the front early. Martin dropped from 13th to
19th in the first 100 laps, while Gordon labored around ninth.
</P>
<P>
   LAP LEADERS: Ernie Irvan (14), Ricky Rudd (49), John Andretti
(37)
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED: Kenny Wallace, overheating
</P>
<P>
   UNDER CAUTION: 4 laps
</P>
<P>
   The Second 100
</P>
<P>
   Andretti continued his charge, pulling to five car lead on lap
101, but he crashed into the front stretch wall on lap 105, caused
by a tire going down. He returned for a lap, then returned to his
pit for a sway bar adjustment and lost 25 more. Over the next 80
laps, Sterling Marlin and Rudd swapped the lead three times. Gordon
lost track position to Martin on lap 117 and 118. On lap 143, the
field appeared satisfied to race nose-to-tale, with passing at a
minimum, saving the brakes for when they would need them down the
stretch. They took the first 100 laps to see who had what, then
rested. Jimmy Spencer brought out the third caution, looping his
car in turn three on lap 174. The tempo increased on the restart as
Martin passes Gordon for fourth.
</P>
<P>
   LAP LEADERS: Sterling Marlin (100)
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED: NONE
</P>
<P>
   UNDER CAUTION: 15
</P>
<P>
   The Third 100
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's day ends on a sour note when his motor quits running
on the backstretch on lap 298. He would not return. Gordon and
Martin take turns swapping positions, and drivers are beginning to
complain about the slick track. Again, there was more nose-to-tail
racing than side-by-side. Cars were sliding through the corners.
The heat began to take it's toll. Ted Musgrave sought relief and
got it from, Steve Grissom. ''I didn't expect the track to be this
hot,'' Musgrave noted. Spencer makes things even hotter, spinning
again in turn three, bringing out another caution. In all the
smoke, Rudd slipped under Marlin to take the lead, now with only 20
cars on the lead lap. At the race's halfway point, it was an odd
top five - Marlin, Rudd and Wally Dallenbach, followed by Gordon,
Jarrett and Martin. Things got scary on lap 267 when a tire comes
off the car of Geoff Bodine. It bounced of pit wall into middle of
the track, barely missing the cars of Johnny Benson and Joe
Nemechek.
</P>
<P>
   LAP LEADERS: Sterling Marlin (87), Ricky Rudd (13)
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED: Dale Jarrett, motor; Geoff Bodine, handling
</P>
<P>
   UNDER CAUTION: 25 laps
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth 100
</P>
<P>
   ''I came down the front stretch and it started making a funny
noise. that was it,'' Jarrett said after pushing his car from pit
road to behind the wall on lap 302. Following a caution on lap
325-330, Rudd pulls away from Marlin, Martin and Gordon. It's a
short ride. Caution: Mike Skinner and Kenny Irwin get together
going into turn two rather aggressively, bringing out another
caution. Words, not nice ones, are exchanged over the team radios.
On the restart, Rudd gets great start before Skinner, again, and
Spencer touched, setting off another spin around midway the
backstretch, bringing out caution No. 8. In the middle of this
comes Jeff Burton, passing Gordon for fourth, Martin for third and
Rudd for second. He then runs down Marlin and takes the lead on
turn three on 387. It doesn't last.
</P>
<P>
   LAP LEADERS: Ricky Rudd (51), Sterling Marlin (33), Jeff Burton
(16),
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED: Jeff Bodine, handling
</P>
<P>
   UNDER CAUTION: 19
</P>
<P>
   The Final 100
</P>
<P>
   Burton slows and Rudd regains the lead on lap 410. A new face
appears. Bobby Hamilton, who won here in the spring, was 15th on
lap 312 and moves to second on lap 410. Burton slips to third.
Caution slows things when Marlin stalls on the back stretch. Rudd
beats the field out on the restart, followed by Gordon, Rick Bickle
Burton and Martin. Hamilton falls to seventh in the run back to the
start-finish line. Rudd pulls away to 12-car lead just before
Hamilton and Irwin spin in turn four on lap 439, bringing out
caution No. 11. Gordon made a most efficient move through the
smoke, running down pit road and holding on to second place. On the
restart, Rudd was off to three-car length lead and Gordon was
losing ground to Martin in third. As the laps led down, Rudd
maintained his three second lead, with a lapped car between him and
Gordon, and took the checkered flag, for his 16th victory,
maintaining his consecutive victory streak.
</P>
<P>
   LAP LEADERS: Jeff Burton (10), Ricky Rudd (90)
</P>
<P>
   RETIRED: John Andretti, handling.
</P>
<P>
   UNDER CAUTION: 13
</P>
<P>
   WHO WAS HOT
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd. Won from the pole, leading four times for 148 laps
to extend his 16-year record of winning at least once this year.
</P>
<P>
   WHO WAS NOT
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett had his motor quit on lap 291, finished 42nd. He
now trails Jeff Gordon by 470 points in the NASCAR Winston Cup
championship race.
</P>
<P>
   POINTS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   After 27 races, Jeff Gordon, 4297; Mark Martin, 4098; Dale
Jarrett, 3827; Rusty Wallace, 3716; Bobby Labonte, 3553.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
