<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-EXPOS-MCGWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE ENDS SEASON WITH RECORD-SETTING 70 HOME RUNS  
(sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ His seasonlong performance so surpassed any
individual performance major league baseball has ever seen that,
Mark McGwire said, ``I'm in awe of myself right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing that performance with a flourish, McGwire clouted two
more home runs on the last day of the regular season on Sunday,
raising his record total to an unheard of 70. Like a long-distance
runner with an explosive finishing kick, McGwire sprinted away from
the guy next to him, Sammy Sosa, by hitting five home runs in his
last 11 times at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who remained at 66 home runs after hitting none on Sunday,
is not finished playing. The Cubs, the team he has carried all
season, will meet the San Francisco Giants in Chicago Monday night
to determine the fourth and final team, the wild-card team, in the
National League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa will be hard-pressed to catch McGwire, the
larger-than-life superstar who has imbedded himself in the hearts
of St. Louis and has captivated the rest of the country with his
performance and his demeanor. A player has hit four home runs in a
game only 12 times in major league history, none for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck,'' McGwire said earnestly long distance to the man
who has become his ally in home runs and understanding of what he
has gone through the past six months. ``We've been going back and
forth. It's been a tremendous ride for he and I.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who broke Roger Maris' 37-year-old record of 61 at
Busch Stadium on Sept. 8 with a line drive over the left field
fence, trailed Sosa only twice this season, each time for less than
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa slugged his way into the lead last Friday night by hitting
his 66th home run in Houston, but 45 minutes later McGwire tied
him, then didn't look back. He socked a pair of home runs against
Montreal pitchers Saturday and connected against two Expos' rookies
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He lofted one of his patented towering fly balls against Mike
Thurman in the third inning that descended gracefully into the
left-field stands for No. 69. Then, an hour and 9 minutes later, he
swung at the first pitch he saw from Carl Pavano and lined it over
the left field fence for No. 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I did it; can you?'' he said at a post-game
news conference that had become as much a part of his day as
hitting home runs. ``It's absolutely amazing. It blows me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting five home runs in the span of 11 at-bats is incredible
even for the hitter who finished the season with a record low ratio
of one home run every 7.27 at-bats. McGwire had registered the
previous low ratio of 8.13 in 1996, when he hit 52 home runs,
surpassing Babe Ruth's record 8.48 he achieved in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said hitting home runs is getting pitches to hit,
keeping your stroke intact and working hard,'' he said, discussing
his fantastic finish. ``Home runs aren't easy to do. When you work
as hard as I've worked the last few years to really work on my
swing and get full extension, it's paid off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
