<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-KOHL-540&AMP;ADD-     09-27 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOHL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN DEFEAT, GERMAN CHANCELLOR KOHL MAKES HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GERMANY-EUROPE, GERMANY-VOTE, GERMANY-REACT) 
(js) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was characteristic that even when Helmut Kohl was finally
ousted in Germany's national elections, he scored a first _ this
time as the first post-war German chancellor to be voted out of
office.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a first Kohl relished, to be sure, nor one he likely
worried about. For all his extraordinary firsts and records, both
political and physical _ the first chancellor of a re-united
Germany; the longest-serving German chancellor since Otto von
Bismarck; and, at 6-foot-4 and somewhere around 300 pounds,
indisputably the largest leader in modern Europe _ Kohl has not
spent much of the past 16 years pondering his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hell with history,'' he once snapped at an aide who raised
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   His medium was politics, and it was a medium in which he was
master, even if in the end he failed to recognize when the moment
came to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Kohl attracted an unending stream of
unflattering jokes, and was often perceived by German intellectuals
as something of an embarrassing provincial pol. But nobody ever
questioned his total control of his own party, the Christian
Democratic Union, nor his skill in guiding his nation through the
Byzantine politics of post-war and post-Communist Europe.
</P>
<P>
   If he disdained talk of his ``place in history,'' Kohl bridled
when his opponents accused him of lacking vision. His was as
concrete as it was consistent: to unify his people in the context
of a unified Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who has a better vision here in the Federal Republic?'' he
declared in 1990, on the eve of German re-unification. ``I know no
better concept than the one I represent _ European unification _
because in 10 years we will write 2000 and not 1900, and this
country and this continent will have a chance in the year 2000, and
beyond, only if they are united. OK, there is the vision.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of unity as a ``compass'' in his politics. ``My compass
also says, to an almost emotional degree, friendship with France,
friendship with the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If his formulation lacked the eloquence of a Helmut Schmidt or a
Willy Brandt, Kohl never deviated from his compass, even when his
decisions ran against the political tide.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, his determination to maintain West Germany in a
U.S.-led NATO by allowing the deployment of Pershing II missiles
prompted massive and brutal protests, yet he persevered.
</P>
<P>
   And once the disintegration of the Communist world made the
dream of re-unification possible, he managed the Herculean task of
gaining the acquiescence of the skeptical leaders of the United
States, the Soviet Union, Britain and France, and then physically
reuniting the Germanys, within 11 months of the collapse of the
Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement proved considerably more painful than Kohl
promised, and it was the enormous cost of reunification that
eventually led to Kohl's political fall. But not many politicians
or historians have argued that Kohl erred in his decision to press
ahead with reunification as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wrong about some things since 1990, but who hasn't
been?'' Kohl mused in the spring of 1994 _ one of the many times
when the polls predicted prematurely that his era was coming to an
end.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet more than his vision or even his political skills, Kohl's
longevity was probably due to the degree to which he represented
his generation of western Germans.
</P>
<P>
   What his adversaries often perceived as an uncanny political
antenna was rooted in the degree to which he represented a
generation of Germans struggling to reconcile the stigma of their
history with their remarkable economic and political revival.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen when the war ended, Kohl was old enough to know
first-hand the horrors of Nazism and the war, but young enough to
claim what he called ``the absolution of late birth'' _ a notion
that irritated some listeners, but was shared by many of his and
younger generations.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the hinterlands of the Roman Catholic Rhineland, he,
like many West Germans, learned to balance a quiet patriotism
against a constant awareness of how others perceived his people.
Although his insistence on hosting President Ronald Reagan at a
cemetery where some SS soldiers were buried created a furor in
1985, many of his visits, most notably to Poland and to Israel,
became milestones of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   A man who relished quintessentially German foods like stuffed
sow's belly and plum pie, who never shed his provincial Rhineland
accent and commuted regularly to his home town of Ludwigshafen to
mingle with its respectable, hard-working, heavy-eating, prosperous
burghers, Kohl was the image of what his CDU represented. He was
what one writer described as ``the cross-section of the good German
citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Active in the party almost from the time of its founding after
the war, Kohl rose rapidly, scoring ``first'' at every step: at 30
the youngest member of his state legislature; at 33 the youngest
floor leader; at 39 the youngest state premier; at 43 the youngest
chairman of the Christian Democratic Union; and finally, in 1982,
at the age of 52, the youngest chancellor. He came to control every
facet and every leader of the party, shaping them into a personal
instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at every step along his career, critics spoke of his
``luck'' and predicted that he would go no further. His first
speech as a legislator was so terrible that his colleagues wrote
him off. In 1976, the legendary head of the Christian Social Union
in Bavaria, Franz Josef Strauss, declared that Kohl was ``totally
incapable.'' And when Kohl did become chancellor in 1982, his
adversaries noted, it was not through an election, but because the
small Free Democratic Party shifted support from the Social
Democrats to Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kohl never did fare well in polls, usually gaining
office by being at the head of his party's list rather than through
a direct victory. In Sunday's voting, he was defeated in his home
constituency of Ludwigshafen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet so often did he defy his challengers and foes that stories
of his revivals became political cliches. When this election came
along, it was a measure of Kohl's reputation that nobody predicted
his loss with any certainty, even when all the polls pointed to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
