<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HR-MAIN-COX     09-27 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HR-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire praises fans after establishing HR record
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ He had homered in five of his last 11 at-bats, and
his last two hits cleared the fence. But Mark McGwire wasn't
through with business on Sunday. He had a rather large group to
thank.
</P>
<P>
   So after his 70th home run was in the record book, McGwire
walked to the plate and tipped his cap to the 46,110 fans at Busch
Stadium, following the Cardinals' 6-3 victory over Montreal. With
tears rolling down his cheeks and a smile on his red-bearded face,
McGwire pointed to the home crowd and said, ``This probably
wouldn't have happened this season without you.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans went berserk one final time.
</P>
<P>
   Those fans and a baseball nation on Sunday witnessed a perfect
curtain call for a seemingly perfect season for baseball and
McGwire. After hitting two homers on Saturday to break a 66-all tie
with Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa, McGwire nailed his name to the
record with Nos. 69 and 70. McGwire had trailed Sosa for 45 minutes
on Friday night before tying the race at 66 with an fifth-inning
homer. He now leads by four.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa gets one final chance today, when the Cubs and Giants play
each other to determine the NL wildcard spot. But it is unlikely
that he can overcome McGwire's feat. No player in major league
history has ever hit five home runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stranger than fiction, what this man has done,'' St.
Louis manager Tony LaRussa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a season I will never forget, ever forget, and I hope
nobody in baseball ever forget it,'' McGwire said. ``It's over
with, right? I'm absolutely exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a September to remember for baseball. The highlight came
on Sept. 8, when McGwire passed Roger Maris, who had set a record
of 61 in 1961. His two-homer performance on Sunday was the 10th
time this year that he has hit more than one in a game.
</P>
<P>
   His first came on his second at-bat in the third inning on a 1-1
pitch from Expos rookie Mike Thurman. It landed 377 feet away in
the left-field stands. McGwire was walked on four pitches in the
fifth. In the seventh, on the first pitch from reliever Carl
Pavano, he drove the ball 370 feet over the left-field fence for a
three-run shot that broke a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he hits 75 next year so people will forget I gave up
No. 70,'' Pavano said.
</P>
<P>
   The last homer was caught by a Washington University research
scientist, who said he is not sure what he will do with the ball.
Maybe he can compute distances, as in 70 homers that traveled
29,598 feet. That's 5.6 miles of home runs, about 400 feet higher
than Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God the season's over or he would hit 80,'' Expos
manager Felipe Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire led the home run race for all but 103 minutes of the
1998 season. Sosa took the lead twice. Each time McGwire hit home
runs on the same night, two on Aug. 19 to go back ahead of Sosa and
then one on Friday to tie him. Since then it has been all McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also drew his 162nd walk on Sunday, which tied him for
the second highest total in major league history with Ted Williams
(1947 and 1949). McGwire now has 180 homers in his last three
seasons and 94 in 206 games with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis certainly benefitted. Despite finishing 19 games out
of first place, the Cardinals drew almost 3.2 million fans and sold
out their last 14 games. McGwire's contract stipulates that he gets
$1 for every fan over 2.8 million mark, so he received an extra
$395,021 to his $9.5 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who finished with 147 RBIs, now heads back to his home
Southern California, to relax and reflect with his 10-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never even thought about it, dreamed about it,'' McGwire
said, when asked about passing Maris. ``It's absolutely amazing. It
blows me away.''
</P>
<P>
   I. J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
