<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-FOOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unexpected sophomore a standout in win over UNC
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Harvey Who?
</P>
<P>
   After the loss of Harvey Middleton and Derrick Steagall,
compounded by the injuries to Mike Sheridan and Jon Muyres, Georgia
Tech's 1998 receiving unit was supposed to be a patchwork job.
</P>
<P>
   So then what was that going on up at North Carolina on Saturday
night? Who was on the other end of quarterback Joe Hamilton's 303
yards passing and three touchdowns in a 43-21 win against the Tar
Heels?
</P>
<P>
   Dez White, for one.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore wideout was a star on Saturday night with six
catches for 171 yards and two touchdowns, all career highs. Those
171 yards were good for the seventh best single-game receiving
output in Tech history and most of them came with two-time
All-American cornerback Dre Bly on his tail.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play from scrimmage, Hamilton found White all alone
20 yards downfield. White dropped to his knees and pumped his fists
like he was celebrating with some bicep curls. He was in that same
pose in a photo that ran in newspapers from Raleigh to Atlanta
Sunday showing his reaction to a 56-yard touchdown catch in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   White, who spent his freshman season dropping passes all over
the practice field, caught all but two balls thrown his way on
Saturday, including two deep balls, the game's most important
touchdown on a 20-yard reception early in the second quarter, and
three passes to convert third downs. His only drop came on a corner
route in the end zone when he apparently lost the ball in the
lights.
</P>
<P>
   White doesn't appear to be resting on any progress he's made
over the early part of this season. He stayed after practice last
Thursday to throw and catch a ball tied to a fence by an elastic
band.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing that on his own,'' Tech coach George O'Leary said
Sunday. ''That's why he's getting better. He's one of the hardest
workers on the team. He's still making some mistakes, but he really
has improved from last year doing the little things receivers do.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Rogers is starting to show how much he can add at slot
receiver. He was Tech's second-leading receiver on Saturday with
three catches for 63 yards. David Powell caught one pass for a big
gain (38 yards) and tight end Russell Matvay made his only catch
count on a fourth down conversion for an 18-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan was back from a knee sprain on Saturday night but
wasn't really needed. He caught one pass for no gain. Muyres didn't
make the trip because of his foot injury. Still, O'Leary knows Tech
needs both those guys fullspeed and active for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still never have enough playmakers,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   MUYRES UPDATE: An MRI last Thursday confirmed that Muyres has
plantar fasciaitis, inflammation of a tendon extending from his
achilles to the bottom of his foot. Muyres had rested for three
weeks when he tried to come backto practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said Muyres will see a specialist on Tuesday to
determine what else can be done. Muyres, a junior, has not taken a
redshirt year and that is an option, though not one he or O'Leary
wants to exercise at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to have Jon Muyres in there,'' O'Leary said. ''The
kid wants to play. It's a tough position to play when you're not
100 percent healthy. Basically we want to make sure we've tried
everything, that there's nothing more we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
