u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JONES-NYT &LR;      09-27 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES PAVING WAY FOR A JONES SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-HILLARY-POLITICS,
CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-STRATEGY.) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A senior aide to President Clinton sought Sunday to
prepare the public for a possible settlement of Paula Jones' sexual
misconduct lawsuit, saying that it should not be taken as an
admission by the president that Mrs. Jones' accusations are true.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy White House counsel Bruce Lindsey, one of Clinton's
closest confidants, told reporters in San Antonio, where he is
traveling with the president, that the negotiations between lawyers
for both sides ``have nothing to do with wrongdoing on anybody's
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey suggested that the efforts to settle the lawsuit were
merely an effort to get rid of a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suits are settled all the time,'' he said. ``People made a
determination that the costs of settlement are less than the costs
of going forward.'' He said that the president had already paid
dearly in lost time because of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But other White House advisers have acknowledged there are other
reasons Clinton is suddenly eager to settle. Although the president
and his lawyers have derided the lawsuit for years as an outrageous
legal fraud, they say they believe that a settlement would help
them battle impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers said Sunday they would not budge very much
from their demand that Clinton pay $1 million to settle her
lawsuit, a position based on a calculation that the president's
need to end the matter is greater than hers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's lawyers have already offered $500,000 for
her to withdraw the lawsuit that led to his current impeachment
problems. Both sides said they believed a settlement was possible
and could be reached sometime this week. The Jones camp had earlier
set a deadline of Tuesday morning for negotiations but that has
already been relaxed, lawyers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones filed suit against Clinton in 1994, contending that
three years earlier, when he was governor of Arkansas, he had her
summoned to his hotel suite in Little Rock and, when alone, made a
crude sexual proposition. In a deposition taken in January, Clinton
testified under oath to Mrs. Jones' lawyers that he had not engaged
in ``sexual relations'' with Monica Lewinsky. He has since admitted
that he and Ms. Lewinsky had had intimate contact.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones lawsuit was dismissed last April and, while it is
exceedingly rare for a party to pay to settle a lawsuit he has
already won, Clinton's advisers have said that they feared that an
appeals court would reinstate the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always denied Mrs. Jones' accusation, and previous
settlement negotiations had foundered on her insistence that he
provide an apology or some form of acknowledgment that he had
behaved badly.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers have dropped the demand for an apology,
saying that Clinton's admission of a liaison with Ms. Lewinsky has
made such a concession unnecessary. ``We think by now everyone
knows that Paula was telling the truth,'' John Whitehead, one of
Mrs. Jones' lawyers said in an interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
