<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BOHLS-COX     09-27 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BOHLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys' Garrett played like the backup he is
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys came up just short. About 13
laterals and a trombone player short. That's if you really thought
Dallas had a chance on Oakland's final free punt to duplicate the
University of California's madcap, highlight-reel kick return
through the horn section of Stanford's band to stun the Cardinal
more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they were a quarterback short _ a true starting
quarterback anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Blame this 13-12 loss to the Raiders on the fall of Troy two
weeks ago at Mile High Stadium. When Troy Aikman broke his left
collarbone against Denver, forcing Jason Garrett into the starting
lineup, the Cowboys got exactly what they paid for: a backup
quarterback making near the NFL minimum, giving maximum effort with
minimal skills.
</P>
<P>
   This is no knock on Garrett. He is what he is. A super guy, a
solid player, a cerebral guy (read: he can't air it out 60 yards),
a backup guy. He went to Princeton for a reason, and he's been
Dallas' second-string quarterback for six seasons for another
reason. He does not have the arm of Aikman or the experience of
Aikman or the savvy of Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   He cost Dallas the game, but he was not supposed to be in a
position of having to win the game in the first place. That is not
his job description, as outlined by boss Chan Gailey, who prefers
that Garrett play smart and not make crucial mistakes. On Sunday at
Texas Stadium, he made crucial mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   He threw a drive-killing interception in the Oakland end zone
when Michael Irvin went left and Garrett threw right. He had a
false-start penalty and failed to connect on a third-down pass to
Chris Warren before Richie Cunningham misfired on a usually
makeable, 37-yard field goal. He misread double coverage and forced
a deep ball to Billy Davis that was easily picked off by safety
Eric Turner within 91 seconds remaining, effectively ending the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett knew he did all those things and readily accepted the
blame. Irvin, however, stewed privately, dressing in private
quarters and leaving without a comment.
</P>
<P>
   Of the miscommunication with Irvin, Garrett said, ``Michael
turned the thing inside, and I threw the ball outside. I made a
poor throw. It was my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the final throw to Davis, Garrett said, ``Obviously, it was a
poor decision.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can ever say Garrett doesn't have class. The contrast
between his first two starts was striking in their similarities. In
the Cowboys' dramatic 31-7 trouncing of the New York Giants on
Monday night, he threw for 222 yards. On Sunday, he again threw for
222 yards but had two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Giants, however, Garrett was simply part of a
machine that scored on a punt return and an interception return and
got suffocating defensive play that held New York to 56 yards
rushing. On Sunday, Garrett was asked to win the game because
Emmitt Smith was held to 59 yards and a 2.8-yard average while
Oakland chewed up yardage and precious clock time with 129 yards
rushing, most of them from Napoleon Kaufman, who averaged 4.8 yards
per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett was hardly the sole factor behind Dallas' loss. Davis
had a pivotal drop on the second play of the half on what would
have been a big gainer. There was the rare Cunningham missed field
goal. Tight end David LaFleur was close to a touchdown on a post
pattern until cornerback Eric Allen tipped away the ball. But why
didn't the Cowboys go back to that play or ever look for LaFleur
again? He's had two catches for eight yards in four games, making
him the biggest draft bust since Shante Carver.
</P>
<P>
   True, Oakland lucked out on its one big offensive play of the
game, a 75-yard, off-the-shoulder-pads, off-the-hands,
off-the-Sears-Tower touchdown catch by James Jett. But it played
fire-eating run defense and tackled punt returner Deion Sanders
before he ever made the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The loss could cost 2-2 Dallas home-field advantage down the
line but probably not more. Remember, somebody has to win the NFC
Least. Garrett will play .500 ball as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason did some good things and some things you wished he'd
done over,'' Gailey said. ``I don't have a magic formula. I can't
sprinkle any magic dust around.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Garrett was to blame, but he had company. And his 3-1
career record is still better than anyone could expect from a
clipboard technician (the NFL Players Association insists on
respectful euphemism). You don't see Trent Green saving the
Redskins or rookies Ryan Leaf or Peyton Manning perching their
teams on the Super Bowl's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   There's a learning process at work here, and Dallas was just
reminded of that painful lesson. Garrett's a perennial backup
quarterback for a reason. Now the Cowboys should back him up with a
stronger supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
