u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-HAITI-NYT &LR;      09-27 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-HAITI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAITIANS FAIL TO PREPARE AFTER MANY FALSE ALARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GARY PIERRE-PIERRE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONT SONDE, Haiti _ When it became clear last Monday that
Hurricane Georges would hit Haiti, Jean-Claude Delice, a
development official here in the Artibonite Valley, went on the
radio begging residents to evacuate their homes and sent a team of
his people with bullhorns to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   But few people in this farming area about 60 miles from the
capital, Port-au-Prince, paid attention. Similar warnings issued
before past storms had proven unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody took us seriously,'' Delice said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later, torrential rains and high winds from
the hurricane hit the area, forcing residents to flee in haste.
</P>
<P>
   Homes, livestock and crops were swept away by the flooding that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, entire villages were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Delice sent his men out again, this time in large trucks to
remote villages to rescue stranded residents.
</P>
<P>
   Delice said his organization was operating three shelters for a
total of about 1,500 people who were receiving a daily ration of
bread, milk, rice and beans, and water. But his supplies are
running perilously low as more homeless people flock to shelters
every day seeking help, Delice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't have the means to feed all of these people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm and flooding killed at least 94 people, with 60 still
missing. Hurricane Georges also destroyed much cropland in this
region, a fertile crescent of huge rice patties and banana
plantations that is considered Haiti's heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Now officials face the problems of providing immediate relief to
the stricken farmers and restoring crops and livestock production.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the destruction wrought on this country, the poorest in
the Western Hemisphere, there is a pervasive feeling here that the
damage could have been considerably worse, that the Dominican
Republic, which shares the island of Hispaniola, took the brunt of
the storm's force.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, officials and residents here blamed the
severity of the flooding on the government's failure to stop the
deforestation of Haiti's mountains by people felling trees for
charcoal. The denuded mountains absorb little rainwater, increasing
runoff and flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has not done anything to combat erosion,'' said
Sen. Rvelt Chery, an agronomist and a member of President Rene
Preval's party. ``Are we going to wait for another natural disaster
to do something?''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday in Pont Sonde, at a gymnasium turned into a makeshift
shelter, scores of people crowded around the courtyard and told in
chilling details how they barely escaped death, and mourned
relatives and friends who were not as lucky. Some said they had
paddled to safety in canoes, many hopped aboard trucks and others
climbed up trees.
</P>
<P>
   Claudette Augustin said she was sleeping when she suddenly
sensed that she was under water. Her husband went into the next
room and grabbed their two children. They made it to safety aboard
a pickup truck. As they drove away, their possessions streamed
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost everything,'' said Mrs. Augustin, clutching her
children, Alfred, 7, and Dieudonne, 10. ``The whole town was like
an ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Florisia Jean said that when the flood came, her first reaction
was to grab her five children and whisk them away to safety.
``That's all I have left,'' she said pointing to the blue skirt and
white T-shirt she was wearing. ``We are in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a week after Hurricane Georges left its path of
destruction, makeshift shelters at schools, churches and civic
centers here and across the country have been overwhelmed as
hundreds of people continue to fill them daily. So far there are
more than 150,000 people left homeless, officials in the capital
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the victims live in far-off areas that are difficult to
reach even under normal conditions. And while it has not rained in
Haiti in several days, many villages and towns remain heavily
flooded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to differentiate between land and sea,'' said Elange
Theodule, a father of three children who was forced to flee his
hometown of Seguin, a coastal hamlet near here. ``My first priority
was saving my family.''
</P>
<P>
   For many here, the hardest thing was the loss of their
livestock. In rural Haiti they are a kind of savings account for
farmers, who use them to pay for events like first communion,
baptisms and funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sleeping on trees like our animals,'' Clovis Daniel, a
cattle rancher who lost his entire stock of 15, said, referring to
sleeping quarters that he shared with about a hundred other people.
``Next time, we will listen. We know the realities of a storm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGES28-COX     09-27 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georges to kick into Gulf Monday
 &HT;    (EDS: CQ Tchoutacabouffa River and D'Iberville.)
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAVELAND, Miss. _ Charles &AMP; Ramona's Lounge was feeling the
punch Sunday from tidal surges and heavy rains kicked up by the
approach of Hurricane Georges, the most dreaded visitor since
Camille flooded this bayou town nearly 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The churning waters of the Mississippi Sound rushed across Beach
Boulevard before noon Sunday, long before Georges' expected
landfall today, a frightening omen for the low-lying southwestern
tip of Mississippi where thousands fled for higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to get kicked royally,'' said Orville Ferrell,
47, a construction worker drinking Bud Light at Charles &AMP; Ramona's.
</P>
<P>
   Three blocks from the Waveland waterfront, the cinderblock pool
hall filled with four feet of water when Camille, the century's
most powerful hurricane, struck in 1969 with winds topping 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Georges' 110-mph winds aren't nearly as strong, but the broad,
plodding storm is forecast to dump torrential rains for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Gulf Coast is also positioned to be battered by
Georges' most punishing northeastern winds and tidal surges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not scared, you need to be scared,'' said A.J.
Holloway, mayor of Biloxi, the waterfront gambling town under a
curfew extending along much of the Gulf Coast since Sunday night.
``It is severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since Hurricane Elena in 1985 has the Mississippi Gulf Coast
suffered widespread hurricane damage. Since then, billions have
been invested in coastal development spurred by casino gambling's
arrival in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 coastal casinos were closed, including the Copa Casino, a
refurbished cruise ship in Gulfport. Emergency preparedness
officials wanted the vessel to be towed to open waters, but it
waited too long and the Coast Guard would not let it leave, Switzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulfport area is bracing for ``as much as 30 hours of
hurricane-force winds and 60 hours of gale-force winds,'' said C.T.
Switzer, president of the Harrision County Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be something different than what we've had in
the past,'' Switzer said. ``Usually hurricanes have come through
here with six or seven hours of wind and rain, and we're through.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gulfport, a roadside sign at St. Andrew Church of God in
Christ in Gulfport admonished, ``Be sure your anchor holds to the
rock.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rural community of Pineville, near Long Beach, Billy
Bell, 53, positioned his fleet of dump trucks facing northward so
that debris blowing from the south wouldn't shatter the windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it would be going somewhere else,'' he said, smoking a
cigar and contemplating whether to evacuate to a shelter. ``I'll
decide when the winds get up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, winds in advance of Georges forced water into the
bayous that threatened houses and mobile homes along the Jourdan
River. Captains seeking refuge for their vessels anchored them on
the Tchoutacabouffa River near I-10, west of D'Iberville.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities closed all draw bridges, which prevented other
vessels from moving into inland rivers to seek shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Plywood covering doors and windows marred the stately historic
homes along the Mississippi Sound in Pass Christian and Bay St.
Louis. Newspapers lay in driveways Sunday morning, suggesting that
homeowners had already evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stay,'' said 80-year-old Charles R. Johnson,
retired pastor of Christ Episcopal Church in Bay St. Louis. He
stood with his daughter-in-law and six grandchildren beneath a
sweeping live oak tree with branches sculpted by decades of winds.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that Georges wouldn't be as bad as Camille, which
flooded the rectory where he lived and forced him to tread through
waist-deep water to another house.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, though, the house where he now lives with his
family has a second floor.
</P>
<P>
   In Long Beach, homeowners filled bags from a huge pile of
grayish-white sand. Ric Williams, 33, figured he'd try to block
water from entering his front and back doors.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ``If the water gets high enough, all the sand bags
in the world will not make any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Some emergency shelters near the coast filled rapidly, and
late-comers were instructed to travel to shelters hurriedly opened
farther inland.
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson County, officials opened four more shelters Sunday.
``That has put a strain on our manpower and our supplies, but I am
not going to turn anybody away,'' said Joe Rosa, manager of the
American Red Cross shelter at St. Martin High School near Biloxi.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross estimated that more than 3,500 people were already
in shelters as far away as Vicksburg, Jackson, and Meridian, with
the number steadily climbing. The Mississippi National Guard opened
Camp Shelby, south of Hattiesburg, to evacuees. Officials said
facilities there could house as many as 5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer said about 250 shelters were open along the coast. He
said the county would do everything possible to provide food but
that people ought to be prepared for up to three days in the
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   From the second-level deck of the Patio Apartments in Long
Beach, Joe Bergeron, 46, watched the rising sound creep toward U.S.
90, the four-lane highway that runs along Mississippi's 26 miles of
beachfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect deck for a hurricane party,'' he said. ``But
I'm staying sober in case I have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Highways heading northward were busy, as were the few businesses
that remained open during mandatory evacuation orders in Harrison,
Hancock and Jackson counties.
</P>
<P>
   Waffle Houses strung along I-10 were packed, including the one
in Diamondhead. Motorists waited nervously for seats, as cooks
scrambled to keep up with orders before items, including bacon and
hamburger buns, ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The Flying J Travel Plaza near Gulfport finally closed its doors
around noon and shut down its gas pump, leaving people waiting in
line to buy fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the Hampton Inn in Ocean Springs urged guests to
fill their bathtubs with water, as an emergency supply for drinking
and flushing toilets.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard closed ports at Pascagoula and Gulfport to
commercial shipping traffic late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi's barrier islands _ Petit Bois, Ship and Horn _ were
evacuated Friday, when Mississippi Gov. Kirk Fordice declared a
state of emergency. The state's four deep-water ports were also
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
