<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gulf residents, visitors keep nervous eye on Georges
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ In downtown Mobile, which sits on the
northwestern end of Mobile Bay and uses name like Canal and Water
for its streets, staff at the Radisson Admiral Semmes Hotel started
stacking sandbags outside the building's glass doors around 6 p.m.
Sunday. By then, gusts stirred by Hurricane Georges had picked up
and rain fell harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting,'' said the hotel's gift shop owner, who
identified herself only as Donna. ``We have a lot of out-of-town
guests, press and insurance agents. We had some people here from
Lousiana who got stuck here because the airport closed.''
</P>
<P>
   On its way to an expected landfall near New Orleans, Georges
lashed beaches east of here, knocking down a pier at Orange Beach,
and sending 25-foot waves crashing against concrete barriers
protecting buildings at Gulf Shores.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening Sunday the normally busy Perdido Beach
Boulevard through Gulf Shores and Orange Beach was deserted of all
but emergencyt vehicles, as officials
</P>
<P>
   Pat Jackson, with the Mobile/Bay Area Red Cross, estimated that
nearly 1,000 people had gone to eight shelters opened in Baldwin
County, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's deputies stood at the Florida-Alabama state line
turning back motorists attempting to flee Georges' feeder lines
striking the Florida Panhandle around Pensacola. Officials said the
storm was even more intense along the Alabama coast.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Davis, 81, was one of the guests at the Radisson hotel in
Mobile about eight blocks from his home. ``I'm here at the
insistence of my daughter,'' said Davis, who lives alone and went
through Hurricane Frederic, which struck here in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just usuallty go to bed and sleep through them,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Dauphin Street, Mobile's version of New Orlean's Bourbon
Street, businesses were shut down, their plateglass windows covered
with plywood or masking tape. The aptly named ``Monsoons'' tavern
was closed but its white and purple neon sign burned brightly in
the gloomy dusk.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, 11,000 residents near Mobile _ most of them on
the barrier islands _ had lost electricity. Minimal hurricane gusts
of 75 mph blew across Dauphin Island around 6 p.m. Sustained
measurements clocked at 60 mph grew steadily through the night. For
those with power who watched the local Fox affiliate, they saw
WALA-TV broadcast storm coverage in a split-screen that showed the
Atlanta Falcons-San Francisco 49ers game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mobile County Commission declared a state of emergency late
Sunday afternoon as some residents ventured out of their homes to
sightsee during lulls between feeder bands.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
