NYT-09-27-98 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-VOTE-ART-1STL     09-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-VOTE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BONN, Germany: to risk.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Greens have in the past called for a review of Germany's
NATO membership, causing concern in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, however, vowed continuity in foreign policy. He also
promised to foster reconciliation in a country still divided
between the west and its formerly Communist east, and said his most
important goal would be the fight ``against the plague of
unemployment.'' More than 4 million people, or 10.6 percent of the
population, are out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had a close relationship with Kohl, said in a
statement that he looked forward to working closely with Schroeder.
``Germany is one of America's closest allies,'' he said. ``As
always our two governments will be fully engaged in a comprehensive
policy agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Two central transformations set in motion under Kohl will now be
completed by Schroeder: the return next year of the German capital
to Berlin 44 years after Hitler's defeat, and the abandonment in
2002 of the beloved German mark, symbol of postwar stability, for a
European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not opt for an alliance with the Greens, or if his
majority proves too slim to make that partnership workable, the
alternative for Schroeder would be a ``grand coalition'' with the
Christian Democrats, an unwieldy alliance not tried for three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder declined to discuss possible coalitions until Monday,
saying he wanted to savor his victory. But he met late Sunday with
Joschka Fischer, the leader of the Greens, who has said he would
like to become deputy chancellor and foreign minister. The Greens
took 6.7 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl dismissed the possibility of a grand coalition, saying the
electorate ``has clearly opted for Red-Green.'' Kohl's finance
minister, Theo Waigel, said such a coalition would be ``absolutely
the wrong way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared clear that having suffered an overwhelming defeat,
the Christian Democrats were determined to let Schroeder confront
Germany's problems without them, hoping to benefit from the
difficulties he is almost certain to encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl made clear that he would abandon the leadership of the
Christian Democrats. He said he would ask the next party congress
to propose a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that Kohl made a fundamental mistake in
seeking a fifth term himself, rather than passing the mantle to his
deputy, Wolfgang Schaeuble. Several opinion polls have shown
Schaeuble to be the most popular politician in Germany, while
Kohl's lack of popularity was driven home by the fact that on
Sunday he lost his home seat of Ludwigshafen to a Social Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary reverse for the leader universally
hailed just eight years ago as Germany reunited. But unification
has proved more costly and difficult than foreseen, and the
tensions it engendered certainly contributed to Kohl's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many promises were made by Kohl, and nothing happened,''
said Uwe Terhorst, a disillusioned supporter of the Christian
Democrats. ``Workers were frustrated, taxes were up, and people had
lost faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In the former east, where one in five people of working age is
out of work, the level of disenchantment was revealed in a strong
vote for the Party of Democratic Socialism, the successor to the
East German Communist Party. It gained an estimated 5 percent of
the national vote, virtually all of it in the former East.
</P>
<P>
   Under German electoral law, a 5 percent score or a direct
victory in at least three districts is the condition for entering
parliament. As the party won four districts, it was assured of
entering the Bundestag.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's majority with the Greens _ perhaps 334 seats of a
total of 656 _ would have been much greater if the former
Communists had failed to qualify and their votes had been
redistributed, increasing the seats of the parties that did make it
into parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, premier of the northern state of Lower Saxony, will
become only the seventh chancellor of the postwar republic. He has
vowed not to govern in a coalition with the former Communists. It
is a measure of Germany's sensitive history _ marked by Hitler's
fascism and more than four decades of Communist rule over East
Germany _ that even today a coalition with the Party of Democratic
Socialism is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Europe, the situation is different. In France,
Jospin governs in coalition with the Communists, and in Italy,
Romano Prodi relies on the support of the former Communists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
