</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DOMREP-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER DISASTER, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC IS ON ROCKY ROAD TO REBUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HURRICANE-GEORGES and HURRICANE-HAITI.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER and RAYMOND HERNANDEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO DE MACORIS, Dominican Republic _ Under a blazing
Caribbean sun that made him squint as he worked, Rafael Dennis
began trying to rebuild his mother's little wood-frame house Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   It was not going to be an easy job.
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of thousands of people here in the Dominican
Republic whose homes were blown down or damaged when Hurricane
Georges struck last Tuesday, Dennis, in one of the hardest hit
areas, had almost nothing to work with. No lumber, no roofing
materials. Not even nails.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with much of the wreckage of the storm cleared away, Dennis
and many of the others were salvaging rusty nails, unbroken boards
and anything else they could find to piece their homes back
together. In every neighborhood, it seemed, men were up on ladders,
balanced on roofs with hammers and saws flashing in the sun, as the
country struggled to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis and some of the others said they hoped the government
would send trucks with corrugated tin for roofs. But they also knew
that the authorities had been preoccupied with opening roads,
restoring electricity and searching for missing people.
</P>
<P>
   And although relief supplies have begun to arrive from abroad,
many of the country's 8 million people have yet to receive any
help. Moreover, people who have tried to buy supplies say some
merchants have doubled their prices.
</P>
<P>
   For some Dominicans the worst of Hurricane Georges is still not
over. Adriano Tejada, the chief spokesman for President Leonel
Fernandez, said that at least a handful of towns and villages north
and west of the capital were still cut off by flood waters. The
government shipped food to a staging point near some of those
places, but it was not clear whether it reached the final
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have reported 201 deaths, mainly from
flooding and mudslides, but Hugh Parmer, a Texas lawyer who is now
in charge of humanitarian aid for the U.S. Agency for International
Development, said in an interview here that as many as 200 more
might be dead.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dominican government has not yet issued an estimate of
the cost of the destruction, Parmer said he expected it to run to
about $3 billion, or about $500 million more than the nation's
entire operating budget for this year. Officials have estimated the
hurricane damage in Puerto Rico at $2 billion. One reason losses
there were lower, Parmer said, was that Puerto Rico appeared to
have been better prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Four U.S. representatives, led by Elton Gallegly, R-Calif., the
chairman of the subcommittee on Western Hemisphere affairs, flew in
from Puerto Rico Sunday afternoon to talk with Fernandez and other
officials and to visit a shelter for storm victims. As they were
leaving a few hours later, Robert Menendez, D-N.J., said he would
support an increase in aid for the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Parmer said the United States had already spent about $500,000
in the relief effort here so far, and it expected to spend up to
several million dollars altogether.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dominican newspapers have reported that the hurricane caught
many Dominicans by surprise and the newspapers have criticized the
government, saying that it failed to issue adequate warnings.
Sunday morning, one of the leading newspapers, Listin Diario,
quoted Nicolas Cardinal de Jesus Lopez Rodriguez as saying the
government's lack of preparation had contributed to the nation's
losses. Responding earlier to the newspapers, Elpedio Baez, the
Dominican Civil Defense director, said he believed that the
criticism was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Parmer said Dominican officials had privately conceded to him
that they ``just underestimated the impact'' of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 20 years since they've had a bad storm like this,''
he said. ``It's human nature that when something happens that long
ago, you forget.''
</P>
<P>
   San Pedro de Macoris, overlooking the Caribbean, 32 miles west
of the capital city of Santo Domingo, had the misfortune of being
directly in the path of the hurricane as it steered a deadly course
along the southern coast before veering inland and tearing across
Haiti, the Dominican Republic's neighbor on the island of
Hispaniola.
</P>
<P>
   San Pedro is a city of more than 100,000 people, mostly poor and
working class, dominated by sugar mills and dreams of big league
baseball. It is the home of Sammy Sosa and scores of other baseball
stars. Even in their misery, nearly everyone seemed to be thinking
Sunday of the Chicago Cubs slugger as he battled to become the home
run king.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is great to see a fellow Dominican with such stature,''
said Efrain Vasquez, a 29-year-old factory worker, as he sat on a
stone bench in the small plaza known as Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane jabbed and punched at this entire city. But the
most crippling blows fell on the poorest people whose homes, like
those of Dennis and his mother, had been fine shelters from the sun
and the usual tropical downpours, but were no match for the
110-mile-per-hour gusts of Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Juana Garcia lives in a neighborhood of small wood and
concrete-block houses, Barrio Blanco, along the eastern bank of the
Higamo River. She and her six children figured they would ride out
the storm in their two-room concrete-block house. But as the winds
began to shake the house, they ran to a neighbor's bigger house,
higher up the bank. When the winds died down, all that was left of
Ms. Garcia's house was the front wall and half of another wall.
</P>
<P>
   At the white-washed, colonial-style Cathedral of San Pedro,
homeless families have set up house in the pews. And they are
pretty much on their own. Miguelina Contrera, a widow who ran to
the church when the calm eye of the storm passed over, after the
windows in her house had been blown out and the roof torn off, said
that neither the government nor the church had offered the refugees
anything but shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the clothes she and her daughters, ages 2 and 9, were
wearing, they had only a garbage bag with two thin blankets and a
couple of shirts. Beside them was a yellow plastic motor oil jug
with water that Ms. Contrera said was not fit to drink.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's industrial park, where row after row of low-rise
factories produce things like clothing and simple medical
equipment, tractor-trailers still lay on their sides Sunday as
workers patched roofs and tried to coax drenched machinery to work.
</P>
<P>
   Working on his mother's home Sunday, Dennis said he was not sure
where or when he would get his hands on the lumber and roofing
supplies he needed. But, he said, he thought he had salvaged enough
to finish at least a single room so she could stop living with
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to do this,'' he said. ``I feel bad because she's lost
everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
