<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MOORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet the new Falcons, same as the old Falcons
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nothing changes around here. Little cable cars
still race halfway to the sky. That golden bridge hasn't ceased
sparkling across the bay. Oh, and the San Francisco 49ers continue
to make the Atlanta Falcons look absolutely pathetic whenever they
visit Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the new Falcons. These were the old Falcons, minus
Charles Dimry. Then again, Dimry was around in spirit Sunday at
3Com Park during the Falcons' latest Bashing by the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Ignore the Falcons' rush near the end to squeeze the final score
to a tolerable 31-20. Said 49ers safety Merton Hanks, ``It was a
combination of them playing hard in the second half and us shutting
it down.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the 49ers lost interest after they rolled to the
easiest of 31-7 leads at halftime to expose the Falcons' 2-0 start
as a fraud. But the good news for the Falcons is that they don't
have to play the 49ers every week in a league filled with
mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the bad news was delivered to the Falcons by their
exceptional hosts, and that is the Falcons remain a long ways from
reaching the elite any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a long ways,'' said Falcons president Taylor Smith,
echoing the words of Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who declared, ``As
you can see, we're definitely not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many around the Falcons' locker room agreed, but they really
hadn't much of a choice. ``Let's face it,'' said Falcons safety
Eugene Robinson, shaking his head, before telling nothing but the
truth. ``That first half for us was horrid. We did nothing. We did
absolutely nothing. I mean, they just beat the crap out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho-hum. And did we tell you that the drive down the coast to
Monterey remains quite lovely this time of year?
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who don't remember Dimry, Jerry Rice certainly
does. Once, Rice advanced his legend as the NFL's deadliest
receiver by torching Dimry in the Falcons' secondary for five
touchdowns. This time, Rice finished with only two, but he powered
his way to 162 yards on eight catches.
</P>
<P>
   Rice had help, too. In fact, with Dimry's spirit running deeply
for the Falcons' defensive backs in general and cornerback Juran
Bolden and Robinson in particular, nobody wearing a Falcons uniform
has yet to tackle anybody wearing a 49ers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, while the Falcons' pass rush was allowing 49ers
quarterback Steve Young to count the number of seagulls in the sky
whenever he dropped into the pocket, Falcons quarterback Chris
Chandler was wondering if he'd leave town with his fingers and
toes. He was sacked seven times, but it seemed like 70 times.
</P>
<P>
   Ho-hum. This sounds like last year, and the year before that,
and each of the four years before that. Only the final score to
these blowouts changes when the Falcons dare to meet the 49ers
around here.
</P>
<P>
   On this soggy afternoon, it took the 49ers only 43 seconds after
the opening kickoff to race toward making history repeat. That's
when (who else?) Young fired a 66-yard touchdown pass to (who
else?) Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we came back in the second half, `` Robinson said,
``there are no moral victories in this league. It was just a
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
E-mail: tlmajc(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
