<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers' dominance over Falcons continues with 31-20 win
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Atlanta Falcons may have improved in
relation to where they were this time one year ago, but one thing
hasn't changed a bit. They can't win in San Francisco's 3Com Park,
where the 49es beat them 31-20 Sunday. It was the seventh straight
time the Falcons have lost here.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, there was significant improvement. Atlanta came in
having lost six straight games in San Francisco by an average score
of 43-16, so it closed that margin down.
</P>
<P>
   But the final score was misleading. The 49ers piled up 538 yards
of offense, including 394 in a first half that saw them take a 31-7
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (2-1) made it close by winning the second half, but
the 49ers (3-0) turned a bit conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said all week going in that this was going to be a
measuring stick to see where exactly we are, and as you could see
we're not there yet,'' said Falcons coach Dan Reeves, whose team
had won eight of its previous 10 games after a 1-7 start last year.
``We aren't there. But I like our football team from the standpoint
that they didn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons tried to make a run at the 49ers behind Jamal
Anderson, who ran for 91 of his game-high 123 yards in the second
half, including a career-long 42-yarder that set up his 4-yard TD
with 13:11 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, quarterback Chris Chandler hit Terance Mathis on a 31-yard
TD pass _ the second TD connection of the game between those two _
with 7:23 left. The point-after attempt was blocked though, leaving
the score 31-10. The Falcons hopes ended with 3:19 left, when
Chandler threw his third interception of the game by missing
running back Gary Downs down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler completed 16-of-38 passes for 254 yards, two TDs and
the three interceptions, but some of that wasn't his fault.
</P>
<P>
   There were multiple dropped passes, including what should have
been a 58-yard TD pass to Tony Martin. An offensive line with
rookies Ephraim Salaam at right tackle and Bob Hallen at left guard
(starter Calvin Collins left after the first series when he
re-aggravated an ankle sprain), allowed seven sacks. And when
Chandler wasn't going down, he was often running for his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a ways to go,'' said Chandler, wincing in pain has
he had ice on a sprained wrist, and his ankle in a bucket of ice
water. ``The young guys have got to start playing like veterans. A
lot of things got exposed today, areas that we have to improve
rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   This one started ugly for Atlanta, when 49ers quarterback Steve
Young hit Jerry Rice for a 66-yard touchdown pass on the second
play of the game. Rice beat cornerback Juran Bolden as he crossed
from left to right. San Francisco then scored on its next three
possessions, and four of five in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Young completed 28-of-39 passes for 387 yards, three TDs, and an
interception. Rice caught eight passes for 162 yards and two TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
