<HEADLINE>
PURSUING A DIFFERENT VISION AT THE LOS ANGELES TIMES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times, which in the last decade has experimented
with a variety of strategies for covering the sprawling megalopolis
around the city, is swiftly moving toward a major reorganization.
The move is likely to give the newspaper a higher national profile
and significantly alter its signature regional coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Editors at the paper said a loss of 50 to 75 positions, mostly
on the paper's large regional editions, was likely. But
redeployments and attrition may lessen the likelihood of layoffs,
they said. Still, a recent staff notice announcing the push to
develop ``cost-efficient models'' for regional editions has created
anxiety in a newsroom that vividly recalls the layoffs of more than
150 colleagues three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   These changes come at the end of a year that has seen the start
of five local supplements _ sections circulated one, two or five
days a week in highly localized areas _ which offer close-in
coverage of everything from local school sports to local civic and
business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And next month the newspaper plans to begin a new national
edition. In the last year it has added at least 10 business
reporters and expanded education coverage, according to Leo
Wolinsky, the newspaper's managing editor for news.
</P>
<P>
   The new moves, and the Sept. 18 notice that heralded them,
reflect the well-publicized vision of the Times' iconoclastic
publisher, Mark Willes, at the end of his first year in that job.
Willes, who is also the chief executive of the Times Mirror Co.,
the newspaper's parent company, hopes to show that newspapers can
make more money and provide better coverage by reinventing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   His commitment to having the editorial and business departments
join forces was evident in the way the notice was drafted, over the
joint signatures of its business leader, Kathryn Downing, the
newspaper's president and chief executive, and Michael Parks, the
editor and executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also raised warning flags about the newspaper's
revenue, particularly from classified advertising. It warned that
``national and classified revenues are not growing at the rates we
anticipated, and overall we are not achieving our anticipated
revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror's stock price, like that of most newspaper
companies, began to drop this summer shortly before the market
decline. It peaked at $65.8125 on June 10, and closed Friday at
$52.6875.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Sept. 18 staff notice enumerated eight ``principles,''
described as ``the foundation for the Times vision work now under
way.'' The first of these states: ``We hold that journalistic
quality, integrity and independence are essential.'' Other
principles make reference to improving ``the performance of our
communities,'' achieving 5 percent revenue growth annually and
increasing circulation ``by 500,000 on our way to increasing it by
1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent report from the Audit Bureau of Circulations,
for March 31, showed the Times' circulation had reversed a long
decline, going up slightly to 1,095,007 daily, and 1,385,373 on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the top editors and business executives of the Times'
regional editions in the San Fernando Valley and Ventura County, to
the north of the city, are scheduled to present recommendations for
streamlining and perhaps consolidating what have been
semiautonomous organizations. The third and largest regional
edition, based in Orange County, to the south, is not immediately
effected.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County and San Fernando Valley editions of the
newspaper were created in the mid-1980s, and the Ventura edition in
the early 1990s, with independent staffs of reporters and
photographers, to offer their regions distinctive versions of the
Times geared to their regional interests.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, according to editors who have worked in
those sections and spoke on condition of anonymity, as many as 20
pages, including the front page and much of the metropolitan
section, are assembled and reassembled two to four times. The new
reorganization is likely to streamline this process, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be undergoing change for many years to come,''
said Wolinsky, adding that the paper was becoming ``a kind of
newspaper laboratory.'' He added, however, that ``the essence of
The Los Angeles Times isn't going to change; authority and
credibility are all we have to sell, and you can't start messing
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the ``Our Times'' supplements, with their separate
staffs and micro-local orientation, is taken by some regional
reporters as a sign that their work may be seen as superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders of the paper are trying to sell it to us as a
supplement to our local coverage,'' said a reporter for the Valley
edition, who insisted on anonymity. ``But the writing on the wall
is that it will be a substitute.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
