<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI ARABS AND ISRAELI POLICE CLASH IN NORTH ON LAND PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-TALKS) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a disturbance reminiscent of scenes from the
Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza, Israeli riot police
officers clashed with Israeli Arabs in northern Israel on Sunday,
wounding scores with tear gas and rubber-coated bullets as youths
hurled rocks and set road blocks on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The melee was provoked by the Israeli Army's plan to confiscate
acres of olive groves in the Israeli-Arab town of Umm Al-Fahm and
use the area for a firing range. When the border police evicted
protesters from a tent on the site on Sunday, a call went out over
mosque minarets for residents to defend their land.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation intensified during the afternoon and continued
into the late evening, even after an army decision to allow the
fields to be harvested for six more months. Rocks littered the
roads, a bonfire raged at the town's entrance and ambulances took
the wounded, including at least eight police officers, to nearby
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The echoes of the intifada, the Palestinian uprising, were
indisputable as the story played out on Israeli television Sunday
night. There were familiar images: rock-throwing youths covering
their faces with their shirts, helmeted police firing water cannons
and rifles. But in this case, the clash was between Israeli
soldiers and Israeli citizens, inspiring bitter reaction from
Israeli-Arab leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of the police and border guards toward citizens
of Israel reminded me very much of what went on in the West Bank
and in Jabalya camp'' in Gaza, said Hashem Mahameed, a member of
the Israeli Parliament. ``I was wondering whether Israeli security
forces were reconquering Umm Al-Fahm. Is this an occupation?''
</P>
<P>
   The regional police commander, Alik Ron, blamed the Israeli
Islamic Movement, whose leader is the town's mayor, for using the
land dispute as ``a platform'' to incite the population. ``If they
continue with what you're calling an intifada,'' he said, ``there
will be more wounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a hospital bed, the mayor, Raed Salah, said he
believed that the army's land confiscation was part of a ``hidden''
plan to seize land to set up a Jewish settlement town. Salah said
he had been punched in the stomach by a police officer during the
clash.
</P>
<P>
   Since July the army, which had already confiscated hundreds of
acres of farm land in a region whose population is about 50,000,
began negotiating with local leaders to seize more for a gunfire
practice zone. After a protest tent was erected in the zone three
weeks ago, the police told leaders it was unsafe and demanded that
they take it down. On Sunday, they moved in in force.
</P>
<P>
   According to several demonstrators, the eviction was aggressive.
One protester, who gave his name as Ahmed Awada, 25, said the
police stormed the tent during prayers and quickly used clubs to
beat people. Awada, who wore a bandage over a gash on his head,
said he and his brother were beaten.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli-Arab member of Parliament, Abdel Wahab Saraushe, said
the conflict was the expression of a greater frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm warning the prime minister of Israel, the minister of
defense and the minister of the interior to start treating us as a
culture,'' he said, ``to put an end to this problem before it
ignites the Arab streets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
