<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECHARGED HURRICANE GEORGES SLAMS INTO GULF COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(EDS: 2NDTAKE upcoming in 20 minutes.) 
(sw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Hurricane Georges, rampaging again after earlier
devastating Caribbean islands and the Florida Keys, slammed into
the hunkered down seaside cities and resorts of the Gulf Coast on
Sunday night with rain-packed winds of up to 110 mph and a sea
surge of 10 feet or more.
</P>
<P>
   Recharged after a three-day, 10-mph wander across the Gulf's
tropical waters, the storm first began to move ashore in early
evening with it's 50-mph perimeter winds, then as the night wore
on, began to follow up with increasingly strong winds that near its
eye were consistently blowing harder than 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   There was concern that the storm, one of the most dangerous to
hit the vulnerable, low-lying Gulf region in many years, might
stall and not immediately move well inland should it collide with a
wall of high pressure air lying to the north.
</P>
<P>
   In such case, disaster experts said, there was the possibility
of almost catastrophic damage from drawn-our pounding by wind, rain
and surf of the affected coastal strip, which stretched 300 miles
from just west of New Orleans to just east of Panama City in the
Florida panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the stretch, at ground zero for the storm's
eye, was the city of Biloxi, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the region is only a few feet above sea level. And New
Orleans, which is surrounded by levees, lies an average of six feet
below sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Early damage reports made no mention of deaths or injuries, but
they indicated that the marshes and barrier islands in the path of
the storm had suffered a major battering and that behind them, in
the hours that followed, cities, towns, and resort strips were
suffering too, with extensive power outages, large numbers of trees
down and widespread damage to windows and roofs.
</P>
<P>
   On the northeast side of New Orleans, the storm surge in Lake
Ponchartrain was pushing water up against some levees and now and
again a rogue wave would crest over.
</P>
<P>
   The city has many pumps to handle accumulations of water in its
streets and open spaces, including major accumulations of rain
water. But the pumping system was not designed to handle a huge
accumulation made up of a massive over-topping of levees by Lake
Ponchartrain and a drawn-out hurricane downpour that could exceed
20 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of any reports of deaths or injuries was testament, in
part, to the early warnings given coastal residents that the storm
was coming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
