<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6910 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     09-27 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHBURN PITCHES ANGELS PAST A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The Angels looked to the future Sunday, and it seems
pitcher Jarrod Washburn will be in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn, subbing for Chuck Finley on the final day of the
season, pitched the Angels to a 4-2 victory over the Oakland A's
before 22,819 at the Oakland Coliseum. Washburn gave up two runs
and three hits in 62/3 innings to get the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finished the season 85-77, one game better than last
year's 84-78 mark.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Washburn nearly became an Oakland Athletic. It was
Washburn and center fielder Jim Edmonds who were ticketed to
Oakland last July in a trade for Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The trade never happened, McGwire hit 70 homers and the Angels
were left to hope Washburn's career will make fans forget what
might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn went 6-3 with a 4.62 ERA in 15 games this season. He
pitched into the sixth inning in nine of 11 starts and into the
seventh inning in seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think coming into the season I had a very good chance
of getting called up, unless it was as a September call-up,''
Washburn said. ``But because of injuries I got a chance. I think I
showed them I could pitch. I don't want to pitch in the minor
leagues ever again. But if they think I need to go down and work on
something, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me a little bit of (Tom) Glavine (of the Atlanta
Braves),'' said Angels manager Terry Collins. ``He uses his
fastball and changeup, and his breaking pitch is his third pitch.
That's the way Glavine is. He makes pitches with his fastball. He
doesn't overpower you. He lives with command.''
</P>
<P>
   While Washburn won't throw a fastball past anyone, his demeanor
on the mound seems to make up for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is not intimidated by anything,'' Collins said.
``That probably has impressed me as much as anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Chuck (Finley), Kenny (Hill), Omar (Olivares),
hopefully we'll sign (Steve) Sparks. We've got some guys and
hopefully Jarrod will be in the mix. You want options because you
never have enough pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels staked Washburn to a 1-0 lead in the first inning,
when they got three consecutive singles to begin the game. Edmonds
drove in Orlando Palmeiro for the first run of the game, Edmonds'
team-leading 91st RBI of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The A's evened the game at 1 in the second, after Mike Blowers
doubled and went to third on a groundout to second. Scott Spiezio
walked and tried to steal second. He stayed in a rundown long
enough to allow Blowers to score.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson's solo homer (No.15) gave the Angels a 2-1 lead
in the fourth, and Randy Velarde's two-run double made it 4-1 in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Doubles by Matt Stairs and Ben Grieve in the bottom of the
seventh cut the Angels' lead to 4-2 and knocked Washburn out of the
game. Pep Harris, Mike Holtz and Shigetoshi Hasegawa (fifth save)
closed out the win.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice way to end the season for the Angels, but it
hardly outweighed the disappointment felt throughout the clubhouse
from not making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed. We're not happy about it,'' Collins said.
``I know we fought threw a lot of problems, but we won't use that
as an excuse for not getting it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll think about everything over the next few days and this
team will go down as one of the teams I'm most proud of. I'll tell
you what, it's too bad a lot of managers don't have the players I
have. They've grown up and gotten better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
