<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LOOKS FOR LESSONS IN DAVIS CUP DRUBBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (js) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Already beaten before they had even stepped onto the
court, the U.S. Davis Cup team and the U.S. Tennis Association
officials who ran this star-crossed event went through the motions
of completing their demoralizing semifinal against Italy. After
all, the cheapest seats in the house had sold at $90 for a
three-day package, and on Sunday their occupants were owed a pair
of singles matches, meaningless or not.
</P>
<P>
   Italy had sealed the victory in the three-of-five-match
competition on Saturday when a five-set doubles loss by Todd Martin
and Justin Gimelstob gave the Italians a 3-0 edge. The match ended
at 4-1 after the teams split singles matches Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, a nation of tennis underdogs whose top player,
37th-ranked Andrea Gaudenzi, needed a cortisone shot in his aching
right shoulder to survive his weekend anchor duties, moves into the
final. Italy will be host to the defending champion, Sweden, which
blanked the United States by 5-0 in last year's final. Sweden
defeated Spain, 4-1, in Stockholm in their semifinal match.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians snapped the United States' decade-long home winning
streak at 18 rounds and cast further aspersions on the relationship
between Davis Cup officials and the top U.S. players, all of whom
elected to be elsewhere this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got skunked, and I can't say we're happy about it,'' said
Julia Levering, the incoming USTA president, who will inherit the
conundrum of staffing a Davis Cup squad for 1999, the centennial
year of this international competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at this loss as an investment in the future,''
she said. ``Because we didn't have our top players in Milwaukee, it
gave the new guard a chance to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The current president of the USTA, Dr. Harry Marmion, refused to
indict the losing semifinalists or the captain who recruited them,
Tom Gullikson, who is also the USTA's director of coaching for its
entire development program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team as presently constituted represented the best
of the American players who made themselves available to us,''
Marmion said. ``Playing for your country is very relevant to this
group, and I think Tom is almost the perfect coach. He has their
ear.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marmion conceded that neither he nor Gullikson has had the
ear of Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi or Michael Chang, who along with
Jim Courier arguably represent the best generation of players the
United States has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never have this situation again, where the top players
don't understand what it means to play for their country,'' Marmion
said. ``We let this generation of players get away without
inculcating them, and that's our fault, not theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Marmion said that had the Americans handled the Italians, he
would have urged Gullikson to stick with this same group for the
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sampras has his own agenda and already said he didn't want to
play, Chang has been more neutral but seemed not to be available
either, and as for Agassi, while it's true he puts fannies in the
seats and has won some big matches for us, the world does not
revolve around Andre Agassi, despite what he may think,'' Marmion
said. He was referring to Agassi's contention that had the USTA
staged this round on the West Coast, he would have sandwiched his
own duties as host at a charity gala in Las Vegas, Nev. between
singles matches.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sampras and Agassi were conspicuous by their absence, while
Jan-Michael Gambill and Gimelstob, neither of whom had an iota of
experience inside the Davis Cup pressure cooker, were conspicuous
by their presence. Each lost his debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all in situations we haven't been in before,'' Todd
Martin said at Thursday's bare-bones draw ceremony. Martin, forced
into his role as team leader by the vacancies left by Sampras and
Agassi, acknowledged that he would be ``the goat'' of the
proceedings if the weekend experiment flopped. It did, and after
losses to Davide Sanguinetti in Friday's singles and the doubles
loss to Gaudenzi and Diego Nargiso, Martin opted out of his singles
assignment Sunday and was replaced by Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   As he had been throughout the weekend, Courier was relegated to
the sidelines, a decision of Gullikson's that, as the round wore
on, was subject to second-guessing. As was his court selection.
</P>
<P>
   The hardcourt installed inside Milwaukee Arena at Gullikson's
behest, which was supposed to stump the clay-loving Italians,
instead played so slowly that it was the Americans who felt as if
they had stumbled onto an alien surface.
</P>
<P>
   While Marmion refused to fault Gullikson for his team picks, he
did leave his captain culpable for the court selection. ``The court
was Tom's responsibility; he knows it, and he blew it,'' Marmion
said. ``But I don't think the court is why we lost. I think the
time has come when we're going to have to learn to live with some
younger teams. There's going to be some lean years; but maybe it's
good for our soul to lose once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Match Points
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's matches, Gianluca Pozzi of Italy defeated Justin
Gimelstob, 7-6 (7-4), 7-5, and Jan-Michael Gambill of the United
States defeated Davide Sanguinetti, 4-6, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
