<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball's treat to fans: a finish worth remembering
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yogi was mistaken. After one of the most riveting
Sunday finales in baseball history, it ain't over even when it's
over.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of the regular season, the Cubs and Giants lost
dramatically within a minute of each other. Moments after the
Astros beat Chicago 4-3 in 11 innings in Houston, Neifi Perez
homered off Robb Nen in the bottom of the ninth to complete
Colorado's remarkable 9-8 comeback in Denver. That left the Cubs
and Giants at 89-73 and tied for the NL wild card spot, which
they'll decide tonight in a one-game playoff at Wrigley Field
(8:07, ESPN). The winner opens the NL Division Series Wednesday in
Atlanta (4:07).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Tom Glavine said after the Braves' 7-2 victory
denied the Mets a three-way tie for the wild card and gave Atlanta
its 106th win of the year. ``You don't know who to prepare for,
what to prepare for. It's a state of limbo. I don't think anybody
likes to be in a state of limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to anybody who we play,'' Glavine said of
the Cubs (6-3 against Atlanta this season after winning the last
five games) and Giants (2-7 versus the Braves). We'd just like to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   The other three best-of-five first-round pairings are set. The
Indians and Red Sox, the AL wild card, open the post-season Tuesday
in Cleveland at 1:07 p.m., the first of two afternoon affairs
before that series shifts to Boston. The AL East champion Yankees,
who won their 114th game Sunday, host the Rangers Tuesday and
Wednesday nights (8:07).
</P>
<P>
   The NL Central champion Astros open the other NL series Tuesday
at home against San Diego (4:07 p.m.). After an off day Wednesday,
the series resumes in the Astrodome Thursday afternoon before
shifting to San Diego Saturday and, if necessary, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the Cubs and Giants meet tonight in the NL's first
one-game playoff since 1980, when Houston beat Los Angeles to win
the NL West. On Sunday, the Astros prevented the Cubs from
clinching their first post-season berth since 1989. Trailing 3-1,
Houston scored twice in the eighth inning before Carl Everett
tripled in the 11th and scored on Richard Hidalgo's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa didn't homer Sunday and fell four home runs behind
Mark McGwire, who hit Nos. 69 and 70 in St. Louis. But Sosa still
has a shot at the post-season, courtesy of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 7-0, the Rockies scored six runs in fifth inning and
took an 8-7 lead on Vinny Castilla's two-run homer in the seventh.
Jeff Kent's solo in the eighth tied it, but Perez homered off Nen
to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe somebody is looking out for us,'' Cubs shortstop and
ex-Brave Jeff Blauser said. ``What would somebody with a death-row
reprieve say? Whoopee. We've got another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a 30-second swing between them losing and us
losing,'' said Giants manager Dusty Baker. ``We are happy going to
Chicago. We could be going home to paint the garage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
