<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LAY THEIR FINAL EGG, AND AWFUL TASTE LINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The final indignity of the Mets' 1998 season did not
come when Mike Piazza popped out Sunday to short right center field
for the final out of a 7-2 defeat to the Atlanta Braves in what
might have been the All-Star catcher's final game as a Met.
</P>
<P>
   That the Mets, who lost their last five games to finish with
exactly the same amount of victories (88) as they had last season,
had just been eliminated from the National League wild card race
was painful enough. But before they boarded their plane to New
York, they were subjected to one final reminder of how badly they
had collapsed in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments of one another, Chicago lost in Houston and San
Francisco lost in Denver, and all the Mets had to fly home with was
a sinking feeling, knowing that had they won Sunday _ or any time
since last Sunday _ they would be playing at Shea Stadium on Monday
afternoon, their playoff hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both going to lose, aren't they?'' Mets General
Manager Steve Phillips remarked shortly before leaving Turner
Field, his voice choked up with emotion, as if the full realization
of what had been irretrievably lost had just sunk in.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had dropped a game behind the Cubs and Giants in the
wild card race Saturday night. After they fell 5 runs behind Greg
Maddux (18-9) and the Braves after two innings Sunday afternoon, it
was only a matter of time before their season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against the teams we should have beaten, we didn't do it,''
Piazza said. And he was not talking about the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday evening, the Mets had led the wild card race by one
game over the Cubs and four games over the Giants. New York and
Chicago had five games to play, San Francisco seven. And even
though it is the Cubs who are known for their ill-fated history, it
turned out to be the Mets who lost all five, two of them at home to
the lowly Montreal Expos before the Braves finished sweeping them
out of their season here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even Manager Bobby Valentine, the most positive person in the
organization, appeared to be resigned to his team's fate as he
quietly spoke with reporters before Sunday's game. And afterward,
as Valentine sat glumly in his office, he searched for
explanations.
</P>
<P>
   After managing so splendidly for most of the season, Valentine _
who has never been to the playoffs in a career that has spanned
three decades in the major leagues _ was cursed with a sort-of
reverse Midas touch the last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said Valentine, who was gracious
in defeat. ``If I knew, I would have done something about it.
That's my frustration about it. Everything I tried didn't work.
There should have been something. There should have been
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Valentine second-guessed himself for not starting Hideo
Nomo instead of Armando Reynoso. The decision seemed to be a
no-brainer. Nomo had struggled all season and had not pitched since
Sept. 8. And Reynoso had been one of the major reasons why the Mets
had rallied back into wild card contention, beginning in late July.
</P>
<P>
   But Reynoso was 0-6 lifetime against Atlanta with a 6.37 earned
run average coming in. And Nomo, who was 2-0 with a 2.13 ERA
against the Braves over his career, had been throwing well on the
side.
</P>
<P>
   When Reynoso (7-3) allowed 5 runs in just one and two-thirds
innings _ including a two-out double to Maddux in the bottom of the
second that opened the door for a 4-run outburst _ another of the
manager's moves had backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo eventually did pitch. Not only that, in his first major
league relief appearance, Nomo pitched well, delivering four
scoreless innings of 3-hit ball, while the Mets rallied for a
third-inning run.
</P>
<P>
   And when Piazza stepped up to the plate with one out in the top
of the seventh, runners on first and third, and a run already in,
the Mets, who trailed 5-2, were very much in the game. The stage
was set for another of the miraculous comebacks that had
characterized their season.
</P>
<P>
   But Piazza _ who was the Mets' most valuable player this year,
even though he was not acquired until May 22 _ was struck out for
the second time in three days by Dennis Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was on three pitches, the last of them leaving
Piazza arguing a called third strike. Then, John Rocker came on and
struck out Brian McRae on a full count to leave two more runners
stranded. And, after six more outs, the Mets' season was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we just ran out of gas,'' said Lenny Harris. ``And
there were no gas stations open. They all closed down as soon as we
got to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the Mets face an offseason of uncertainty in which they
could lose their best hitter, Piazza, and their best pitcher, Al
Leiter, to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said Phillips, who had gambled part of
the organization's future for a shot at the post-season when he
acquired Piazza from the Marlins. ``My hopes were grander than just
getting to the playoffs. But I'm also excited about putting a team
together for 1999. And that's what's getting me through today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
