<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-SOSA-     09-27 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-SOSA-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS AND GIANTS TIE; SOSA, 4 BEHIND, GETS LAST SHOT AT MCGWIRE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Sammy Sosa and the Chicago Cubs walked off the indoor
carpet, slump-shouldered losers in the home run race and the
wild-card race. They had blown a lead again, losing 4-3 in the 11th
inning of the last game of their overachieving season. The only
home runs in the Astrodome had been on video, with Mark McGwire
hitting Nos. 69 and 70 on the giant video screen above Sosa's head
in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fate of the Cubs was undecided on the scoreboard, to be
judged by a game in Denver that was tied 8-8 in the ninth inning,
at least for one long minute. As the Cubs trudged up the wooden
stairs to their lockers, they heard the clubhouse boy screaming,
``We play tomorrow!'' The San Francisco Giants also had blown a
lead, losing to the Rockies, 9-8, on a home run in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   So the two races that have captivated baseball, and America,
live for another day.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was homerless Sunday, knocking in the first run but stuck
at 66 home runs. In St. Louis, McGwire tacked on a pair, besting
Roger Maris' 37-year-old record by a once unthinkable cushion of 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   To tie McGwire, Sosa needs four home runs Monday night in
Chicago against the Giants. The winner of the Giants-Cubs game will
occupy the last seat in the National League playoffs, traveling to
Atlanta on Wednesday to begin a five-game series against the
Braves, who put the New York Mets out of their misery Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the games ended, thousands of Cubs fans had
surrounded Wrigley Field in Chicago, buying tickets for the final
game of a magical season.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was upbeat after the game, despite losing to the Giants and
falling behind McGwire. He congratulated McGwire and contemplated
his own happier travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire's going to the beach,'' Sosa said. ``I'm going to go
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a No. 66 cap, Sosa conceded that the home run race was
over. In the entire history of major-league baseball, only 12
players have hit four home runs in a single game. But that's a lot
more than have hit 66 or more home runs in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   Any home runs that Sosa hits in the one-game wild-card playoff
will count in individual statistics for the regular season; home
runs in later playoff games and the World Series will not. The
extra game gives the Cubs 163 chances, the same as McGwire's
Cardinals, who replayed a suspended game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about the home runs any more,'' said Sosa,
who finished the day 2-for-5 with a stolen base and an RBI. ``I'm
really happy for Mark, and say, he's the man. One hundred years
from now, when they mention McGwire's name, maybe they'll mention
me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitcher for the Cubs in the wild-card playoff game
will be Steve Trachsel (14-8), who beat the Giants on Aug. 12 but
has been pummeled in three starts since he gave up McGwire's
record-breaking 62nd home run in St. Louis on Sept. 8. The Giants
are scheduled to start Mark Gardner, 13-5, who had a no-decision in
his only start against the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said he would have to make a point of saying hello this
winter to his fellow Dominican, Neifi Perez, who hit the home run
that beat the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to shake his hand,'' Sosa said. ``We're still alive.
That's the only thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The late-inning failures by the Cubs and Giants raised
scoreboard watching to a high art Sunday. The day began with the
Cubs and Giants tied for the National League's wild-card
consolation prize, and the Mets one game behind. The first game was
decided in Atlanta, as the Mets collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the Astros, who are headed to the playoffs against the
San Diego Padres, the Cubs took a first-inning lead when Sosa
knocked in a run with a line drive single to center with two
runners on base. The Cubs didn't send Mark Grace home from third,
where he was stranded by a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sosa could bat again, McGwire hit his daily home run in
St. Louis. The announcement was withheld until after Sosa struck
out in the second inning. As he was walking out to right field, a
gigantic McGwire appeared above him, hitting No. 69 on video.
</P>
<P>
   The hitting and pitching hero for the Cubs was Terry Mulholland,
who has seen pressure before. He started a World Series game and an
All-Star game as a Phillie. Sunday, the grim-faced Mulholland mowed
down the Astros, striking out nine in eight innings. A bloop hit
tied the score for the Astros in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs went ahead 3-1 in the fourth inning, after the Astros'
second baseman, Craig Biggio, made ``the dumbest play of my
career,'' dropping a routine ball trying to turn a double play _
when there were already two outs. Mulholland then knocked in two
runs with a line-drive double over the head of center fielder
Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   When Sosa came to bat in the fifth, the scoreboard showed the
Giants leading, 3-0, and the Mets falling further behind, 7-2. On
the first pitch to Sosa, the 51,916 Astros and Cubs fans roared
when he hit the ball, but this was no souvenir, falling harmlessly
into Hidalgo's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs blew their lead in the eighth, when the Astros scored
two runs on three hits.
</P>
<P>
   From the ninth inning, the closers took over: Billy Wagner vs.
Rod Beck. Wagner held Sosa to a soft fly ball to center in the
10th, and Sosa walked back to the dugout, pantomiming the swing he
had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard showed the Giants falling behind in Denver, 8-7,
when the Astros rallied in the 10th inning here. Beck stranded
Derek Bell at third base. As Beck was being congratulated in the
Cubs' dugout, the scoreboard showed the Giants scoring to tie the
game, 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th, Beck's high wire act fell to the Astroturf. Former
Met Carl Everett tripled off the wall in right field as Sosa shied
away from the wall. Beck walked Biggio intentionally, and Cubs
Manager Jim Riggleman brought in an outfielder as a fifth
infielder. Hidalgo hit a fly ball to deep left-center field, and
Everett trotted home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
