<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCARLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rudd holds off Gordon to win
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Nothing could derail Ricky Rudd from winning
Sunday's NAPA AutoCare 500 at Martinsville Speedway. Not the
sweltering heat that penetrated the gloves on the wheel or the cool
suit that turned hot seat, leaving him sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a long time coming,'' said Rudd of the victory he
needed for his team and to extend to 16 the number of years with at
least one victory. It also was his third victory at Martinsville
and first here since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The hot seat was one he could have done without. He considered
at one point to give it up and turn things over to Hut Stricklin.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most dominating victory of his career. He led 198 of
the 400 laps and took the checkered flag by .533 seconds ahead of
runnerup Jeff Gordon. Mark Martin was third.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett had the week he'd rather have done without. His
motor gave out on lap 291 and he was through for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such a great car, I didn't want to give it up,'' said
Rudd, who hadn't won since the 1997 Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis.
``We were pretty fast on the speed chart and qualified second. But
lately, we'd qualify good and fall backwards at the start of the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was others who did the falling back. Neither Gordon
nor Martin led a lap, though finishing second and third. His
primary competition was Sterling Marlin, who led four times for 231
laps, but finished four laps down to Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   ``My car just wouldn't come in when I needed it to,'' said
Marlin, who led none of the final 110 laps. ``It's hard to win a
race here. He's won each year for a number of them in a row, so my
hat's off to him.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it was Gordon he feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was coming. He had a fast car and I could see him in my
mirror,'' Rudd said. ``They're famous for that last race charge.
Sterling was really the car to beat, but he faded away. Once we got
even on our tires, though, we were pretty good. I was pretty
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Gordon or Martin's day. Gordon started third and
finished second. Martin went from 13th to six. Neither led a lap, a
first since Phoenix last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it any way I can get it,'' Rudd said. ``This win is
just as big as Indianapolis to me right now. The first half this
year was the toughest I've been through. Maybe that's why we dug
down so deep to make it happen today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom McCollister writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
