A6920 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART     09-27 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW ORLEANS: was coming.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since it formed in the Atlantic off the west coast of Africa a
couple of weeks ago, and started to blow west, the hurricane has
caused more than 300 deaths, most on the Caribbean island of
Hispaniola, and has left hundreds of thousands of people homeless.
Damage estimates range in the billions of dollars, with about $1
billion of that occurring in hard-hit Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a devastating storm,'' said James Lee Witt, head of the
Federal Emergency Management Agency, as his teams prepared to move
into the Gulf Coast area once Hurricane Georges moves on.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of coastal residents fled northward in the
hours before the storm blew ashore, so many that on many highways,
cars, vans and trucks were bumper to bumper for miles on end.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of others took refuge in schools, public buildings and
other shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Here in New Orleans, some ten thousand people were housed in the
hallways and corridors of the massive Superdome, many spreading
their blankets on the concrete and doing what they could, with
their books and puzzles and bags of chips, to make the best of a
bad situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here before for football games, but this ain't no
game,'' said Demetrius Moody, an oil rig operator, as he slumped in
an end-zone seat in the sports arena, which can hold 69,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   In places along the coast where there were no levees to protect
people and property, emergency officials ordered residents to
evacuate. Most moved to higher ground with few, if any, complaints.
</P>
<P>
   And even in areas where evacuation was not mandatory, thousands
left anyway, heeding the words of Mayor Marc Morial of New Orleans,
whose repeated pre-storm warning was: ``Our recommendation to
people is to go. We're in a state of emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   The French Quarter of downtown New Orleans _ where the
unofficial motto is ``Let the Good Times Roll!'' and whose streets
are normally packed with noisy partygoers _ was nearly abandoned in
the hours just before the storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   Bourbon Street was empty of jazz, strippers and tipplers with
only a few dogs wandering about sniffing the garbage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
