<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STEWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWS HIT THE SPOT AFTER THE WEATHER TAKES ITS AUTUMN TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY ROBERTS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing like a steaming bowl of hot stew to warm your
insides when it's dank and gray outside.
</P>
<P>
   Food cooked in a single bubbling pot makes for some of the most
basic meals, and cultures around the world feature stews.
</P>
<P>
   From her homeland of Northern China comes Judy Fu's Land and Sea
Stew, a specialty of the house at her Snappy Dragon restaurant in
Seattle's Maple Leaf neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese people like it during the rainy season or winter
because it's hot _ and very good,'' said David Fu, who manages the
restaurant for his mother. ``It's a warm-tummy meal.''
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't only cold climates that inspire stews. The callaloo
that chef-owner Greg Caldwell of BarBaCoa in Greenwood prepares as
an entree stew takes its cue from the Caribbean, where variations
of callaloo soup appear on different islands. The dish gets its
name from a green grown in the region, but Caldwell substitutes
collard and mustard greens.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco, another warm-weather locale, is the source of tagine, a
stew distinguished by its North African seasonings and inclusion of
fruits and nuts. At the Capitol Club, a Middle Eastern restaurant
on Capitol Hill, chef Michael Felsenstine prepares a version with
lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their origins, stews are inherently flexible and
forgiving. Different combinations of meats, seafood and vegetables
may be substituted for the ingredients specified in these recipes,
depending on what's at the market _ or in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Fu's Land and Sea Stew
</P>
<P>
   Group 1:
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken breast, about 6 ounces, sliced into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces flank steak, sliced into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   6 shrimp balls (available in Asian markets)
</P>
<P>
   Group 2:
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup prawns, deveined
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup scallops
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup squid steak, cut into 1-by-2-inch pieces and scored
</P>
<P>
   1 16-ounce package medium-firm tofu, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Group 3
</P>
<P>
   1 1.7-ounce package mung bean threads (bean vermicelli), soaked
in warm water for 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Napa cabbage, shredded 1/2-inch wide
</P>
<P>
   3 sliced fresh button mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   3 dried shiitake mushrooms, soaked in water, then sliced
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup canned mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Group 4:
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Steamed rice
</P>
<P>
   Bring 6 cups of water to a boil in a large wok or pot. Add each
group of ingredients in succession, pausing slightly after each of
the first two groups to ensure that the chicken and seafood are
fully cooked. When all ingredients have been added (except the
rice), remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a full-bodied chili sauce, such as Lan Chi brand
black bean chili paste. Serve with individual bowls of steamed
rice. Diners traditionally choose morsels of stew, one by one, to
accompany their rice; when the rice is finished, the broth may be
poured into the empty bowls and supped.
</P>
<P>
   Serves four.
</P>
<P>
   From Judy Fu, Snappy Dragon, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Callaloo BarBaCoa
</P>
<P>
   For the prawn stock:
</P>
<P>
   Shells from 30 large prawns
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces butter
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces garlic, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, quartered lengthwise, then chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half quarts water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups white wine
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup fresh-squeezed lime juice
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-quart sauce pan, saute the garlic briefly, then add the
onions and continue to cook until the onions are limp. Add the
prawn shells and pepper and continue to saute until the shells are
fragrant and almost beginning to burn. Add the wine to loosen any
residue from pan bottom; scrape if necessary. Add water and let the
mixture come to a full boil for 10 minutes. Strain the liquid into
another pan and reduce by one-half over medium heat. Remove from
the heat and stir in the lime juice. Let the stock cool and
refrigerate up to two days.
</P>
<P>
   The greens:
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches red chard
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches collard greens
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch mustard greens
</P>
<P>
   1 cup prawn stock
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Wash the greens, remove the stems, ignore the ribs and cut in
narrow shreds. Pour olive oil into a large, heavy pot with a
close-fitting lid and saute garlic, uncovered, over medium heat
until it begins to turn amber. Add the shredded greens and continue
to saute until the greens become very limp. Add 1 cup prawn stock.
Cover the pot and cook over low heat until the thickest ribs are
tender. Remove from heat and let cool, then refrigerate one day.
</P>
<P>
   The Callaloo:
</P>
<P>
   30 prawns
</P>
<P>
   2 poblano peppers, cut in one-quarter-inch dice with seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 habanero peppers, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red bell pepper, cut in one-quarter-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Yukon gold potatoes, cut into one-half-inch dice (enough to make
60 dice)
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken bouillon cube
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Slice the potatoes into wedges,
eight to a potato; crumble a chicken bouillon cube into some olive
oil and coat the wedges. Roast the potato in the oven for 30
minutes. Let cool and dice (potatoes may be prepared in advance and
refrigerated).
</P>
<P>
   Sear the prawns in a dry, non-stick pan over high heat until
they begin to char; don't cook completely, as they will finish
cooking in the stew (prawns may be cooked a day ahead if
refrigerated immediately).
</P>
<P>
   Heat the peppers in a large, dry, non-stick pan until they begin
to brown. Add the prawns and continue cooking for 1 minute,
agitating the pan. Add the potatoes and prepared greens and
continue cooking for 5 minutes with constant agitation. Remove the
prawns and place them in serving bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining prawn stock to the cooking pan and bring the
mixture to a boil. Remove from heat and ladle the broth into the
bowls. Serve with cornbread and tropical fruit salad.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   From Greg Caldwell, BarBaCoa Caribbean Grill, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Tagine of Lamb Shank
</P>
<P>
   1 lamb shank, about 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, medium dice
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, medium dice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ginger, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces dried Black Mission figs
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried apricots
</P>
<P>
   One-half ounce golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces red wine
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   Couscous
</P>
<P>
   For the Spice Mix
</P>
<P>
   Combine:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coriander
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon sumac
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   Rub lamb with spice mix and let sit at room temperature about 20
minutes. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a four-quart sauce pan,
heat oil and brown the lamb shank. Remove shank from pan. Add
onions, carrot, garlic and ginger to pan and saute until they
soften and turn limp. Deglaze pan with red wine. Return shank to
pan, add water, cover with foil and place in oven for 1 hour.
Remove pan from oven, add the dried fruit, cover with foil and
return to oven for 30 minutes or until the meat is falling off the
bone.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over couscous.
</P>
<P>
   Serves four.
</P>
<P>
   From Michael Felsenstine, Capitol Club
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
