r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI &LR;      09-27 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPE FOR A SIMPLER WORLD AND A BREAKFAST FIT EVEN FOR BILL
GATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, I own a Toshiba Satellite with Intel inside, Xywrite III,
WordPerfect, Microsoft Windows and a Megahertz modem.
</P>
<P>
   I have likely violated 37 anti-trust laws before I've finished
breakfast and I am not allowed to plead ignorance because I own the
complete Data for Dummies collection from IDG Books.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to get any help from Bill Gates. He's in big
trouble, too, for trying to simplify my life.
</P>
<P>
   Don't whisper this confession to the feds, but I desperately
need a simpler life.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   Monday I discovered we were missing one of the four little,
round plastic thingies that go on the bottom of the toilet seat.
</P>
<P>
   No problemo.
</P>
<P>
   I raced to a nearby home supply store that is three times the
size of Boeing's largest hangar. The clerk directed me to an aisle
where approximately 173 different toilet seat thingies were on
display. It took me only 87 minutes to determine that none of them
matched my plastic thingies.
</P>
<P>
   I decided I would either have to buy a set of two different
thingies or sell my house. Isn't it a step backward, if I remove
and discard the three perfectly good thingies that remain under the
seat? Would that not only encourage thingie manufacturers to
produce toilet seat cushions in an additional 173 different styles,
sizes and shapes?
</P>
<P>
   Mulling this philosophical dilemma, I wandered over to another
department in the home supply store, approximately a quarter mile
away. I needed to replace the little paper sack that catches the
dirt in my Dustbuster Classic hand vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   I had delayed making this purchase in a one-person consumer
revolt after discovering that three replacement sacks cost as much
as a bottle of good Scotch. Never mind trying to find an economical
bargain brand. If they exist they won't fit. So I was prepared to
bite the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what I learned? The store was still selling Dustbusters,
but no longer carries the little sacks that go inside.
</P>
<P>
   Tell the truth, Janet Reno! Wouldn't the world be a better place
if Bill Gates also manufactured little paper sacks and plastic
thingies?
</P>
<P>
   What did I tell you? I haven't eaten breakfast yet and I'm
probably already in trouble. Well, I might as well make this a good
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast for Bill
</P>
<P>
   3 cups frozen shredded potatoes, thawed
</P>
<P>
   canola oil spray or butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced ham
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup diced green pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup milk
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Plunk the thawed potatoes on paper towels and blot to dry. Dump
the spuds into an ungreased nine-inch pie plate. With your hands,
press the potatoes to form a crust covering the bottom and sides of
the plate. So far I think everything is perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you can spray the potato crust with canola oil or,
if you want to live like a Microsoft millionaire, drizzle the crust
with a third of a cup of melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the crust in a 425-degree oven for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile combine the ham, cheese and pepper. In another bowl
beat together the eggs, milk, salt and pepper. You can use egg
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   When the crust is cooked, spread the ham-cheese mixture over the
bottom, then slurp on the egg mixture. Reduce oven temperature to
350 degrees and continue to bake the ``pie'' for 25 to 30 minutes,
or until a knife stuck in the middle comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Cut into four wedges and serve for breakfast or brunch with a
fresh fruit cup and muffins or toast.
</P>
<P>
   To cut down on the a.m. cooking time, I have baked the potato
crust the night before, then filled it and finished cooking in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   I have also been known to eat bean soup for breakfast and I'm
pretty sure there is a federal law against that. But the attorney
general might not prosecute if she tried a few slurps of this:
</P>
<P>
   Trust-buster Bisque
</P>
<P>
   4 stalks celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 medium carrots, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried basil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned white beans
</P>
<P>
   Combine the first five ingredients in a saucepan and simmer 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the canned beans, then puree this mess in your blender, in
two batches. Reheat and add salt and pepper to taste. This will
make two large or four small bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: If you ever lose the rubber ring that goes inside your
blender, you may have to buy a new kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
