<HEADER>
A6923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-COX     09-27 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs get a break when Rockies beat Giants
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Chicago Cubs have suffered for a long time, so
what's another minute to professional sports' most celebrated
losers?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anything, really. The Cubs, 4-3 losers to Houston in 11
innings on Sunday, were in danger of having their grip pried off
the National League wild-card ticket to the playoffs. But less than
a minute after Richard Hidalgo hit a sacrifice fly to beat the
Cubs, Colorado defeated San Francisco 9-8, creating a tie for the
wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago and San Francisco will play tonight at Wrigley Field,
with the survivor heading to Atlanta to begin the playoffs. The
Cubs have not reached the postseason since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to run to the clubhouse to watch on TV,'' Cubs
catcher Scott Servais said. ``We didn't make it that far when we
found out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, meanwhile, didn't need a victory on Sunday, but one
sure can't hurt their confidence for the playoffs, where they will
open against San Diego. The best-of-five series begins Tuesday at
3:05 p.m. at the Astrodome. The Astros finished with their best
record ever, 102-60.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Sammy Sosa had a chance to catch St. Louis' Mark
McGwire in the home-run record competition. But Sosa failed to hit
one Sunday, and McGwire slugged two, setting the record at 70. Sosa
needs to hit four home runs today to catch McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him, but he's probably gonna go to the beach
tomorrow, and I'm going to play,'' Sosa said. ``I hope I hit two.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone did hit a big home run for the Cubs, though _ Colorado
shortstop Neifi Perez. His ninth of the season in the bottom of the
ninth inning won the game against San Francisco, which led 7-0
before the Rockies scored six runs in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs might consider sending Perez a thank-you note. He
bailed them out after a difficult day in the field for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Houston scored the winning run on Hidalgo's fly ball to center
after pinch hitter Carl Everett hit a line drive over Sosa's head
in right for a triple. Sosa seemed to get caught in between
strategies. First he slowed down, losing any chance of making a
difficult catch. Then he failed to stop and play the ball quickly
off the wall, which would have limited Everett to a double.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it bounced away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky it didn't go over the fence,'' Sosa said. ``Only
Superman could catch that one. I'm not Superman.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago was not nearly as wasteful as the Giants. The Cubs blew
only a 3-1 lead, but they did it in a manner befitting the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, leading off the eighth for the Astros, hit a low
line-drive to left. Jose Hernandez, who had just moved from
shortstop to left field, charged in and missed the ball, turning a
single into a double. Jeff Bagwell drove Hidalgo home with a
single. Bagwell scored from first when Sean Berry hit a fly to
center that dropped between shortstop Jeff Blauser and center
fielder Lance Johnson, the latter stopping in his tracks instead of
taking charge of a ball that was easier for him to catch.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs took their 3-1 lead during the fourth inning in an
unlikely way. With two outs and a runner on first, Servais hit a
grounder to short. Ricky Gutierrez scooped up the ball and flipped
it to Craig Biggio at second. Biggio, winner of the NL Gold Glove
Award for second basemen the last three years, dropped the ball.
Cubs pitcher Terry Mulholland followed with a double to right
center, driving in only his second and third runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   That 3-1 lead stood until the Cubs' defensive foibles in the
eighth inning. But today they have a chance to atone.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs Manager Jim Riggleman understands that everything his team
does at this time of year is magnified and placed in historical
perspective, a result of the franchise's futility. The Cubs have
not won a World Series since 1908 and have not played in one since
1945.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if such history is an unfair weight to carry through a
season, Riggleman said, ``It probably is. It's like (Cubs
President) Andy MacPhail said a couple of years ago, not a day goes
by that someone doesn't mention 1908 and 1945. We carry part of
that burden.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Astros, they begin the playoffs as a popular choice
to win the National League championship and perhaps the World
Series, a vote of confidence that Manager Larry Dierker accepts
philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right with me,'' Dierker said. ``Unless you're a
Braves fan or a Yankees fan, you're looking for a team that has
some appeal. And there's this team down in Texas that no one
thought about, and that's pretty exciting. In my mind, the Braves
are still the favorite in the league, but we're pretty even with
the Braves and the Padres. And even a lesser team can win a
five-game series. It's a tremendous amount of pressure whether you
are a favorite or not. You play a 162-game season, and then you
have a five-game playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
