<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN, SACHS SAID TO DELAY GOING PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. is likely to announce this week
that it will not go public this year, according to people who work
at the Wall Street investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The delay would be an acknowledgment that Goldman's plans to
sell shares in what is now a 130-year-old private partnership have
been derailed by global financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   People who work at Goldman said that its senior partners, Jon
Corzine and Henry Paulson Jr., have scheduled a telephone meeting
for Monday with the firm's 189 general partners around the world.
Corzine and Paulson, who are joint chairmen and chief executives,
are expected to tell the partners that the firm's six-person
executive committee has decided to delay the offering until market
conditions improve.
</P>
<P>
   If the full partnership, which originally authorized the initial
public offering in June, agrees with the executive committee's
decision, a general announcement will be made Tuesday, the people
who work at Goldman said. A Goldman spokesman could not be reached
for comment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's public offering would probably have been one of the
largest in history, with the firm aiming to raise $3 billion by
selling a stake of 10 percent to 15 percent. Partners originally
envisioned that the firm's market value _ and their own net worth _
would increase by three or four times after the offering. But the
sharp stock market decline has slashed the share prices of
Goldman's main rivals by about half from peak levels in July,
reducing the incentive to go public now.
</P>
<P>
   Like other firms on Wall Street, Goldman has had a drop in
operating profits in this year's third quarter. The company
reported that it earned $754 million for the period, down by a
fourth from the second quarter. With world stock and bond markets
still weak after a severe summer sell off, Goldman said that it
foresees smaller profits in the last quarter of the year as well,
making the autumn an inauspicious time to issue shares.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman is also a leader of the consortium of banks and
brokerage houses that committed $3.65 billion last week to the
bailout of Long-Term Capital Management, the speculative hedge fund
whose huge bets on international bond markets turned sour. Goldman
committed $300 million to that effort, nearly 5 percent of its
partners' total capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
