<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTIVISION-STAR-TREK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISION TO MAKE `STAR TREK' VIDEO GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Activision Inc., the video game maker, is going Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to announce this week that it has licensed
from Paramount Pictures the exclusive rights to make ``Star Trek''
video games.
</P>
<P>
   The deal follows one in July in which Activision licensed the
rights to make six video games based on Walt Disney Co. movies,
including the forthcoming ``Bug's Life,'' ``Tarzan'' and ``Toy
Story 2.'' It also recently became the distributor in Britain and
45 other foreign countries for Lucasarts Entertainment, the video
game company.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kotick, chairman and chief executive of Activision, which
is based in Santa Monica, Calif., said that appealing to the
legions of Disney, ``Star Trek'' and ``Star Wars'' fans would
broaden the market for his company, which had sales of $260 million
and net income of $5.8 million in its last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having recognizable franchises is, in my mind, as important as
the product quality itself,'' he said. The ``Star Trek'' games
alone could bring $600 million in revenues over 10 years, he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But video games based on movies, even hits, can flop. Experience
has shown that consumers care much more about the game's quality of
play than about its film connections.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only two of the 20 top-selling games for the Nintendo
64 and Sony Playstation machines were tied to movies. And Hollywood
studios themselves have had only mixed success at best in the video
game business. That is one reason that Disney has decided to let
Activision develop Disney-based games instead of doing it itself.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount, which is owned by Viacom Inc., has already been
leaving game development to game companies. But it has had several
licensees for Star Trek games, which sometimes tripped over one
another in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Having a single licensee will allow for better coordination,
said Andrea Hein, president of Viacom Consumer Products, the
licensing arm of Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deals have not been disclosed. But Activision is
thought to have paid Disney and Paramount tens of millions of
dollars each as guarantees against future royalties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
