<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HRSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa gains extra game to pad 66
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mark McGwire now can take his 70 home runs on a long,
well-deserved vacation. The other player in this summer's longball
festival, though, has more work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, (McGwire) will probably be going to the beach, and
I've got to go play,'' said Sammy Sosa, who seemed more pleased
with his alternative.
</P>
<P>
   With tonight's extra game between the Chicago Cubs and the San
Francisco Giants to decide the National League wildcard, Sosa has
an additional opportunity to pad his home run total of 66. That
would be the only benefit of the Cubs' 4-3 loss to Houston on
Sunday that necessitated this one-game playoff.
</P>
<P>
   He'd need four to catch McGwire, who knocked out two more Sunday
as a parting gift to baseball. Mr. Sosa would like to declare the
home run race officially over.
</P>
<P>
   ``'I'm not thinking about home runs anymore. I just want to go
out there (tonight) and play a good game,'' he said. ``I've got to
make contact, get some RBIs and score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's Sunday was wrapped up in concerns other than his chase of
McGwire. As it went the day before, he saw McGwire add two more
homers to his staggering total on the big screen in the Astrodome.
And, as it went Saturday, Sosa was trying to help out the Cubs in
ways that didn't involve one, big swing.
</P>
<P>
   His first-inning single drove in Jose Hernandez, giving Chicago
a quick 1-0 lead. He singled and stole second with one out in the
eighth, but did not score. Sosa also had the dubious distinction of
chasing Carl Everett's 11th-inning shot all around the Astrodome's
right-field reaches. It was a hot drive to the wall _ ``Only
Superman could get that one,'' Sosa said _ that ricocheted hard off
the fence. It eluded Sosa long enough to earn Everett a triple.
From there, he scored the game-ending run on a sacrifice fly by
Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   The play didn't prove fatal, as the Giants also lost in the last
at-bat at Colorado, maintaining their wildcard tie. Sosa goes home
to Wrigley for at least one more game tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Whatever happens, I'll have a lot of great memories,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for smashing Roger Maris' single-season home run record but
still finishing second to McGwire, Sosa said, ``I hope they
remember me, too. Pretty much all year long, I stayed with him.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as a power-hitter, Sosa showed himself to be a
clairvoyant. After McGwire hit two home runs Saturday to take a
68-66 lead in the race, Sosa declared that his friend likely would
hit two more Sunday and finish with an even 70. That's exactly how
it all played out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can hit two more tomorrow, too,'' he said. No, Sosa
hasn't completely forsaken the home run.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
