</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL ERA COMES TO END IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The political career of Helmut Kohl, among the world's
most enduring statesmen, came to an abrupt, resounding end Sunday
as Germans opted for a younger, more charismatic leader, Gerhard
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Running on his accomplishments of overseeing reunification and
closer European integration, the 68-year-old Kohl had asked voters
to return him for an unprecedented fifth four-year term as
chancellor. But anxious over high unemployment and the difficulties
of implementing reunification, voters threw out a sitting
government for the first time since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour after polls closed, a somber Kohl took to the
stage at the Bonn headquarters of his Christian Democratic Union
party and stunned his supporters by conceding defeat and announcing
his retirement. The speech, remarkable for its swiftness and lack
of emotion, marked the end of one of the century's longest
political careers.
</P>
<P>
   As Kohl was conceding, a jubiliant Schroeder flashed the victory
sign to cheering supporters from his Social Democratic Party, which
will take control of government for the first time in 16 years.
``The era of Helmut Kohl has come to an end,'' said Schroeder, 54,
with his fourth wife standing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder called cutting unemployment ``the most important
goal,'' and vowed to improve the living standards for eastern
Germans, who eight years after reunification complain that they are
treated like second-class citizens. He said he would form an
alliance of industry and union leaders to create a strategy for
making Germany's economy, the world's third-largest behind those of
the United States and Japan, more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   While the final tally is not expected until Monday, exit polling
and initial results suggested that the environmentalist Green Party
will be the junior member of the coalition led by Schroeder. Such a
``red-green'' coalition could be a volatile mix, as the fringe
elements of those parties are far removed from the so-called ``New
Center'' consensus politics that Schroeder touted.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the BBC, however, Schroeder said he would not rule
out a ``grand coalition'' between his party and Kohl's Christian
Democrats, even though leading Christian Democrats were ruling it
out as they began to ponder who would replace Kohl, party leader
for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the unexpectedly strong showing by the Party of
Democratic Socialists, composed of former Communist Party members
from the former East Germany, potential coalition partners were not
doing as well.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has ruled out any pact with the former Communists, who
polled especially well in their eastern Germany base and in East
Berlin, where they are known as the Roten Socken, or Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Initial results suggested that Schroeder's party will win about
40 percent of the vote, and Kohl's party about 35 percent. The
Greens were expected to receive about 6 percent, meaning that they
and the Social Democrats would get about 330 seats, one more than
the 329 needed for a majority in the Bundestag, the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But that majority may be too thin for Schroeder's liking, and he
could seek to form a broader coalition, a prospect that leaders of
the Social Democrats and the Christian Democrats will discuss
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As the longest-serving leader of any modern democracy, Kohl is a
giant figure in Germany, in Europe, and on the world stage. By
contrast, Schroeder, governor of Lower Saxony, one of Germany's 16
states, is unproven on anything but a provincial stage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, voters appeared more concerned about domestic issues,
particularly unemployment, than they were about Kohl's clout as an
international statesman. About 4 million Germans are out of work,
almost 11 percent of the work force.
</P>
<P>
   The economic uncertainty was underscored by polls showing that
despite the ubiquitous campaign posters and unrelenting media
attention, up to a third of Germany's 60 million voters had not
made up their minds until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   History may judge Kohl as important a statesman as Winston
Churchill or Charles de Gaulle. But he, like them, had to be pushed
out rather than leave on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Polls had shown that most Germans would have preferred that
Kohl's deputy, Wolfgang Schaeuble, be his party's candidate for
chancellor, and that Schaeuble could have beaten Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent television interview, Kohl explained his
determination to run rather than retire by saying he wanted to see
through the implementation of a single European currency and German
reunification. But he also betrayed a selfish reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all,'' Kohl said, ``I want to show all those who have
written me off that I am still there, standing firm.''
</P>
<P>
   He had asked voters for the chance to finish guiding the country
into the Euro and to make good on his 1989 promise, made after the
Berlin Wall fell, that he would provide ``flourishing landscapes''
in the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But many in western Germany complained that Kohl had mostly
squandered $750 billion in the east, while many easterners
complained that reunification and the free market had cost them the
jobs and the housing guaranteed under the Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Schroeder had a double-digit lead in the
polls. But Kohl, who has traditionally been underestimated by his
opponents, campaigned ferociously during the last month, whittling
the lead to a few points.
</P>
<P>
   While Kohl stressed his accomplishments and tried to exploit the
tendency of many Germans to avoid risks, Schroeder offered what he
called a new way to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Following the examples of Bill Clinton and Britain's Tony Blair,
to whom he is often compared, Schroeder was vague on how he intends
to steer Germany toward the future in ways fundamentally different
than Kohl's.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentiment for change proved overwhelming. Interviews
with voters in Berlin, where 3 million of the country's 80 million
people live, suggested that many had voted strategically, not for
Schroeder as much as against Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, I would vote for the Greens, and I have a problem
with Schroeder. But we need a change,'' said Zeph Uwe, 33, a city
planner, who voted for Schroeder's party.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Schulz, 56, a former member of East Germany's Communist
army and normally a Green Party supporter, said he voted for
Schroeder simply to get rid of Kohl. ``He promised us flourishing
landscapes, but nothing has changed,'' Schulz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
