<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-BOS     09-27 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROVINCIAL PLAYER STEPS UP TO THE WORLD STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ In 1980, shortly after he was elected to Parliament,
Gerhard Schroeder was heading home after a night on the town when
he suddenly told a friend to pull over at the entrance to the Bonn
home of Germany's chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get in there!'' Schroeder screamed, rattling the
iron gates.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years later, a more mature, more subdued Schroeder is
poised to take his seat as chancellor because he was able to
channel, some would say suppress, the impulsive anger that once
drove him.
</P>
<P>
   By unseating Helmut Kohl, chancellor for 16 years and Europe's
longest-serving and most important leader, Schroeder has become a
giant-slayer, thrust onto the world stage without experience or a
net.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way from his provincial post as governor of Lower
Saxony. Yet it seems a fitting climax to a political career that
began with a searing idealism that was gradually subsumed by a
pragmatism born of a determination to obtain and exercise real
power.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has a fondness for cigars and wives. He has been
married four times. And yet while Kohl's supporters tried to make
the divorces an issue, few here seem to begrudge Schroeder's
marital record.
</P>
<P>
   He has been compared to Bill Clinton and Britain's Tony Blair,
in that he took his traditionally left-wing Social Democratic Party
toward the center in a calculated move to seize power from
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   These days, given the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, Schroeder
probably would prefer being compared to Blair. And yet Schroeder is
more like Clinton, not only because he has risen to international
prominence from governing an obscure, provincial backwater. More
tellingly, Schroeder's thirst for respect and power is, like
Clinton's, a product of growing up poor.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in 1944, just three days before his father, a German
soldier, was killed on the eastern front. His mother, now 84,
worked as a cleaning woman, and he cared for his four sisters. They
lived for many years on welfare, an experience he has cited as
shaping his empathy for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, he got a job at a china shop in his hometown of Lemgo. It
was a revelation to Schroeder, because behind the counter he was
somebody. ``Power fascinated me from the moment that I stood behind
a counter as an apprentice, with no educational qualifications and
no prospects,'' he wrote in his autobiography. ``I wanted to get
out of there, to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to law school and married his high school sweetheart.
The marriage lasted only three years, and soon he was married
again, to a student activist. As a lawyer, he made a name for
himself defending radicals and terrorists, and ran for Parliament
in 1980. Divorced again, he met and married Hiltrud Hampel, a
political scientist known as Hillu.
</P>
<P>
   They became Germany's first political power couple. While Kohl's
wife stayed at home and baked him saumagen, or pig's stomach, Hillu
Schroeder was an outspoken environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder's idealism seemed to shrink even as that of his
third wife grew. He drifted away from her and his party
apparatchiks and began associating with the rich and famous,
including Ferdinand Piech, Volkswagen's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder took up with Doris Kopf, a magazine journalist 20
years his junior. She has only improved his cozy relations with
most elements in the German media.
</P>
<P>
   But his third divorce proved bitter, especially when Hillu went
public and accused her former husband of being vain, stingy, and
opportunistic. She said he had forced her and their two daughters
to move to a smaller apartment, and had refused to pay for their
dog's surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, unflappable as usual, replied by saying his third
wife was a ``fanatic,'' prone to bursting into his Cabinet meetings
while ranting that he and his colleagues were not doing enough to
save bats. In a futile attempt to convert him to vegetarianism, he
said, she refused to allow meat in their home.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some who agree with Hillu's chief complaint about
her former husband: that he sacrificed his principles in a
head-long pursuit of power.
</P>
<P>
   Once an outspoken opponent of the Gulf War, Schroeder now
condemns Saddam Hussein as a dictator who must be crushed. Once a
dyed-in-the-wool leftist, Schroeder waffles on what to do about
reforming the welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Harrold Schmidt, Germany's answer to David Letterman, says that
if Schroeder were the Titanic, it never would have sunk because it
never would have left the harbor, unable to choose a direction.
Then again, he says, if the corpulent Kohl was the Titanic, ``the
iceberg would have sunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt's point seems to have set in. Many Germans thought Kohl
seemed tired and old. Schroeder, who dyes his hair, is a youthful
54, with a young, attractive wife.
</P>
<P>
   In his youth, Schroeder was prone to outbursts. Now he is more
likely to use his piercing blue eyes to emphasize a point. His
supporters say he has matured and will serve Germany, and Europe,
well on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Schroeder offers bland populism, trying to be all
things to all people. Schroeder calls it the ``New Center,''
flexible politics not bound by ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders always have derided Social Democrats as
liberals who have weakened Germany's competitiveness by creating
overly generous fringe benefits for workers and a welfare state
that provides little incentive for people to take entry-level jobs.
Conscious of this, Schroeder recruited as his economic adviser Jost
Stollman, a Harvard Business School-educated entrepreneur who made
millions in the computer industry. Stollman, often described as
Germany's Bill Gates, is Schroeder's trump card against claims that
he is antibusiness.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, business moguls are among Schroeder's best friends,
including Gates. Some party strategists privately complain that
Schroeder spends more time with his rich friends than with them.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder shrugs off such criticism, saying his private life is
separate from his public one. Now, he and Doris Schroeder rival
Tony and Cherie Blair as the power couple of Europe, and, given the
problems at the White House, perhaps the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2157EDT &QL; 
