<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: INVENTOR OF WINDSURFING FINDS HIS PLACE IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 70-year-old retired sign painter, S. Newman Darby, might still
be living in obscurity in Jacksonville, Fla., if an odd couple of
sorts _ a windsurfing industrial engineer and an archivist at the
Smithsonian Institution _ had not decided to champion his cause.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the archivist, Alison Oswald, finished installing a
small exhibit honoring Darby's role in the invention of windsurfing
at the Smithsonian's National Museum of American History in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oswald, who specializes in acquiring collections of
inventors, had never heard of Darby until the summer of 1997, when
Chad Lyons, a windsurfer who lives in Connecticut, made an
impromptu call on her at the museum while he was in town on
business _ trying to promote his own patented invention, a new type
of medical device.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad Lyons came by and said, `You ought to look into who the
real inventor of windsurfing is,''' Ms. Oswald recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Two Californians had been widely credited with inventing
windsurfing, a sport that is a cross between surfing and sailing
and that has been an Olympic event since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Drake, an aeronautics engineer, and his partner, Hoyle
Schweitzer, received U.S. patent 3,487,800 for a sailboard _ what
Schweitzer later trademarked as a Windsurfer _ in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   But that is five years after Darby says he first maneuvered his
sailboard around the Chesapeake Bay, in 1965. Later that year,
Darby published an article about his new form of sailing in Popular
Science and advertised his invention in the back of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Although that particular issue of Popular Science had a
circulation of about 6 million, Drake and Schweitzer did not list
the article as part of their ``prior art'' _ evidence of related
inventions that is supposed to be filed along with a patent
application.
</P>
<P>
   But why didn't Darby obtain a patent back in the mid-1960s?
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially, we couldn't afford to do the patent,'' he said.
``I was trying to raise a young family and to make a living as a
sign painter and an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Darby did go into the sailboard business with his brothers,
Ronald and Ken, manufacturing an estimated 160 boards and selling
about half of them for $295 apiece, from 1965 through the next few
years. Their company is still in business, but no longer makes
boards.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons was teaching windsailing when he first heard of Darby
through a student who decided to start a business manufacturing and
selling his own sailboard design.
</P>
<P>
   When Lyons' student, as well as other sailboard manufacturers,
were sued by Schweitzer's Windsurfer company for patent
infringement, Darby's name emerged during the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   So when Lyons was asked in the early 1990s by the U.S.
Windsurfing Association to help collect artifacts of the sport for
a proposed museum, he looked up Darby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great record-keeper,'' Lyons said of Darby, who kept
early boards and sails as well as notes and photographs, including
an 8-millimeter home movie that his wife, Naomi, who also sewed the
sails for her husband, shot of Darby sailboarding in the summer of
1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a quandary,'' Lyons said. ``I was afraid that
bringing up Newman might divide this tribal community we call
windsurfing, which pays tribute to these California guys. So I was
going to keep a lid on Newman until I got him into the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   But financing fell through and the museum never materialized.
Then, in 1996, American Windsurfer, a glossy quarterly magazine
based in Gilford, N.H., published an article titled ``Origins of
Windsurfing,'' featuring two extensive interviews with Drake and
Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons called the editor and publisher, John Chao, and urged him
to send a copy of the issue to Newman Darby. Darby sallied back
with a letter and a three-hour home video chronicling what he
contended was his role in the development of board surfing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the magazine published a two-part interview with Darby.
``The photographs and the film footage were so complete and so
compelling that we were stunned that such evidence existed and we
didn't know about it,'' Chao wrote. ``Suddenly what we prided as
the definitive article on the `Origins of Windsurfing' became
embarrassingly incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian recently took possession of many of Darby's
artifacts, including one of his early sailboards.
</P>
<P>
   Chao said that neither Drake nor Schweitzer had written or
called to comment on Darby's claims that he was the rightful
inventor of sailboarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really quite interesting how there was an absence of
response or denial,'' Chao said in a telephone interview. ``If I
had invented something and someone else claimed otherwise I would
have been very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Drake nor Schweitzer could be reached for comment. In
his original interview in American Windsurfer, however, Drake did
not claim to be the inventor of the universal joint _ the pivoting
joint that attaches the sail to the surface of the board, which is
a key feature of a sailboard _ but rather said that he could more
accurately be described as its ``re-inventor.''
</P>
<P>
   Darby never made any money off sailboarding. But neither did
Drake reap the enormous profits that his erstwhile partner did.
Schweitzer bought Drake's patent rights for $36,000 in 1972.
Hundreds of thousands of boards have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lyons says he does not want to minimize the role
that the two Californians played in starting the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Drake and Schweitzer, we would have never had this
popular sport,'' Lyons said. ``It's not clear that Newman would
have ever come up with the idea of a wishbone boom or other
technical refinements. And Schweitzer was far more firm in his
convictions that this could be a popular sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he added, ``Newman probably doesn't agree with me
on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
