<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INQUIRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER, DOLE SUPPORT IMPEACHMENT HEARINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two respected Republican elders eyed by the White
House as possible brokers for an expedited impeachment or censure
deal said Sunday that it is far too early to seek a negotiated
agreement and that the House should open an impeachment inquiry in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by moderate Republicans Bob Dole and Howard Baker,
coming amid Republican congressional recalcitrance toward any deal,
could prove devastating to White House efforts to broker an
agreement before the House launches a full-bore impeachment
proceeding next week.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he supported a deal between the White House and
congressional leaders that would allow President Clinton to receive
a rapid impeachment vote or stay in office, Baker, a former Senate
majority leader, presidential candidate, and chief of staff to
Ronald Reagan, said simply, ``No.'' He added: ``Impeachment
hearings are necessary. The system has to work.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Dole, Clinton's Republican rival in the 1996
campaign and a former Senate majority leader, said no agreement was
feasible or even wise until after the November congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is that it's way too early to even speculate about
that,'' Dole said, speaking on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``The
Democrats would love that to happen. It has to go through the
process. Get the process started, let the elections happen, come
back and get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had privately offered to have Clinton testify
before the House Judiciary Committee and admit to significant
wrongdoing if the House would agree to hold a quick vote on his
fate. Some Clinton strategists had envisioned a powerful team of
statesmanlike Republicans and Democrats prevailing on the Congress
to cut a deal for the sake of the institutions involved.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection by Baker and Dole also occurred on the same day
that lawyers for Paula Corbin Jones publicly confirmed they are
involved in talks with Clinton's attorneys on a possible settlement
of her sexual harassment case, which had been thrown out of court
by a judge in April but remains on appeal. One Jones lawyer, David
Pyke, described himself as ``very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers and political strategists would like to settle
the case for a variety of reasons, the foremost being that if the
suit were resolved, Clinton could then admit to Congress as part of
any impeachment settlement deal that he lied in his January Jones
deposition without facing further legal repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers also fear that the federal judge in the Jones
suit, Susan Webber Wright, could still hold Clinton in contempt for
lying in the deposition, and that the appellate court may now be
more likely to rule in favor of Jones because of Clinton's
admission of his affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they realize that there are very significant risks
of contempt and other sanctions that either the appeals court or
the trial court could impose upon Mr. Clinton that would lead to a
victory in our case,'' said Donovan Campbell, a Jones lawyer, on
ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also said he plans to take action on evidence that
another woman filed a false affidavit in the Jones case denying
that Clinton had harassed her. In the report sent to Congress this
month by independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, a woman identified
in the Jones case as Jane Doe 5 told prosecutors that a Jan. 2
affidavit filed for Jones's lawyers denying that Clinton had made
unwelcome sexual advances was ``false.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just wondering how much perjury and false evidence can
the federal court system stand before something is done?'' said
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton continued on a campaign and fund-raising trip
in California, and some key Democrats continued to press toward a
congressional deal on an expedited impeachment process or a
censure. Massachusetts Senator John F. Kerry, conceding that the
prospects were diminishing, said Republicans may face voter wrath
for prolonging any impeachment proceeding with lengthy hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a political process, yes, but it's a process that is
supposed to reflect the American people,'' Kerry said on CBS's
``Face the Nation.'' ``Congress should listen to the American
people on this one. The American people know what this case is
about, and they want us to handle this in a mature and a dignified
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, though, with little apparent impact, warned Clinton that
he must not continue attacking Republicans as he has for the last
several days, saying he doesn't think such a strategy is
``advisable.''
</P>
<P>
   But just minutes after Kerry spoke, Clinton strategist James
Carville appeared on ``Meet the Press'' and declared ``war'' on
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, saying he will soon be ``rolling into
battle.'' In an apparent reference to Gingrich's 1996 ethics
problems, Carville described him as a ``sanctioned, certified,
adjudicated, and confessed liar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most crowded place in Washington is Newt Gingrich's hip
pocket, because it has got every member of the Republican Caucus in
it,'' Carville said. ``They are scared to death. He came out and
unilaterally said, `I am the person that decides that there's not
going to be any deal.' Well, I've got news, Newt Gingrich, I'm
meeting with people all over Washington this week, and we're going
to mount an attack to tell the truth about what's behind this.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole warned Republicans again not to push too far too hard in
their investigation for fear of inspiring the wrath of the public,
which still offers strong support for Clinton's job performance in
most public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for everyone to take a deep breath _ all the
American people, Democrats, Republicans, the White House,'' said
Dole. ``It's not going to happen before the election. It's probably
not going to happen until next year. Don't be overzealous. Let the
process work. Be fair to the president and everyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2213EDT &QL; 
