<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-NETWORKS-AOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL NETWORKS IN PACT WITH AMERICA ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (js) 
 BY STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed a risky step when Rob Glaser, chairman of Real
Networks &UR;  &LR; Inc., appeared before the Senate Judiciary Committee in
July, joining a chorus of Microsoft bashers. He complained that
some of Microsoft &UR;  &LR; Corp.'s latest software refused to work properly
with his company's so-called streaming programs, which deliver
audio and video over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser is no garden-variety Microsoft adversary. He is himself a
former Microsoft executive, and Microsoft holds an 10 percent stake
in his fast-growing Seattle company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his public dispute with Microsoft has certainly not hurt
Glaser's business so far. There are no signs of retaliation from
his giant neighbor, former employer and investor in Redmond, Wash.
Meanwhile, people in increasing numbers _ now more than 30 million
_ are using his software.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, Real Networks plans to announce that America
Online &UR;  &LR; Inc., the online leader, has chosen its technology as the
main way for users to play streaming media on the new version of
the service, AOL 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   That word comes as America Online begins its own marketing drive
Monday for AOL 4.0 _ not only an upgrade for its 13 million current
subscribers, but also an effort to lure the millions of other
people who will be sent America Online disks in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   The America Online agreement is a marketing coup for Real
Networks. ``It is piggybacking on AOL's powerful distribution
network,'' said Jae Kim of Paul Kagan &AMP; Associates, a research
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, in Glaser's view, is on its way to becoming a
mainstream mass medium for receiving the recorded voice and
television-style videos. Already, 85 percent of the Web sites that
offer streaming media make use of the technology from Real
Networks.
</P>
<P>
   And if anything, he says, the spat with Microsoft over his
Senate testimony seemed to help, with the volume of daily downloads
from the company's site (www.real.com) rising by nearly 20 percent
immediately afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``People heard and read about streaming media,'' Glaser said,
``and wanted to see what all the hubbub was about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0181 </DOCNO>
