A6966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      09-27 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING THIS WEEK: A WEB HAIR TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.) (js) 
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the company that brought the first live broadcasts of
childbirth and open-heart surgery to the World Wide Web comes the
latest opportunity for medical rubbernecking: a live Webcast of a
hair-transplant operation.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling how many people will decide to tune in for
the event (www.ahn.com), which will take place on Wednesday at
Baptist Hospital in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sometimes poor picture quality and frequent
busy-server signals, nearly a million people managed to log in at
some point during the morning of June 16 to see a 40-year-old woman
named Elizabeth giving birth to a 7-pound, 8-ounce boy. And in
August, nearly 600,000 people caught part of a live Webcast of a
48-year-old Texas woman's quadruple-bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from America's Health Network, the cable TV company
based in Orlando, Fla., that produces the shows, insist that the
Webcasts are not merely aimed at raising brand awareness for the
network but are also intended to educate the public.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Fetherling, the network's president, said he hoped the
hair-transplant show would appeal to some of the 30 million people
_ nearly a third of them women _ who he said had some degree of
so-called male pattern baldness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet,'' he said, ``offers people a confidential way to
watch the procedure and ask questions about hair transplantation _
often a very sensitive subject.''
</P>
<P>
   During the procedure, the network's
physician-turned-color-commentator, Dr. Walt Larimore, will call
the action as a Nashville, Tenn., plastic surgeon removes a patch
of skin from the hairy part of the patient's head and then inserts
more than 1,000 hair grafts in the bald part of his scalp. The
operation will take four to five hours, accompanied by an online
chat session in which viewers can discuss the surgery and ask
questions.
</P>
<P>
   America's Health Network intends to make medical Webcasts a
monthly event. October will bring an online breast-cancer surgery
and November an eye operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
