<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGWIRE-SEVENTY-COX     09-27 0214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGWIRE-SEVENTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    69, 70! McGwire goes out blasting
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When Mark McGwire had taken his final swing on
Sunday, when most of the fans had stopped cheering and left Busch
Stadium, one sign of this great baseball season remained in huge,
bright numerals on the big screen in center field.
</P>
<P>
   70.
</P>
<P>
   With two home runs in Sunday's last game of the regular season,
McGwire finished with an unbelievable 70 home runs, nine more than
Roger Maris, who held the previous record of 61 for 37 years.
McGwire finished with four more homers than Cubs outfielder Sammy
Sosa, who watched McGwire's four homers on the final two days of
the season effectively end the race.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa will get one more chance tonight, when the Cubs play the
Giants in a game that will decide the National League wild card
participant in the playoffs. Home runs in that game will be added
to his regular-season total.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might never happen again,'' McGwire said. ``I'll never let
this season go.''
</P>
<P>
   I. J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
