</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-LOUISIANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ORLEANS BRACES FOR GEORGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Hurricane Georges, with sustained winds of more
than 110 miles per hour, menaced the Mississippi Gulf Coast and the
heavily populated New Orleans area last night while hundreds of
thousands of residents fled the most powerful storm to threaten the
region in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it appeared Georges was moving away from a direct
hit on the mouth of the Mississippi River and metropolitan New
Orleans, the US Weather Bureau said it was on the verge of a
Category 3 rating, an intensity that could cause great damage
across a wide swath of land from the Florida Panhandle to the bayou
country of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Storm surges of up to 20 feet were predicted, a rise in the
normal level of coastal and marsh water that would overwhelm the
area. With plenty of warning, occupants of the area began boarding
homes and departing as early as Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate highways, which had been filled with thousands of
motorists seeking higher ground, were closed by authorities Sunday
afternoon. The New Orleans International Airport was shut all day
as ominous clouds gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary wind gusts topping 50 miles per hour hit New Orleans
late Sunday, and higher levels were reported along the Gulf Coast,
with the eye of the hurricane still lurking off-shore.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans, which is about 6 feet below sea level, was
particularly in peril. The city, wrapped by the Mississippi River,
the Gulf Coast, and Lake Pontchartrain, was swamped by nearly 20
inches of rain from tropical storms earlier this month, and
meteorologists say there is no room for more rain.
</P>
<P>
   There were predictions of 25 more inches of rain, coupled with a
storm surge that could drive millions of gallons of water up the
Mississippi River toward the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the best city in America,'' Mayor Marc Morial said.
``But this may not have been the best place 300 years ago to place
a city.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential problems, Morial declared: ``We are
prepared.'' Pumps, which deliver water overloads from city streets,
were primed and hundreds of members of emergency crews were in
place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid fears that much of the city could be under 6 feet of water,
residents searched frantically for high ground on which to park
their cars. By noon Sunday, virtually every high-rise parking
garage was full.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of New Orleanians left of their own volition,
evacuations were ordered in low-lying parishes outside the city.
Curfews were imposed across the region, disrupting the tourist
industry.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell, the storm washed over US Highway 90 along the
Mississippi Gulf Coast. The casinos that have popularized the route
have been shut down since Friday and much of the usual flow of
people had already disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   As far north as Birmingham, Ala., about 260 miles from the
coast, there were no vacancies left in motels along the major
evacuation routes.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet prevailed in other endangered places in Louisiana, even
though some shelters were so crowded that new locations had to be
opened to accommodate the overflow.
</P>
<P>
   The city opened what is probably the largest hurricane shelter
ever: the Superdome. Long lines of people carried blankets and
pillows, and registered for entry. Rising water could flood the
playing field and lower-deck seats. The nearly 10,000 people at the
stadium were directed to higher decks.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Ronnie Jones of the Louisiana State Police reported
early last night that waves were topping the levees along Lake
Pontchartrain. ``The worst is yet to come for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The raucous French Quarter of New Orleans was reduced to a quiet
neighborhood. Restaurants were boarded and streets were deserted.
Even Harry's Bar, an around-the-clock, 365-days-a-year, emporium,
was shut down. National Guardsmen patrolled the streets.
</P>
<P>
   A rock concert in City Park, expected to attract more than
25,000 spectators this weekend, was canceled by city officials, and
smaller events, such as the annual William Faulkner literary
conference, were terminated, leaving hundreds of tourists to seek
flights before the airport closed.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Gulf Coast have watched the approach of Georges
with apprehension for more than a week since it seemed to be aimed,
laser-like, at the area from the time it developed in the South
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The storm raked the Caribbean last week, with a death toll of
more than 300, as it swept across Puerto Rico, the Dominican
Republic, Haiti, and Cuba. In recent days, it has meandered through
the Gulf of Mexico, building strength over the water after leaving
the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the area have a long, unhappy experience with
stormy autumn weather.
</P>
<P>
   Seawalls were destroyed, homes swamped and miles of trees
leveled by a hurricane in 1947, before names were attached to
storms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, New Orleans suffered serious flooding after being hit
by Hurricane Betsy. Four years later, the Gulf Coast was devastated
by Hurricane Camille, one of the strongest storms in history, which
resulted in more than 250 deaths and billions of dollars in
property damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
