<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: WILLY LOMAN IS BACK; ART FROM RUSSIA;   PICASSO'S
CERAMICS; POETRY FEAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y., Wash.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Death of a Salesman' Revival
</P>
<P>
   Still 63, Willy Loman has his shoes shined and his bags packed
for another bout with life. Monday night the Goodman Theater in
Chicago begins its 1998-99 Mainstage season with a revival of the
Arthur Miller classic, ``Death of a Salesman,'' which opened in
1949 and won a Pulitzer Prize, a Tony Award and the Drama Critics'
Circle Award. In the production, continuing through Nov. 7 and
staged by Robert Falls, Willy is portrayed by Brian Dennehy; Kevin
Anderson plays his son Biff, and Elizabeth Franz plays Willy's
wife, Linda. Information: (312) 443-3800.
</P>
<P>
   In Celebration
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tapping two of the world's foremost repositories of
drawings for 120 works by artists like Rubens, Matisse, Picasso,
Rembrandt, Daumier, Bernini, Modigliani, Poussin and van Gogh, the
Morgan Library has begun the exhibition ``Master Drawings from the
Hermitage and Pushkin Museums.'' Many of these works, from the 15th
to the 20th centuries, have never been shown outside Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan will be the only site of the exhibition, running
until Jan. 10. The show is part of a yearlong celebration of the
library's 75th anniversary as an institution open to the public.
The library began as the private collection of financier J.P.
Morgan. Information: (212) 685-0610.
</P>
<P>
   Private Stock
</P>
<P>
   Unique is not a word to be used lightly, but the 60 ceramics by
Picasso that went on display Sunday at the Tacoma Art Museum in
Tacoma, Wash., bear that designation. All the sculptures, vessels
and tiles are from the artist's private collection. And though many
of his ceramics were produced by the hundreds, these are described
as one-of-a-kind. The ceramics were inherited by Marina Picasso,
the artist's granddaughter, and few have been displayed in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Ceramics From the Marina Picasso Collection,'' running
through Jan. 10, the museum will show Picasso prints and drawings
elaborating on themes in the ceramics. This part of the exhibition
features preparatory drawings for Picasso's ``Guernica'' from the
Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofia in Madrid. Information:
(253) 272-4258.
</P>
<P>
   Meter Men
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ushering in its 60th-anniversary season, the
Unterberg Poetry Center of the 92nd Street Y has a feast this week
for devotees of the art.
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 4 at Playhouse 91 in Manhattan is the premiere of a
theatrical production of Dante's ``Inferno,'' translated and
adapted by Robert Pinsky, the U.S. poet laureate. At 8 Monday
night, the poet Seamus Heaney, a Nobel laureate from Ireland, will
give a reading at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he and Pinsky will be honored with crowns of laurels
at an anniversary celebration. Information: (212) 996-1100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
