<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CANDIDATE URGES REPUBLICANS TO TAKE LOW-KEY APPROACH TO
SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Taking a more moderate approach than most
Republicans, California State Controller Matt Fong said the GOP
should proceed cautiously against President Clinton to avoid a
potential backlash among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Fong, with polls giving him a slight lead over Democratic U.S.
Sen. Barbara Boxer in their Nov. 3 election, said Sunday he also
would have preferred that the House Judiciary Committee had not
released so much information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans should exercise some prudence and judgment
or there could be an impact,'' Fong said, following a speech to the
California Republican Party convention. ``It could be very
difficult on all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I obviously am not there, I would have liked to see the
tapes (of President Clinton's grand jury testimony) go to members
of Congress first before it was made public. I recognize it could
have been leaked, but I would have taken that extra step.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong said that during his speeches he has tried to remain away
from the controversy involving Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not running against Bill Clinton,'' Fong said. ``I'm
running against Barbara Boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he did not hesitate to use the issue in an attack on Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of her hypocrisy,'' Fong said. ``She's an
attack dog when it comes to those she opposed. When it came to
Republicans, like (Supreme Court Justice) Clarence Thomas or
(former Sen.) Bob Packwood, she was relentless. But when it comes
to her friends, there is a double standard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Boxer has said she condemns Clinton's actions with
intern Monica Lewinsky and his failure to admit to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer spokesman Roy Behr said her campaign was not surprised by
Fong's comments Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, Matt Fong has shown the only thing he has to offer
the people of California is to be a sex critic,'' Behr said. ``He
clearly knows if he was ever to talk about the issues, he would
lose this election. He can't talk about choice, education or the
economy, because he's out of the mainstream on all those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong waged a strong attack against Boxer during his speech
Sunday, calling her ``an example of the 1960s liberal,'' as he
characterized himself as a ``21st century Republican looking to the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her vision is bankrupt,'' Fong said. ``She is resorting to the
politics of fear. As we move to the next century, the Republican
Party will be about unity and hope in the state and the country. We
are not Asian-Americans or African-Americans. We are all
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong said he and Boxer had different views on everything from
education to national defense, as he again proposed an expansion of
a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara Boxer dismisses this as `Star Wars,' '' Fong said.
``Well, this is not a movie with Darth Vader as the enemy and a
Death Star as a threat. This is about having a defense system than
can stop ballistic missiles fired by a terrorist or a rogue
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer has questioned the need _ and cost _ for such a system at
a time when the Cold War has ended.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Fong, many Republicans feel encouraged about the
election because of Clinton's problems.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Chairman Mike Schroeder said the party has $1.85 million to
spend on its get-out-the-vote efforts and has recruited some 80,000
volunteers around the state to work on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Fong was reluctant to criticize Clinton or Lt. Gov.
Gray Davis, the Democratic nominee for governor, Schroeder was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray Davis is attempting to embrace the money tree but not get
spattered by the stench from the White House,'' Schroeder said,
referring to Davis' use of Clinton's fund-raising prowess even as
he has mildly criticized the president.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Schroeder said the party needed to be aggressive this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never have as good an opportunity to win as now,''
Schroeder said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
