<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR YANKS, ONLY 125 VICTORIES WILL DO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In their spectacular season of 114 victories, the
Yankees were so talented, so deep, so much better than any other
American League team, it was as if they were on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, they need to be in overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   They need what Manager Joe Torre calls ``the extra fire that
burns when it's important,'' beginning Tuesday night at Yankee
Stadium in the opener of their three-of-five-game American League
Division Series with the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   After a season of never really having a crucial series or even a
crucial game, the Yankees now need to win three crucial series and
11 crucial games if they are to win 125 games and the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   If not, these Yankees will be remembered for not winning the
World Series (or not winning the AL Championship Series or not
winning the division series) rather than for winning the AL East
title. If not, their 114 victories will be remembered as a footnote
to a flop.
</P>
<P>
   For these Yankees, it's not that any one game is a must now. For
these Yankees, 125 victories are a must.
</P>
<P>
   History is ominous. After the 1906 Chicago Cubs won a record 116
games, they lost the World Series to the Hitless Wonder White Sox
in six games. After the 1954 Cleveland Indians won 111 games for
what was then AL record, they lost the World Series to the New York
Giants in four straight.
</P>
<P>
   In other sports, history has been kinder to dominant teams.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1972 Miami Dolphins streaked through an undefeated
season, they went on to win Super Bowl VII for a 17-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1995-96 Chicago Bulls won a record 72 games, they went
on to win their fourth of six championships in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Yankees need to go on to win what would be a
major-league-record 125 games. As if winning crucial games were a
light switch on a wall, can they suddenly turn it on now that the
playoffs are here?
</P>
<P>
   Torre, naturally, thinks his Yankees can turn it on.
</P>
<P>
   But when it was mentioned that the Yankees had not had a crucial
series or a crucial game all season, the manager remembered when
the Yankees won two in Seattle after losing four of their first
five games at Anaheim, Oakland and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those wins in Seattle were a good signature for us,'' Torre
said, ``and then the way we came back in some games. Against the
Phillies when Tino Martinez hit two homers. Darryl Strawberry's
grand slam against Oakland. It showed we don't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were isolated games against assorted opponents, not a
playoff series against a quality opponent like Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't win the West the way the Rangers did and not feel
good about yourself,'' Torre said. ``They beat the team they had to
beat, the Angels, five straight times. That's pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre also remembers how the Rangers, with the slugger Juan
Gonzalez earning his Senor Octubre nickname, battled the Yankees in
their 1996 division series before losing, three games to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't pitch,'' Torre said, ``Texas is going to score a
lot of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching matchups are David Wells-Todd Stottlemyre Tuesday
night and Andy Pettitte-Rick Helling on Wednesday night. When the
series resumes at the Ballpark in Arlington on Friday night, David
Cone will go against Aaron Sele, with Orlando ``El Duque''
Hernandez against John Burkett on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a fifth game on Sunday at Yankee Stadium, it would
presumably be Wells against Stottlemyre again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first round always scares me,'' Torre said, alluding to
last year's first-round loss to the Cleveland Indians. ``I felt
good last year with a 2-1 lead.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees, who had qualified for last year's playoffs as
the wild-card team, were knocked out in five games.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees played a sloppy game in Tampa Bay recently,
Torre warned his players that they can't suddenly ``turn it on''
when the playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game in Tampa,'' the manager said, ``we were doing things
we aren't supposed to be doing _ throwing to the wrong base, not
thinking out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees can't afford to do that now. That's why Torre is
already looking to how Wells and the Yankees perform early in
Tuesday night's opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we have a 1-2-3 first inning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, a 1-2-3 sweep of the division series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
