<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTING TITLE FOR WILLIAMS, WITH FREE AGENCY AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams came into the season fearful that his
impending free agency might be a distraction. It appears to have
been more of a motivation. Williams went 2-for-2 Sunday, improved
his batting average to .339 and won the American League batting
title.
</P>
<P>
   Williams began the day leading Boston's Mo Vaughn by only .33602
to .33553. Before the Yankees' game started, Vaughn grounded out in
Boston's home game against Baltimore, lowering his average to
.3349.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn homered in his second at-bat, singled in his third at-bat
and made an out his fourth time up, leaving his average at .3366;
it was determined that Vaughn would have to play into extra innings
to catch Williams, who had two singles and a sacrifice fly. ``I
really made a great effort to try to not let it bother me,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this information was relayed to Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager, who then decided to remove Williams in the bottom of the
sixth inning. Once the Yankees made their move, Vaughn was taken
out of the Red Sox lineup, a concession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great, absolutely,'' Williams said. ``It's such a
great feeling when you add your name to the list of players who've
accomplished this feat.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre Announces Roster
</P>
<P>
   Torre finalized his division series roster after Sunday's game,
telling Darren Holmes he had picked Graeme Lloyd for the 10-man
pitching staff instead of Holmes (who did not wait to speak to
reporters). The other pitchers: David Wells, Andy Pettitte, David
Cone, Orlando Hernandez, Hideki Irabu, Mike Stanton, Mariano
Rivera, Jeff Nelson and Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, too, was told he was on the team, after he
pounded his third grand slam in 10 days. After Spencer homered
Sunday, he had seven home runs in his last 26 at-bats, and he
appeared stunned by his binge. ``That'll probably never happen
again,'' said Spencer, whose three grand slams match the career
total for Torre, who played 18 seasons. ``Just to get the chance _
I was pretty excited this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre is torn by his choices for a starting left fielder. He
could go with experience, Darryl Strawberry or Tim Raines. Or he
could go with his hottest bat, Spencer. Torre may wait until
Tuesday before he decides. ``I'm not sure,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The other Yankees' position players: catchers Joe Girardi and
Jorge Posada, infielders Tino Martinez, Derek Jeter, Chuck
Knoblauch, Scott Brosius, Homer Bush and Luis Sojo and outfielders
Paul O'Neill, Williams, Chad Curtis, Spencer, Raines and
Strawberry. The designated hitter will be Chili Davis.
</P>
</TEXT>
