<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERACHIEVING DODGERS SAY GOOD-BYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They promised they would stay in touch, but after
looking at each other for the past eight months, the Dodgers
players sensed something much more final than just the end of a
long season.
</P>
<P>
   So they dressed quickly after Sunday's 2-1 victory over the
Milwaukee Brewers, leaving behind a few bats and wrist bands for
the clubhouse guys and a trail of disappointment for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   In the splendid summer of Sosa and McGwire, the Dodgers finished
83-79, which doesn't sound so bad unless you factor in the gross
underachievement of a team with a $61 million payroll. If not for
the seemingly daily off-field turmoil, or a blockbuster trade for
the ages, the Dodgers might not have been heard from at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a bright side, it is knowing that a season like
this will never happen again,'' first baseman Eric Karros said.
``We can go into next season knowing that the team won't be sold
and the front office won't be overhauled. I'd say right there we're
off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   By beating the Brewers on Sunday, Dodgers starter Chan Ho Park
won a career-high 15th game. The Dodgers also finished over .500
for the fifth consecutive year. To do it, they went 15-9 in
September when the games didn't matter, although they weren't
officially eliminated from the National League wild-card race until
Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Park allowed eight hits and one run in six innings, struck out
seven and walked two. Roger Cedeno hit his second home run on the
homestand, but don't be fooled into thinking he will be anywhere
near the Dodgers starting lineup next year. Those were his only two
hits in 24 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Trenidad Hubbard, who needed to go 3 for 3 on Sunday to reach
.300, went 1 for 4. But his double to open the sixth off Brewers
starter Bill Pulsipher (3-4) led to the eventual winning run. He
scored on a sacrifice fly by Mark Grudzielanek, who established
himself as the Dodgers shortstop after coming over from Montreal on
July 31 with Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   It was moves like that trade and the Mike Piazza deal that were
expected to jump start the Dodgers in 1998. Instead, the team was
25-27 after the trade with Montreal. Interestingly, the Houston
Astros, who won the NL Central, went 37-16 after acquiring Randy
Johnson from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Park's victory didn't convince anyone that the Dodgers don't
need to acquire a No.1 starter next season who can help stabilize a
young rotation. Johnson is a free agent. So is the Padres' Kevin
Brown. And offensively the team was last in the National League in
on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Those are issues that will be addressed this winter by new
general manager Kevin Malone, who must maneuver with $53 million
already guaranteed to 12 players next season.
</P>
<P>
   Another is closer Jeff Shaw, the midseason acquisition who
pitched the ninth inning Sunday to record his 25th save with the
Dodgers and 48th overall. He can demand a trade because he came
from Cincinnati in the middle of a multi-year contract. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest faces Sunday belonged to manager Glenn Hoffman and
his coaching staff, whose fates will be decided within the next few
days. Hoffman is not expected to be back. The Dodgers went 46-41
after he replaced fired Bill Russell on June 22, but with the quick
front-office moves by Malone the past few weeks, it seems Hoffman
never was expected to be more than a caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been difficult season for everyone,'' Hoffman said.
``But you have to look at the positives. We got to see Adrian
Beltre. Pitchers like Chan Ho and Brian Bohanon stepped up. And I
will never have anything bad to say about the effort these guys
gave me this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers never seemed to recover from the May 15 trade
that sent Piazza and Todd Zeile to the Florida Marlins for Gary
Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson and Jim Eisenreich.
Bonilla still was not recovered from offseason surgery and Johnson
did not play up to his All-Star status. Sheffield was an impressive
offensive player, but like Piazza, was not a team leader.
</P>
<P>
   But the trade also acted as an escape hatch in the clubhouse. As
San Diego was running away with the National League West, there was
the booming voice of Bonilla saying: ``You don't understand what a
trade like this can do to a team. It takes time to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, it never did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
