<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' GLITTERING REGULAR SEASON IS A MERE PRELUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Videotaped memories from the 1996 World Series filled
the refrigerator-sized television screen in the players' lounge
Sunday morning at Yankee Stadium: Jim Leyritz hitting the pivotal
home run, the large dark eyes of Yankees manager Joe Torre glazed
with tears after the final out. Two years later, the Yankees will
pursue another World Series title, which would be the
organization's 24th.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is the same, but the stakes are higher: the Yankees
will play for their place in history. They thumped Tampa Bay, 8-3,
Sunday and finished the regular season with 114 victories and 48
defeats. Only one other team in one other year won more
regular-season games, the 1906 Chicago Cubs, who compiled a record
of 116-36.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cubs lost the World Series that season. Should the
Yankees get past Texas in the division series that starts Tuesday,
win the American League Championship Series and then the World
Series, the title would follow one of the greatest regular-season
performances. They could be called baseball's best team. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose in the playoffs or the World Series, however, they
will be forgotten, in the same way time has forgotten the 1969
Baltimore Orioles, the 1954 Cleveland Indians, the 1988 Oakland As
_ all exceptional regular-season teams that did not win in October.
Losing in the World Series, Reggie Jackson suggested two months
ago, reduces any great regular season to ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the World Series, Torre said Sunday, ``would add on to
it, when you can add on to what we've done already.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it would be a terrific disappointment to lose,'' he said.
``But you have to understand something: We're going in with 114
wins, Texas is going in with less than that. Either one of us who
doesn't go beyond this first round is going to be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner: ``Now
we've got to get ready for the war. We've just been in a battle up
to now. I think there's a quality about this team. They're
warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said the other day that regardless of what occurs in the
next four weeks, the Yankees' regular season had been filled with
achievements and moments that would not be forgotten. Bernie
Williams went 2-for-2 Sunday and clinched the batting title with a
.339 average, and Shane Spencer, the Yankees' late-season comet,
hammered his third grand slam in 10 days. It was his seventh homer
in 26 at-bats. David Wells pitched a perfect game in May, Scott
Brosius drove in 98 runs, Derek Jeter accumulated 203 hits, David
Cone won 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees opened with three consecutive losses but finished
with seven consecutive victories. In between, Cuban defector
Orlando Hernandez wept at the end of his long journey to the big
leagues and then won 12 games, Darryl Strawberry revitalized his
career, and the Yankees brawled with Baltimore. They wrapped up a
playoff spot earlier than any other team, and on that day, they did
not realize they had clinched. When they stumbled in September,
Torre angrily challenged them to push themselves, and the Yankees
responded.
</P>
<P>
   They led the league in runs scored, allowed the fewest runs,
ranked third in fielding percentage, second in stolen bases. Ten
players, including Spencer, hit 10 or more home runs, tying a
major-league record. The Yankees' record was 102-1 when they are
leading after eight innings, a reflection of their bullpen. They
won the AL East by 22 games, the largest margin in club history.
</P>
<P>
   They played hard. They always did.
</P>
<P>
   Their postseason will define what is remembered 50 years from
now. After six months and 162 games, four weeks of playoffs will
determine what is remembered about the '98 Yankees. Success in the
postseason, Williams said, ``is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we've been looking forward to since we got to spring
training,'' he said. ``We never knew how far we were going to get _
we knew that if we played hard, we'd get into a position to be
where we're at. Although it's been a very special year for me, and
the team individually, we're still looking ahead. We still have
some work we need to do, and we're looking forward to the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Tessmer is 26, a longtime minor-league pitcher, soft-spoken
and earnest, a native of Meadville, Pa. The Yankees' early season
rainouts and late-summer injuries created a need for a right-handed
reliever, and Tessmer was promoted from Class AAA to make his
major-league debut on Aug. 27. He remembers Mike Stanton welcoming
him to the bullpen that night, telling him to simply concentrate on
what he did well, encouraging him; and he remembers how, when he
was credited with the victory that day, all of the veterans
congratulated him warmly, as if he had been around the entire
season.
</P>
<P>
   A small part of this club's legacy belongs to Tessmer, but that
legacy will be shaped in the playoffs. He knows he will probably
not pitch in the postseason, and preparing for his likely
departure, he packed an equipment bag Sunday, saving a space for
his Yankees jersey, No. 62. ``I want my jersey,'' he said, laughing
a bit. ``I don't know if I have to pay for it, but I'm taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has thought about the days when he can hand a framed picture
of the 1998 Yankees to one of his grandchildren and point to that
serious-looking young man with the protruding ears standing in the
second row of the team picture, between David Cone and Luis Sojo.
That was me, Tessmer might say. That is me.
</P>
<P>
   Tessmer, Williams, Cone. They all could live forever in their
own corridor of history. The stakes are high.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 49,608 attended the final regular-season game at
Yankee Stadium on Sunday, giving the Yankees a total attendance of
2,949,734 _ a club record, but short of the 3 million figure George
Steinbrenner said would prompt discussions about the team staying
in the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MAURO-COX     09-27 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MAURO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton speaks for Mauro at candidate's fund-raisers
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) National Political
categories.)
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ A friend in need turned to a friend in deep
turmoil on Sunday, as a Democrat fighting for a chance teamed up
with a Democrat fighting for his job.
</P>
<P>
   Gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro, in deep need of campaign
cash for his uphill race against Republican Gov. George W. Bush,
and President Clinton, who saw roadside signs of discontent along
the motorcade route here, made stops in San Antonio and Houston to
raise about $1 million for the Mauro campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For the old friends, it was a mixed reaction kind of day. At the
homes of wealthy lawyers in the two cities, Texas Democrats rallied
to support their beleaguered president and underdog gubernatorial
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, Clinton and Mauro saw a Sunday afternoon
display of discontent. As they drove to Frank Herrera's house for
the San Antonio event, they passed hundreds of protesters and
supporters. The former far outnumbered the latter.
</P>
<P>
   At one corner, a lone Mauro sign was encircled by scores of
anti-Clinton placards, including one that said, ``Liar, liar, pants
on fire'' and another that said: ``Pervert. Go home to Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Don Free of San Antonio tried to calm a crying infant on
his back as the leader of the free world approached. ``Shhhh,''
Free told daughter Maria. ``Here comes the bad man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro knew sentiments might run high, but said he never had
second thoughts about bringing Clinton to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not running from my friends,'' he said while awaiting Air
Force One. ``He's a friend. He's a friend when he is up in the
polls. He's a friend when he is down in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   At Herrera's home, former Gov. Ann Richards put it more bluntly.
``Bill Clinton isn't the first man I've had to forgive, and he
probably won't be the last,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, laughing, retorted, ``I want to thank my friend Ann
Richards for finding ways to say things that no one else can say to
make the point no one can misunderstand.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 200 and 300 people showed up at Herrera's home,
including 40 who paid the top price of $5,000, according to Mauro
spokesman Billy Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also found friendly faces along the route. After the
event, the motorcade stopped twice near Herrera's home so Mauro and
the president could pose for photos with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   By showing up Sunday, Clinton showed he is standing by a friend
not at the zenith of his political career. The most recent Texas
Poll, completed in August, gave Bush a 47-point lead, an edge
almost as remarkable as the fundraising margin he enjoys. In
mid-July, the most recent reporting deadline, the Bush campaign
said it had $14 million on hand. Mauro's campaign said it had
$220,000.
</P>
<P>
   At Herrera's home, Clinton drew an enthusiastic response with a
speech heavy on national-level issues and devoid of any mention of
Bush, a top contender for the GOP presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton opened with a personal note.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, many of you whom I've already met have said some
wonderful things to me about my family, and I thank you for that,''
said Clinton. ``You know, it's easy to forget in Washington, but
presidents and their families are still people, and it meant more
to me than you'll ever know.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Mauro must battle a general attitude, fueled by a
strong economy, of ``well, things are going well, why do
anything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our enemy is not adversity,'' said the president. ``Look at
this crowd. Feel your own enthusiasm. Remember what many of you
said to me today. Adversity is our friend. It forces us to dig
deep, to ask ourselves what we believe in, what kind of people we
are, what kind of people we want to be, where we want to go and
what we want to do with our lives. Adversity is our friend. Our
enemies are complacency and cynicism. Those are our enemies, and
don't misunderstand it.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Clinton, Mauro blasted Bush as a do-nothing
governor. ``George Bush hasn't done squat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes insisted the governor has done
squat. ``The vast majority of Texans know better and will show
Garry Mauro that on Nov. 3,'' she said of the challenger's charge.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time on the campaign trail, Mauro launched a
mild salvo at Bush's past, a past that the governor has said
involved a period when he was ``young and irresponsible.'' Bush
said he quit drinking in 1986 after a 40th birthday party that
convinced him alcohol was getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is a decent man from a decent family, but George
Bush thinks life begins at 41,'' Mauro said. ``Except for throwing
out a few baseballs at Rangers' games, he's been coasting all his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the events, Mauro said the prepared line was based on
Bush's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just joking about how he talks about he was young and
irresponsible, and you never know exactly when the cutoff is. And
all he ever talks about is he quit drinking at 40, so I guess
that's when he stopped being irresponsible,'' said Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   The joke was not appreciated by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before (age 41) he graduated from college, graduated from
business school, flew fighter jets, built and oil and gas business,
assembled partners and bought a baseball team,'' said Hughes. Bush
served as managing general partner of the Texas Rangers prior to
running for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
