<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MAURO-COX     09-27 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MAURO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton speaks for Mauro at candidate's fund-raisers
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) National Political
categories.)
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ A friend in need turned to a friend in deep
turmoil on Sunday, as a Democrat fighting for a chance teamed up
with a Democrat fighting for his job.
</P>
<P>
   Gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro, in deep need of campaign
cash for his uphill race against Republican Gov. George W. Bush,
and President Clinton, who saw roadside signs of discontent along
the motorcade route here, made stops in San Antonio and Houston to
raise about $1 million for the Mauro campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For the old friends, it was a mixed reaction kind of day. At the
homes of wealthy lawyers in the two cities, Texas Democrats rallied
to support their beleaguered president and underdog gubernatorial
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, Clinton and Mauro saw a Sunday afternoon
display of discontent. As they drove to Frank Herrera's house for
the San Antonio event, they passed hundreds of protesters and
supporters. The former far outnumbered the latter.
</P>
<P>
   At one corner, a lone Mauro sign was encircled by scores of
anti-Clinton placards, including one that said, ``Liar, liar, pants
on fire'' and another that said: ``Pervert. Go home to Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Don Free of San Antonio tried to calm a crying infant on
his back as the leader of the free world approached. ``Shhhh,''
Free told daughter Maria. ``Here comes the bad man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro knew sentiments might run high, but said he never had
second thoughts about bringing Clinton to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not running from my friends,'' he said while awaiting Air
Force One. ``He's a friend. He's a friend when he is up in the
polls. He's a friend when he is down in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   At Herrera's home, former Gov. Ann Richards put it more bluntly.
``Bill Clinton isn't the first man I've had to forgive, and he
probably won't be the last,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, laughing, retorted, ``I want to thank my friend Ann
Richards for finding ways to say things that no one else can say to
make the point no one can misunderstand.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 200 and 300 people showed up at Herrera's home,
including 40 who paid the top price of $5,000, according to Mauro
spokesman Billy Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also found friendly faces along the route. After the
event, the motorcade stopped twice near Herrera's home so Mauro and
the president could pose for photos with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   By showing up Sunday, Clinton showed he is standing by a friend
not at the zenith of his political career. The most recent Texas
Poll, completed in August, gave Bush a 47-point lead, an edge
almost as remarkable as the fundraising margin he enjoys. In
mid-July, the most recent reporting deadline, the Bush campaign
said it had $14 million on hand. Mauro's campaign said it had
$220,000.
</P>
<P>
   At Herrera's home, Clinton drew an enthusiastic response with a
speech heavy on national-level issues and devoid of any mention of
Bush, a top contender for the GOP presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton opened with a personal note.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, many of you whom I've already met have said some
wonderful things to me about my family, and I thank you for that,''
said Clinton. ``You know, it's easy to forget in Washington, but
presidents and their families are still people, and it meant more
to me than you'll ever know.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Mauro must battle a general attitude, fueled by a
strong economy, of ``well, things are going well, why do
anything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our enemy is not adversity,'' said the president. ``Look at
this crowd. Feel your own enthusiasm. Remember what many of you
said to me today. Adversity is our friend. It forces us to dig
deep, to ask ourselves what we believe in, what kind of people we
are, what kind of people we want to be, where we want to go and
what we want to do with our lives. Adversity is our friend. Our
enemies are complacency and cynicism. Those are our enemies, and
don't misunderstand it.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Clinton, Mauro blasted Bush as a do-nothing
governor. ``George Bush hasn't done squat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes insisted the governor has done
squat. ``The vast majority of Texans know better and will show
Garry Mauro that on Nov. 3,'' she said of the challenger's charge.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time on the campaign trail, Mauro launched a
mild salvo at Bush's past, a past that the governor has said
involved a period when he was ``young and irresponsible.'' Bush
said he quit drinking in 1986 after a 40th birthday party that
convinced him alcohol was getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is a decent man from a decent family, but George
Bush thinks life begins at 41,'' Mauro said. ``Except for throwing
out a few baseballs at Rangers' games, he's been coasting all his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the events, Mauro said the prepared line was based on
Bush's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just joking about how he talks about he was young and
irresponsible, and you never know exactly when the cutoff is. And
all he ever talks about is he quit drinking at 40, so I guess
that's when he stopped being irresponsible,'' said Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   The joke was not appreciated by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before (age 41) he graduated from college, graduated from
business school, flew fighter jets, built and oil and gas business,
assembled partners and bought a baseball team,'' said Hughes. Bush
served as managing general partner of the Texas Rangers prior to
running for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
