<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-COLLAPSE-625     09-27 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-COLLAPSE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: THE METS' PATHETIC CONCLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BBN-METS-BRAVES) 
(mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Mets' last stand in 1998 was no stand at
all. It was a pathetic conclusion to what could, and should, have
been something much more memorable. The final week of the season
deteriorated, from the Mets standing above the wild-card world six
days ago to the Mets stumbling, sitting, kneeling and finally
expiring Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   One peek at distraught manager Bobby Valentine sitting inside a
cramped office with gray cinderblock walls revealed just as much as
``Braves 7, Mets 2'' on the scoreboard at Turner Field. Valentine
chewed on a pen cap, picked his teeth with it and doodled on a pink
message pad as he was repeatedly asked how the Mets let such a
promising ride come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a time when the Mets reflect on the positives that
emerged from this draining season, but they should not even try to
do that now, or even next month. Not after they caved in quickly
and decisively to Greg Maddux Sunday and finished with five
straight losses, all of them in crucial games. The Mets should
ponder just what they forfeited. Ponder it for a long time, as
Valentine undoubtedly will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season didn't end a week ago,'' Valentine said. ``We had a
job to do, and we didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not even close. At a time when one defeat was enough for
fans to chew their cuticles and a very confident manager to turn
more somber, the Mets somehow sputtered five times. It was
inexplicable and inexcusable, but it was explainable. The Mets
managed just 10 runs in two games with the Expos and three with the
Braves, stranding 46 runners; they made silly mistakes, like Jay
Payton's base-running blunder Friday night, and some of Valentine's
decisions failed.
</P>
<P>
   In the five most important games of the season, the Mets turned
into the Arizona Diamondbacks. They performed like a shabby team
and they had shabby timing. Especially with the Cubs and Giants
both losing Sunday, meaning a victory would have given the Mets new
life and a playoff game at Shea Stadium Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in our hands,'' Al Leiter said. ``We controlled our own
destiny, and we didn't do it. Everybody in this room should put the
blame on themselves. We should have all been a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Valentine. The Mets were in a desperate situation in which
they had to win, and both the Giants and the Cubs had to lose to
force a three-way tie, so Valentine wondered what he could have
done differently. Once Atlanta scorched Armando Reynoso Sunday for
five runs in two innings, Valentine had more time to question
himself, and he even conceded, startlingly, that he should have
started Hideo Nomo. Nomo followed Reynoso and did not permit a run
in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomo was throwing real well,'' Valentine said. ``I probably
should have started him. We talked about it. He didn't think it was
the right thing for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? Since when does Valentine let the pitcher dictate if
he should start a game? If Valentine really felt that Nomo would
have been a better choice than Reynoso, he should have made the
call. That was the only time Valentine criticized himself, but he
sounded as if he had second-guessed every decision, from which
pinch-runner he used to which color ink he used on the lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   ``My frustration is I should have done something about it,''
said Valentine, his gray hair tousled, his pants unbuckled and his
brown eyes in a trance. ``Everything I tried didn't work. I should
have done something. I wish I did something.''
</P>
<P>
   The helpless feeling is one that will not and should not go
away. The Mets should use it next season as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a nothing feeling,'' Valentine said. ``There is no
feeling right now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perhaps the Mets were more realistic or less caring than
Valentine, but no players were as morose. Brian McRae picked up the
remote control in the silent clubhouse and actually flipped on the
Cubs-Astros game. Turk Wendell walked around with a pile of
T-shirts declaring the Mets the 1998 wild-card team, shirts he
tried to hide. Despite the painful and incorrect message, John
Franco asked Wendell for a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need something to clean my car with,'' Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine needed to get out of the crowded office or he might
have eaten the pen cap or started crying. The manager started many
answers by saying ``I don't know'' before giving slow, choppy
responses. He looked and sounded bewildered and said the only thing
he was going to do was drink, eat and phone his wife and son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no plans to analyze anything,'' Valentine said. ``I
have no plans right now. My only plan was to go to New York and
play tomorrow. I don't have a plan right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the Mets. And it is their own fault, five times over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
