<P>
   (NYT9) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- TV-COSTS-MEDIA,
9-27 -- Marshall Herskovitz, left, and Ed Zwick, the creators of
the 1980s ABC hit show ``Thirtysomething,'' will create four new
television series for a share in the shows' future profits instead
of upfront fees. ``This seems to be the trend. In making this deal,
we were looking for a way for the artist to fit into this changing
dynamic,'' says Zwick. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DURHAM, N.C. -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- LINUX-SYSTEM-2, 9-27 --
Red Hat Software is charging $50 for an operating system called
Linux that anyone can get free on the Internet, and it is paying
programmers decent wages to write code that it will give away. Red
Hat's Gnome project aims to make Linux easier to use by creating a
graphical interface. Its members include, from left, Owen Taylor,
Michael Fulbright, Jonathan Blandford, Federico Mena and Carsten
Haitzler. (M.J. Sharp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DURHAM, N.C. -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- LINUX-SYSTEM-1, 9-27 --
Robert Young, the chief executive of Red Hat Software, insists that
open-source products can make money. ``The software industry is
built on intellectual property,'' says Young, a 44-year-old
Canadian who used to run a computer-leasing business. Red Hat
Software is charging $50 for an operating system called Linux that
anyone can get free on the Internet, and it is paying programmers
decent wages to write code that it will give away. (M.J. Sharp/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAN PEDRO DE MACORIS, Dominican Republic -- Sept. 27,
1998 -- HURRICANE-DOMREP, 9-27 -- Like hundreds of thousands of
people here in the Dominican Republic whose homes were blown down
or damaged when Hurricane Georges struck last Tuesday, Franci
Mercedes hung clothes to dry Sunday amid the remains of her house.
Although relief supplies have begun to arrive from abroad, many of
the country's 8 million people have yet to receive any help.
Moreover, people who have tried to buy supplies say some merchants
have doubled their prices. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SAN FRANCSICO -- Sept. 27, 1998 --
CLINTON-HILLARY-POLITICS, 9-27 -- Hillary Rodham Clinton
campaigning for Sen. Barbara Boxer of California, right, in San
Francisco on Friday. Mrs. Clinton was on a three-day, five-state
fund-raising tour on behalf of Democratic candidates for Congress.
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOULDER, Colo. -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- COLO-HOUSE-RACE, 9-27
-- State Rep. Mark Udall, 48, left, a Democrat, and Mayor Robert
Greenlee, 57, of Boulder, a Republican, before their debate last
week in their Colorado Congressional race, which is expected to be
competitive. For nearly a quarter century, Colorado's 2nd District
has been a safe seat for Democrats -- and an altar for Republican
sacrificial lambs. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- REAGAN-BIOGRAPHY, 9-27 --
Edmund Morris, 58, the official biographer of Ronald Reagan, has
yet to finish his epic, authorized biography of the former
president. The biography was originally scheduled for publication
seven years ago. Morris calculates that he has been needled with
the question 726,354,925,267 times. ``The book's been delayed
because of the fanatical perfectionism of the neurotic author,''
says Morris. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PLOCIC, Yugoslavia -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIANS,
9-27 -- Qamil Kryeziu, 50, returned to the village of Plocic in
Kosovo, where he and his five children and 70-year-old father have
sought refuge, to find his next-door neighbor's property still
burning after being torched by Serbian forces. Kryeziu's own house
was also burned by the Serbs. This adds to the tally of more than
200 villages described by European Union monitors as moderately or
severely damaged since the Serb offensive began in late July. (Wade
Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW DELHI, India -- Sept. 27, 1998 -- INDIA-FAKE-DOCTORS,
9-27 -- Mohammad Gulam Mustafa, 27, a slum ``doctor'' in New Delhi,
who has completed only 11 years of school, treating Nargis, the
daughter of Naima, the wife of a vegetable-seller. Mustafa opened
his practice when he was 19. In dingy little shops that swarm with
flies, throughout New Delhi, weary people, illuminated by dangling
bare light bulbs, unquestioningly accept all manner of pills and
shots from young men who have never gone to college. (Celia W.
Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
