<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SHARKS IN THE SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   Alfonse D'Amato, who represents New York in the U.S. Senate,
appears to be planning a re-election campaign aimed at increasing
the tensions and distrust between New York's residents. That is a
remarkable conception of what it means to be a statewide elected
official.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's latest television ads against his Democratic opponent,
Rep. Charles Schumer, claim that because Schumer comes from
Brooklyn, he ``doesn't think upstate New York matters.'' Meanwhile,
the state Republican Party is running similar commercials that
depict New York City politicians as sharks, swimming up the Hudson
to steal money from helpless upstate taxpayers. ``They're back,''
says an announcer to music from the movie ``Jaws.'' ``New York City
liberals have plans for higher taxes and higher spending, and you
know what that means _ higher taxes for us, more spending for
them.'' The Republicans are playing to a suspicion, long encouraged
by upstate politicians, that the city is a drain on their economy,
gobbling up far more than its share of resources. In truth, the
city has been the economic engine for the state, and the real
beneficiaries of an imbalance between taxes and spending are the
small rural towns upstate, which are extremely dependent on state
jobs and state aid paid for by all New York taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   No one should begrudge helping these needy towns, and if the
political culture of New York were not so impaired, the state would
have long since resolved some of the problems that have kept it
lagging behind most of the rest of the country in job growth. But
the mutual distrust between upstate New Yorkers and New York City
is a political cancer that has laid waste to the state's
government. The Legislature flounders perpetually because its
members believe they were sent to Albany to champion their regions
rather than work for the well-being of the entire state. Lawmakers
have never been able to agree on sacrifice for the common good
because in New York's warped political culture there is no common
good, only a never-ending struggle to grab more for your own side.
</P>
<P>
   The governor serves as the only real symbol of a unified New
York, and it is incredible that Gov. George Pataki, the party's
standard-bearer, would allow his party to run ads that aim at
turning one part of the state against another. Pataki is well ahead
in the polls and nurtures national ambitions, and his own ads are
mainly feel-good paeans to his virtues. He cannot really believe he
needs to run against New York City in order to be re-elected, but
he cannot dodge responsibility for divisive commercials that are
being paid for by his party on behalf of his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the ``liberal New York City politicians'' card upstate
is an easy dodge that transfers voter discontent away from local
politicians and dumps it on a scapegoat far away. D'Amato did not
invent the tactic, but he is perhaps the first official who
actually represents New York City residents to use it against his
own constituents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
