<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOMERUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE YEAR OF THE HITTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   The baseball playoffs begin Tuesday, which leaves far too little
time to savor the manifold pleasures of a regular season that seems
disinclined to leave the stage. The season will not, in fact,
officially end until Monday night, when the Cubs and Giants play an
extra game to determine the National League's wild-card team. The
Yankee manager, Joe Torre, called it ``the best year I've been
involved with, and it was at the proper time'' _ by which he meant
that this summer's heroics may finally have restored the game of
baseball to its rightful place at or near the top of the U.S.
sporting pyramid, and laid to rest the sullen memories of the
strike-ridden seasons of 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   If Torre is right, the hitters are primarily responsible. This
has been the year of the booming bat, with balls soaring to left,
right, center and plain out of sight. Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa,
both of whom broke Roger Maris' 37-year-old record of 61 home runs,
battled for the home-run prize until the very last weekend, when
McGwire settled the issue by belting four homers in two days for a
mind-boggling total of 70. Theirs was a splendid rivalry that
excited interest even among casual observers of the game. But it
also obscured a host of other impressive achievements. There were a
dozen players with more than 40 home runs, including Cleveland's
(and upper Manhattan's) Manny Ramirez, who hit eight homers in five
games near the end of the season. Barry Bonds of San Francisco
became the first player ever to hit 400 home runs and steal 400
bases in a career. Meanwhile, Sosa drove in 158 runs (and may add
to that total on Monday night), well short of Hack Wilson's record
of 190, set in 1930, but better than anyone since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Whether baseball's owners and players can capitalize on their
sudden good fortune remains to be seen. But for now it is enough to
think back on a wonderful year marred by only one disappointment,
at least in these precincts. The Mets did not make the playoffs.
But the fact that they came so close with a team that was not
expected to do much of anything gives us one more reason to look
forward to next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
