<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-CHARGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS REGAIN THEIR STRUT OVER CHARGERS, 34-16 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The formula is not new to these Giants, and they
knew where they were headed Sunday when they saw the rattled rookie
Ryan Leaf throwing the football into their formations without much
thought.
</P>
<P>
   The swagger was back in the Giants' defensive players, and they
swarmed at the San Diego Chargers and their young quarterback. Four
interceptions later, the Giants had righted their record to 2-2,
won on the West Coast for the first time in seven years and
regained a piece of the National Football Conference East lead with
a thorough 34-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a performance that brought a sigh of relief to the
Giants' locker room and spared them from their worst doubts.
</P>
<P>
   At a team meeting on Saturday, coach Jim Fassel had reminded his
players that they have goals, emphasizing the present tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we had goals,'' Fassel said. ``We have goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Sunday's game was over, the players acknowledged they
had overcome a loss of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been knocked on our heels a little,'' Giants
quarterback Danny Kanell said. ``But we couldn't let a little
setback become a big setback.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the Giants' collapse against Dallas last
Monday, Fassel and his assistants decided to alter their approach,
making it more simple and yet highly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Giants were certain they could force turnovers,
and they did. Leaf, who completed 15 of 34 passes for 193 yards,
left the game in the third quarter, booed off the field after his
fourth interception was run back for a touchdown by the Giants' new
starting free safety, Percy Ellsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth had two interceptions, his first leading to the
Giants' third touchdown and a 21-0 first-half lead.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Fassel decided to let Kanell throw the football
downfield more often, to work the middle of the field with Ike
Hilliard and Chris Calloway. And then, there was a subtle surprise:
Fassel gave the football to the rarely used Gary Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who played last season for the Chargers, admitted last
week that he was disappointed that he was returning to San Diego
with just 21 yards rushing on 10 carries in the Giants' first three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's disappointment appears to have been put to good use by
Fassel, who unleashed Brown as the Giants' secret weapon.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time this season, the Giants' running game had
some bite. Brown did not look like Rodney Hampton, the man he was
signed to replace, and his rushing totals (66 yards on 20 carries)
were not overwhelming. But he did get valuable first-down yards on
several drives, and he looked effective as the between-the-tackles
runner the Giants need him to be.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, on the Giants' second possession of the game, Brown
scored from 4 yards out to give them a 7-0 lead they never
relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked hard for them,'' Brown said of the Chargers. ``It
hurt to have to leave and I ran today with a year's worth of
emotion _ all that wondering why they had to let me go.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kanell, ``Gary was a man possessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's rushing and Kanell's passing were greatly aided by the
performance of the Giants' offensive line. This unit _ much
maligned the last two weeks _ played a strong game. There were
holes for the running backs and adequate protection for Kanell, who
completed 17 of 33 passes for 208 yards and was not sacked.
</P>
<P>
   The line's consistent play allowed the Giants to mount a few
long drives and had the Chargers' defense confused. Kanell, who
started slowly but later threw accurately and quickly, found
Calloway for a 25-yard touchdown pass near the end of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense operated with the faster tempo Fassel
prefers, which was another goal. When the Giants faced a
fourth-and-1 at the Chargers' goal line midway through the second
quarter, the coach decided not to back down from his more
aggressive offensive approach.
</P>
<P>
   He went for it, and Charles Way scored with a second-effort
surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were knocking on the door there and I couldn't back out,''
Fassel said. ``That's how we came out to start the game _ no
motion, no trickery, just meat-and-potatoes football. We won the
old-fashioned way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Giants, that included a harassing performance by the
defense. When three John Carney field goals had brought the
Chargers back into the game and cut the Giants' lead to 21-9,
Ellsworth stepped in front of a Leaf pass over the middle for his
second interception of the game. Ellsworth returned it 20 yards for
a 19-point Giants lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hid behind the linemen and I recognized the pattern the wide
receiver was running,'' said Ellsworth, who started in place of the
team's usual free safety, Tito Wooten, who has a hamstring strain.
``I knew the quarterback couldn't see me, and I just waited and
then broke.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers removed Leaf after Ellsworth's touchdown, replacing
him with Craig Whelihan, who completed the first pass he threw.
Four plays after he entered the game, he lofted a pass over
cornerback Phillippi Sparks and into the hands of wide receiver
Charlie Jones for a 41-yard touchdown pass that cut the Giants'
lead to 28-16.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who also got interceptions from Sparks and
cornerback Carleton Gray, stifled that comeback with some solid
defense and a steady drive at the start of the fourth quarter that
led to a 32-yard field goal by Brad Daluiso and put the Giants
safely ahead. Daluiso added a 19-yard field goal to give the Giants
a 34-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This felt exactly like the games we won last year,'' Ellsworth
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel gave a different version.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was exactly as we laid it out,'' the coach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
