<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER TOURS UPSTATE IN A COUNTERATTACK ON D'AMATO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. _ After a week of being assailed in television
advertising as a ``liberal Brooklyn congressman'' hostile to
upstate interests, Charles Schumer campaigned across western and
central New York Sunday, ticking off the names of relatives who had
lived there and blaming Sen. Alfonse D'Amato for the economic
decline that has gripped this region.
</P>
<P>
   From an airport terminal in Rochester to a union gathering in
Syracuse to the front porch of the house where his father grew up
in this central New York city, the Democratic candidate for the
U.S. Senate asserted that, his ZIP code and accent notwithstanding,
he was sympathetic to the concerns of voters north of New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's visit here, which followed a series of television
advertisements directed by Schumer at upstate audiences, signaled
the extent to which both Schumer and D'Amato are viewing upstate as
critical to the outcome of the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Schumer spoke about the anemic economy in the
region, pledging to push legislation that, he said, would lower the
cost of electricity and air fares, two major constraints on
economic growth. But again and again, Schumer was reminded of the
potency of D'Amato's saturation television campaign as he was
repeatedly asked by reporters how a lawmaker who had spent his life
representing New York City constituents could understand upstaters'
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Schumer is a tough-on-crime, tax-cutting, moderate
Democrat, whose dad was raised in Utica, who shares the same values
as upstate New Yorkers,'' Schumer said into a clutch of television
cameras in Syracuse. He accused D'Amato of dividing the state for
political gain, adding, ``All his name-calling and negativity does
nothing positive for the people of this state _downstate or
upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, D'Amato countered Schumer's move by venturing into
the congressman's district, making a direct appeal to Jewish voters
and predicting that he would beat Schumer in his own backyard.
``I'm going to carry this district,'' said D'Amato, who also
campaigned Sunday in Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato bristled at Schumer's assertion that the Republican
senator was running a divisive campaign and that he had failed to
tend to the needs of New York's troubled upstate economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's total nonsense,'' he said after speaking at a Holocaust
memorial service at the East Midwood Jewish Center in Brooklyn.
``If you look at the record, you will see that repeatedly we have
delivered over and over again for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato declared that Schumer had been divisive in Congress by
voting, for example, to raise the gasoline tax. ``His votes are
being divisive,'' said D'Amato, who has also supported a gas tax
increase. ``You've got to represent all the people. I have. I
represented the interests of upstate, while at the same token,
fighting for, championing and getting the largest increase for mass
transportation because the people here in Brooklyn need it. And
I've never played one against the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges between the two men captured a day in which
D'Amato and Schumer battled over constituencies _ geographic and
ethnic _ that both sides see as critical to victory in what has
become one of the closest watched contests in the country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   D'Amato announced his intention to visit Brooklyn shortly after
learning that Schumer had organized a trip upstate in an apparent
attempt to confront D'Amato in a part of the state that D'Amato has
identified as his prime battleground. Schumer was trailed by a
chartered plane filled with reporters as he sought to rebut the
notion that he would be unable to compete with D'Amato for support
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, dodging thunderstorms that chased his single-propeller
plane through a bumpy itinerary that included Rochester, Syracuse,
Utica and Albany (Ithaca and Binghamton were rained out), signaled
how he intended to compete with D'Amato upstate. He said the
senator had shown no concern about how this part of New York had
lagged behind the economic recovery most of the nation had enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything to create jobs in western New York,''
Schumer said. ``Al D'Amato hasn't talked about jobs. He hasn't
talked about ways to get businesses to come here and stay here. He
has no plan. Rochester doesn't need a senator who once every six
years comes up to Rochester, calls somebody some names and then
vanishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who accompanied Schumer accused D'Amato of running a
divisive campaign. ``They're going to try to pit one part of the
state against the other for political advantage,'' said state Sen.
Richard Dollinger of Rochester. ``I believe it's outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer went to considerable lengths to try to dodge D'Amato's
effort to characterize him as alien to upstate. At every
opportunity, he took note of some relative who had made a home, no
matter how briefly, in this part of the world. ``I feel at home
here,'' he said in Rochester. ``I love this city. I have relatives
here. In fact, my uncle is the head of surgery at Strong Memorial
Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   At Schumer's request, his parents drove up from Brooklyn to join
him in Utica, so his father, Abe, who is 75, could pose with him at
the home where the elder Schumer lived for three of the nine years
he was here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even in front of his father's house, there were reminders of
the difficulties Schumer faced here. John Cosgrove, a lawyer from
the town of Clinton, who served in the Assembly in the 1960s,
stopped by to praise Schumer's candidacy. When asked his party
affiliation, Cosgove responded loudly, ``I was a Democrat,'' but
then dropped his voice to a whisper. ``And a liberal. But don't put
that word in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
