<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-CAMPAIGN-TACTI     09-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CAMPAIGN-TACTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS VOTE, YOU CAN TAKE MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Would a ``real mensch'' trash Manhattan to curry
favor in Munnsville?
</P>
<P>
   Would a genuine champion of upstate interests embrace Ed (Rural
Life Is a Joke) Koch?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, New York state Democrats insist, is no on both
counts. Hence their highly unorthodox step of promising to buy air
time to rebroadcast Sen. Alfonse D'Amato's own advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Democrats announced plans to run an ad in upstate
media markets that the Republican senator himself has broadcast
exclusively over New York City airwaves. In this ad, Koch and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani put aside their differences to praise the senator,
calling him a ``real mensch.''
</P>
<P>
   Downstate, meanwhile, the Democrats say they plan to rebroadcast
a commercial created by the state Republican Party for upstate
viewing only. This ad depicts city Democrats, quite literally, as
rapacious sharks gobbling up tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are exposing downstaters to what Republicans have to say
about them when they think they are not listening,'' said the state
Democratic chairwoman, Judith Hope, who called the shark ad ``very
cynical and even offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   By running the two ads in media markets where they were most
certainly not intended to be shown _ or at least by talking about
doing so _ Democrats hope to dramatize internal contradictions in
the senator's campaign. In effect, they are betting that D'Amato
has miscalculated, pushing too hard _ and too early _ on the old
upstate-downstate rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   But the last few elections also suggest that the risk D'Amato is
taking in alienating city voters may well be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   City residents tend to imagine that they live at the center of
the world, to say nothing of the state. And while the city's
influence, in cultural and economic terms, is disproportionately
large, its influence in electoral politics is just the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century ago, city voters made up half the state's
electorate. Today, they make up just over a third. And even that
figure overstates their significance, with a consistently low voter
turnout rate.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, for example, when George Pataki was a
little-known state senator running against Gov. Mario Cuomo,
two-thirds of all registered voters outside the city went to the
polls. But within the city, fewer than half did. Had the city's
turnout been comparable to the rest of the state's, Cuomo would
almost certainly still be governor, while Pataki would be a
little-known former state senator.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before that, when Cuomo ran against the
much-ridiculed Pierre Rinfret, only 37 percent of the city's
registered voters went to the polls, while outside the city, 57
percent did. That year, Cuomo was pushing a $2 billion
environmental bond act that was defeated largely because of voter
apathy in the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Experts cite many factors in the low city turnout, most
significantly demography. ``By and large,'' said Frances Fox Piven,
a professor of political science at the City University's Graduate
Center, ``the pattern for fully a century now is that if you have
less income, less education and are a member of a minority group,
the less likely you are to turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Piven, politicians could draw more city voters
to the polls if they focused on the right issues, like income
inequality, unemployment and health care access. The problem for
Democrats, obviously, is that these are precisely the kind of
issues associated with good old-fashioned New York City liberalism.
Thus, they are precisely the kind of issues that can be used to
galvanize opposition upstate.
</P>
<P>
   If the last two gubernatorial elections are a guide, city
residents will cast somewhere between 25 and 30 percent of the vote
this November, a significant figure to be sure but hardly decisive.
</P>
<P>
   So while it may be unseemly for D'Amato, himself Nassau
County-bred, to attack his Democratic opponent, Rep. Charles
Schumer, for his New York City roots, it is quite logical for him
to do.
</P>
<P>
   In a D'Amato ad that the Democrats have decided not to
rebroadcast, a large saw cuts the state in two while an announcer
warns voters of Schumer's metro-centrism. ``Liberal Brooklyn
congressman Chuck Schumer doesn't think upstate New York matters,''
the narrator intones.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the sharpest irony of the Republican strategy is that in
statewide elections, it is increasingly New York City that doesn't
matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
