<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-ROCKIES-NY     09-27 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEN GETS RELIEF AFTER LOSING IN RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVE LIPSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The distraught San Francisco Giants closer Robb Nen
thought his season was over as he walked off Coors Field Sunday
afternoon after serving up a game-losing home run to the Colorado
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   But in an improbable twist to an improbable season, unbeknownst
to many of the Giants, the Chicago Cubs had dramatically lost only
a moment earlier to force a one-game playoff Monday in Chicago for
the National League wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' Nen said. ``I didn't find out until we were
in the clubhouse. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   So despite the crushing bottom-of-the-ninth-inning home run by
shortstop Neifi Perez, the Giants head for Chicago's Wrigley Field,
somehow still in the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were five games behind with just 11 games to play,
but they won nine of those games, including seven of their last
eight to surpass the Mets and draw even with the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling how hopeless the team's chances had seemed when it
faced that five-game deficit on Sept. 18, the veteran outfielder
Joe Carter said: ``If someone had told us then that we were going
to be in a one-game playoff, we would have taken it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are a franchise with a storied history of stretch
drives and this one brought back memories of the legendary 1951
run, when the team made up 13{ games in the final six weeks,
culminating with Bobby Thomson's ``shot heard round the world'' to
win a three-game playoff with the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played our hearts out the past week,'' Giants shortstop
Rich Aurilia said. ``I think it's kind of fun. This is something
you dream about as a little kid, a one-game playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker, who said he recently dreamed that
his team would make the playoffs, expected to start the
right-hander Mark Gardner (13-5, 4.27) in the tie-breaker against
the Cubs right-hander Steve Trachsel (14-8, 4.60).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to be going to Chicago,'' Baker said. ``I mean, we
could be going back to San Francisco. We could be going back to
paint our garages.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing before 48,028 fans on a sun-splashed afternoon in Coors
Field, the Giants seemed in control early, jumping out to a 7-0
lead and watching the outfield scoreboard for details of the Cubs'
game with the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was a typical Coors Field-type game again, where no
lead is safe,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' rookie of the year candidate, Todd Helton, capped a
six-run fifth inning with his 25th home run, a three-run blast off
John Johnstone, to narrow the margin to 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, third baseman Vinny Castilla gave the Rockies
the lead with his 46th home run, a two-run shot, but Giants second
baseman Jeff Kent tied the game with a solo shot in the eighth off
Pedro Astacio.
</P>
<P>
   Nen entered the game in the bottom of the ninth and the first
batter he faced was Perez, a shortstop who was hitting .274 with
eight home runs. Perez took Nen's first pitch for a ball and then
slammed a fastball into the right-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was comforting to discover that the Cubs had also
lost, Nen said: ``I don't know if you're ever relieved when you
give up a solo home run to lose the game. We had a chance to win
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies took their traditional end-of-season lap around the
field, but Sunday's victory was only a small bit of solace. Larry
Walker did manage to lock up the NL batting title by going two for
four to finish with a .363 average, but the team that had expected
to contend for a pennant ended up with a 77-85 record. The Giants
are 89-73, with one game to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go from emotional high to emotional low, but that's the
game of baseball,'' said Carter, who went three for four with a
homer and two runs batted in and is a major reason for the Giants'
resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   They won only two of their first 13 games after the All-Star
Game break, but but after acquiring Carter from the Baltimore
Orioles and reliever Jose Mesa from the Cleveland Indians on July
23, they went 35-24.
</P>
<P>
   Noting his impending retirement, the crowd gave Carter a
standing ovation before his first at-bat in the second inning, and
the slugger responded by doffing his helmet and blowing kisses,
then singling to center and stealing second. ``I appreciate the
gesture the fans gave,'' he said. ``That was real touching.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the outfielder who won the 1993 World Series for Toronto
with a game-winning homer has at least one more game to play in his
storied career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in Wrigley Field,'' Carter noted. ``As Ernie Banks would
say, `Let's play two.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
