<DOCNO> NYT19980927.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-YANKEE-STADIUM-ART     09-27 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YANKEE-STADIUM-ART-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 BRONX LEADER UNVEILS PLAN TO KEEP YANKEES IN STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hoping to place the Bronx back at the center of the
debate over a home for the Yankees, Bronx Borough President
Fernando Ferrer plans to offer a proposal Monday to renovate Yankee
Stadium, install 120 luxury boxes, ease traffic congestion and
redevelop the neighborhood with a waterfront park, a Yankee Hall of
Fame and sports-related stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer's proposal, called Yankee Village, comes a month before
George Steinbrenner III, the Yankees' principal owner, is expected
to announce his decision on where the team will play after its
lease with the city expires in 2002. Steinbrenner has long
threatened to move his team to New Jersey or Manhattan, complaining
that the Bronx stadium has too few luxury boxes and parking spaces,
and that the neighborhood is unpleasant, unsafe and a traffic
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer's plan, which he commissioned himself and which combines
elements of several previous stadium proposals, would cost an
estimated $535 million, far less than any new stadium. But its
chances of becoming reality seem far-fetched, given Ferrer's fierce
and frequent criticism of the two people whose support for any
stadium plan is essential: Steinbrenner and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its fate, the Ferrer plan is likely to add another
layer of complexity to the speculation and debate caused by
Steinbrenner's shaky commitment to the Bronx. Giuliani has praised
the economic benefits of a billion-dollar stadium on the West Side
of Manhattan. New Jersey beckons with its own plans. Even The
Star-Ledger of Newark has weighed in, publishing its own plan
Sunday for a stadium in northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But even though a Yankee move has at times seemed a foregone
conclusion, the debate's focus has shifted in recent weeks back to
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Gov. George Pataki declared that the Yankees
``belong in the Bronx, period.'' Pataki _ perhaps feeling pressure
from the Democratic candidate for governor, City Council Speaker
Peter Vallone, who strongly favors keeping the team in the Bronx _
now contends that traffic jams, widespread opposition and the high
cost of construction in Manhattan ``argue strongly against that
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner himself suggested in July that the Yankees might
stay in the Bronx if they drew 3 million fans this season. A
spokesman later backed away from that statement, but the team set
an attendance record anyway _ 2,949,734 by Sunday, the end of the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   And now Ferrer has a plan that seems intended to blunt each of
Steinbrenner's familiar arguments for moving away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proposal,'' Ferrer said, ``will present to fans and
visitors a year-round entertainment venue that will begin to return
to the city the enormous investment the city will, and has already
made, in the New York Yankees. It's fan-friendly, fiscally prudent
and answers the legitimate concerns raised by the Yankees and by
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Ferrer's proposal, the 75-year-old stadium would regain
its historic entrance porticos, perimeter wall at the upper deck
and distinctive copper friezes, while a new, glass-enclosed
concourse would be built on the outside wall. Babe Ruth Plaza would
be moved to the west side of the 50,000-seat stadium, where
restaurants, sports shops, batting cages and a museum would provide
year-round attractions. Fans would arrive and depart from an
expanded ferry terminal, a renovated subway station, a new
Metro-North station and newly configured highway ramps.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer said that Yankee Village would cost less than half the
price of a proposed stadium in Manhattan, with an estimated $360
million coming from state, federal and private sources and only
$175 million from the city.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was prepared by the Manhattan architectural firm of
Beyer Blinder Belle, which designed the Ford Theater on 42nd Street
and the renovation of Grand Central Terminal. Richard Blinder, a
partner at the firm, said he weaved together his own ideas,
features of the National Tennis Center in Queens, Chelsea Piers in
Manhattan and previous design efforts to address complaints by the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can restore the stadium, invigorate it with a kind
of high-tech circulation system and give George all his luxury
boxes,'' Blinder said.
</P>
<P>
   Blinder said he did the study for only $25,000 because he
believed in the project and because an alternative _ the Yankees'
relocating to Manhattan _ ``is horrible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Built in 1923, Yankee Stadium was the first three-tiered
ballpark and the first to be called a stadium. In the mid-1970s,
Mayor John Lindsay renovated the stadium, but failed to make good
on promises to rehabilitate the neighborhood as the cost ballooned
to $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer's proposal seeks to restore many of the original elements
obliterated by the earlier renovation, although some things may be
gone forever. The original Yankee bat rack and bullpen steps are at
the Smithsonian Institution, while the foul poles and some of the
lights are in Osaka, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ferrer's plan, luxury boxes would be built along the
entire mezzanine level, while the stadium club, with a new dining
terrace, would be moved to left field.
</P>
<P>
   To answer the most persistent complaints from Steinbrenner and
fans about traffic congestion and parking, Yankee Village calls for
the creation of a total of 10,340 parking spaces (up from about
7,000) at six garages that are designed to feed traffic across one
of two bridges or onto local streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic problems at Yankee Stadium are solvable,'' said
Samuel Schwartz, a transportation consultant and a former city
traffic commissioner who has seen parts of Ferrer's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer's plan tries to go beyond simply solving the team's
problems by integrating the stadium into the economic life of the
surrounding neighborhood. Under the plan, restaurants and retail
stores would be built alongside the Yankee Hall of Fame.
Storefronts and street lighting would be improved along River
Avenue and 161st Street.
</P>
<P>
   The new garages would be limited to three stories to reduce the
impact on the community and the exit time for automobiles. At the
same time, sports centers with ball fields for local teams would be
atop garages on the northeast and south sides of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Ferrer said, he would have the city condemn the
dilapidated Bronx Terminal Market, a 32-acre site on the south side
of the stadium, to build a waterfront park along the Harlem River
and 450,000 square feet of commercial space for so-called big-box
retailers like Sports Authority or Modells that would draw people
to the area year-round, not just during the 81 home games the
Yankees play every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this will revive the existing commercial areas and
restore the neighborhood parks for Little League teams that play in
the shadow of Yankee Stadium,'' Ferrer said. ``It will ignite a
whole system of active and passive parks with vibrant new
commercial areas and make this as exciting as Camden Yards or the
National Tennis Center.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
